1. d4 {This is a very popular move one for White pretty much at all levels, and the main subject of my course. White is planning to fight for the center with 2. c4 next.   In this chapter I will introduce you to the main openings of our course: the Nimzo-Indian and the Bogo-Indian.} Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlying theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 {White takes more central space and is ready to play 3. Nc3 & e4 next.} e6 {This is a very important move! We anticipate Nc3 and get ready to pin the knight with Bb4 , which is the Nimzo-Indian Defense. We also plan to met Nf3 with Bb4+ , which is the Bogo-Indian Defense.} 3. Nc3 {This is the most principled move as White is threatening to win total control of the center with 4. e4 next.} (3. Nf3 {This is a slow positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ $1 {This is the Bogo-Indian, the main weapon for us against 3.. Nf3. . The key concept is to trade our bishop for their bishop or the knight and put our pawns on the dark squares with ... d6 & ... e5 in the future, creating a powerful pawn chain. The main lines that are covered are:} 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ $1 {This is the key idea, covered in this chapter.} ({Nc3} 6... Bc3 7. Bxc3 Ne4 $1 {Covered in this chapter.})) (3. Nd2 {White plans to win the bishop pair with a3 next.} b6 {see this chapter .}) 3... Bb4 {The key move and this is the beginning of the Nimzo-Indian. We aim to put pressure on White's center with the pieces and often trade the bishop for the c3 -knight, doubling White's pawns. In general, Black often gets quick development while White tries to build up the center. Let me give you an overview of White's most popular moves and our setup as Black.} 4. a3 {This is the most direct way to deal with the pin, known as the Sämisch Variation, named after the German chess player and theoretician Friedrich Sämisch.} (4. f3 {This line was very popular in the 1990s, and was a choice of many attacking players such as young Alexei Shirov. White tries to improve on the Sämisch variation without losing the tempo on 3. a3 and take over the center with d5 next.} d5 $1 {We stop White's plan as soon as possible. Please note that it is a rare occasion that we move our d-pawn this early in this opening. Thus, the structure arising from these lines are not typical of the Nimzo and you have to pay attention to be precise early on! Now, since White can't easily play e4 . Opening up the game with} 5. cxd5 exd5 {is not recommended as the knight on g1 gets stranded. We cover this line here.}) (4. Bg5 {This is the Leningrad Variation. White answers a pin with a pin, hoping to induce ... h6 and ... g5 to take advantage of Black's weakened kingside. These days, it's a rare guest at tournaments for all levels.} c5 $1 {This is more accurate than 4... h6 as there are lines where the bishop on g5 will be attacked via our queen on a5 . We cover this line here .}) (4. g3 {White goes for the immediate fianchetto of their light-square bishop. This is called the Romanishin Variation, named after the Ukrainian GM Oleg Romanishin.} c5 5. Nf3 Ne4 {White's slow play enabled us to add another attack on the c3 -knight, adding pressure on the pin. White's most popular moves are to protect the knight with the queen either} 6. Qd3 {or Qc2 . Our reaction will be exactly the same, which is easy to remember, we trade on d4 and play ... Qa5 next. See here .}) (4. Bd2 {White immediately stops the pin and gets ready to play a3 later and recapture on c3 with the bishop, thus avoiding doubled pawns. This line was always considered harmless for Nimzo players, but recently some top players have decided to explore it deeper and found some ideas for White.} c5 $1 {I believe that challenging White in the center is the simplest approach, as previously recommended O-O gives White too many options. See this chapter .}) (4. Nf3 {This is often called the Kasparov variation as young Kasparov famously uncorked it during his 2nd match vs Karpov in 1985. However, since Kasparov typically answered} c5 {with} 5. g3 {, this would transpose to the Romanishin Variation, analyzed here . For this chapter, I will focus on 5. e3 which will transpose to a well-known line of the Rubinstein known as the Huebner Variation, named after a famous German Grandmaster, Robert Huebner. c5! Please note that normally against the Rubinstein 4. e3. we answer with 4... b6 . However, if we play 4... b6 now we would have to learn a big chapter with 5. Bg5 . Not that it's any dangerous for Black, but I don't want to overwhelm you with learning too much theory of a rare line. Instead, I will teach you the Huebner Wall! Here's the link to this chapter.}) (4. Qc2 {This is the Classical variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after a typical 5. a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5. e4 . However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves. Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 $1 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo-Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our dark-squared bishop. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas! See this chapter here.}) (4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein variation. White is not worried about Black taking on c3 and doubling the pawns for now. Instead, White aims for a solid setup either with 5. Bd3 & Nge2 or 5. Bd3 & Nf3 or the immediate 5. Nge2 . Luckily, my original recommendation from Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time, and I would recommend it for this course as well, 4... b6 ! Of course, I did a complete overhaul and have lots of improvements ready for you!} b6 {We answer White's slow play with a sound idea of activating our light-squared bishop. If White plays for 5. Nge2  & a3 we develop the bishop to a6 to challenge White on the f1 - a6 diagonal.   If White goes for a classical setup with Bd3/ Nf3 or Bd3 /Nge2 we fianchetto the bishop on b7 . The Good news is that this line still hasn't gained as much popularity as the autopilot move 4... O-O , thus most likely your opponent may be less prepared.   These days Caruana has championed this move on multiple occasions. He famously used it to win a mini-match vs GM Nakamura as Norway Chess 2024 (Hikaru escaped with a draw in classical but lost in Armageddon). Knowing that Caruana plays this line is the highest stamp of approval!}) 4... Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {We have a classic imbalance in chess: White gets a bishop pair and a strong center (with f3 & e4 next) but at the cost of doubled pawns.} b6 {It's very important for Black to attack c4 -pawn as quickly as possible with ... Nc6 , ... Ba6 & ... Na5 next. Some rules of thumb to remember:   1) Don't castle short early! As a matter of fact we often leave our king in the center or castle queenside.   2) Don't play an early ... d5 pawn push, as this will only help White to un-double the pawns.} ({Please note that} 5... Nc6 6. f3 b6 {will transpose. This is covered in this chapter.}) *

