1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow, positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after the German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among the world's best players in the 1920s and 1930s. He even got to challenge the World Champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice, in 1929 and 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White, I win because I am White. When I am Black, I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Bd2 ({White's main line, outnumbering} 4. Nbd2 {about 2 to 1 at the Master level.}) 4... Qe7 {Black has a number of choices here, and if you want to broaden your repertoire, you might explore some of them.} (4... Bxd2+ {is solid but unambitious. By exchanging the Bishops immediately, Black takes all of the pressure off of White and allows White the greatest freedom to choose a setup. As a result, Black tends to equalize at best, but usually not more.}) (4... a5 {is interesting and can lead to some lines similar to the lines in this course, but it also gives White the option to trade Bishops on b4 immediately, leading to a family of pawn structures we don't cover here. IM Sielecki recommends this line in his 2015 repertoire book on the Nimzo- and Bogo-Indian.}) (4... c5 $5 {is a positionally ambitious line. Black wants to induce White to play d5 and then use the c5 -square for a knight. It has fallen out of fashion at the highest levels, but GMs Najer and Esipenko still wheel it out once in a while.}) 5. g3 {This is the main line. White wants to fianchetto the bishop for maximum pressure on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} Nc6 {This slightly unusual move prepares the natural Bg2 , with a hidden tactical idea.} 6. Bg2 {White's most natural follow-up move to g3 , but this allows a cool idea: to take on d2 with check.} Bxd2+ {Practically forcing White to take with the b1 -knight, as taking with the queen allows a cool tactical idea: ... Ne4 ! which we will cover in detail.} 7. Nbxd2 {This is the best recapture, but as you will see the knight is sub-optimally placed on d2 in the resulting middlegame.} O-O ({I think this move order is most precise as} 7... d6 {allows an interesting regrouping} 8. Nf1 $5 {& 9. Ne3 .}) 8. O-O d6 {This is the key move of our simple strategic plan: play ... d6 & ... e5 creating a dream pawn chain and opening up our light-squared bishop.} 9. e4 {White's main move, trying to gain space.} e5 {We create a powerful pawn chain. Please note that with our pawns being on the dark squares, cannot be attacked by the enemy bishop. As a matter of fact, White's bishop is often getting locked in on g2 .} 10. d5 Nb8 {Don't worry about violating one of the core opening principles: 'Don't move the same piece twice.' Here, it's obvious due to the closed nature of the position that long-term plans and maneuvers take precedence over the classic tempo game.  Black wants to reroute the knight to a c5 -outpost via a6 , but first we need to secure it with ... a5 .  Let's pause and discuss this important tabiya for the Bogo opening. We have a classic King's Indian structure but with a very important twist: the dark-squared bishops are traded! I believe this favors Black long-term since often in the KID the bishop is stuck on g7 .  White is surely missing the e3 -bishop that is probably their best piece in normal KID structures. How would this change affect the plans? For one, Black is not obliged to go for the throat with a classic pawn storm on the kingside. Instead, we are flexible.  As a matter of fact, often we plan on the queenside with ... a5 , ... Na6 , and later ... c6 and even ... b5 . But Black can also go for the classic ... f5 pawn push.  White typically tries to regroup with Ne1 - d3 and push for b4 - c5 or f4 to gain more space. Also, keep in mind that White's knight on d2 is misplaced as it prefers to be on c3 . The same for White's bishop, as it's blocked by his own pawns: e4 - d5 - c4 .} {Here, White typically chooses between Ne1 and b4 .} 11. b4 {White starts the typical queenside expansion.} a5 {This is always a good insertion to make White play a3 .} 12. a3 ({Please note that} 12. b5 $2 {is a terrible positional concession, as Black wins the c5 -outpost for free.}) 12... Na6 {This is the most natural square for the knight. Yes, for now, we are not really threatening to win the b4 -pawn. However, we put pressure on the queenside and keep the c8 - h3 diagonal open for our bishop.} 13. Qb3 {White's best. The point is to protect b4 while connecting the rooks. It's funny that I reached this position vs GM Hakobyan in 2018, after first analyzing it for the original Black book back in 2005!   Sometimes, you have to wait for 13 years to show your prep! Luckily, my prep withstood the test of time with modern engines, which shows you how solid this opening is for Black!} c6 {Black's typical plan in these structures. We undermine the c6 -pawn, trying to get counterplay on the queenside. Keep in mind, there's nothing wrong with natural ... Bd7 or ... Bg4 moves as well. However, sooner or later, I believe ... c6 should be played.} 14. Ne1 {This is a typical move to transfer the knight to d3 .} cxd5 ({I think this is a bit more accurate than} 14... Bd7 {, which was recommended in the original book. We would like to see how White recaptures, since vs exd5 the bishop wants to go to f5 .}) 15. cxd5 axb4 16. axb4 Bd7 {Black is ready to use the b5 -outpost for their bishop or the a6 -knight.} 17. Nd3 Nc7 {The knight is heading to b5 and d4 . For the model game (except White's pawn was on f3 ) please see Skembris-Beliavsky .} *

