1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after the German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among the world's best players in the 1920s and 1930s. He even got to challenge the World Champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice, in 1929 and 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White, I win because I am White. When I am Black, I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Bd2 ({White's main line, outnumbering} 4. Nbd2 {about 2 to 1 at the Master level.}) 4... Qe7 {Black has a number of choices here, and if you want to broaden your repertoire, you might explore some of them.} (4... Bxd2+ {is solid but unambitious. By exchanging the Bishops immediately, Black takes all of the pressure off of White and allows White the greatest freedom to choose a setup. As a result, Black tends to equalize at best, but usually not more.}) (4... a5 {is interesting and can lead to some lines similar to the lines in this course, but it also gives White the option to trade Bishops on b4 immediately, leading to a family of pawn structures we don't cover here. IM Sielecki recommends this line in his 2015 repertoire book on the Nimzo- and Bogo-Indian.}) (4... c5 $5 {is a positionally ambitious line. Black wants to induce White to play d5 and then use the c5 -square for a knight. It has fallen out of fashion at the highest levels, but GMs Najer and Esipenko still wheel it out once in a while.}) 5. g3 {This is the main line, White wants to fianchetto the bishop for maximum pressure on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} Nc6 {This slightly unusual move prepares the natural Bg2 , with a hidden tactical idea.} 6. Nc3 ({The top choice of GMs these days as they are aware of the tactical idea after} 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ {and now White has to take on d2 with the knight, which is a concession since the knight is more active on c3 . Please note that} 7. Qxd2 {runs into a well-known trick with} Ne4 $1 {See the 6.Bg2 chapter for more detailed explanation.}) 6... Bxc3 {We use this opportunity to trade a few pieces and land our knight on e4 . Remember the old principle: the side with less space should seek piece trades.} 7. Bxc3 Ne4 {White has to react to a positional threat of ... Nxc3 , doubling the pawns.} 8. Rc1 {This is the main line.} O-O 9. Bg2 d6 ({Here, White chooses between an aggressive} 9... d5 {or a simple} 10. O-O {.}) 10. O-O {White goes for a simple development plan.} e5 {We execute the main idea of our setup: building a beautiful c7 - d6 - e5 pawn chain that points directly at White's king.} ({I believe it's slightly more accurate than the original book recommendation of} 10... Nxc3 11. Rxc3 e5 {since White has the extra option of .}) 11. d5 {This is the main move by far, White gains space and wins a tempo.} Nxc3 {We don't have to take this bishop quite yet, but since it's part of our plan we might as well do it with tempo.} 12. Rxc3 Nb8 {As a rule of thumb, we almost always retreat the knight to b8 in these structures. The point is that it can get to the c5 -outpost. Here are some important points to keep in mind in this tabiya structure:   1) White's temporary advantage in development is not very relevant due the closed nature of the position.   2) White's plan is to play on the queenside by breaking through with c5 .   3) Black's plan is to play on the kingside with potential ... f5 - f4 but also to take over the queenside, thanks to the powerful c5 -outpost.   4) Black's bishop is superior due to better mobility, where's White's bishop is stuck behind the pawns and is usually a purely defensive piece.} {White's main options are: c5 , Nd2 and b4 .} 13. b4 {This is White's most popular move, with an obvious idea to play for c5 next.} Nd7 ({I like this a bit more than the originally recommended} 13... Bg4 {. But both moves are playable.}) 14. Qc2 {This is the most common move in DB.} ({White prepares c5 .} 14. Nd2 {this transposes to 13.Nd2 .}) 14... a5 {A standard idea to open up the a-file.} 15. a3 axb4 16. axb4 e4 17. Nd4 Nf6 {I prefer Black already! White can't easily play for c5 since the d5 -pawn is loose. Black, on the other hand, has several plans such as ... Qe5 , ... Bd7 and eventually an ... h5 - h4 expansion.} *

