1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after the German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among the world's best players in the 1920s and 1930s. He even got to challenge the World Champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice, in 1929 and 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White, I win because I am White. When I am Black, I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Bd2 ({White's main line, outnumbering} 4. Nbd2 {about 2 to 1 at the Master level.}) 4... Qe7 {Black has a number of choices here, and if you want to broaden your repertoire, you might explore some of them.} (4... Bxd2+ {is solid but unambitious. By exchanging the Bishops immediately, Black takes all of the pressure off of White and allows White the greatest freedom to choose a setup. As a result, Black tends to equalize at best, but usually not more.}) (4... a5 {is interesting and can lead to some lines similar to the lines in this course, but it also gives White the option to trade Bishops on b4 immediately, leading to a family of pawn structures we don't cover here. IM Sielecki recommends this line in his 2015 repertoire book on the Nimzo- and Bogo-Indian.}) (4... c5 $5 {is a positionally ambitious line. Black wants to induce White to play d5 and then use the c5 -square for a knight. It has fallen out of fashion at the highest levels, but GMs Najer and Esipenko still wheel it out once in a while.}) 5. g3 {This is the main line, White wants to fianchetto the bishop for maximum pressure on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} Nc6 {This slightly unusual move prepares the natural Bg2 , with a hidden tactical idea.} 6. Nc3 ({The top choice of GMs these days as they are aware of the tactical idea after} 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ {and now White has to take on d2 with the knight, which is a concession since the knight is more active on c3 . Please note that} 7. Qxd2 {runs into a well-known trick with} Ne4 $1 {See the 6.Bg2 chapter for more detailed explanation.}) 6... Bxc3 {We use this opportunity to trade a few pieces and land our knight on e4 . Remember the old principle: the side with less space should seek piece trades.} 7. Bxc3 Ne4 {White has to react to a positional threat of ... Nxc3 , doubling the pawns.} 8. Rc1 {This is the main line.} O-O 9. Bg2 d6 ({Here, White chooses between an aggressive} 9... d5 {or a simple} 10. O-O {.}) 10. d5 Nb8 {These days I like this over the original recommendation of ... Nxc3 since I believe the knight on e4 limits White's options.} (10... Nxc3 11. Rxc3 Nb8 12. dxe6 fxe6 {allows} 13. Re3 $1 {which is a bit annoying, for example:} e5 14. O-O Nc6 15. Nd4 $1 {with an edge for White.}) 11. dxe6 fxe6 12. O-O a5 {A prophylactic move, stopping White's natural b4 expansion, while gaining some space & securing the c5 -outpost. Here, White has several plans:} {1) Preserve the bishop pair with Be1 or Bd4 . 2) Play for central domination with Nd4 . 3) The simple b3 with an idea of Bb2 .} 13. Be1 {White maintains the bishop pair but e1 -bishop is quite passive! This gives Black just enough time to get counterplay.} Nc5 14. b3 e5 {Achieving our ideal structure.} 15. Bc3 Nc6 16. Nd2 Bg4 {Black finished development with easy play. Our c7 - d6 - e5 pawn chain kills the c3 -bishop while our knights and LSB are giving White some headaches. The game is balanced but I prefer Black.} *

