[Black "Nimzo - 4.Qc2 Classical Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E33"]
[PlyCount "22"]
[GameId "2176748629177007"]

1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qc2 {This is the Classical Variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after a typical 5. a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5.e4. However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves.  Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo-Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our DSB. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas!} 5. Nf3 {This is by the far the most common way to protect the d4 -pawn. White is still being flexible with his LSB that could be developed to g5 .} d6 {The move order is very important here! We delay castling for a very important reason, anticipating the logical pin with 6. Bg5 in order to spring a devilish trap on our unexpected opponent!} 6. Bg5 {The most played move. Why not pin a knight and develop the bishop at the same time? But this is exactly what we want!} h6 {Asking the bishop its intentions, we expect the autopilot response Bg5 in order to spring our trap!} 7. Bh4 {White's most logical and most played move, which turns out to be a mistake already! By the way, this move has appeared in over 7,000 online blitz games and has been played 68% of the time in this position!} g5 {Now, we get to uncork our trap!} 8. Bg3 ({Sacrifice on g5 doesn't work, after} 8. Nxg5 $2 hxg5 9. Bxg5 {Black wins with pretty much any logical move, but} Nxd4 {is easiest.}) 8... g4 {And just like that White will lost a key central pawn. Engine gives -1 already!} 9. Nd2 Nxd4 {We grab the free central pawn while attacking the queen, but our trap is not fully complete as you will see shortly.} 10. Qa4+ {White gets giddy with joy, thinking they win a piece with this double attack, but...} Bd7 {Make sure to play this move with a poker face, or perhaps even shake your head in disgust as though you just blundered a piece...} 11. Qxb4 {An unfortunate, game ending blunder for our opponent.} Nc2+ {The family forks completes our trap and triggers immediate resignation from White. When your opponent shakes your hand, remember to mention that you knew all of this from a Chessable course! Many of my students won games like this, and now it's time for you to celebrate winning a nice miniature as well!} *

