1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qc2 {This is the Classical Variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after a typical 5. a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5.e4. However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves.  Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo-Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our DSB. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas!} 5. Nf3 {This is by the far the most common way to protect the d4 -pawn. White is still being flexible with his LSB that could be developed to g5 .} d6 {The move order is very important here! We delay castling for a very important reason, anticipating the logical pin with 6. Bg5 in order to spring a devilish trap on our unexpected opponent!} 6. Bd2 {This is the best move and stronger players know about the ... h6 +g5 trap.   White intends to play a3 and take back on c3 with the bishop.} O-O {Black's most natural move. We anticipate a3 and get ready to execute our central break plan with ... Re8 and ... e5 next.} 7. a3 Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Re8 ({This is a big improvement over the original book recommendation of} 8... Qe7 {. While the idea is the same to play for ... e5 , I believe it's more accurate to start with 8... Re8 as we will shall see.}) 9. e4 {White grabs the center and together with the bishop pair is about to claim a nice edge, but...} e5 {Just in time! This instructive central thrust is very important. But the follow-up is even cooler.} 10. d5 {White grabs more space and expects a knight retreat, but we have a surprise for our opponent!} Nd4 {The key idea! As you can see White is paying the price for leaving the king on e1 for too long. After the trade on d4 , the rook on e8 opens up with big threats on the e-file.} 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Bxd4 Nxe4 ({It's also fine to take on d4 with the rook,} 12... Rxe4+ {.}) 13. Be2 ({A very natural move, but already a mistake! Better is} 13. O-O-O {but after} Qh4 {, we get plenty of counterplay.}) 13... Qg5 {A strong move, hitting the g2 -pawn. White is in big danger already.} 14. O-O Bh3 15. Bf3 Nd2 {This fork wins on the spot, White can't defend against so many threats.} *

