1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qc2 {This is the Classical Variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after a typical 5. a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5.e4. However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves.  Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo-Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our DSB. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas!} 5. Nf3 {This is by the far the most common way to protect the d4 -pawn. White is still being flexible with his LSB that could be developed to g5 .} d6 {The move order is very important here! We delay castling for a very important reason, anticipating the logical pin with 6. Bg5 in order to spring a devilish trap on our unexpected opponent!} 6. Bd2 {This is the best move and stronger players know about the ... h6 +g5 trap.   White intends to play a3 and take back on c3 with the bishop.} O-O {Black's most natural move. We anticipate a3 and get ready to execute our central break plan with ... Re8 and ... e5 next.} 7. a3 Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Re8 ({This is a big improvement over the original book recommendation of} 8... Qe7 {. While the idea is the same to play for ... e5 , I believe it's more accurate to start with 8... Re8 as we will shall see.}) 9. e3 {White is getting ready to develop his LSB and castle kingside. But our plan is very simple: ... e5 pawn push!} e5 {Black executes the key strategic idea of this opening. We create a nice pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and open up our LSB.} 10. d5 {This is the ambitious option, but we don't mind the closed nature of the resulting positions since we have the knights vs the bishop pair.} Ne7 {Often, we retreat the knight to b8 in order to reroute it to c5 , but since White always has b4 ready, we shift our focus to undermining the d5 - c4 pawns with either ... c6 or ... b5 in the future.} 11. e4 {A logical move, White completes the central grip grabbing more space. However, White's kingside is still not fully developed and we use the time to undermine White's center.} c6 {An instructive idea to chip away at White's strong center and a strong novelty!} 12. Be2 {A logical move. White is getting ready to complete their development with O-O next.} Ng6 {The knight is aiming for f4 -outpost.} 13. O-O Nf4 {Black's knight is a monster on f4 . Please notice that the close nature of this position makes White's bishop pair irrelevant.} 14. Rfe1 Bg4 {We completely our development and put extra pressure on the f3 -knight.} 15. Bd1 b5 {I like this cool idea to take advantage of White's poor coordination. This is a fun position for us to play and White can easily go wrong.} 16. dxc6 (16. cxb5 cxd5 17. exd5 N6xd5) 16... bxc4 17. Qa4 Qb6 18. Qxc4 Rac8 19. Ba4 {Too greedy.} Bxf3 20. gxf3 {White's kingside is now permanently ruined.} N6h5 {Black will follow up with ... Re6 and a big attack.} *

