[Black "Nimzo - 4.e3 Rubinstein Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E45"]
[PlyCount "24"]
[GameId "2176748629177010"]

1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein Variation. White is not worried about Black taking on c3 and doubling the pawns for now. Instead, White aims for a solid setup either with Bd3 & Nge2 or Bd3 & Nf3 or the immediate Nge2 . Luckily, my original recommendation from Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time, and I would recommend it for this course as well, 4... b6 ! Of course, I did a complete overhaul and have lots of improvements ready for you!} b6 {We answer White's slow play with a sound idea of activating our light-squared bishop. If White plays for 5. Nge2 & a3 we develop the bishop to a6 to challenge White on the f1 - a6 diagonal.} ({If White goes for a classical setup with Bd3/Nf3 or Bd3/Nge2 we fianchetto the bishop on b7 . The good news is that this line still hasn't gained as much popularity as the autopilot move} 4... O-O {, thus it is likely your opponent may be less prepared. These days Caruana has championed this move on multiple occasions. He famously used it to win a mini-match vs GM Nakamura as Norway Chess 2024 (Hikaru escaped with a draw in classical but lost in Armageddon). Knowing that Caruana plays this line is the highest stamp of approval!}) 5. Nge2 ({In the Master Database, this move is seen almost 3 times more than} 5. Bd3 {, so make sure to be ready for it! White's idea to play a3 next and obtain the bishop pair 'for free', meaning that they don't want to ruin their pawn structure with bxc3 .}) 5... Ba6 {We have to act fast as White is about to get the bishop pair, which is a long-term asset. Thus, we need to get our counterplay going quickly.} 6. a3 {White executes their main idea.} Bxc3+ 7. Nxc3 d5 {The key idea! If not for this move, White would be significantly better. However, now we keep attacking the pawn on c4 , hoping to induce cxd5 which would enable us to trade light-squared bishops.} 8. Qa4+ {White aims to take on d5 only after ... c6 , but Black is fine here as well.} c6 9. cxd5 Bxf1 10. dxc6 {This walks into a powerful trap!} b5 {This nice intermezzo allows Black to save his bishop and remain a piece up!} 11. Nxb5 Bxb5 12. Qxb5 Qc7 {Other moves win as well but this is the cleanest.} *

