[GameId "2176748629177011"]

1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein Variation. White is not worried about Black taking on c3 and doubling the pawns for now. Instead, White aims for a solid setup either with Bd3 & Nge2 or Bd3 & Nf3 or the immediate Nge2 . Luckily, my original recommendation from Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time, and I would recommend it for this course as well, 4... b6 ! Of course, I did a complete overhaul and have lots of improvements ready for you!} b6 {We answer White's slow play with a sound idea of activating our light-squared bishop. If White plays for 5. Nge2 & a3 we develop the bishop to a6 to challenge White on the f1 - a6 diagonal.} ({If White goes for a classical setup with Bd3/Nf3 or Bd3/Nge2 we fianchetto the bishop on b7 . The good news is that this line still hasn't gained as much popularity as the autopilot move} 4... O-O {, thus it is likely your opponent may be less prepared. These days Caruana has championed this move on multiple occasions. He famously used it to win a mini-match vs GM Nakamura as Norway Chess 2024 (Hikaru escaped with a draw in classical but lost in Armageddon). Knowing that Caruana plays this line is the highest stamp of approval!}) 5. Bd3 {White is going for the classical development approach and not worried about ... Bxc3 + for now.} Bb7 6. Nf3 {White's most popular setup. They are going for rapid development aiming to castle quickly. The drawback is of course that we can double the pawns with ... Bxc3 +.} O-O 7. O-O Bxc3 {This is my preferred choice as I believe it fits our general strategy of establishing a clear pawn weakness and attacking it next.} 8. bxc3 {Now, White's pawn structure is ruined but it's not easy to attack it yet. Therefore, we continue with normal development.} c5 {We apply a well-known positional motif of 'fixing' the double pawns, i.e. blocking them with our pawn and make them immobile.} {White's main plan is to prepare e4 . They can do it via Nd2 or Qe2 or Re1 . We will look at all these options.} 9. Re1 {White is ready to play e4 next.} Ne4 {The key blockading idea! We are about to secure our knight on e4 with ... f5 next, completely locking up the center and, in turn, White's bishops!} 10. Qc2 f5 {Black has achieved a dream blockade!} 11. Nd2 {White's most logical move, trying to break up the blockade by trading the e4 -knight.} Qh4 {The queen enters the game just in time! Now we attack f2 and protect the knight at the same time.} 12. g3 {A sad necessity, White weakens the long diagonal even more.} Qf6 {Black sets up the x-ray attack on f2 , thus indirectly protecting our e4 -knight.} 13. f4 Nxd2 14. Bxd2 d6 {I prefer Black here due to many weaknesses in White's camp and their weak king. White's bishop pair is not so relevant here with a closed & fixed structure.   Let's follow the game between the famous Youtuber IM John Bartholomew and GM Yuri Shulman to see the possible ideas in the resulting middlegame.} (14... d5 $5 {a logical idea to open up the game for the bishop exd5} 15. cxd5 Bxd5 16. c4 {Be6! The bishop is better placed here as it over-protects f5 and targets c4 -pawn. Bc3} Qf7 17. e4 Bxc4 $1 {Black is correct to enter these complications.} 18. exf5 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 {d5! Even stronger than the game continuation. Now, White has to find the right moves: Re7!} {( Nd7 Qxd6 Qxf5 this position is about even but Black ended up winning after a long fight. 0-1 Bartholomew, J (2435)-Shulman, Y (2563) Reykjavik ISL 2013)} Qe7 {Qxd5+ Qf7 Qxa8 Qd7!⩱ Black is a bit better, but White has enough to hold the balance.}) *

