1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein Variation. White is not worried about Black taking on c3 and doubling the pawns for now. Instead, White aims for a solid setup either with Bd3 & Nge2 or Bd3 & Nf3 or the immediate Nge2 . Luckily, my original recommendation from Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time, and I would recommend it for this course as well, 4... b6 ! Of course, I did a complete overhaul and have lots of improvements ready for you!} b6 {We answer White's slow play with a sound idea of activating our light-squared bishop. If White plays for 5. Nge2 & a3 we develop the bishop to a6 to challenge White on the f1 - a6 diagonal.} ({If White goes for a classical setup with Bd3/Nf3 or Bd3/Nge2 we fianchetto the bishop on b7 . The good news is that this line still hasn't gained as much popularity as the autopilot move} 4... O-O {, thus it is likely your opponent may be less prepared. These days Caruana has championed this move on multiple occasions. He famously used it to win a mini-match vs GM Nakamura as Norway Chess 2024 (Hikaru escaped with a draw in classical but lost in Armageddon). Knowing that Caruana plays this line is the highest stamp of approval!}) 5. Bd3 {White is going for the classical development approach and not worried about ... Bxc3 + for now.} Bb7 6. Nge2 {This is a less popular move as White sacrifices the g2 -pawn. But it's not without venom as we saw recently GM Giri faced this move at the Olympiad 2024 and lost with Black.} Bxg2 {We are brave and take the pawn!} 7. Rg1 Bf3 {The most precise. Now, White has to deal with two pins!} 8. Qc2 {White sidesteps the pin while taking control over e4 , preparing Rg3 next.} Nc6 {The most precise! We don't care about the g7 -pawn and go for rapid development.} 9. Rxg7 Nh5 10. Rg1 Qh4 {Very strong for Black. We will castle long next.} *

