1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. a3 {This is the most direct way to deal with the pin, known as the Sämisch Variation, named after the German chess player and theoretician Friedrich Sämisch.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {We have a classic imbalance in chess: White gets a bishop pair and a strong center (with f3 & e4 next) but at the cost of doubled pawns.} b6 {It's very important for Black to attack the c4 -pawn as quickly as possible with ... Nc6 , ... Ba6 & ... Na5 next. Some rules of thumb to remember:   1) Don't castle short early! As a matter of fact we often leave our king in the center or castle queenside.   2) Don't play an early ... d5 pawn push, as this will only help White to undouble the pawns.} ({Please note that} 5... Nc6 6. f3 b6 {will transpose.}) 6. f3 {White is getting ready to play e4 to build the big center.} Nc6 ({Please note that we can also start with ...Ba6 first, but it would transpose after e4} 6... Nc6 {.}) 7. e4 Ba6 {White has achieved the goal of grabbing the center, but notice that all of their pieces are still on the initial row, while we already developed 3 minor pieces and about to play ... Na5 next.} ({Here White has three ways to continue: Bg5 going for the pin, Bd3 with the idea to meet ... Na5 with Qe2 , or} 7... e5 {going for even more space.}) 8. Bd3 {White is ready to meet ... Na5 with Qe2 .} Na5 9. Qe2 d6 ({I like this simple and flexible move best. I believe it's better than the original book recommendation of ... Qc8 since after} 9... Qc8 10. e5 Ng8 {White can get a big initiative with} 11. Nh3 $1 {For those who like to explore more forcing lines, I can also recommend} c5 $5) 10. Nh3 Nb3 {Black has many good moves but I like the simple idea of trading our knight for the c1 -bishop.} 11. Rb1 Nxc1 12. Rxc1 e5 {Black clearly has a better pawn structure while White lost the bishop pair and remains with weak queenside pawns.} 13. O-O Bc8 {A cool regrouping, our bishop is more powerful on c8 - h3 diagonal, plus we force the knight to f2 .} 14. Nf2 Nh5 {Black takes control of f4 and opens up the queen.} 15. g3 Qg5 16. Kh1 O-O {Black finally castles and stands a bit better. We have a better pawn structure and can play on both wings either with ... c5 or a long-term ... f5 plan. White is lacking any plan and has to resort to passive defense.} *

