1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Nf3 {This is often called the Kasparov Variation as young Kasparov famously uncorked it during his 2nd match vs Karpov in 1985.} ({However, since Kasparov typically answered} 4. c5 {with g3 , this would transpose to the Romanshin Variation, analyzed here .  For this chapter, I focus on e3 which will transpose to a well-known line of the Rubinstein known as the Huebner Variation, named after a famous German Grandmaster, Robert Huebner.}) 4... c5 ({Please note that normally against the Rubinstein e3 we answer with} 4... b6 {. However, if we play b6 now we would have to learn a big chapter with} 5. Bg5 {. Not that it's any dangerous for Black, but I don't want to overwhelm you with learning too much theory of a rare line.   Instead, I will teach you the Huebner Wall!}) 5. e3 Nc6 {We develop normally and put pressure on White's center.} 6. Bd3 {White's most common move, they go for rapid development as well.} Bxc3+ {Let's double White's pawns and create a long-term pawn weakness.} 7. bxc3 d6 {Black is ready to setup the Huebner wall with ... e5 next.} 8. e4 e5 {This setup is known as the Huebner Variation or the Huebner Wall. Black builds a wall of pawns on the dark squares, limiting the scope of White's bishops.   These positions are bread and butter for Nimzo players, and I'd like to teach you the common plans and ideas.} 9. d5 {White gains space but locks up the center.} Ne7 {Sometimes Black plays ... Na5 to put pressure on c4 -pawn, but in the Huebner Variation this is the best retreating square for the knight. We aim to play on the kingside with ... Ng6 where the knight will cover the vital f4 -square.} 10. Nd2 {White typically reroutes the knight to e3 via f1 , not wasting any time on castling.} h6 {A useful waiting move.} 11. Nf1 Qa5 {Let's tickle the weak c3 -pawn to see how White will react.} 12. Bd2 Bd7 {I like this natural novelty, Black gets ready to castle long!} 13. Ne3 O-O-O 14. O-O Kb8 {Black safeguards his king by moving it to a8 prior to starting the attack.} 15. Rb1 Ka8 16. Qc2 g5 {Let's go!} 17. Rb2 Ng4 {We trade White's best piece.} 18. Rfb1 Nxe3 19. Bxe3 Rb8 {We protect our only weakness the b7 -pawn. White ran out of ideas on the queenside while Black has a free hand on the the kingside.} 20. Qc1 f5 {With a big attack coming! Black gets to have all the fun! Engines already love Black giving us a -1 advantage.} *

