1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. a3 {This move clearly stops any ... Bb4 ideas, but White cannot fight for the opening advantage with such moves. I will give you two weapons against this:   A fighting Benoni, where a3 is a waste of a tempo since White often needs to play a4 . And a simple central strategy, where we play for 3... d5 , aiming to get QGD/QGA up a tempo with easy equality.} c5 {This is the most fighting option, inviting White to a Benoni where they are a tempo down.} 4. d5 g6 {We complete our fianchetto first and later deal with White's d5 -pawn.} 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. e4 d6 {We keep the tension and will take on d5 at the right moment.} 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Be2 exd5 {We clarify the situation in the center.} 9. cxd5 b5 {This is the most forcing way to get counterplay.} ({We can also play} 9... Bg4 {with a more positional game with a later ... a6 & ... b5 expansion.}) 10. Bxb5 ({Taking with the knight} 10. Nxb5 {allows} Nxe4 {, which is a favorable trade for us.}) 10... Nxe4 {The key tactical idea, we will follow up with ... Qa5 + next.} 11. Nxe4 Qa5+ 12. Nfd2 ({This is White's best. Please note that} 12. Nc3 $2 {gets White in trouble after} Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Qxb5 {and now White can't castle.}) 12... Qxb5 13. Nxd6 Qa6 {We prevent White from castling. White can still achieve equality by finding the correct moves.} 14. N2c4 Nd7 15. O-O Ne5 16. Nxc8 Raxc8 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 {This is a well-known Benoni position where Black has enough play for the pawn. At some point we will play ... Rfd8 & ... Bd4 and win the d5 -pawn. The engine pretty much gives 0.00.} *

