1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack is a cousin of the London System. White hopes to play an e3 , Bd3 , and c3 setup next.} h6 {We attack White's bishop right away. Now, White has a choice between 4. Bxf6 and 4. Bh4 .} 4. Bxf6 {White gives up the bishop pair, hoping to build a strong center with e4 & d4 .} Qxf6 5. e4 {White achieves their goal, but I believe the bishop pair and the flexible pawn structure gives us better chances long term.} d6 {We first secure the e5 -square.} 6. Nc3 g6 {Our original recommendation is still approved by modern engines 20 years later! The bishop is more powerful on the long diagonal.} 7. Qd2 {White prepares to castle long.} Bg7 8. O-O-O a6 {We get ready to counterattack with ... b5 next.} ({Please note that} 8... Qe7 {first, followed by ... b5 is fine as well.}) ({Here, White can try: Bd3 , Qe3 , and} 8... e5 {.}) 9. Bd3 {A logical move, White completes development and connects their rooks.} Nc6 {This is even stronger than original recommendation of 9... Qe7 , as we attack the d4 -pawn and take control of e5 .} 10. Ne2 b5 {We start our queenside expansion. Black will play ... Rb8 next and push their pawns. In the meantime, White's attack is nowhere to be seen.   Conclusion: The Torre Attack is best met with 3... h6 ! If White goes for the trade on f6 with e4 / d4 center grab, we develop naturally with ... d6 , ... g6 , and ... Bg7 . Remember, to get counterplay with ... b5 and keep in mind that two bishops will tear up the board once the game opens up.   If White goes for a positional approach with 4. Bh4 , we strike the center with ... c5 ! The ideas are similar to the London System. If possible, we trade the light-squared bishops with ... Ba6 , or if White stops this plan with Qe2 then we go for the fianchetto plan with ... Bb7 followed by ... d6 and a timely trade of the DSB with ... Nh5 ! Black eventually gets an extra central pawn and tries to prepare a long-term ... e5 break.} *

