1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. g3 {White plans to develop via Bg2 , O-O , Nc3 and then focus on the center. It's an easy few moves for us as well. We will play ... Bg7 , ... Nc6 , and ... d6 .} (3. e4 {For this, please the Anti-Maroczy.}) (3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d5 {For this variation, please see here}) (3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 ({(} 4. e3 Nf6 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {For this variation, please see here )}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {For this variation, please see the here}) 3... Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. O-O d6 6. Nc3 Bf5 {We've reached the main tabiya of our setup. Black plans to play ... Qd7 and set up a classic battery to prepare ... Bh3 .   Please note that it's vital for us to stop White from playing d4 too easily, thus we keep the knight on g8 for now. Sometimes, we also launch Harry the h-pawn for a caveman attack! White's most common options are:   1) Continue with normal development and play 7. d3   2) Stop our battery with 7. h3 and Kh2   3) Go for the double fianchetto with 7. b3} 7. d3 Qd7 {This is the natural follow-up move for our plan. Now, White has to make a choice, allow the bishop trade or not.} 8. Re1 {This is the autopilot reaction to the threat of ... Bh3 . White is getting the rook out of the way to meet ... Bh3 with Bh1 .} Bh3 {It's a good idea to force the bishop in the corner.} 9. Bh1 {Of course, taking on h3 makes no sense if you play Re1 .} h5 {Harry the h-pawn joins the party! White has to be careful as the timely ... h4 push may open up his king for a deadly attack.} 10. Ng5 {This is the most common move I see in blitz, but funny enough it doesn't stop our plan!} h4 {Of course, we keep on pushing to rip out the h-file!} 11. Nxh3 hxg3 ({Make sure to remember this key intermezzo! Taking the knight with} 11... Qxh3 {is ok but it gives White an opportunity to defend with} 12. Bg2 $1) 12. hxg3 (12. Bg2 {is met with} Rxh3 $1 {with a big attack.}) (12. fxg3 $2 {loses after .}) 12... Rxh3 {This is even stronger than 12... Qxh3 .} 13. Bg2 {It looks as though White is now able to fend off Black's attack, but in reality the attack is quite strong even without Black's LSB.} O-O-O ({While both} 13... Rh7 {and Rh5 are good, I like this direct approach, offering White the exchange.}) 14. Bxh3 {This move actually loses.} Qxh3 {Black has an unstoppable attack now.} 15. Nd5 {White tries to bring the knight to f4 .} Be5 {Stopping Nf4 .} 16. Nf4 Bxf4 17. Bxf4 Nf6 {Now, White has to deal with big big threats ... Ng4 or ... Rh8 .} 18. e3 {Trying to defend with Qf3 next.} Rh8 19. Qf3 g5 {We lure the bishop to g5 , freeing up the e5 -square.} 20. Bxg5 Ng4 {Our big threat is ... Nce5 next.} 21. Qg2 {White escapes in the endgame, but it won't stop their king from getting mated!} Qxg2+ 22. Kxg2 Rh2+ {Giving White a few options, but no matter where the king goes he's busted.} 23. Kf3 {The king goes for a walk.} Nce5+ 24. Ke4 e6 {White is getting mated in 4 moves! I have to share with you this beautiful line to the end.} 25. Rf1 Rxf2 26. Rxf2 Nxf2+ 27. Kf4 Nfxd3+ 28. Ke4 f5# {One of the prettiest checkmates I've ever seen!} *

