1. c4 c5 2. g3 {With this move order White often tries to delay Nf3 , or play without Nf3 .} g6 {Our response is simple to continue with symmetry, but keep in the mind we like symmetry as long as White doesn't play Nf3 . Make sure that you don't accidentally meet Nf3 with ... Nf6 ? as this would ruin our entire setup!} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {For now, we still continue with symmetrical development. It's very important to keep full control over the d4 -outpost, thus we need to keep the knight on g8 . Now, White has to make a big decision here:} {Go for the main line with Nf3 or play a tricky waiting move a3!? or try to develop e3 and Nge2 . We will cover both 5. a3 !? and 5. e3 in the theoretical chapters.} 5. a3 {A tricky waiting move! White wants to see how Black develops and then choose their setup. Plus a3 is a useful move as they can play for the typical English plan with Rb1 & b4 next. Remember, White is basically playing the Dragon with reversed colors and wants to swing with the tail!} b6 {I love this rare move! It's based on a very simple concept: do you want to play for a3 & b4 ? Then, be my guest! Black will have time to set up the fianchetto on b7 and neutralize White's best piece, the g2 bishop. Plus, there's another bonus idea to Black's setup as you will see shorty.} 6. b4 {White even gets to play b4 in one go!} Bb7 {We neutralize White's g2 -bishop.} 7. Rb1 {A standard idea. White's rook gets out of the long diagonal, creating a threat of bxc5 .} Bxc3 {This is the bonus surprise that I mentioned earlier! Normally, one would not trade this beautiful bishop for the c3 knight, but this is an exception! The key idea is like in the Nimzo-Indian, White's doubled c-pawns are too much of a liability.} 8. dxc3 d6 {We secure the c5 -pawn and White is now playing with a ruined pawn structure on the queenside. There have only been a handful of games in the DB with this position, so it's quite fresh!} 9. Nf3 Nf6 10. O-O ({White can't really stop our from castling as} 10. Bh6 {is met by} Ng4 $1) 10... O-O 11. Bh6 Re8 {At first, it may seem really dangerous for us with White's bishop on h6 . However, my analysis shows that White can't really create tangible threats while we have a clear plan in mind: trade light-squared bishops and target the c4 -pawn.} 12. Nd2 Qc7 {With the idea to play ... Ne5 next, trading the bishops.} 13. Qb3 Ne5 14. Bxb7 Qxb7 {Black has a serious advantage as the c4 -pawn is quite weak. Plus, White's king is exposed as well: imagine our queen coming to h3 and playing ... Ng4 .   Conclusion: If White delays Nf3 , they typically go for the early a3 / b4 plan or the central e3 , Nge2 , & d4 setup. In the first case, make sure to remember the simple setup based on 5... b6 ! Black will fianchetto the bishop and neutralize White on the long diagonal.   Don't forget about the cool idea of 7... Bxc3 ! We trade our DSB for the knight and double White's pawns, similar to the Nimzo. This gives Black excellent long-term chances and we often take over the game, especially after the trade of the light-squared bishops.   In case White goes for 5. e3 , we answer with Harry the h-pawn push 5... h5 ! This often leads to fun and exciting chess, especially if White allows 6. Nge2  h4 ! where we dominate on the kingside.   White's best is 6. h3 , but even there, we seek counterplay with ... d6 & ... h4 in order to meet g4 with ... f5 ! with a complex middlegame and good chances to outplay our opponent.} *

