1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4 {This is the most testing option. White plans to go for the Maroczy setup with 4. d4 next. Luckily, I have an interesting fresh idea to share with you that I covered in my Hyper-Accelerated Dragon (HAD) Lifetime Repertoire on Chessable already. We go for 3... Bg7 and an early 4... Qa5 +!?. The way I reach this via a 1. e4 move order is:} (3. e4 {c5 Nf3 g6 c4}) 3... Bg7 4. d4 Qa5+ {As I mentioned, this is covered in detail in my 1. e4  c5 HAD course and I'm happy to share the full analysis here.} 5. Nc3 {White's most popular reply} d6 {With this move Black keeps White guessing how he would release the tension in the center. Our main idea is to apply more pressure with a future ... Nc6 or ... Bg4 .} 6. d5 {This is the most ambitious try. White takes the game into the closed structure that resembles the Dzindzi-Indian. But keep in mind, typically 1.e4 players hate playing closed positions!} Bxc3+ {The main idea of the Dzindzi-Indian. Black ruins White's structure.} 7. bxc3 Bg4 ({I like this rare move, putting more pressure on White. Keep in mind that in closed positions, knights are better than bishops.} 7... Qxc3+ $6 {is playable but too risky} 8. Bd2 {with good compensation for the pawn and easy play for White.}) 8. Qc2 {most common reply, but walks straight into our plan} Bxf3 9. gxf3 {This is an interesting position. White's bishop pair and more space is counterbalanced by his weak pawns. I believe the closed nature of the position gives Black better practical chances, even though the engine slightly prefers White at first.} Nd7 10. f4 Ngf6 11. Bd3 {this natural developing move is already wrong.} O-O-O {The key idea to remember! We typically castle long so that we can attack White on the kingside!} 12. O-O h6 {A nice idea that was played by a strong Russian GM Malakhov back in 2016. Black is ready to blow open the kingside with ... g5 !} 13. Re1 {White is seeking counterplay with e5 .} (13. Be3 $6 {allows our main idea!} g5 $1 14. fxg5 $2 hxg5 {with a killer attack. WOOF!}) 13... Qc7 14. Qe2 e5 {Preventing White from playing e5 himself! Now, we get an endgame almost by force.} 15. dxe6 fxe6 16. e5 ({White has to open up the game in order not to be worse.} 16. Be3 e5 $1) 16... dxe5 17. fxe5 Qxe5 18. Qxe5 Nxe5 19. Rxe5 Rxd3 20. Rxc5+ Kd8 {The endgame is about equal and Black eventually won the game: Kreisl-Malakhov Novi Sad, 2016.} *

