1. Nf3 {In this chapter we will cover the Reti opening where White goes for the immediate kingside fianchetto with 2. g3 , 3. Bg2 , and 4. O-O .} c5 2. g3 ({After} 2. c4 g6 {we transpose to the English lines.}) 2... g6 {We also fianchetto our bishop.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O Nc6 5. d3 {White still has a choice to go for 6. e4 or 6. c4 plans.} d6 {We also achieved our Dragon setup and wait for White to show us their plan.} 6. e4 {This approach takes the game into the King's Indian Attack (KIA) or the Closed Sicilian territory. If you already studied my HAD course, you know what to do: we finish development with ... Nf6 & ... O-O and start playing on the queenside with ... Rb8 and ... b5 . Remember the basic rule of thumb when coming up with a plan: The Dragon swings with its tail!} Nf6 {We continue to develop the kingside. White typically fights for the center with c3 , Re1 & d4 or goes 7. Nbd2 .} 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Re1 Rb8 {We prepare the classic ... b5 push, our Dragon swings with his tail! We can also start with an immediate 8... e5 .} 9. a4 {White hopes to slow us down and trade the a-pawn once we play ... b5 in order to open up the a-file for the rook.} e5 {I think this is better than the autopilot 9... a6 as we stop e5 ideas. Now, White's LSB is quite passive.} ({After} 9... a6 10. e5 {White opens up their LSB, and the game is about even.}) 10. Nc4 h6 {A useful move. We prevent Bg5 and stop any Ng5 jumps after ... Be6 . Keep in mind that Black has many good moves here, it's more about knowing the right plan and where to put your pieces.} 11. c3 Be6 {We develop our bishop and overprotect the d5 -square.} 12. Ne3 Qd7 {Black is a bit better as it's hard for White to find a plan. We have many different plans: play for the central push with ... d5 , or prepare the classic queenside expansion with ... a6 & ... b5 .} *

