1. Nf3 c5 2. b3 {This combo of Nf3 & b3 is a aimed to stop our plan of ... g6 . However, I will show you a cool idea where we still get to fianchetto our bishop.} Nc6 3. Bb2 Nf6 {We don't mind the trade on f6 as it would give us two powerful bishops.} 4. e3 {This is the most common move. White prepares d4 and plans to play Be2 & O-O .} g6 {We still fianchetto our bishop! Again, we are not afraid of Bxf6 exf6 structures. GM Nakamura has played this line with White many times in blitz. He typically goes for Bxf6 or d4 plans. Let's take a look.} 5. d4 {This is probably White's best, they fight for the center.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 {White keeps their b2 -bishop open but gives us a favorable two central pawns vs 1 imbalance.} Bg7 {We continue with natural development.} 7. Be2 (7. Nxc6 bxc6 {only helps us by getting another pawn closer to the center.}) 7... O-O 8. O-O Nxd4 ({Black has many promising moves, but I like this one best. We trade on d4 first prior to playing ... d5 , otherwise White has an option to ruin our pawn structure after} 8... d5 {.}) 9. Bxd4 d5 {We are first to grab control over the center. If allowed, we will play ... Qd6 & ... e5 next.} 10. Nd2 Qd6 {Simple chess. We are ready to play ... e5 next.} 11. c4 ({A standard reaction by White in this line.} 11. Nf3 {stops e5 , but we will activate our pieces with ... Bf5 , ... Rfd8 & ... Rac8 .}) 11... e5 ({The key move! In the Candidates 2024, Abasov played an inferior and passive} 11... Rd8 $2 {against Firouzja and quickly ended up in trouble:} 12. cxd5 Qxd5 13. Bf3 Qf5 14. Rc1 Ne8 15. Rc5 e5 16. Nc4 {and lost the game.}) 12. Bb2 Rd8 {We activate the rook anticipating the trade on d5 .} 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Nc4 Qe7 {Even though the position is about even, I prefer Black due to the central pawn on e5 and nice pressure on the d-file. Please note that White's queen doesn't have a safe square as it will be harassed on the c-file with the other rook after ... Bf5 & ... Rac8 .} *

