1. f4 {This is the Bird's Opening. White plays in the spirit of the reversed Dutch.} d5 ({We can start with} 1... g6 {as recommended in the original book, since} 2. e4 c5 {transposes to our favorite Sicilian. But most people will react to g6 with} 3. Nf3 {and} d5 {will just transpose.}) 2. Nf3 g6 {The fianchetto plan is the most effective weapon vs various reversed Dutch formations. Now, White can choose between 3. g3 aiming for reversed Leningrad Dutch or 3. e3 with Stonewall setup after d4 , c3 .} 3. e3 Bg7 4. d4 {This is known as the Stonewall setup. White hopes to solidify his position with c3 and use the e5 -outpost to generate an attack. However, I will teach you an effective method of neutralizing this plan.} Nh6 {This is the bonus of being down a tempo! Since White's last move weakened the e4 -square, we try to get the f5 -outpost for our knight, which eventually can reroute to d6 . In addition, the knight will support the trade of light-squared bishops with ... Bf5 in the future. Remember, this is the key strategic idea for Black!} 5. Bd3 O-O 6. O-O c5 {We grab more space and offer a favorable trade.} 7. c3 {White's autopilot move. They complete the Stonewall setup, but seriously weaken their light square, especially e4 . Also, White is often struggling to activate the passive c1 -bishop.} (7. dxc5 $2 {is met with} Nd7 {regaining the pawn.}) 7... Qc7 {I like this flexible move. We protect the c5 -pawn and get ready to play the thematic ... Bf5 next.} 8. Qe2 Bf5 {We execute the key strategic idea: the trade of light-squared bishops. Now, you see how the knight on h6 is helping us.} 9. Ne5 {White's knight on e5 is only visually appealing, but in reality it's a paper tiger.} Nd7 10. Nd2 Bxd3 11. Nxd3 Nf5 {The knight replaces the bishop and aims to get to d6 .} 12. Nf3 Nd6 {The idea square for our knight. Eventually, we will get the e4 -outpost with ... Nf6 & ... Nfe4 .} 13. Nfe5 c4 {Gaining more space.} 14. Nf2 Nf6 {Black has won the strategic battle. We control the e4 -outpost and will launch the queenside play with ... b5 and ... a5 next. In the meantime, White is playing without a plan with a passive bishop on c1 .} *

