1. b3 {This is the Larsen's Opening where White tries to delay the fight for the center and fianchetto the dark-squared bishop. I recommend an idea based on the central strategy 1... e5 but with a twist: we plan to sacrifice our central pawn for the bishop pair later.} e5 {We fight for the center from move one!} 2. Bb2 Nc6 {We develop our knight and defend the pawn, aiming to take over the center with ... d5 next. Here, White has two approaches:} ({e3 with the idea to meet} 2... d5 {with a Bb5 pin. This is the main line.}) {Or, c4 trying to get the game into English territory.} 3. e3 {This is the main line. White wants to meet d5 with .} d5 {We grab the full control of the center.} 4. Bb5 {White creates a direct threat of Bxe5 , using the pin tactic.} Nge7 {We 'fall' for White's trap! This idea was a shocking revelation to me a few years ago, when I started working with neural network engine, Leela. Now, it's a known concept and just as popular as the main line 4... Bd6 .} 5. Bxe5 {White takes our gift.} a6 {The point! Now, White has to part with the bishop pair.} 6. Bxc6+ Nxc6 {This is an interesting position. We gave up a central pawn, but have the two bishops and a serious lead in development. If you love initiative, you will enjoy playing this line.} 7. Bb2 {This is the most common move by far. White keeps the bishop on the long diagonal. However, it allows us to put pressure on White's kingside with ... Qg5 !} Qg5 {The key idea to remember! White doesn't have an easy way to deal with ... Qxg2 and has to make serious concessions.} 8. Qf3 {This is the most common move since both Kf1 & g3 are serious concessions. But now, White's queen gets chased around with tempi.} Bg4 {We develop our bishop with a tempo!} 9. Qg3 Bd6 {Another tempo move.} 10. f4 Qf5 {Our queen is now targeting the c2 -pawn.} {White's only move to avoid being seriously worse is h3! which is not easy!} 11. Bxg7 {This loses.} Rg8 12. Bc3 O-O-O 13. d3 d4 {And it's clear that White is falling apart due to a huge attack.} *

