{This is an important tabiya for the Bogo opening. We have a classic King's Indian structure but with a very important twist: the dark-squared bishops are traded! I believe this favors Black long term since often in the KID the bishop is stuck on g7 . White is surely missing the e3 -bishop that is probably his best piece in normal KID structures.   How would this change affect plans? For one, Black is not obliged to go for the throat with a classic pawn storm on the kingside. Instead, we are flexible. As a matter of fact, often we play on the queenside with ... a5 , ... Na6 and later ... c6 and even ... b5 . But Black can also go for the classic ... f5 pawn push.   White typically tries to regroup with Ne1 - d3 and push for b4 - c5 or f4 to gain more space. Also, keep in mind that White's knight on d2 is misplaced as it prefers to be on c3 . The same is true for White's bishop, as it's blocked by their own e4 , d5 , & c4 pawns.} 11. Z0 *

