1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow, positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after a German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among World's best players in 1920-30s. He even got to challenge the world champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice in 1929 and in 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White I win because I am White. When I am Black I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Bd2 ({White's main line, outnumbering} 4. Nbd2 {about 2 to 1 at the Master level.}) 4... Qe7 {Black has a number of choices here, and if you want to broaden your repertoire, you might explore some of them.} (4... Bxd2+ {is solid but unambitious. By exchanging the Bishops immediately, Black takes all of the pressure off of White and allows White the greatest freedom to choose a setup. As a result, Black tends to equalize at best, but usually not more.}) (4... a5 {is interesting and can lead to some lines similar to the lines in this course, but it also gives White the option to trade Bishops on b4 immediately, leading to a family of pawn structures we don't cover here. IM Sielecki recommends this line in his 2015 repertoire book on the Nimzo- and Bogo-Indian.}) (4... c5 $5 {is a positionally ambitious line. Black wants to induce White to play d5 and then use the c5 -square for a knight. It has fallen out of fashion at the highest levels, but GMs Naijer and Esipenko still wheel it out once in a while.}) 5. e3 {This is a somewhat passive approach, White just wants to develop the light-squared bishop quickly and castle. Since it was recommended by GM Sam Shankland in his LTR 1. d4 course, we have to take it seriously.} b6 {I like this move with idea to take over the long diagonal after ... Bb7 .} 6. Bd3 {This is Shankland's recommended setup.} Bb7 7. O-O Bxd2 ({I recommend to trade on d2 as after} 7... O-O 8. Nc3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Ne4 10. Be1 {White keeps the pair of bishops.}) 8. Nbxd2 {GM Shankland claims a slight edge for White here as he's about to play e4 . However, as we already know from other Bogo lines, we can easily meet e4 with ... d6 & ... e5 .} d6 {We prepare to meet e4 with ... e5 .} 9. e4 e5 {We execute the key idea in the Bogo: creating an important c7 - d6 - e5 pawn chain and challenging White in the center.} 10. Re1 {White keeps their options open and doesn't commit to closing the center.} (10. d5 {is met by the thematic} a5 $1 {where Black is fighting for the c5 -outpost.}) 10... O-O 11. d5 a5 {We fight for the c5 -outpost.} 12. a3 Nbd7 13. b4 Ra7 {A clever idea to double the rooks on the a-file and put pressure on White. Keep in mind that White should never play b5 ? as it gives up the c5 -outpost completely.} 14. Qc2 {White anticipates us to double the rooks and transfers the queen to b2 .} Rfa8 15. Qb2 g6 {Black now has prospects on the kingside with ... Nh5 and ... Bc8 while keeping an eye on the right opportunity to play ... axb4 .} *

