1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow, positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after a German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among World's best players in 1920-30s. He even got to challenge the world champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice in 1929 and in 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White I win because I am White. When I am Black I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Bd2 ({White's main line, outnumbering} 4. Nbd2 {about 2 to 1 at the Master level.}) 4... Qe7 {Black has a number of choices here, and if you want to broaden your repertoire, you might explore some of them.} (4... Bxd2+ {is solid but unambitious. By exchanging the Bishops immediately, Black takes all of the pressure off of White and allows White the greatest freedom to choose a setup. As a result, Black tends to equalize at best, but usually not more.}) (4... a5 {is interesting and can lead to some lines similar to the lines in this course, but it also gives White the option to trade Bishops on b4 immediately, leading to a family of pawn structures we don't cover here. IM Sielecki recommends this line in his 2015 repertoire book on the Nimzo- and Bogo-Indian.}) (4... c5 $5 {is a positionally ambitious line. Black wants to induce White to play d5 and then use the c5 -square for a knight. It has fallen out of fashion at the highest levels, but GMs Naijer and Esipenko still wheel it out once in a while.}) 5. g3 {This is the main line. White wants to fianchetto the bishop for maximum pressure on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} Nc6 {This slightly unusual move prepares the natural 6.Bg2 , with a hidden tactical idea.} 6. Bg2 {White's most natural follow-up to g3 , but this allows a cool idea: to take on d2 with check.} Bxd2+ {Practically forcing White to take with the b1 -knight, as taking with the queen allows a cool tactical idea: ... Ne4 !, which we will cover in detail.} 7. Qxd2 {The cool tactical idea.} Ne4 {Make sure to remember this move! Black forces the queen away from the e1 - a5 diagonal.} 8. Qc2 Qb4+ {All of a sudden, White doesn't have a good way to deal with this check without making some kind of concession.} 9. Nbd2 {This natural move loses a pawn by force! It's funny that even though this is a well-known trick, over 4,500 people have fallen for it in blitz!} Nxd2 {White will either lose the d4 -pawn or the c4 -pawn now.} 10. Qxd2 {The lesser of two evils.} Qxc4 11. O-O {White lost a pawn but at least was first to finish development. However, I believe that Black is better.} Qb4 12. Qc2 {Naturally, White wants to avoid queen trades, being a pawn down.} d5 {Black's plan is to finish development with ... O-O and then slowly unravel the queenside with ... Bd7 , etc.} 13. Rac1 O-O 14. a3 Qb6 15. Rfd1 Bd7 16. e3 f6 {Restricting White's knight.} 17. Ne1 Be8 {Followed by ... Bh5 , Black's bishop will get activated with easy play.} *

