s Naijer and Esipenko still wheel it out once in a while.}) 5. g3 {This is the main line. White wants to fianchetto the bishop for maximum pressure on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} Nc6 {This slightly unusual move prepares the natural 6.Bg2 , with a hidden tactical idea.} 6. Bg2 {White's most natural follow-up to g3 , but this allows a cool idea: to take on d2 with check.} Bxd2+ {Practically forcing White to take with the b1 -knight, as taking with the queen allows a cool tactical idea: ... Ne4 !, which we will cover in detail.} 7. Qxd2 {The cool tactical idea.} Ne4 {Make sure to remember this move! Black forces the queen away from the e1 - a5 diagonal.} 8. Qc2 Qb4+ {All of a sudden, White doesn't have a good way to deal with this check without making some kind of concession.} 9. Nc3 {This allows us to take on c3 and double White's pawns.} Nxc3 10. bxc3 {This loses the c4 -pawn, but White does get some compensation.} Qxc4 11. O-O d6 12. e4 e5 {Black's extra b-pawn should give us a nice edge.} *

