1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow, positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after a German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among World's best players in 1920-30s. He even got to challenge the world champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice in 1929 and in 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White I win because I am White. When I am Black I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Bd2 ({White's main line, outnumbering} 4. Nbd2 {about 2 to 1 at the Master level.}) 4... Qe7 {Black has a number of choices here, and if you want to broaden your repertoire, you might explore some of them.} (4... Bxd2+ {is solid but unambitious. By exchanging the Bishops immediately, Black takes all of the pressure off of White and allows White the greatest freedom to choose a setup. As a result, Black tends to equalize at best, but usually not more.}) (4... a5 {is interesting and can lead to some lines similar to the lines in this course, but it also gives White the option to trade Bishops on b4 immediately, leading to a family of pawn structures we don't cover here. IM Sielecki recommends this line in his 2015 repertoire book on the Nimzo- and Bogo-Indian.}) (4... c5 $5 {is a positionally ambitious line. Black wants to induce White to play d5 and then use the c5 -square for a knight. It has fallen out of fashion at the highest levels, but GMs Naijer and Esipenko still wheel it out once in a while.}) 5. g3 {This is the main line. White wants to fianchetto the bishop for maximum pressure on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} Nc6 {This slightly unusual move prepares the natural 6.Bg2 , with a hidden tactical idea.} 6. Bg2 {White's most natural follow-up to g3 , but this allows a cool idea: to take on d2 with check.} Bxd2+ {Practically forcing White to take with the b1 -knight, as taking with the queen allows a cool tactical idea: ... Ne4 !, which we will cover in detail.} 7. Nbxd2 {This is the best recapture, but as you will see, the knight is suboptimally placed on d2 in the resulting middlegame.} O-O ({I think this move order is most precise as} 7... d6 {allows an interesting regrouping} 8. Nf1 $5 {& 9.Ne3 .}) 8. O-O d6 {This is the key move of our simple strategic plan: play ... d6 & ... e5 , creating a dream pawn chain and opening up our light-squared bishop.} 9. e4 {White's main move, trying to gain space.} e5 {We create a powerful pawn chain. Please note that with our pawns on the dark squares, they cannot be attacked by the enemy bishop. As a matter of fact, White's bishop is often getting locked in on g2 .} 10. dxe5 dxe5 {This gives Black a long-term strategic edge due to the strong d4 -outpost.} *

