 with a classic pawn storm on the kingside. Instead, we are flexible.  As a matter of fact, often we plan on the queenside with ... a5 , ... Na6 , and later ... c6 and even ... b5 . But Black can also go for the classic ... f5 pawn push.  White typically tries to regroup with Ne1 - d3 and push for b4 - c5 or f4 to gain more space. Also, keep in mind that White's knight on d2 is misplaced as it prefers to be on c3 . The same for White's bishop, as it's blocked by his own pawns: e4 - d5 - c4 .} {Here, White typically chooses between Ne1 and b4 .} 11. Ne1 {The knight is heading to d3 where it will support a b4 / c5 push or f4 .} a5 {The key part of our plan, Black is trying to stop ... b4 and secure the c5 -outpost.} 12. Nd3 Na6 13. f4 {White chooses to expand on the kingside.  Here, I will give you an improvement over my originally recommended c6 .} b6 {This is the simplest plan, we just want to overprotect the c5 -outpost and ask White a question: what are you going to do next?} 14. a3 {White is about to play b4 , but we are just in time.} Nc5 15. Nxc5 bxc5 {Take a look at Black's rock-solid pawn structure. White is lacking any plan, while we can put pressure on the half-open b-file.} *

