s Naijer and Esipenko still wheel it out once in a while.}) 5. g3 {This is the main line. White wants to fianchetto the bishop for maximum pressure on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} Nc6 {This slightly unusual move prepares the natural 6.Bg2 , with a hidden tactical idea.} 6. Bg2 {White's most natural follow-up to g3 , but this allows a cool idea: to take on d2 with check.} Bxd2+ {Practically forcing White to take with the b1 -knight, as taking with the queen allows a cool tactical idea: ... Ne4 !, which we will cover in detail.} 7. Nbxd2 {This is the best recapture, but as you will see, the knight is suboptimally placed on d2 in the resulting middlegame.} O-O ({I think this move order is most precise as} 7... d6 {allows an interesting regrouping} 8. Nf1 $5 {& 9.Ne3 .}) 8. O-O d6 {This is the key move of our simple strategic plan: play ... d6 & ... e5 , creating a dream pawn chain and opening up our light-squared bishop.} 9. e4 {White's main move, trying to gain space.} e5 {We create a powerful pawn chain. Please note that with our pawns on the dark squares, they cannot be attacked by the enemy bishop. As a matter of fact, White's bishop is often getting locked in on g2 .} 10. d5 Nb8 {Don't worry about violating one of the core opening principles: 'Don't move the same piece twice.' Here, it's obvious due to the closed nature of the position that long-term plans and maneuvers take precedence over the classic tempo game.  Black wants to reroute the knight to a c5 -outpost via a6 , but first we need to secure it with ... a5 .  Let's pause and discuss this important tabiya for the Bogo opening. We have a classic King's Indian structure but with a very important twist: the dark-squared bishops are traded! I believe this favors Black long-term since often in the KID the bishop is stuck on g7 .  White is surely missing the e3 -bishop that is probably their best piece in normal KID structures. How would this change affect the plans? For one, Black is not obliged to go for the throat with a classic pawn storm on the kingside. Instead, we are flexible.  As a matter of fact, often we plan on the queenside with ... a5 , ... Na6 , and later ... c6 and even ... b5 . But Black can also go for the classic ... f5 pawn push.  White typically tries to regroup with Ne1 - d3 and push for b4 - c5 or f4 to gain more space. Also, keep in mind that White's knight on d2 is misplaced as it prefers to be on c3 . The same for White's bishop, as it's blocked by his own pawns: e4 - d5 - c4 .} {Here, White typically chooses between Ne1 and b4 .} 11. Ne1 {The knight is heading to d3 where it will support a b4 / c5 push or f4 .} a5 {The key part of our plan, Black is trying to stop ... b4 and secure the c5 -outpost.} 12. Nd3 Na6 13. a3 {White is planning natural expansion with b4 & c5 .} Bg4 {I like this move to induce f3 and also give White an opportunity to go wrong.} 14. Qc2 {This natural move is a serious strategic error. Now Black wins the c5 -outpost with an instructive trade.} Be2 15. Rfe1 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Nc5 17. Qc3 a4 {This move permanently secures our knight on c5 with a clear long-term edge.} *

