1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow, positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after a German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among World's best players in 1920-30s. He even got to challenge the world champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice in 1929 and in 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White I win because I am White. When I am Black I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Bd2 ({White's main line, outnumbering} 4. Nbd2 {about 2 to 1 at the Master level.}) 4... Qe7 {Black has a number of choices here, and if you want to broaden your repertoire, you might explore some of them.} (4... Bxd2+ {is solid but unambitious. By exchanging the Bishops immediately, Black takes all of the pressure off of White and allows White the greatest freedom to choose a setup. As a result, Black tends to equalize at best, but usually not more.}) (4... a5 {is interesting and can lead to some lines similar to the lines in this course, but it also gives White the option to trade Bishops on b4 immediately, leading to a family of pawn structures we don't cover here. IM Sielecki recommends this line in his 2015 repertoire book on the Nimzo- and Bogo-Indian.}) (4... c5 $5 {is a positionally ambitious line. Black wants to induce White to play d5 and then use the c5 -square for a knight. It has fallen out of fashion at the highest levels, but GMs Naijer and Esipenko still wheel it out once in a while.}) 5. g3 {This is the main line. White wants to fianchetto the bishop for maximum pressure on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} Nc6 {This slightly unusual move prepares the natural 6.Bg2 , with a hidden tactical idea.} 6. Bg2 {White's most natural follow-up to g3 , but this allows a cool idea: to take on d2 with check.} Bxd2+ {Practically forcing White to take with the b1 -knight, as taking with the queen allows a cool tactical idea: ... Ne4 !, which we will cover in detail.} 7. Nbxd2 {This is the best recapture, but as you will see, the knight is suboptimally placed on d2 in the resulting middlegame.} O-O ({I think this move order is most precise as} 7... d6 {allows an interesting regrouping} 8. Nf1 $5 {& 9.Ne3 .}) 8. O-O d6 {This is the key move of our simple strategic plan: play ... d6 & ... e5 , creating a dream pawn chain and opening up our light-squared bishop.} 9. e4 {White's main move, trying to gain space.} e5 {We create a powerful pawn chain. Please note that with our pawns on the dark squares, they cannot be attacked by the enemy bishop. As a matter of fact, White's bishop is often getting locked in on g2 .} 10. d5 Nb8 {Don't worry about violating one of the core opening principles: 'Don't move the same piece twice.' Here, it's obvious due to the closed nature of the position that long-term plans and maneuvers take precedence over the classic tempo game.  Black wants to reroute the knight to a c5 -outpost via a6 , but first we need to secure it with ... a5 .  Let's pause and discuss this important tabiya for the Bogo opening. We have a classic King's Indian structure but with a very important twist: the dark-squared bishops are traded! I believe this favors Black long-term since often in the KID the bishop is stuck on g7 .  White is surely missing the e3 -bishop that is probably their best piece in normal KID structures. How would this change affect the plans? For one, Black is not obliged to go for the throat with a classic pawn storm on the kingside. Instead, we are flexible.  As a matter of fact, often we plan on the queenside with ... a5 , ... Na6 , and later ... c6 and even ... b5 . But Black can also go for the classic ... f5 pawn push.  White typically tries to regroup with Ne1 - d3 and push for b4 - c5 or f4 to gain more space. Also, keep in mind that White's knight on d2 is misplaced as it prefers to be on c3 . The same for White's bishop, as it's blocked by his own pawns: e4 - d5 - c4 .} {Here, White typically chooses between Ne1 and b4 .} 11. Ne1 {The knight is heading to d3 where it will support a b4 / c5 push or f4 .} a5 {The key part of our plan, Black is trying to stop ... b4 and secure the c5 -outpost.} 12. Nd3 Na6 13. a3 {White is planning natural expansion with b4 & c5 .} Bg4 {I like this move to induce f3 and also give White an opportunity to go wrong.} 14. f3 Bd7 {By inserting ... Bg4 & f3 , White's g1 - a7 diagonal becomes even softer, plus their bishop gets locked in even more.} 15. b4 {A logical follow-up to a3 . White grabs more space on the queenside.} c6 {An important idea for you to remember! Black undermines White's queenside.} 16. Qb3 {White strengthens the queenside and connects the rook. Here, Black has an instructive idea.} cxd5 17. cxd5 {A natural way to recapture. White maintains the pawn chain but gives up control over b5 .} axb4 18. axb4 Nc7 {The knight is now heading to b5 & d4 . Take a look how Black executes his plan flawlessly in the model game: Skembris-Beliavsky , 1994.} *

