the b4 -outpost for our knight.} 17. b5 Nb4 {The knight is quite strong, so White decided to trade it off.} 18. Nd3 Nxd3 19. Qxd3 {We've reached a roughly equal position. White's extra space is not an issue for us anymore as we only have two minor pieces.   The fact that our e5 -, d6 -, & c5 -pawns are on dark squares give us a better endgame, as they can never be attacked by White's bishop. Let me show you one possible plan of expansion on the kingside.} h5 ({In the game against GM Hakobyan, I played} 19... Rfb8 20. Ra3 Qd8 {in order to neutralize White on the a-file. After a long struggle and some bad endgame plans, I eventually managed to draw.}) 20. Ra3 {Let's say White tries to win the open file with Rca1 next.} (20. h4 {weakens the g4 -square, and we can play} Ng4 {.}) 20... h4 21. Rca1 Rxa3 22. Rxa3 g6 {With idea to play ... Kg7 to activate the rook via h8 .} 23. Ra7 Bc8 {We've completely stopped White's counterplay on the queenside and will play ... Kg7 and ... Rh8 with a possible attack.} *

