[White "2) Bogo: 4.Bd2 Main Line"]
[Black "Bogo 4.Bd2 Main Line - 8.Qc2 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E11"]
[PlyCount "26"]
[GameId "2176748629308140"]

1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after the German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among the world's best players in the 1920s and 1930s. He even got to challenge the World Champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice, in 1929 and 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White, I win because I am White. When I am Black, I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Bd2 ({White's main line, outnumbering} 4. Nbd2 {about 2 to 1 at the Master level.}) 4... Qe7 5. g3 {This is the main line, White wants to fianchetto the bishop for maximum pressure on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} Nc6 {This slightly unusual move prepares for the natural 6.Bg2 , with a hidden tactical idea.} 6. Nc3 ({The top choice of GMs these days, as they are aware of the tactical idea after} 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ {and now White has to take on d2 with the knight, which is a concession since the knight is more active on c3 . Please note that} 7. Qxd2 {runs into a well-known trick with} Ne4 $1 {See the 6.Bg2 chapter for a more detailed explanation.}) 6... Bxc3 {We use this opportunity to trade a few pieces and land our knight on e4 . Remember the old principle: the side with less space should seek piece trades.} 7. Bxc3 Ne4 {White has to react to a positional threat of ... Nxc3 , doubling the pawns.} 8. Qc2 {This is a more tame variation as Black can now trade queens.} Nxc3 9. Qxc3 Qb4 {The endgame is totally fine for Black. It's true that many GM games end in a draw after a few moves, but you can still play out this position against less experienced endgame players.} 10. Rc1 Qxc3+ 11. Rxc3 a5 ({A cool idea to establish dark-square control in case White plays} 11... d5 {.}) ({In our original book,} 11... d6 {was given, which is also fine.}) 12. d5 Nb4 13. a3 Na6 {Now the point of ... a5 is clear, White cannot play b4 . Black will follow up with ... d6 and ... Nc5 , taking over the dark squares.} *

