d6 ({Here, White chooses between an aggressive} 9... d5 {or a simple} 10. O-O {.}) 10. O-O {White goes for a simple development plan.} e5 {We execute the main idea of our setup: building a beautiful c7 - d6 - e5 pawn chain that points directly at White's king.} ({I believe it's slightly more accurate than the original book recommendation of} 10... Nxc3 11. Rxc3 e5 {since White has the extra option of .}) 11. Be1 {White preserves the bishop, but I think it's just too passive on e1 .} f5 {This is a promising attack for Black!} 12. d5 Nb8 13. b4 a5 {A useful move to open up the a-file.} 14. a3 ({If} 14. bxa5 {then} Nc5 {and White's extra pawn is meaningless.}) 14... axb4 15. axb4 Nd7 16. Nd2 Ndf6 {Black supports the monster knight on e4 and gets ready to attack on the kingside. It's clear that White's bishop is not a happy customer on e1 .} *

