1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after the German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among the world's best players in the 1920s and 1930s. He even got to challenge the World Champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice, in 1929 and 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White, I win because I am White. When I am Black, I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Bd2 ({White's main line, outnumbering} 4. Nbd2 {about 2 to 1 at the Master level.}) 4... Qe7 5. g3 {This is the main line, White wants to fianchetto the bishop for maximum pressure on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} Nc6 {This slightly unusual move prepares for the natural 6.Bg2 , with a hidden tactical idea.} 6. Nc3 ({The top choice of GMs these days, as they are aware of the tactical idea after} 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ {and now White has to take on d2 with the knight, which is a concession since the knight is more active on c3 . Please note that} 7. Qxd2 {runs into a well-known trick with} Ne4 $1 {See the 6.Bg2 chapter for a more detailed explanation.}) 6... Bxc3 {We use this opportunity to trade a few pieces and land our knight on e4 . Remember the old principle: the side with less space should seek piece trades.} 7. Bxc3 Ne4 {White has to react to a positional threat of ... Nxc3 , doubling the pawns.} 8. Rc1 {This is the main line.} O-O 9. Bg2 d6 ({Here, White chooses between an aggressive} 9... d5 {or a simple} 10. O-O {.}) 10. O-O {White goes for a simple development plan.} e5 {We execute the main idea of our setup: building a beautiful c7 - d6 - e5 pawn chain that points directly at White's king.} ({I believe it's slightly more accurate than the original book recommendation of} 10... Nxc3 11. Rxc3 e5 {since White has the extra option of .}) 11. d5 {This is the main move by far, White gains space and wins a tempo.} Nxc3 {We don't have to take this bishop quite yet, but since it's part of our plan, we might as well do it with a tempo.} 12. Rxc3 Nb8 {As a rule of thumb, we almost always retreat the knight to b8 in these structures. The point is that it can get to the c5 -outpost. Here are some important points to keep in mind in this tabiya structure:   1) White's temporary advantage in development is not very relevant due the closed nature of the position.   2) White's plan is to play on the queenside by breaking through with c5 .   3) Black's plan is to play on the kingside with a potential ... f5 - f4 but also to take over the queenside, thanks to the powerful c5 -outpost.   4) Black's bishop is superior due to better mobility, where's White's bishop is stuck behind the pawns and is usually a purely defensive piece.} {White's main options are c5 , Nd2 , and b4 .} 13. c5 {White's most direct approach.} a5 ({An improvement over the original book, as} 13... dxc5 {allows White a strong initiative for the pawn with} 14. Re3 $1 {Now, Black stops b4 and gets ready to play ... Na6 to put pressure on the c5 -pawn.}) 14. Nd2 Na6 {Black forces White's hand and wins the c5 -outpost.} 15. cxd6 cxd6 16. Nc4 Qd8 {Perhaps the most difficult move of this line! We protect the b6 -square and the a5 -pawn.} 17. Qb3 Nc5 18. Qb6 Na4 {Black forces a favorable endgame.} 19. Qxd6 {This was played by strong Indian GM Gupta vs GM Amin in 2012, but the exchange sacrifice is only good enough for equality.} Nxc3 20. bxc3 Qxd6 21. Nxd6 Ra6 ({Much stronger than the game continuation} 21... f6 $2) 22. Nc4 Bf5 {This is one of many moves that leads to rough equality.} 23. Nxe5 ({If} 23. e4 {then} Rc8 $1) 23... Re8 24. f4 f6 {Black wins the pawn back with ... Rxe2 next, and it's White who has to fight for equality.} *

