1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after the German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among the world's best players in the 1920s and 1930s. He even got to challenge the World Champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice, in 1929 and 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White, I win because I am White. When I am Black, I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Bd2 ({White's main line, outnumbering} 4. Nbd2 {about 2 to 1 at the Master level.}) 4... Qe7 5. g3 {This is the main line, White wants to fianchetto the bishop for maximum pressure on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} Nc6 {This slightly unusual move prepares for the natural 6.Bg2 , with a hidden tactical idea.} 6. Nc3 ({The top choice of GMs these days, as they are aware of the tactical idea after} 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ {and now White has to take on d2 with the knight, which is a concession since the knight is more active on c3 . Please note that} 7. Qxd2 {runs into a well-known trick with} Ne4 $1 {See the 6.Bg2 chapter for a more detailed explanation.}) 6... Bxc3 {We use this opportunity to trade a few pieces and land our knight on e4 . Remember the old principle: the side with less space should seek piece trades.} 7. Bxc3 Ne4 {White has to react to a positional threat of ... Nxc3 , doubling the pawns.} 8. Rc1 {This is the main line.} O-O 9. Bg2 d6 ({Here, White chooses between an aggressive} 9... d5 {or a simple} 10. O-O {.}) 10. O-O {White goes for a simple development plan.} e5 {We execute the main idea of our setup: building a beautiful c7 - d6 - e5 pawn chain that points directly at White's king.} ({I believe it's slightly more accurate than the original book recommendation of} 10... Nxc3 11. Rxc3 e5 {since White has the extra option of .}) 11. d5 {This is the main move by far, White gains space and wins a tempo.} Nxc3 {We don't have to take this bishop quite yet, but since it's part of our plan, we might as well do it with a tempo.} 12. Rxc3 Nb8 {As a rule of thumb, we almost always retreat the knight to b8 in these structures. The point is that it can get to the c5 -outpost. Here are some important points to keep in mind in this tabiya structure:   1) White's temporary advantage in development is not very relevant due the closed nature of the position.   2) White's plan is to play on the queenside by breaking through with c5 .   3) Black's plan is to play on the kingside with a potential ... f5 - f4 but also to take over the queenside, thanks to the powerful c5 -outpost.   4) Black's bishop is superior due to better mobility, where's White's bishop is stuck behind the pawns and is usually a purely defensive piece.} {White's main options are c5 , Nd2 , and b4 .} 13. Nd2 {White doesn't rush with pushing their queenside pawns and improves the knight first.} Nd7 {The knight controls c5 but can help in the attack on the kingside as well.} ({The immediate} 13... f5 {allows} 14. c5 $1) 14. b4 f5 {Both sides are executing their plans.} 15. c5 {White needs to act quickly.} e4 ({This is the simplest, but Black has other promising moves such as} 15... a5 {& Nf6 .}) 16. cxd6 cxd6 17. Rc7 Qd8 {An important intermezzo! Now, pay attention to the next few moves as Black is preparing a cool idea to kick out the rook from the 7th rank.} 18. Qc2 a5 {It's always useful to open up the a-file for our rook.} 19. a3 axb4 20. axb4 Nf6 {This hits d5 -pawn and even stronger than 20... Ra2 given in the original book.} 21. Qc3 Ne8 {Black completes the plan and kicks out the rook!} ({Not} 21... Nxd5 $4 22. Qxg7# {oops!}) 22. Rc4 Bd7 {I think Black already has a small edge. We've managed to lock up White's bishop on g2 and kick out the rook. Now, White is facing a serious problem with ... Bb5 next.} *

