d6 ({Here, White chooses between an aggressive} 9... d5 {or a simple} 10. O-O {.}) 10. O-O {White goes for a simple development plan.} e5 {We execute the main idea of our setup: building a beautiful c7 - d6 - e5 pawn chain that points directly at White's king.} ({I believe it's slightly more accurate than the original book recommendation of} 10... Nxc3 11. Rxc3 e5 {since White has the extra option of .}) 11. d5 {This is the main move by far, White gains space and wins a tempo.} Nxc3 {We don't have to take this bishop quite yet, but since it's part of our plan, we might as well do it with a tempo.} 12. Rxc3 Nb8 {As a rule of thumb, we almost always retreat the knight to b8 in these structures. The point is that it can get to the c5 -outpost. Here are some important points to keep in mind in this tabiya structure:   1) White's temporary advantage in development is not very relevant due the closed nature of the position.   2) White's plan is to play on the queenside by breaking through with c5 .   3) Black's plan is to play on the kingside with a potential ... f5 - f4 but also to take over the queenside, thanks to the powerful c5 -outpost.   4) Black's bishop is superior due to better mobility, where's White's bishop is stuck behind the pawns and is usually a purely defensive piece.} {White's main options are c5 , Nd2 , and b4 .} 13. b4 {This is White's most popular move, with an obvious idea to play for c5 next.} Nd7 ({I like this a bit more than the originally recommended} 13... Bg4 {, but both moves are playable.}) 14. c5 {A promising pawn sacrifice to open up the game, but we don't take the bait!} a5 {Simple and strong, we chip away at White's queenside with easy game. Let's take a look at possible options.} ({a3 ( cxd6 cxd6 Ra3 b6 Qd2 Nf6 bxa5 Qd8= Black will win the a5 -pawn with a roughly even game.) axb4 axb4} 14... e4 $1 15. Nd2 ({(} 15. Nd4 dxc5 16. bxc5 Nxc5 17. Qc2 b6 {and White doesn't have full compensation for the pawn.)}) 15... Nf6 16. Qb3 Bf5 17. Rfc1 h5 $1 {A typical idea in these positions to expand with h4 next.} 18. cxd6 cxd6 19. Rc7 Qe5 20. Rxb7 {Ra1 Rbc7 Rfa8∓ Black has a big edge as the d5 -pawn will fall next.}) *

