d6 ({Here, White chooses between an aggressive} 9... d5 {or a simple} 10. O-O {.}) 10. O-O {White goes for a simple development plan.} e5 {We execute the main idea of our setup: building a beautiful c7 - d6 - e5 pawn chain that points directly at White's king.} ({I believe it's slightly more accurate than the original book recommendation of} 10... Nxc3 11. Rxc3 e5 {since White has the extra option of .}) 11. d5 {This is the main move by far, White gains space and wins a tempo.} Nxc3 {We don't have to take this bishop quite yet, but since it's part of our plan, we might as well do it with a tempo.} 12. Rxc3 Nb8 {As a rule of thumb, we almost always retreat the knight to b8 in these structures. The point is that it can get to the c5 -outpost. Here are some important points to keep in mind in this tabiya structure:   1) White's temporary advantage in development is not very relevant due the closed nature of the position.   2) White's plan is to play on the queenside by breaking through with c5 .   3) Black's plan is to play on the kingside with a potential ... f5 - f4 but also to take over the queenside, thanks to the powerful c5 -outpost.   4) Black's bishop is superior due to better mobility, where's White's bishop is stuck behind the pawns and is usually a purely defensive piece.} {White's main options are c5 , Nd2 , and b4 .} 13. b4 {This is White's most popular move, with an obvious idea to play for c5 next.} Nd7 ({I like this a bit more than the originally recommended} 13... Bg4 {, but both moves are playable.}) 14. Qc2 {This is the most common move in DB. White prepares c5 . 14. Nd2 this transposes to 13.Nd2 .} a5 {A standard idea to open up the a-file.} 15. Ra3 {White pins our a-pawn.} b6 {We protect the a5 -pawn.} 16. Nd2 f5 {Now that the queenside is secure, we expand on the kingside.} 17. Nb3 a4 {The a-pawn will be sacrificed eventually but White will lose quite some time as a result, giving us a big attack!} 18. Nd2 e4 {I believe Black gets excellent compensation for the pawn.} 19. Rxa4 Rxa4 20. Qxa4 e3 {Now, White's in big trouble!} 21. Nf3 exf2+ 22. Rxf2 Nf6 {White has to deal with too many threats such as ... Ng4 and ... Qe3 . The engine already prefers Black, even though we are a pawn down!} *

