1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after the German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among the world's best players in the 1920s and 1930s. He even got to challenge the World Champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice, in 1929 and 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White, I win because I am White. When I am Black, I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Bd2 ({White's main line, outnumbering} 4. Nbd2 {about 2 to 1 at the Master level.}) 4... Qe7 5. g3 {This is the main line, White wants to fianchetto the bishop for maximum pressure on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} Nc6 {This slightly unusual move prepares for the natural 6.Bg2 , with a hidden tactical idea.} 6. Nc3 ({The top choice of GMs these days, as they are aware of the tactical idea after} 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ {and now White has to take on d2 with the knight, which is a concession since the knight is more active on c3 . Please note that} 7. Qxd2 {runs into a well-known trick with} Ne4 $1 {See the 6.Bg2 chapter for a more detailed explanation.}) 6... Bxc3 {We use this opportunity to trade a few pieces and land our knight on e4 . Remember the old principle: the side with less space should seek piece trades.} 7. Bxc3 Ne4 {White has to react to a positional threat of ... Nxc3 , doubling the pawns.} 8. Rc1 {This is the main line.} O-O 9. Bg2 d6 ({Here, White chooses between an aggressive} 9... d5 {or a simple} 10. O-O {.}) 10. d5 Nb8 {These days I like this over the original recommendation of ... Nxc3 since I believe the knight on e4 limits White's options.} (10... Nxc3 11. Rxc3 Nb8 12. dxe6 fxe6 {allows} 13. Re3 $1 {which is a bit annoying, for example:} e5 14. O-O Nc6 15. Nd4 $1 {with an edge for White.}) 11. dxe6 fxe6 12. O-O a5 {A prophylactic move, stopping White's natural b4 expansion, while gaining some space & securing the c5 -outpost. Here, White has several plans:} {1) Preserve the bishop pair with Be1 or Bd4 2) Play for central domination with Nd4 3) The simple b3 with an idea of Bb2 .} 13. Nd4 {A standard idea to play for central domination and open up g2 -bishop.} Nxc3 {At this point we should grab the bishop.} 14. Rxc3 e5 {Black sets up the dream pawn chain with a tempo and opens up our bishop.} 15. Nc2 {White is ready to reroute the knight to e3 & d5 .} Nc6 16. Ne3 Nd4 {Black's knight is also hopping to a central outpost.} 17. Nd5 Qd8 18. e3 Ne6 {White was able to kick our knight back, but as a result the d5 -knight is almost trapped in the middle of the board.} 19. Ra3 {Probably White's best try to put pressure on the a-file.} (19. Rc2 {is a bit tame, after} Nc5 20. b3 Bf5 21. Rd2 Qd7 {with a roughly even game.}) 19... Rb8 {I like this sneaky rook move! We get out of the pin on the a-file and prepare a little trap.} (19... c6 $6 20. Nc3 Nc5 $2 {allows} 21. b4 $1) 20. Qd2 (20. Rxa5 $2 c6 $1 {oops!}) 20... b6 {Black achieves a rock-solid pawn formation on dark squares, denying White any play on the queenside. Yes, White has a strong knight on d5 , but so what? There's no obvious plan. Black will finish development with ... Bb7 with a complex game to follow.} *

