d6 ({Here, White chooses between an aggressive} 9... d5 {or a simple} 10. O-O {.}) 10. d5 Nb8 {These days I like this over the original recommendation of ... Nxc3 since I believe the knight on e4 limits White's options.} (10... Nxc3 11. Rxc3 Nb8 12. dxe6 fxe6 {allows} 13. Re3 $1 {which is a bit annoying, for example:} e5 14. O-O Nc6 15. Nd4 $1 {with an edge for White.}) 11. dxe6 fxe6 12. O-O a5 {A prophylactic move, stopping White's natural b4 expansion, while gaining some space & securing the c5 -outpost. Here, White has several plans:} {1) Preserve the bishop pair with Be1 or Bd4 2) Play for central domination with Nd4 3) The simple b3 with an idea of Bb2 .} 13. Bd4 {Another way to preserve the bishop pair, but again White loses some time.} Nc6 {A nice tempo on the bishop.} 14. Be3 Bd7 {Black completes development.} 15. Nd4 Nf6 {Not an obvious move, but f6 is the best square for the knight.} (15... Nc5 $2 16. Nxc6 Bxc6 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Bxc5 dxc5 {and Black's pawn structure is in ruins...}) 16. Nb5 {I think this is White's best option, but Black is rock solid.} Be8 {We protect the c7 -pawn and open better prospects for our bishop. White's bishop pair may give him a slight edge, but I don't see a clear plan of improvement as c5 is always met with ... d5 ! Let me show you a possible plan for Black.} 17. h3 Nd8 {A useful idea to remember! Black is getting ready to trade light-squared bishops with ... Bc6 .} 18. Qd2 Bc6 {With the light-squared bishops traded, White will no longer have the bishop pair advantage, plus their king would be weakened. Please note that if White trades on c6 , remember to take back with the pawn!} 19. Bxc6 bxc6 {Now White's knight would have to retreat and Black's massive pawn phalanx will eventually take over the center.} *

