1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after the German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among the world's best players in the 1920s and 1930s. He even got to challenge the World Champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice, in 1929 and 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White, I win because I am White. When I am Black, I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Bd2 ({White's main line, outnumbering} 4. Nbd2 {about 2 to 1 at the Master level.}) 4... Qe7 5. g3 {This is the main line, White wants to fianchetto the bishop for maximum pressure on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} Nc6 {This slightly unusual move prepares for the natural 6.Bg2 , with a hidden tactical idea.} 6. Nc3 ({The top choice of GMs these days, as they are aware of the tactical idea after} 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ {and now White has to take on d2 with the knight, which is a concession since the knight is more active on c3 . Please note that} 7. Qxd2 {runs into a well-known trick with} Ne4 $1 {See the 6.Bg2 chapter for a more detailed explanation.}) 6... Bxc3 {We use this opportunity to trade a few pieces and land our knight on e4 . Remember the old principle: the side with less space should seek piece trades.} 7. Bxc3 Ne4 {White has to react to a positional threat of ... Nxc3 , doubling the pawns.} 8. Rc1 {This is the main line.} O-O 9. Bg2 d6 ({Here, White chooses between an aggressive} 9... d5 {or a simple} 10. O-O {.}) 10. d5 Nb8 {These days I like this over the original recommendation of ... Nxc3 since I believe the knight on e4 limits White's options.} (10... Nxc3 11. Rxc3 Nb8 12. dxe6 fxe6 {allows} 13. Re3 $1 {which is a bit annoying, for example:} e5 14. O-O Nc6 15. Nd4 $1 {with an edge for White.}) 11. dxe6 fxe6 12. O-O a5 {A prophylactic move, stopping White's natural b4 expansion, while gaining some space & securing the c5 -outpost. Here, White has several plans:} {1) Preserve the bishop pair with Be1 or Bd4 2) Play for central domination with Nd4 3) The simple b3 with an idea of Bb2 .} 13. b3 {White is ready to play Bb2 next.} Nxc3 {Of course, we trade on c3 before White has a chance to play Bb2 .} 14. Rxc3 Nd7 {At first, the engine seems to like White as Black's pieces are still somewhat cramped. However, the more I analyzed this position, the more I realized White has no plan. Black will slowly untangle their pieces and get a decent game. Let's take a look at possible scenarios.} 15. Qd2 e5 16. Ng5 {This is probably White's best try and sets up a nasty trap.} Kh8 ({Not} 16... h6 $2 {due to} 17. Ne6 $1) 17. Be4 {A natural move to put pressure on h7 -pawn.} h6 {Now it's our turn to set up a trap.} 18. Nh7 {White's knight falls into our mousetrap, and it won't get out!.} (18. Nf3 {is best, with rough equality after} Nc5 19. Bb1 Bf5 20. Bxf5 Rxf5 21. Nh4 Rf6 {.}) 18... Rf7 19. Bg6 {It looks like White trapped our rook...} Nc5 {The key move – we can easily give up the exchange, as the h7 -knight is trapped.} 20. f4 Bh3 {This is even stronger than ... Bf5 right away.} 21. Rf2 Bf5 22. Bxf7 Qxf7 {... Ne4 will win material, and after ... Kxh7 , White is lost.} *

