{Conclusion: In the 4.Bd2 Bogo with 6.Nc3 , remember to simplify the position with Bxc3 & ... Ne4 . If White plays Qc2 then further simplification with ... Nxc3 and ... Qb4 ! is in order.   Remember that the endgame is totally fine for Black and you can even play it for a win as I showed you in the model game. The main line 8. Rc1 leads to a more complex fight, where White has two main choices: 10.O-O or 10.d5 . If White plays for simple development with O-O , we answer with e5! followed by ... Nxc3 & ... Nb8 . Black sets up the key c7 - d6 - e5 pawn chain pointing at White's king with a promising attack. If White goes for a central push with d5 and dxe6 , the game opens up more and requires some accuracy from Black such as a5! The positions are more nuanced as there's no forcing play, but once you learn all the ideas you should feel comfortable with Black's rock-solid pawn structure.} 1. Z0 *

