1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow, positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after the German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among the world's best players in the 1920s and 1930s. He even got to challenge the World Champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice, in 1929 and 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White, I win because I am White. When I am Black, I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Nbd2 ({This system is played less often than} 4. Bd2 {, but it's still popular at Grandmaster level due to the long-term positional factor: White's aim is to get the bishop pair after 5. a3 .   The drawback is that it gives Black time to choose among several setups.}) 4... b6 {I recommend the most solid setup. Yes, we will part with the bishop pair after ... Bxd2 +, but in return our light-squared bishop will reign supreme on the long diagonal.} 5. g3 {This is a harmless plan since our bishop on b7 will easily neutralize White's counterpart on g2 .} Bb7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O a5 {I like this waiting move, anticipating a3 from White.} 8. Qc2 {A logical move, White wants to play Rd1 next.} c5 {A cool idea and a rare move! We play against White's center.} 9. Rd1 {A logical follow up to Qc2 , but this allows favorable trades for us.} cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 {The trade of light-squared bishops is usually favorable for us as White's king is weakened.} Qc8 {The queen belongs on c8 where she would put lots of pressure on the long diagonal. Black is at least equal here.} *

