1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow, positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after the German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among the world's best players in the 1920s and 1930s. He even got to challenge the World Champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice, in 1929 and 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White, I win because I am White. When I am Black, I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Nbd2 ({This system is played less often than} 4. Bd2 {, but it's still popular at Grandmaster level due to the long-term positional factor: White's aim is to get the bishop pair after 5. a3 .   The drawback is that it gives Black time to choose among several setups.}) 4... b6 {I recommend the most solid setup. Yes, we will part with the bishop pair after ... Bxd2 +, but in return our light-squared bishop will reign supreme on the long diagonal.} 5. e3 {This is a harmless plan, mostly played by players to avoid theory. Yet, you should know a good setup for Black.} Bb7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O d5 {We normally don't play the ... d5 push in this repertoire, but here it's totally justified as White's bishop is stuck on c1 .} 8. a3 Be7 {I think this is more accurate than ... Bd6 .} 9. b4 {White tries to use the extra tempo with a3 , but Black is fine.} c5 {This is an easy equalizer as our pieces are well-placed. The game is still quite complex.} 10. bxc5 bxc5 11. Rb1 Ba6 {A nice pin on the c4 -pawn.} 12. Ne5 {White tries to take advantage of the e5 -outpost in order to meet ... Nbd7 with Nc6 !} Qc8 {A strong idea. We protect our a6 -bishop and get ready to play ... Nbd7 next. The position is about even.} *

