1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow, positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after the German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among the world's best players in the 1920s and 1930s. He even got to challenge the World Champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice, in 1929 and 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White, I win because I am White. When I am Black, I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Nbd2 ({This system is played less often than} 4. Bd2 {, but it's still popular at Grandmaster level due to the long-term positional factor: White's aim is to get the bishop pair after 5. a3 .   The drawback is that it gives Black time to choose among several setups.}) 4... b6 {I recommend the most solid setup. Yes, we will part with the bishop pair after ... Bxd2 +, but in return our light-squared bishop will reign supreme on the long diagonal.} 5. a3 {This is the most popular move, White aims to get the bishop pair right away.} Bxd2+ ({Here White can recapture in 3 different ways, but Qxd2 is almost 5 times more popular than Nxd2 or} 5... Bxd2+ {.}) 6. Bxd2 Bb7 ({I like this even better than} 6... h6 {, which I originally recommended, since I will show you that Black is never afraid of Bg5 here.}) 7. Bg5 {White tries to take advantage of Black's missing DSB and pins the knight, but the pin is easily broken!} h6 8. Bh4 d6 ({We can also start with the immediate} 8... g5 {, but ... d6 is still an important move to deny White the e5 -square.}) 9. e3 g5 {Don't be afraid to go after White's bishop with this kingside expansion.} 10. Bg3 Ne4 {This is the key idea. Now it's hard for White to play h4 as we always have ... Nxg3 .} 11. Bd3 ({After} 11. h4 $6 Nxg3 12. fxg3 {, Black has a superior pawn structure.}) 11... h5 {The most aggressive. Now we have a big threat of ... h4 , trapping White's DSB.} 12. h4 g4 13. Ng5 {This is White's best try.} Nxg5 14. hxg5 Qxg5 15. Bh4 Qg7 {White has minimal compensation for the pawn, but with ... Nd7 next, we have nothing to fear.} *

