 can also start with the immediate} 8... g5 {, but ... d6 is still an important move to deny White the e5 -square.}) 9. e3 g5 {Don't be afraid to go after White's bishop with this kingside expansion.} 10. Bg3 Ne4 {This is the key idea. Now it's hard for White to play h4 as we always have ... Nxg3 .} 11. Bd3 ({After} 11. h4 $6 Nxg3 12. fxg3 {, Black has a superior pawn structure.}) 11... h5 {The most aggressive. Now we have a big threat of ... h4 , trapping White's DSB.} 12. d5 {Perhaps this White's best attempt at an advantage, but as long as we don't take the pawn on d5 , Black is fine.} Nxg3 13. hxg3 Qf6 {Black's queen is well-placed here, we plan to go ... Nd7 and ... O-O-O next.} 14. Qc2 Nd7 15. O-O-O O-O-O {We've reached a complex position, but I prefer Black here. Sooner or later, the central tension will be resolved, and our bishop will get activated. I don't see any plans for White, while Black will play ... Nc5 next.} *

