repare Bh2 .} Qe7 {I like to be flexible here, as we can also castle queenside. In the meantime, we prepare ... e5 .} 10. Be2 e5 {A typical idea in many Bogo positions.} 11. Bh2 exd4 {A concrete solution.} 12. Nxd4 {This is the best move, but not an obvious one, as White gives up the g2 -pawn.} Bxg2 13. Rg1 Be4 ({Don't be greedy here; it's more important to control the long diagonal.} 13... Bxh3 $2 {allows} 14. Bf3 $1) 14. Rxg7 {White gets the pawn back, but the rook is in danger of being trapped.} O-O-O {Black had several good moves, but this is the easiest.} ({Please note that} 14... Bg6 {doesn't quite trap the rook as White has} 15. Bf4 {with the idea of Bh6 .}) 15. Qa4 Rhg8 {We trade rooks and set up a small trap.} 16. Rxg8 Rxg8 17. Nc6 {This is White's only move to not be worse.} Bxc6 18. Qxc6 Qe4 {We force the endgame.} 19. Qxe4 Nxe4 {The endgame is roughly even. White's bishop on h2 is quite passive but their LSB is strong. We will play ... Kd8 - e7 next, ... f5 if allowed, and try to put pressure on the g-file.} *

