1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow, positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after the German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among the world's best players in the 1920s and 1930s. He even got to challenge the World Champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice, in 1929 and 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White, I win because I am White. When I am Black, I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Nbd2 ({This system is played less often than} 4. Bd2 {, but it's still popular at Grandmaster level due to the long-term positional factor: White's aim is to get the bishop pair after 5. a3 .   The drawback is that it gives Black time to choose among several setups.}) 4... b6 {I recommend the most solid setup. Yes, we will part with the bishop pair after ... Bxd2 +, but in return our light-squared bishop will reign supreme on the long diagonal.} 5. a3 {This is the most popular move, White aims to get the bishop pair right away.} Bxd2+ ({Here White can recapture in 3 different ways, but Qxd2 is almost 5 times more popular than Nxd2 or} 5... Bxd2+ {.}) 6. Nxd2 {This is the least popular recapture, but it was recently played by the newly crowned World Champion, Gukesh D, so we have to take it seriously!} Bb7 {We develop the bishop while stopping White's center grab with e4 .} 7. e3 O-O 8. b3 {White is satisfied with having the bishop pair and proceeds to develop with Bb2 next. This is our opportunity to take advantage of White's slow development and strike in the center.} d5 {Please note that this is a different approach than ... d6 , which is recommended vs 6.Qd2 . I believe that opening up the game with ... d5 will give us quick counterplay, as White is significantly underdeveloped.} 9. cxd5 {This is the move chosen by Gukesh at the recent 2024 European Club Championship.} Qxd5 {This is the best recapture and is what GM Petursson did. The queen is very active on d5 and cannot be attacked with Bc4? due to Qxg2 .} 10. Bb2 Nbd7 11. f3 {White is getting ready to strike with 12.e4 next.} c5 {Just in time! We cannot allow White a strong center supported by the bishop pair.} 12. e4 Qg5 {We target White's underdeveloped kingside.} 13. Qe2 Rfd8 ({This logical novelty of bringing the rook into the game is even stronger than} 13... cxd4 {.}) 14. Qf2 Rac8 {Black's pieces are fully mobilized while White is still lacking development and his king is stuck in the center.} 15. Bd3 Nh5 {The knight is heading to f4 .} 16. g3 cxd4 17. Bxd4 f5 {A timely way to undermine White's center. Now White is in serious trouble.} 18. exf5 Ne5 {We use the tactics on the d-file.} 19. Bxe5 Rxd3 {Believe it or not, but White is already totally lost. The engine gives us a -5 advantage! White can't castle without losing the knight. Basically, they're playing down two rooks!} *

