1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow, positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after the German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among the world's best players in the 1920s and 1930s. He even got to challenge the World Champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice, in 1929 and 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White, I win because I am White. When I am Black, I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Nbd2 ({This system is played less often than} 4. Bd2 {, but it's still popular at Grandmaster level due to the long-term positional factor: White's aim is to get the bishop pair after 5. a3 .   The drawback is that it gives Black time to choose among several setups.}) 4... b6 {I recommend the most solid setup. Yes, we will part with the bishop pair after ... Bxd2 +, but in return our light-squared bishop will reign supreme on the long diagonal.} 5. a3 {This is the most popular move, White aims to get the bishop pair right away.} Bxd2+ ({Here White can recapture in 3 different ways, but Qxd2 is almost 5 times more popular than Nxd2 or} 5... Bxd2+ {.}) 6. Qxd2 {This is the most common recapture. White wants to play b3 / b4 and fianchetto the bishop on b2 . They will develop the kingside with e3 , Be2 , and O-O , trying to exploit the bishop pair advantage in the middlegame.} Bb7 {We develop our bishop to the long diagonal.} 7. e3 d6 {Move orders matter! It's important not to play ... O-O or ... a5 early, as I will later show you a cool idea where we can castle queenside under the right circumstances.   While it's tempting to double White's pawns by taking of f3 , it's not a good idea, since White will have the open g-file, two bishops and a mobile pawn center.} 8. b4 {White's most ambitious option. Make sure to meet it with ... a5 ! right away!} a5 {We offer White a choice to push the pawn to b5 or protect the rook with Bb2 .} 9. Bb2 {This is White's best try, but I have a cool line I'd like to show you.} axb4 {We first get ready to swap a pair of rooks.} 10. axb4 Rxa1+ 11. Bxa1 Bxf3 {Now we double White's pawns.} 12. gxf3 O-O {At first, I was a bit scared to give White the g-file in front of our king, especially in combination with the a1 -bishop. However, further analysis showed that only Black can be better in this middlegame. Let me show you why.} 13. Rg1 Nbd7 14. Bd3 (14. d5 {is met with} e5 {, with similar play as the main line.}) 14... Nh5 {Our knight on h5 has two very important functions: it protects g7 and opens up the way for our queen.} 15. d5 e5 {Simple chess. With our last move, we locked a1 -bishop out of the game and now Black is taking over. The engine already claims an edge for us, but let me show you how easily White gets into trouble.} 16. Qc2 g6 17. Ke2 {White's king is actually less safe than ours!} Qh4 {Our major pieces enter the fight and White's h2 -pawn is lost. We will activate the rook via a8 next.} *

