{It's clear that White will have to make concessions now with Rg1 or Bf1 to protect this vital pawn. We will castle next and will attack the enemy king.} 1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow, positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after the German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among the world's best players in the 1920s and 1930s. He even got to challenge the World Champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice, in 1929 and 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White, I win because I am White. When I am Black, I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Nbd2 ({This system is played less often than} 4. Bd2 {, but it's still popular at Grandmaster level due to the long-term positional factor: White's aim is to get the bishop pair after 5. a3 .   The drawback is that it gives Black time to choose among several setups.}) 4... b6 {I recommend the most solid setup. Yes, we will part with the bishop pair after ... Bxd2 +, but in return our light-squared bishop will reign supreme on the long diagonal.} 5. a3 {This is the most popular move, White aims to get the bishop pair right away.} Bxd2+ ({Here White can recapture in 3 different ways, but Qxd2 is almost 5 times more popular than Nxd2 or} 5... Bxd2+ {.}) 6. Qxd2 {This is the most common recapture. White wants to play b3 / b4 and fianchetto the bishop on b2 . They will develop the kingside with e3 , Be2 , and O-O , trying to exploit the bishop pair advantage in the middlegame.} Bb7 {We develop our bishop to the long diagonal.} 7. e3 d6 {Move orders matter! It's important not to play ... O-O or ... a5 early, as I will later show you a cool idea where we can castle queenside under the right circumstances.   While it's tempting to double White's pawns by taking of f3 , it's not a good idea, since White will have the open g-file, two bishops and a mobile pawn center.} 8. Be2 {White's most logical move. They prepare short castle and later plan to develop the c1 bishop on b2 .} (8. b3 {would transpose after} Nbd7 9. Bb2 a5 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O {.}) 8... Nbd7 ({Please note that we delay castling as we still want to give White a chance to play b4} 8... a5 $1 {b5?! and now we can play ... Qe7 and ... O-O-O with a big kingside attack as shown in the  8.b4 a5 9.b5  line.}) 9. b4 a5 ({We are hoping to see} 9... b5 {from White.}) 10. Bb2 {The only independent option.} axb4 {We swap a pair of rooks to expose White's loose bishop on a1 in a future tactic.} 11. axb4 Rxa1+ 12. Bxa1 {Now it's important to notice that White hasn't castled yet and we have some cool tactics ahead to expose the weak back rank.} Ne4 {First, we activate the knight with a tempo.} 13. Qc2 Ng5 {This is a powerful novelty that has not been played yet at the GM level. White is having problems on the long diagonal.} 14. Nxg5 Qxg5 *

