1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nf3 {This is a slow, positional approach by White, avoiding the complex battles of the Nimzo-Indian. However, our next move is the same!} Bb4+ {This is the Bogo-Indian or Bogo, named after the German-Russian chess player Efim Bogoljubow, who was among the world's best players in the 1920s and 1930s. He even got to challenge the World Champion Alexander Alekhine for the title but lost twice, in 1929 and 1934.} {There's a famous saying by Bogoljubow, where he doesn't hide supreme self-confidence: When I am White, I win because I am White. When I am Black, I win because I am Bogoljubow .  Here, White has a choice between two main moves: Bd2 , the more popular main line, or Nbd2 with the idea to play a3 later and gain the bishop pair. Please note that Nc3 will just transpose back into the Nimzo.} 4. Nbd2 ({This system is played less often than} 4. Bd2 {, but it's still popular at Grandmaster level due to the long-term positional factor: White's aim is to get the bishop pair after 5. a3 .   The drawback is that it gives Black time to choose among several setups.}) 4... b6 {I recommend the most solid setup. Yes, we will part with the bishop pair after ... Bxd2 +, but in return our light-squared bishop will reign supreme on the long diagonal.} 5. a3 {This is the most popular move, White aims to get the bishop pair right away.} Bxd2+ ({Here White can recapture in 3 different ways, but Qxd2 is almost 5 times more popular than Nxd2 or} 5... Bxd2+ {.}) 6. Qxd2 {This is the most common recapture. White wants to play b3 / b4 and fianchetto the bishop on b2 . They will develop the kingside with e3 , Be2 , and O-O , trying to exploit the bishop pair advantage in the middlegame.} Bb7 {We develop our bishop to the long diagonal.} 7. e3 d6 {Move orders matter! It's important not to play ... O-O or ... a5 early, as I will later show you a cool idea where we can castle queenside under the right circumstances.   While it's tempting to double White's pawns by taking of f3 , it's not a good idea, since White will have the open g-file, two bishops and a mobile pawn center.} 8. Be2 {White's most logical move. They prepare short castle and later plan to develop the c1 bishop on b2 .} (8. b3 {would transpose after} Nbd7 9. Bb2 a5 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O {.}) 8... Nbd7 ({Please note that we delay castling as we still want to give White a chance to play b4} 8... a5 $1 {b5?! and now we can play ... Qe7 and ... O-O-O with a big kingside attack as shown in the  8.b4 a5 9.b5  line.}) 9. O-O {White's most logical move. They finish kingside development first and want to play b3 / b4 next.} a5 {I like this logical expansion to stop b4 .} ({We can still try to trick White with} 9... Qe7 $5 10. b4 a5 {, hoping for} 11. b5 {and then we can castle long. But the problem is that White has a simple move: Bb2! Now, all of the ideas with ... axb4 and ... Rxa1 lose their merit since White can recapture with Rxa1 .}) 10. b3 {A natural move to stop ... a4 and prepare fianchetto with Bb2 .} O-O {We finish development first and get ready to start the attack with ... Ne4 and ... f5 next.} 11. Bb2 Ne4 ({I will teach you the most aggressive plan, even though Black has many solid moves such as} 11... Qe7 {and} 12. c5 {, but these lead to more complex positional fights.}) 12. Qc2 {This is the standard retreat that you will see in almost all your games. Let's pause and try to understand this position.  White has no pawn weaknesses, has a bit more space due to the d4 - & c4 -pawns, but of course, their major asset is the bishop pair. Therefore, long-term maneuvering favors our opponent.   You may wonder, what do we have in return? The answer is: attack! We can play for an ... f5 expansion, bring the rook to f6 if allowed, and try to connect with our b7 -bishop to checkmate White's king. Of course, White has plenty of defensive resources, but remember, it's always easier to attack than to defend!} f5 {We launch our attack!} 13. Rfd1 {This is a logical build-up move. White wants to prepare d5 and reserves c1 for the other rook.} Rf6 {We don't mind d5 and transfer our rook to h6 .} 14. d5 Rh6 15. dxe6 Ndc5 {Black is ready to win back the pawn with ... Nxe6 .} ({Or} 15... Nf8 {with the same idea.}) 16. Rd5 {This engine idea is quite good, but only if we take the rook.} Nxe6 17. Rxf5 Qe8 {We've reached a very complex position. I believe that it's much easier to attack than to defend, so I would take Black. Our plan is to get the queen involved in the attack with ... Qg6 next.} *

