ct with our b7 -bishop to checkmate White's king. Of course, White has plenty of defensive resources, but remember, it's always easier to attack than to defend!} f5 {We launch our attack!} 13. d5 {This pawn sacrifice is considered best to slow down our attack and open up the b2 -bishop.} e5 {An instructive moment! We care more about keeping the center locked rather than winning a pawn.} ({After} 13... exd5 $2 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. Rad1 {, White is much better as the knight is coming to d4 next, with many threats.}) 14. Nd2 {This is White's most common move, the idea is simple: try to trade off our strong knight on e4 .} Nxd2 15. Qxd2 Qe7 ({Black has to be patient about building up the attack since} 15... Rf6 {runs into} 16. f4 $1 {Here, we prepare the useful ... c6 to open up our bishop. The position is quite complex and White has several plans: launch the queenside expansion with b4 or slow us down with f3 or f4 .}) 16. f4 {White is slowing down our attack and opens up the c1 -bishop.} exf4 {We are first to take over the e-file.} ({If you want to avoid the endgame,} 16... Nc5 $5 {is a less forcing option worth investigating.}) 17. exf4 Rae8 18. Rae1 Qe3+ {Black forces an equal endgame.} 19. Qxe3 Rxe3 {Now, it's White who has to be careful as the b3 -pawn is weak. Best case scenario is both rooks will be traded, and the endgame is drawn since Black has no weaknesses.} *

