3 d6 {Move orders matter! It's important not to play ... O-O or ... a5 early, as I will later show you a cool idea where we can castle queenside under the right circumstances.   While it's tempting to double White's pawns by taking of f3 , it's not a good idea, since White will have the open g-file, two bishops and a mobile pawn center.} 8. Be2 {White's most logical move. They prepare short castle and later plan to develop the c1 bishop on b2 .} (8. b3 {would transpose after} Nbd7 9. Bb2 a5 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O {.}) 8... Nbd7 ({Please note that we delay castling as we still want to give White a chance to play b4} 8... a5 $1 {b5?! and now we can play ... Qe7 and ... O-O-O with a big kingside attack as shown in the  8.b4 a5 9.b5  line.}) 9. O-O {White's most logical move. They finish kingside development first and want to play b3 / b4 next.} a5 {I like this logical expansion to stop b4 .} ({We can still try to trick White with} 9... Qe7 $5 10. b4 a5 {, hoping for} 11. b5 {and then we can castle long. But the problem is that White has a simple move: Bb2! Now, all of the ideas with ... axb4 and ... Rxa1 lose their merit since White can recapture with Rxa1 .}) 10. b3 {A natural move to stop ... a4 and prepare fianchetto with Bb2 .} O-O {We finish development first and get ready to start the attack with ... Ne4 and ... f5 next.} 11. Bb2 Ne4 ({I will teach you the most aggressive plan, even though Black has many solid moves such as} 11... Qe7 {and} 12. c5 {, but these lead to more complex positional fights.}) 12. Qc2 {This is the standard retreat that you will see in almost all your games. Let's pause and try to understand this position.  White has no pawn weaknesses, has a bit more space due to the d4 - & c4 -pawns, but of course, their major asset is the bishop pair. Therefore, long-term maneuvering favors our opponent.   You may wonder, what do we have in return? The answer is: attack! We can play for an ... f5 expansion, bring the rook to f6 if allowed, and try to connect with our b7 -bishop to checkmate White's king. Of course, White has plenty of defensive resources, but remember, it's always easier to attack than to defend!} f5 {We launch our attack!} 13. d5 {This pawn sacrifice is considered best to slow down our attack and open up the b2 -bishop.} e5 {An instructive moment! We care more about keeping the center locked rather than winning a pawn.} ({After} 13... exd5 $2 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. Rad1 {, White is much better as the knight is coming to d4 next, with many threats.}) 14. Nd2 {This is White's most common move, the idea is simple: try to trade off our strong knight on e4 .} Nxd2 15. Qxd2 Qe7 ({Black has to be patient about building up the attack since} 15... Rf6 {runs into} 16. f4 $1 {Here, we prepare the useful ... c6 to open up our bishop. The position is quite complex and White has several plans: launch the queenside expansion with b4 or slow us down with f3 or f4 .}) 16. f3 {White anticipates the opening of the long diagonal after ... c6 and tries to blunt our bishop.} c6 {Good timing, we try to bring our bishop into the game.} 17. dxc6 Bxc6 18. Rfd1 {White hits our backwards d-pawn.} Rf6 {The rook is well-placed here. It defends d6 and gets ready to attack on h6 or g6 .} 19. b4 Raf8 {We abandon the a-pawn and put all our money on the attack.} 20. bxa5 {Too greedy.} Rh6 21. axb6 Qh4 {This attack is quite hard to repel, for example:} 22. h3 Rg6 23. Kh1 Rff6 {Getting ready to play ... Rg3 and double our rooks.} 24. Bf1 Rg3 25. a4 Rfg6 {Now, White is losing by force.} 26. a5 Rxh3+ ({Of course} 26... Bxf3 {and Rxf3 also lead to mate.}) 27. gxh3 Bxf3+ {With a forced mate.} *

