[GameId "2176748629439264"]

1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qc2 {This is the Classical Variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after the typical 5.a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5.e4 . However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves.  Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our DSB. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas!} 5. e3 ({This is the only other serious alternative to} 5. Nf3 {but it's a bit passive as White locks the bishop on c1 .}) 5... O-O {A logical move, Black is first to castle while White still has to make 3 moves to castle kingside.} 6. Bd3 {A logical move, White develops the bishop first and will follow with Nge2 & O-O .} e5 {Since White never played Nf3 , we can play ... e5 in one go!} 7. d5 e4 {A nice counterpunch! We sacrifice a pawn for activity.} ({After Be2 Ne5 Bd2} 7... Bxc3+ {Bxc3 d6 Black's big central control and White's poor knight on g1 give us a comfortable position. We will develop with ... Bf5 next.}) 8. Bxe4 Nxe4 9. Qxe4 Bxc3+ {A good opportunity to double the pawns.} 10. bxc3 Re8 {A nice tempo on the queen.} 11. Qc2 Ne5 {It's clear that Black gets excellent play for the pawn. Just take a look at White pieces at the back rank.} 12. Qe2 {White is being greedy!} ({It's not too late to give back the pawn with} 12. Ne2 {and O-O but of course Black is fine there. For example:} Nxc4 13. O-O d6 {, and it's clear that our bishop is superior to White's, plus we have the better pawn structure.}) 12... Qf6 {One out of many strong moves. Engine already gives -2 for us, even though we are down a pawn!} 13. f4 Ng6 {White is totally lost due to a simple double attack with ... Qxc3 + or ... Nxf4 next.} *

