1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qc2 {This is the Classical Variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after the typical 5.a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5.e4 . However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves.  Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our DSB. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas!} 5. e3 ({This is the only other serious alternative to} 5. Nf3 {but it's a bit passive as White locks the bishop on c1 .}) 5... O-O {A logical move, Black is first to castle while White still has to make 3 moves to castle kingside.} 6. Bd3 {A logical move, White develops the bishop first and will follow with Nge2 & O-O .} e5 {Since White never played Nf3 , we can play ... e5 in one go!} 7. Nge2 {White is about to castle, but we use this time to counter in the center.} Re8 {Creating a pretty obvious threat of ... e4 .} 8. O-O {White castled and sidestepped our threat, but here we can a nice idea to strike in the center.} Bxc3 9. Qxc3 (9. bxc3 $4 {loses to} e4 {while Nxc3 drops the d4 -pawn.}) 9... d5 {Black's lead in development now carried over to central domination. The game could continue:} 10. b3 e4 {A nice novelty to establish more central control and lock up the bishops.} 11. Bc2 Bf5 {Black is first to finish development. We will play ... Ne7 and ... c6 to create a nice attacking pawn chain and eventually weaken White's king with Harry the h-pawn launch.} *

