1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qc2 {This is the Classical Variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after the typical 5.a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5.e4 . However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves.  Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our DSB. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas!} 5. e3 ({This is the only other serious alternative to} 5. Nf3 {but it's a bit passive as White locks the bishop on c1 .}) 5... O-O {A logical move, Black is first to castle while White still has to make 3 moves to castle kingside.} 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 {White achieved their bishop pair advantage but at the cost of time. Now, we need to prepare fast action in the center.} Re8 {Black X-rays the enemy king and gets ready to push either ... e5 or ... d5 , depending on what White does next.} 8. Ne2 d5 {This was played by GM Vidit vs another Chessable author, GM L'Ami, in 2023. I like it even more than ... e5 as it opens up the center.} ({After} 8... e5 $2 9. d5 $1 {White gets to keep the center closed and can claim a small edge due to the bishop pair.}) 9. cxd5 Nxd5 ({This is even stronger that Vidit's} 9... Ne4 {, but he also got a nice edge out of the opening.}) 10. Qc2 e5 {We blow open the center!} 11. dxe5 Nxe5 {Our knights dominate the center and it's obvious that White is behind in development. Here's one possible line:} 12. Ng3 Nf4 {As Bobby Fischer said: 'Tactics flow from a superior position'. White is in big trouble already.} 13. e4 (13. exf4 Nf3# {Handshake A nice way to finish the game.}) 13... Nfd3+ 14. Bxd3 Nxd3+ {We force the king out in the open!} 15. Ke2 Ne5 {We now have a nice target, the enemy king in the center!} 16. Rd1 Qh4 17. h3 b6 {With a big threat of ... Ba6 +. Black has a great attack!} *

