{We are about to blow open the center to get to White's monarch. The engine claims -3 advantage and Black is having all the fun! Please note that Qxc5?? loses the queen after either knight jump to e4 with check.} 1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qc2 {This is the Classical Variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after the typical 5.a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5.e4 . However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves.  Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our DSB. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas!} 5. e3 ({This is the only other serious alternative to} 5. Nf3 {but it's a bit passive as White locks the bishop on c1 .}) 5... O-O {A logical move, Black is first to castle while White still has to make 3 moves to castle kingside.} 6. Nge2 {White tries to combine the ideas from the Rubinstein Variation to play a3 and Nxc3 , but it's too slow!} d5 {One of the rare occasions where we switch our plans and go for the central push. There's a hidden trick here.} 7. a3 {This logical follow-up to Nge2 is a mistake already!} dxc4 {Now the point of an early ... d5 move is revealed. White can't take our bishop.} 8. axb4 ({Better is} 8. Ng3 Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 {but after} b5 {, Black keeps the extra pawn.}) 8... Nxb4 {White's in trouble now.} 9. Qa4 Nd3+ 10. Kd2 Nxf2 11. Rg1 {Here it's clear that Black has huge compensation for the piece. As a matter of fact, we already have 3 pawns for it. So, technically the material is balanced, but just look at White's king!} c5 {... e5 first is also good.} 12. Qxc4 e5 *

