1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qc2 {This is the Classical Variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after the typical 5.a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5.e4 . However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves.  Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our DSB. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas!} 5. e3 ({This is the only other serious alternative to} 5. Nf3 {but it's a bit passive as White locks the bishop on c1 .}) 5... e5 {This is an interesting fresh idea that I saw in a game of our Silicon friend, Leela. Why not fight for the center if the knight is still on g1 ?} 6. d5 Ne7 7. Nge2 {White is now ready to play 8. a3 and recapture back with the knight.} a5 {A clever way to save our bishop.} 8. a3 Bc5 9. Ng3 d6 {Black has established the dream pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and plans to play on the kingside.} 10. Be2 O-O 11. Na4 Ba7 {The bishop is an important piece as it keeps White from playing e4 , giving us the control of the g1 - a7 diagonal.} 12. O-O Ng4 {A nice idea. Black is regrouping the knight to h6 and opens up the way for the f-pawn.} 13. h3 Nh6 14. b4 f5 {Black has a promising attack as we plan to play for the ... f4 push. Leela won a beautiful game against a 3100 (!) engine in just 31 moves. See the Model Game Zahak-Leela, 2021 .} *

