1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qc2 {This is the Classical Variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after the typical 5.a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5.e4 . However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves.  Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our DSB. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas!} 5. a3 {I have to say that normally, I wouldn't cover such poor moves in the opening. However, White played this in 6,500 blitz games online (!) likely due to a premove.} Nxd4 {Christmas came early for us in this game as we get a central pawn for free. Another benefit of playing 4...Nc6 !} 6. Qd3 Bxc3+ ({The simplest, but you can also play} 6... Nb3 {.}) 7. Qxc3 e5 {We grab the center and protect our knight. Black has many other good moves as well.} 8. e3 Ne4 {The knights dominate the center and poor queen is running out of squares.} 9. Qd3 Nc5 10. Qc3 Ndb3 {It's clear that Black is totally winning now.} 11. Qxe5+ Qe7 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 13. Rb1 d5 {... Bf5 next.} 14. cxd5 Bf5 {Game over.} *

