{Black is already better as we will win the h2 -pawn next since White has to play Rg3 to stop a deadly ... Bh3 threat.} 1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qc2 {This is the Classical Variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after the typical 5.a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5.e4 . However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves.  Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our DSB. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas!} 5. Nf3 {This is by the far the most common way to protect the d4 -pawn. White is still being flexible with their LSB that could be developed to g5 .} d6 {The move order is very important here! We delay castling for a very important reason, anticipating the logical pin with Bg5 in order to spring a devilish trap on our unexpected opponent!} 6. Bg5 {The most played move. Why not pin a knight and develop the bishop at the same time? But this is exactly what we want!} h6 {Asking the bishop its intentions. We hope for the autopilot response Bh4 to spring our trap!} 7. Bd2 {White's best move, transposing to the 7.Bd2 line, but with the inclusion of the move ... h6 . I would say that ... h6 typically favors Black as we get a free tempo to create a luft for our king, but there are moments where it may backfire if White decides to castle queenside and launch a pawn storm with g4 - g5 . So, we need to be careful!} O-O {To be consistent, I recommend the same move as without first inserting Bg5 & ... h6 .} ({But keeping our options open with} 7... e5 $5 {is worth a try.}) 8. a3 {White forces us to take on c3 , obtaining the bishop pair.} Bxc3 9. Bxc3 {We've reached the same exact position as covered in the 7.Bd2 line, except one important difference, the pawn on h6 . This is where we have to be careful as White can castle queenside and launch the kingside attack with g4 - g5 . Please note that the pawn on h6 acts as hook to speed up White's attack.} e5 {This pawn sacrifice works well with the pawn being on h6 !} (9... Re8 10. O-O-O Qe7 11. Rg1 {, and White will follow up with g4 with an attack.}) 10. dxe5 (10. d5 Ne7 {leads to similar play as covered in 6.Bd2 line.}) 10... dxe5 11. Nxe5 {White grabs the central pawn.} Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Re8 {We get serious compensation for the pawn as White's king is stuck in the center.} 13. Rd1 Qe7 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. e3 Qc6 {A cool idea to slow down White's development. Now their bishop is stuck on f1 .} 16. Rg1 {White abandons the right to castle and plans to launch the pawn storm with g4 .} Be6 17. g4 Rad8 {We are not afraid of White's pseudo-attack and take over the open file.} 18. Rxd8 Rxd8 19. g5 hxg5 20. Rxg5 Qh1 *

