1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qc2 {This is the Classical Variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after the typical 5.a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5.e4 . However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves.  Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our DSB. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas!} 5. Nf3 {This is by the far the most common way to protect the d4 -pawn. White is still being flexible with their LSB that could be developed to g5 .} d6 {The move order is very important here! We delay castling for a very important reason, anticipating the logical pin with Bg5 in order to spring a devilish trap on our unexpected opponent!} 6. Bg5 {The most played move. Why not pin a knight and develop the bishop at the same time? But this is exactly what we want!} h6 {Asking the bishop its intentions. We hope for the autopilot response Bh4 to spring our trap!} 7. Bxf6 {This harmless trade was played against me by the young Hikaru Nakamura back in 2002. Hikaru was already rated 2600 USCF at that time, age 15!} Qxf6 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 O-O 10. Rd1 {Hikaru is ready to meet the ... e5 push with d5 and covers the d4 -square just in case.} ({Or} 10. e3 e5 {with similar ideas as in the game.}) 10... e5 {Black achieves the dream pawn chain and opens up the c8 -bishop. Please note how White still needs to make 3 (!) moves to complete development.} 11. d5 Ne7 ({I anticipated action on the kingside and move my knight in that direction, but there's nothing wrong with} 11... Nb8 {either going for the eventual c5 -outpost after ... a5 .}) 12. e4 {This allows Black to execute a fast ... f5 break.} Qg6 13. Nd2 f5 {And with so much pressure on g2 and e4 , White's king is facing some difficulties.} *

