1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qc2 {This is the Classical Variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after the typical 5.a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5.e4 . However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves.  Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our DSB. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas!} 5. Nf3 {This is by the far the most common way to protect the d4 -pawn. White is still being flexible with their LSB that could be developed to g5 .} d6 {The move order is very important here! We delay castling for a very important reason, anticipating the logical pin with Bg5 in order to spring a devilish trap on our unexpected opponent!} 6. a3 {White resolves the pin right away.} Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 a5 {I like this prophylactic move to stop the b4 expansion.} 8. b3 ({This a typical response to ... a5 . White is now ready to meet} 8. a4 $2 {with b4 .}) 8... O-O {We castle first. Please note that White still needs 3 moves to castle kingside!} 9. Bg5 h6 {A simple way to deal with pin, we plan to meet Bh4 with ... g5 !} 10. Bh4 g5 {Don't be afraid to push this pawn, our king is very safe.} 11. Bg3 ({White can't really sacrifice on g5 since} 11. Nxg5 $2 hxg5 12. Bxg5 {loses to} Ne4 $1 {Fork!.}) 11... Ne4 {A nice square for our knight, plus we win a tempo as well.} 12. Qc2 f5 {Black achieves total domination on the kingside. White has no way of getting to our king.} 13. e3 Qf6 {Black enjoys a small plus already. We plan to play for ... e5 next.} *

