1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qc2 {This is the Classical Variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after the typical 5.a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5.e4 . However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves.  Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our DSB. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas!} 5. Nf3 {This is by the far the most common way to protect the d4 -pawn. White is still being flexible with their LSB that could be developed to g5 .} d6 {The move order is very important here! We delay castling for a very important reason, anticipating the logical pin with Bg5 in order to spring a devilish trap on our unexpected opponent!} 6. a3 {White resolves the pin right away.} Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 a5 {I like this prophylactic move to stop the b4 expansion.} 8. b3 ({This a typical response to ... a5 . White is now ready to meet} 8. a4 $2 {with b4 .}) 8... O-O {We castle first. Please note that White still needs 3 moves to castle kingside!} 9. Bb2 {A logical square for the bishop.} Re8 {We prepare our main strategic idea, ... e5 .} 10. Rd1 {White creates an X-ray on our queen, but the queen is happy to move to e7 anyways.} Qe7 {We renew our ... e5 push and White can't stop it!} 11. e3 e5 12. Be2 Bg4 {Black finishes development first and creates a hidden trap if White castles. Please note that 13... e4 was good as well.} 13. d5 ({The logical} 13. O-O $2 {loses a piece due to} e4 $1) 13... Nb8 {A typical regrouping. The knight will go to d7 .} 14. Qc2 ({Again} 14. O-O $2 {loses due to} e4 $1) 14... Nbd7 {I reached this position vs a strong Polish 2600 GM, Kamil Miton back in 2007. While the position is quite complex, I managed to win a nice game that you can find in the Model Games section.} ({Black's position is very solid and we have many plans to choose from. In the game, White went for transferring the knight to f5 after h3} 14... Bh5 15. Nh4 Bxe2 {. However, I was able to drop my queen back and take over the kingside with Qf8} 16. Qxe2 g6 {Ng3 h5! and eventually got a big kingside attack.}) *

