1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qc2 {This is the Classical Variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after the typical 5.a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5.e4 . However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves.  Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our DSB. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas!} 5. Nf3 {This is by the far the most common way to protect the d4 -pawn. White is still being flexible with their LSB that could be developed to g5 .} d6 {The move order is very important here! We delay castling for a very important reason, anticipating the logical pin with Bg5 in order to spring a devilish trap on our unexpected opponent!} 6. Bd2 {This is the best move and stronger players know about the ... h6 & ... g5 trap. White intends to play a3 and take back on c3 with the bishop.} O-O {Black's most natural move. We anticipate a3 and get ready to execute our central break plan with ... Re8 and ... e5 next.} 7. a3 Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Re8 ({This is a big improvement over the original book recommendation of} 8... Qe7 {. While the idea is the same, to play for the ... e5 push, I believe it's more accurate to start with Re8 , as we will see.}) 9. Rd1 {White creates an X-ray on our queen, preventing the ... e5 push.} Qe7 {A simple sidestep, now ... e5 cannot be stopped. Please note that e7 is the ideal square for our queen anyway.} 10. e3 {This is by the far the most common move. White gets ready to develop the LSB and castle.} e5 {Just like in  9.e3 e5 ! , we execute the key idea of the opening by building a nice pawn chain and opening up our LSB.} 11. d5 ({If White trades on e5 with} 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Be2 {, we have a similar position as covered after  9.e3 .}) 11... Nb8 {An important nuance! Since the e7 -square is covered by our queen, we cannot proceed as mentioned in the  9.e3 e5 10.d5 Ne7 line . So, we need to change plans. Luckily, the knight on b8 is flexible and can get to c5 after ... a5 - a4 .} 12. Be2 {White's most logical move. They are about to finish development with O-O next.} a5 {White White is busy finishing up development, we are securing the c5 -outpost for our knight.} 13. O-O a4 {We fix the pawns and now getting ready to transfer the knight on c5 .} 14. c5 {This is White's best attempt to fight for advantage.} Bd7 {Getting ready to play ... Na6 next.} 15. cxd6 cxd6 16. e4 Na6 {White cannot easily stop ... Nc5 next. Here's one possible line:} 17. Nd2 b5 {Grabbing more space!} 18. Qd3 Nc5 19. Qe3 Ng4 ({An important regrouping. Trading with} 19... Bg4 20. Bxg4 {f3 Bd7 results in an even game, we will still play for ... f5 .}) 20. Qf3 Nh6 {Black has finished the knight maneuver and will play for ... f5 next with easy play. White, on the other hand, doesn't have a clear plan.} *

