1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qc2 {This is the Classical Variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after the typical 5.a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5.e4 . However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves.  Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our DSB. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas!} 5. Nf3 {This is by the far the most common way to protect the d4 -pawn. White is still being flexible with their LSB that could be developed to g5 .} d6 {The move order is very important here! We delay castling for a very important reason, anticipating the logical pin with Bg5 in order to spring a devilish trap on our unexpected opponent!} 6. Bd2 {This is the best move and stronger players know about the ... h6 & ... g5 trap. White intends to play a3 and take back on c3 with the bishop.} O-O {Black's most natural move. We anticipate a3 and get ready to execute our central break plan with ... Re8 and ... e5 next.} 7. a3 Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Re8 ({This is a big improvement over the original book recommendation of} 8... Qe7 {. While the idea is the same, to play for the ... e5 push, I believe it's more accurate to start with Re8 , as we will see.}) 9. e3 {White is getting ready to develop their LSB and castle kingside. But our plan is very simple: the ... e5 pawn push!} e5 {Black executes the key strategic idea of this opening. We create a nice pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and open up our LSB.} 10. dxe5 {At first sight, it seems that White surrenders the center, but we have to be careful as the game does open up a bit and our opponent has the bishop pair.} dxe5 {Now, we have the central pawn, which would blunt White's DSB.} 11. Be2 {White gets ready to castle kingside.} ({Inserting} 11. Rd1 Qe7 {doesn't change our plan of playing for ... a5 next.}) (11. Bd3 {runs into} e4 $1) 11... a5 {This is a useful move, we would like to fix White's queenside with ... a4 next.} ({Nothing is wrong with} 11... Bg4 {as well.}) 12. O-O a4 {We achieve our goal of fixing White's pawns, and in the future, one of our knights may land on the b3 -outpost.} 13. Rfd1 {White wins the d-file for now, but our queen belongs on e7 anyway.} Qe7 14. h3 {White prevents ... Bg4 .} g6 {Surprisingly, this is the best move, as White can't easily prevent ... Bf5 .} 15. Nd2 Bf5 16. Bd3 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 Red8 18. Qc2 {Neither side minded the draw in Lysyj,I (2666)-Tkachiev,V (2637), Warsaw 2013, but Black has a cool idea:} Nd4 {Usually, we play this idea with the king on e1 , but it works here just as well.} 19. exd4 exd4 20. Bb4 c5 {We will win back the piece with a more active pawn structure thanks to the pawn on d4 , but objectively, the game is roughly even.} *

