tronger players know about the ... h6 & ... g5 trap. White intends to play a3 and take back on c3 with the bishop.} O-O {Black's most natural move. We anticipate a3 and get ready to execute our central break plan with ... Re8 and ... e5 next.} 7. a3 Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Re8 ({This is a big improvement over the original book recommendation of} 8... Qe7 {. While the idea is the same, to play for the ... e5 push, I believe it's more accurate to start with Re8 , as we will see.}) 9. e3 {White is getting ready to develop their LSB and castle kingside. But our plan is very simple: the ... e5 pawn push!} e5 {Black executes the key strategic idea of this opening. We create a nice pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and open up our LSB.} 10. Be2 ({Not} 10. Bd3 $4 {due to} e4 $1 {Fork.}) 10... Ne4 {Black has many good moves, but I like this fun sacrifice, as we will get the piece back, of course.} 11. Qxe4 exd4 {This discovered attack wins the piece back.} 12. Qc2 dxc3 13. Qxc3 b6 {I prefer to develop the bishop on the long diagonal.} 14. O-O Bb7 {Both sides have finished development and the game is about even. Black has a rock solid pawn structure with no weaknesses. We will play ... Ne5 next.} *

