tronger players know about the ... h6 & ... g5 trap. White intends to play a3 and take back on c3 with the bishop.} O-O {Black's most natural move. We anticipate a3 and get ready to execute our central break plan with ... Re8 and ... e5 next.} 7. a3 Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Re8 ({This is a big improvement over the original book recommendation of} 8... Qe7 {. While the idea is the same, to play for the ... e5 push, I believe it's more accurate to start with Re8 , as we will see.}) 9. e3 {White is getting ready to develop their LSB and castle kingside. But our plan is very simple: the ... e5 pawn push!} e5 {Black executes the key strategic idea of this opening. We create a nice pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and open up our LSB.} 10. d5 {This is the ambitious option, but we don't mind the closed nature of the resulting positions, since we have the knights vs the bishop pair.} Ne7 {We often retreat the knight to b8 in order to reroute it to c5 , but since White always has b4 ready, we shift our focus to undermining the d5 - & c4 -pawns with either ... c6 or ... b5 .} 11. Bd3 {This natural move was played recently by GM Benjamin Bok.} b5 {A fresh idea, not yet played at the GM level. We undermine White's c4 -pawn, trying to trade our b-pawn for White's d-pawn.} 12. cxb5 Nexd5 {Now White has to be careful as the ... e4 fork is a big threat.} 13. Nd2 {White prevents ... e4 .} a6 {I like the simple idea of trading off the b5 -pawn.} 14. bxa6 Nxc3 15. Qxc3 e4 {A nice intermezzo to gain some more space.} 16. Be2 Bxa6 17. Bxa6 Rxa6 18. O-O d5 {The dust has settled and we have an interesting pawn imbalance. What's better: two wing pawns or two central pawns?   As a rule of thumb, the central pawns are better unless we are in some deep endgame. Black will play ... c6 next to create a nice pawn chain and reroute the knight to e5 , where it would jump to d3 or support our attack on the kingside.} *

