1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qc2 {This is the Classical Variation and the most common one at all levels, so you should be prepared! White protects the knight on c3 and ready to recapture back with the queen after the typical 5.a3 .   White is also getting ready to take over the center with a central push 5.e4 . However, White violates one of the core opening principles, don't move your queen out early! As a matter of fact, queen moves don't count as development moves.  Think about it, White still has to make 4 moves to castle kingside, whereas Black can play ... O-O already. Thus, the key to this variation is to understand that Black needs to play actively and develop as quickly as possible, while putting pressure on White's center.} Nc6 {Surprisingly, this logical move that develops our knight and attacks the d4 -pawn is super rare. It's only the 5th most popular move, making it a big surprise for our less prepared opponent. The ideas of this line are very similar to the Bogo Indian where we plan to establish a strong pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and typically trade our DSB. It's good to have a repertoire with common pawn structures and ideas!} 5. Nf3 {This is by the far the most common way to protect the d4 -pawn. White is still being flexible with their LSB that could be developed to g5 .} d6 {The move order is very important here! We delay castling for a very important reason, anticipating the logical pin with Bg5 in order to spring a devilish trap on our unexpected opponent!} 6. Bd2 {This is the best move and stronger players know about the ... h6 & ... g5 trap. White intends to play a3 and take back on c3 with the bishop.} O-O {Black's most natural move. We anticipate a3 and get ready to execute our central break plan with ... Re8 and ... e5 next.} 7. a3 Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Re8 ({This is a big improvement over the original book recommendation of} 8... Qe7 {. While the idea is the same, to play for the ... e5 push, I believe it's more accurate to start with Re8 , as we will see.}) 9. e3 {White is getting ready to develop their LSB and castle kingside. But our plan is very simple: the ... e5 pawn push!} e5 {Black executes the key strategic idea of this opening. We create a nice pawn chain: c7 - d6 - e5 and open up our LSB.} 10. d5 {This is the ambitious option, but we don't mind the closed nature of the resulting positions, since we have the knights vs the bishop pair.} Ne7 {We often retreat the knight to b8 in order to reroute it to c5 , but since White always has b4 ready, we shift our focus to undermining the d5 - & c4 -pawns with either ... c6 or ... b5 .} 11. e4 {A logical move, White completes the central grip grabbing more space. However, White's kingside is still not fully developed and we use the time to undermine White's center.} c6 {An instructive idea and a strong novelty, chipping away at White's strong center!} 12. dxc6 {We are happy to see this trade as we will have more central pawns now.} bxc6 13. Rd1 {Creating an X-ray against our queen.} Ng6 {Prophylaxis against c5 .} 14. c5 {This looks logical, but it's bad!} d5 {The engine already gives us -2 advantage! White has lost the strategic battle.} ({For example: exd5} 14... Nd5 {(Both e4 and cxd5 are good as well.)} 15. Be2 {e4! Nd4} Ngf4 16. O-O Qg5 {with a crushing attack!}) *

