[GameId "2176748629545802"]

1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein Variation. White is not worried about Black taking on c3 and doubling the pawns for now. Instead, White aims for a solid setup either with 5.Bd3 & Nge2 or 5.Bd3 & Nf3 or the immediate 5.Nge2 .} {Luckily, my original recommendation from Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time, and I would recommend it for this course as well, b6! Of course, I did a complete overhaul and have lots of improvements ready for you!} b6 ({We answer White's slow play with a sound idea of developing our light-squared bishop. If White plays for Nge2 & a3 , we develop the bishop to a6 to challenge White on the f1 - a6 diagonal.   If White goes for a classical setup with Bd3 & Nf3 or Bd3 & Nge2 , we fianchetto the bishop on b7 . The good news is that this line still hasn't gained as much popularity as the autopilot move} 4... O-O {, thus it is likely your opponent may be less prepared.   These days Caruana has championed this move on multiple occasions. He famously used it to win a mini-match vs GM Nakamura at Norway Chess 2024 (Hikaru escaped with a draw in classical but lost in Armageddon). Knowing that Caruana plays this line is the highest stamp of approval!}) 5. Nge2 ({In the Master Database, this move is almost 3 times more common than} 5. Bd3 {, so make sure to be ready for it! White's idea to play a3 next and obtain the bishop pair 'for free', meaning that they don't want to ruin their pawn structure with bxc3 .}) 5... Ba6 {We have to act fast as White is about to get the bishop pair, which is a long-term asset. Thus, we need to get our counterplay going quickly.} 6. Nf4 ({This is less accurate than} 6. Ng3 {, as the knight on f4 is an easy target after a timely ... e5 push.}) 6... Bxc3+ {This is easy to remember, as we play same move against 6.Ng3 .} ({However,} 6... c5 $5 {is also very promising.}) 7. bxc3 Nc6 {Now, since White is not threatening a center grab with e4 , we are getting quick counterplay both vs the c4 -pawn with ... Na5 and vs the f4 -knight with ... e5 !} 8. Bd3 e5 {Making the knight move again, as dxe5 clearly is positional suicide.} 9. Nd5 e4 {Remember this move! Now, we offer our e4 -pawn for the c4 -pawn.} 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. Bxe4 Bxc4 {Our bishop is a serious menace on the f1 - a6 diagonal and White has to trade it off in order to castle.} 12. Bd3 Bxd3 ({This is the simplest but} 12... Na5 {is fine too.}) 13. Qxd3 Qg6 {We force White into a favorable endgame.} 14. Qxg6 hxg6 {I believe Black is a bit better here since we have a powerful idea ... Na5 & ... Nc4 with a monster knight.} 15. e4 Na5 {The knight is taking over c4 .} 16. Ke2 d5 (16... c6 {is also good, but this clears up the center.}) 17. exd5 (17. e5 {helps Black as it closes the position and gives us a permanent outpost on c4 .}) 17... O-O-O 18. Be3 Rxd5 {While objectively the position is even, I believe Black has better practical chances due to the many weaknesses in White's camp.} *

