[GameId "2176748629558092"]

1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein Variation. White is not worried about Black taking on c3 and doubling the pawns for now. Instead, White aims for a solid setup either with 5.Bd3 & Nge2 or 5.Bd3 & Nf3 or the immediate 5.Nge2 .} {Luckily, my original recommendation from Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time, and I would recommend it for this course as well, b6! Of course, I did a complete overhaul and have lots of improvements ready for you!} b6 ({We answer White's slow play with a sound idea of developing our light-squared bishop. If White plays for Nge2 & a3 , we develop the bishop to a6 to challenge White on the f1 - a6 diagonal.   If White goes for a classical setup with Bd3 & Nf3 or Bd3 & Nge2 , we fianchetto the bishop on b7 . The good news is that this line still hasn't gained as much popularity as the autopilot move} 4... O-O {, thus it is likely your opponent may be less prepared.   These days Caruana has championed this move on multiple occasions. He famously used it to win a mini-match vs GM Nakamura at Norway Chess 2024 (Hikaru escaped with a draw in classical but lost in Armageddon). Knowing that Caruana plays this line is the highest stamp of approval!}) 5. Nge2 ({In the Master Database, this move is almost 3 times more common than} 5. Bd3 {, so make sure to be ready for it! White's idea to play a3 next and obtain the bishop pair 'for free', meaning that they don't want to ruin their pawn structure with bxc3 .}) 5... Ba6 {We have to act fast as White is about to get the bishop pair, which is a long-term asset. Thus, we need to get our counterplay going quickly.} 6. Qa4 {This rare move was seen recently in Sarana-Caruana, 2024. Even though it was a blitz game, Caruana demonstrated some amazing home prep. Let's take a look.} c5 {Black takes advantage of White's poor development and strikes in the center.} 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 O-O {We have a classic Nimzo imbalance: Black's better development vs White's bishop pair and space advantage.} 9. d5 ({Sarana correctly wins more space, as} 9. Be2 {allows us to play} cxd4 10. exd4 d5 $1 {with excellent pressure in the center.}) 9... exd5 10. cxd5 Bxf1 11. Rxf1 {White has gained more space but lost the bishop pair and the right to castle kingside.} d6 12. f3 {White prepares e4 .} Nbd7 13. e4 {This pawn structure is similar to the Benoni or a King's Indian Sämisch. Black's plan is to prepare a queenside pawn storm.} Ne5 {A useful move with the idea ... Nd3 , forcing the queen to retreat.} 14. Qc2 b5 {A typical idea to sacrifice the pawn for initiative.} ({We could also play} 14... c4 $5) 15. Bf4 {Sarana doesn't take the bait.} Re8 {A sneaky move.} 16. Nxb5 ({Missing Black's idea. Better is} 16. Kf2 c4 {with nice play for Black.}) 16... Nxd5 {A timely sacrifice to open up the enemy king.} 17. Bxe5 (17. exd5 $2 {loses to} Nd3+ {and ... Nxf4 .}) 17... Rxe5 18. Qd2 Rb8 19. Nc3 Nb6 20. Rf2 d5 {Caruana's energetic play resulted in a nice advantage. Later, he messed up and lost under time pressure, but White is already in serious trouble.} 21. Qf4 Qe8 22. Rd1 d4 23. Ne2 f5 {And White's position is collapsing. The engine already gives us -3!} *

