hite is about to get the bishop pair, which is a long-term asset. Thus, we need to get our counterplay going quickly.} 6. a3 {White executes their main idea.} Bxc3+ 7. Nxc3 d5 {The key idea! If not for this move, White would be significantly better. However, now we keep attacking the pawn on c4 , hoping to induce cxd5 which would enable us to trade light-squared bishops.} 8. Qf3 {White uses the pin to stop us from taking on c4 , but we can just continue development.} O-O 9. g4 {This attacking idea is not dangerous for us at all.} c6 {A rock-solid move, inviting g5 .} 10. b3 {This move was played by several GMs. Clearly, it doesn't work well with g4 , where is White attack?} dxc4 {I like the idea of opening up the game and trying to take advantage of White's poor development.} 11. bxc4 e5 {A cool pawn sacrifice, which is fully justified, as White's king is still stuck in the center.} 12. dxe5 Nfd7 13. Qg3 Nc5 {With our knight about to jump to d3 , White's position is now in danger.} 14. e4 Qd4 15. Bb2 Nbd7 16. Rd1 Qxe5 17. Qxe5 Nxe5 {Next, we will win the c4 -pawn. Black is clearly better.} *

