hite is about to get the bishop pair, which is a long-term asset. Thus, we need to get our counterplay going quickly.} 6. a3 {White executes their main idea.} Bxc3+ 7. Nxc3 d5 {The key idea! If not for this move, White would be significantly better. However, now we keep attacking the pawn on c4 , hoping to induce cxd5 which would enable us to trade light-squared bishops.} 8. Qa4+ {White only wants to take on d5 after ... c6 , but Black is fine here as well.} c6 9. cxd5 Bxf1 10. Rxf1 {This was played in a recent GM battle by famous Dutch streamer Benjamin Bok.} ({If} 10. Kxf1 {, the play is similar: Black will play} exd5 {& ... O-O with a comfortable position.}) 10... exd5 {Black gets a great version of the Carlsbad pawn structure with major benefits: White's king is stuck on e1 , The light-squared bishops were exchanged, White's bishop is locked on c1 .} 11. f3 Qd6 {Taking advantage of White's weak h2 -pawn.} 12. g3 O-O {Black is already a bit better with harmonious development and will play ... Nbd7 next. Whereas White has yet to solve the problem with his king.   This is from the game Bok, B - Matviishen, V, Dulles 2022.} *

