1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein Variation. White is not worried about Black taking on c3 and doubling the pawns for now. Instead, White aims for a solid setup either with 5.Bd3 & Nge2 or 5.Bd3 & Nf3 or the immediate 5.Nge2 .} {Luckily, my original recommendation from Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time, and I would recommend it for this course as well, b6! Of course, I did a complete overhaul and have lots of improvements ready for you!} b6 ({We answer White's slow play with a sound idea of developing our light-squared bishop. If White plays for Nge2 & a3 , we develop the bishop to a6 to challenge White on the f1 - a6 diagonal.   If White goes for a classical setup with Bd3 & Nf3 or Bd3 & Nge2 , we fianchetto the bishop on b7 . The good news is that this line still hasn't gained as much popularity as the autopilot move} 4... O-O {, thus it is likely your opponent may be less prepared.   These days Caruana has championed this move on multiple occasions. He famously used it to win a mini-match vs GM Nakamura at Norway Chess 2024 (Hikaru escaped with a draw in classical but lost in Armageddon). Knowing that Caruana plays this line is the highest stamp of approval!}) 5. Nge2 ({In the Master Database, this move is almost 3 times more common than} 5. Bd3 {, so make sure to be ready for it! White's idea to play a3 next and obtain the bishop pair 'for free', meaning that they don't want to ruin their pawn structure with bxc3 .}) 5... Ba6 {We have to act fast as White is about to get the bishop pair, which is a long-term asset. Thus, we need to get our counterplay going quickly.} 6. a3 {White executes their main idea.} Bxc3+ 7. Nxc3 d5 {The key idea! If not for this move, White would be significantly better. However, now we keep attacking the pawn on c4 , hoping to induce cxd5 which would enable us to trade light-squared bishops.} 8. b3 {White's most common and solid move. They reinforce c4 and get ready to continue with development.} O-O {We are first to castle, while White still needs two more moves to get their monarch into safety.} 9. Be2 c5 ({This logical move is an improvement over previously suggested} 9... dxc4 {. Black is happy to increase more pressure in the center while White is behind in development.}) 10. O-O {This natural move enables us to create weak pawns in White's camp.} dxc4 11. bxc4 cxd4 12. exd4 Nc6 {This is a classic 'hanging pawns' position where White's d- & c-pawns are clear targets. The classic strategy is to force one of these pawns to move forward and attack the weak squares around it.} 13. Be3 Na5 {We encourage White to push with c5 .} 14. c5 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Nd5 16. Nxd5 exd5 ({With the idea to establish our knight on c4 . I like this even more than} 16... Qxd5 {. Black is a bit better after ... Nc4 next. This is a clear case of a good knight vs a bad bishop imbalance.}) *

