hite is about to get the bishop pair, which is a long-term asset. Thus, we need to get our counterplay going quickly.} 6. a3 {White executes their main idea.} Bxc3+ 7. Nxc3 d5 {The key idea! If not for this move, White would be significantly better. However, now we keep attacking the pawn on c4 , hoping to induce cxd5 which would enable us to trade light-squared bishops.} 8. b3 {White's most common and solid move. They reinforce c4 and get ready to continue with development.} O-O {We are first to castle, while White still needs two more moves to get their monarch into safety.} 9. Be2 c5 ({This logical move is an improvement over previously suggested} 9... dxc4 {. Black is happy to increase more pressure in the center while White is behind in development.}) 10. O-O {This natural move enables us to create weak pawns in White's camp.} dxc4 11. bxc4 cxd4 12. exd4 Nc6 {This is a classic 'hanging pawns' position where White's d- & c-pawns are clear targets. The classic strategy is to force one of these pawns to move forward and attack the weak squares around it.} 13. Be3 Na5 {We encourage White to push with c5 .} 14. Nb5 Bxb5 15. cxb5 Nd5 {We have a nice blockade against White's weak d4 -pawn, known as the Isolated Queen Pawn (IQP). This is a very common pawn weakness in many openings. The bishops don't really offer much compensation, perhaps equality at best. We will play ... Rc8 next with easy play on the queenside.} *

