1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein Variation. White is not worried about Black taking on c3 and doubling the pawns for now. Instead, White aims for a solid setup either with 5.Bd3 & Nge2 or 5.Bd3 & Nf3 or the immediate 5.Nge2 .} {Luckily, my original recommendation from Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time, and I would recommend it for this course as well, b6! Of course, I did a complete overhaul and have lots of improvements ready for you!} b6 ({We answer White's slow play with a sound idea of developing our light-squared bishop. If White plays for Nge2 & a3 , we develop the bishop to a6 to challenge White on the f1 - a6 diagonal.   If White goes for a classical setup with Bd3 & Nf3 or Bd3 & Nge2 , we fianchetto the bishop on b7 . The good news is that this line still hasn't gained as much popularity as the autopilot move} 4... O-O {, thus it is likely your opponent may be less prepared.   These days Caruana has championed this move on multiple occasions. He famously used it to win a mini-match vs GM Nakamura at Norway Chess 2024 (Hikaru escaped with a draw in classical but lost in Armageddon). Knowing that Caruana plays this line is the highest stamp of approval!}) 5. Nge2 ({In the Master Database, this move is almost 3 times more common than} 5. Bd3 {, so make sure to be ready for it! White's idea to play a3 next and obtain the bishop pair 'for free', meaning that they don't want to ruin their pawn structure with bxc3 .}) 5... Ba6 {We have to act fast as White is about to get the bishop pair, which is a long-term asset. Thus, we need to get our counterplay going quickly.} 6. a3 {White executes their main idea.} Bxc3+ 7. Nxc3 d5 {The key idea! If not for this move, White would be significantly better. However, now we keep attacking the pawn on c4 , hoping to induce cxd5 which would enable us to trade light-squared bishops.} 8. b3 {White's most common and solid move. They reinforce c4 and get ready to continue with development.} O-O {We are first to castle, while White still needs two more moves to get their monarch into safety.} 9. Be2 c5 ({This logical move is an improvement over previously suggested} 9... dxc4 {. Black is happy to increase more pressure in the center while White is behind in development.}) 10. dxc5 ({This is White's best move to avoid hanging pawns after} 10. O-O dxc4 11. bxc4 cxd4 {.}) 10... dxc4 {The key move! Make sure to remember this one! Now, we get an endgame.} 11. Bf3 Qxd1+ 12. Kxd1 Rd8+ {A nice 'zwischenzug'!} 13. Kc2 ({Both} 13. Ke1 {and Bd2 are met with ... Nd5 !}) 13... cxb3+ {Another intermezzo.} 14. Kxb3 Nbd7 ({This is a cool exchange sacrifice, which is even stronger than} 14... Nd5 {.}) 15. Bxa8 Nxc5+ {White's king is exposed.} 16. Ka2 (16. Kb2 {is met with} Nd3+ {and ... Nxf2 , grabbing a 2nd pawn. White will move their rook to safety ( Rf1 isn't possible), and we'll capture the bishop on a8 and have a big edge.}) 16... Bc4+ 17. Kb1 Rxa8 {Black has excellent compensation for the exchange: a pawn and White's exposed king. The engine claims White can hold with only moves, but Black is going to have all the fun!} *

