1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein Variation. White is not worried about Black taking on c3 and doubling the pawns for now. Instead, White aims for a solid setup either with 5.Bd3 & Nge2 or 5.Bd3 & Nf3 or the immediate 5.Nge2 .} {Luckily, my original recommendation from Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time, and I would recommend it for this course as well, b6! Of course, I did a complete overhaul and have lots of improvements ready for you!} b6 ({We answer White's slow play with a sound idea of developing our light-squared bishop. If White plays for Nge2 & a3 , we develop the bishop to a6 to challenge White on the f1 - a6 diagonal.   If White goes for a classical setup with Bd3 & Nf3 or Bd3 & Nge2 , we fianchetto the bishop on b7 . The good news is that this line still hasn't gained as much popularity as the autopilot move} 4... O-O {, thus it is likely your opponent may be less prepared.   These days Caruana has championed this move on multiple occasions. He famously used it to win a mini-match vs GM Nakamura at Norway Chess 2024 (Hikaru escaped with a draw in classical but lost in Armageddon). Knowing that Caruana plays this line is the highest stamp of approval!}) 5. Nge2 ({In the Master Database, this move is almost 3 times more common than} 5. Bd3 {, so make sure to be ready for it! White's idea to play a3 next and obtain the bishop pair 'for free', meaning that they don't want to ruin their pawn structure with bxc3 .}) 5... Ba6 {We have to act fast as White is about to get the bishop pair, which is a long-term asset. Thus, we need to get our counterplay going quickly.} 6. Ng3 {This is a more ambitious plan as White doesn't mind doubling their pawns after ... Bxc3 + bxc3 .} Bxc3+ {We take the opportunity to weaken White's pawn structure.} 7. bxc3 d5 {Black doesn't mind eliminating White's doubled pawn as long as the light-squared bishops are traded.} 8. cxd5 {This was tried by Hikaru in the Armageddon game vs Fabi, but Black is too solid.} Bxf1 9. Kxf1 Qxd5 {We can also take with the pawn but here I prefer to activate the queen in the center of the board.} 10. Qd3 {White prepares e4 .} O-O 11. e4 Qa5 {The queen is also perfectly placed on a5 , keeping an eye on the c3 - & a2 -pawns.} 12. e5 Nd5 13. Ne4 f5 {An instructive moment, Black is better developed and wants to open up the f-file.} 14. exf6 Nxf6 15. Nxf6+ Rxf6 16. f3 Nd7 {Black's better development gives us a nice attack, just look at White's king!} *

