hite is about to get the bishop pair, which is a long-term asset. Thus, we need to get our counterplay going quickly.} 6. Ng3 {This is a more ambitious plan as White doesn't mind doubling their pawns after ... Bxc3 + bxc3 .} Bxc3+ {We take the opportunity to weaken White's pawn structure.} 7. bxc3 d5 {Black doesn't mind eliminating White's doubled pawn as long as the light-squared bishops are traded.} 8. cxd5 {This was tried by Hikaru in the Armageddon game vs Fabi, but Black is too solid.} Bxf1 9. Kxf1 Qxd5 {We can also take with the pawn but here I prefer to activate the queen in the center of the board.} 10. Qd3 {White prepares e4 .} O-O 11. e4 Qa5 {The queen is also perfectly placed on a5 , keeping an eye on the c3 - & a2 -pawns.} 12. e5 Nd5 13. Ne4 f5 {An instructive moment, Black is better developed and wants to open up the f-file.} 14. Ng5 Re8 15. Bd2 h6 16. Nf3 c5 {In the original book, we showed how White can easily get into trouble here:} 17. g3 {A logical idea, finishing the castle-by-hand with Kg2 , but Black quickly creates counterplay.} cxd4 18. cxd4 Qa4 (18... Qa6 {with a comfortable endgame is completely fine as well, but I like this even more.}) 19. Kg2 Nc6 {White can safeguard the king but stands worse due to the powerful blockade on d5 by our knight. We will play on the queenside next with ... Rac8 .} *

