hite is about to get the bishop pair, which is a long-term asset. Thus, we need to get our counterplay going quickly.} 6. Ng3 {This is a more ambitious plan as White doesn't mind doubling their pawns after ... Bxc3 + bxc3 .} Bxc3+ {We take the opportunity to weaken White's pawn structure.} 7. bxc3 d5 {Black doesn't mind eliminating White's doubled pawn as long as the light-squared bishops are traded.} 8. Ba3 {White stops us from castling but allows a capture on c4 .} Bxc4 {It's generally beneficial to trade light-squared bishops for us.} 9. Bxc4 dxc4 {Now White can win back the pawn with Qa4+ or play for the initiative with e4 .} 10. Qa4+ Qd7 11. Qxc4 Qc6 {The easiest. We know that endgames are fine once the LSBs are traded.} 12. Qxc6+ Nxc6 13. c4 ({We've reached a common endgame from this variation. White's idea is to grab the center with e4 , thus I propose an improvement over previously recommended} 13. O-O-O {.}) 13... h5 {We use an idea from AlphaZero to weaken White's position by pushing the h-pawn.} 14. h4 {White stops our idea but weakens the g4 -square a bit.} a6 {Another subtle move: we would like to play ... b5 and undermine White's c4 -pawn.} 15. Ke2 b5 16. cxb5 {Playing into our plan.} (16. Rhc1 {was probably better, but even then} Kd7 {maintains the tension.}) 16... axb5 17. Bc5 Nd5 {Black is a bit better, as we will play ... Kd7 next and start attacking the a2 -pawn.} *

