hite is about to get the bishop pair, which is a long-term asset. Thus, we need to get our counterplay going quickly.} 6. Ng3 {This is a more ambitious plan as White doesn't mind doubling their pawns after ... Bxc3 + bxc3 .} Bxc3+ {We take the opportunity to weaken White's pawn structure.} 7. bxc3 d5 {Black doesn't mind eliminating White's doubled pawn as long as the light-squared bishops are traded.} 8. Ba3 {White stops us from castling but allows a capture on c4 .} Bxc4 {It's generally beneficial to trade light-squared bishops for us.} 9. Bxc4 dxc4 {Now White can win back the pawn with Qa4+ or play for the initiative with e4 .} 10. e4 {White has taken over the center and is ready to castle. What to do for Black?} Qd7 {Black stops Qa4 + and prepares to transfer the queen to b5 & a6 . An important idea to remember!} 11. O-O Qb5 12. Rb1 Qa6 13. Qc1 Nc6 ({This is even stronger than previously recommended} 13... Nbd7 {.}) 14. Rd1 O-O-O {Our king is totally safe and we stopped White's d5 push. We will launch the kingside attack next with ... h5 , while it's unclear what White should do.} *

