hite is about to get the bishop pair, which is a long-term asset. Thus, we need to get our counterplay going quickly.} 6. Ng3 {This is a more ambitious plan as White doesn't mind doubling their pawns after ... Bxc3 + bxc3 .} Bxc3+ {We take the opportunity to weaken White's pawn structure.} 7. bxc3 d5 {Black doesn't mind eliminating White's doubled pawn as long as the light-squared bishops are traded.} 8. Ba3 {White stops us from castling but allows a capture on c4 .} Bxc4 {It's generally beneficial to trade light-squared bishops for us.} 9. Bxc4 dxc4 {Now White can win back the pawn with Qa4+ or play for the initiative with e4 .} 10. e4 {White has taken over the center and is ready to castle. What to do for Black?} Qd7 {Black stops Qa4 + and prepares to transfer the queen to b5 & a6 . An important idea to remember!} 11. O-O Qb5 12. e5 {I faced this move vs GM Kaidanov in 2011. White hopes to use their faster development to start an attack on the kingside. However, we get the d5 -outpost for our knight in return.} Nd5 13. Qg4 {White attacks the g7 -pawn, hoping to induce dark-square weaknesses after g6 .} Rg8 ({A strong novelty and a clear improvement over my game, where I reacted with} 13... g6 {. Now, Black wants to play ... Nc6 and castle long.}) 14. f4 Nc6 {We go for development ASAP!} 15. f5 O-O-O ({This is even stronger than grabbing the exchange with} 15... Ne3 {, as after} 16. Qh4 {, White is getting counterplay.}) 16. fxe6 fxe6 17. Qxe6+ Kb8 {The dust has settled. We gave our extra pawn back but, in return, totally safeguarded our king, and our knight on d5 dominates the center. White's c3 -pawn is quite weak, and the bishop is vulnerable to ... Qa4 . I prefer Black here.} *

