hite is about to get the bishop pair, which is a long-term asset. Thus, we need to get our counterplay going quickly.} 6. Ng3 {This is a more ambitious plan as White doesn't mind doubling their pawns after ... Bxc3 + bxc3 .} Bxc3+ {We take the opportunity to weaken White's pawn structure.} 7. bxc3 d5 {Black doesn't mind eliminating White's doubled pawn as long as the light-squared bishops are traded.} 8. Ba3 {White stops us from castling but allows a capture on c4 .} Bxc4 {It's generally beneficial to trade light-squared bishops for us.} 9. Bxc4 dxc4 {Now White can win back the pawn with Qa4+ or play for the initiative with e4 .} 10. e4 {White has taken over the center and is ready to castle. What to do for Black?} Qd7 {Black stops Qa4 + and prepares to transfer the queen to b5 & a6 . An important idea to remember!} 11. O-O Qb5 12. e5 {I faced this move vs GM Kaidanov in 2011. White hopes to use their faster development to start an attack on the kingside. However, we get the d5 -outpost for our knight in return.} Nd5 13. Qg4 {White attacks the g7 -pawn, hoping to induce dark-square weaknesses after g6 .} Rg8 ({A strong novelty and a clear improvement over my game, where I reacted with} 13... g6 {. Now, Black wants to play ... Nc6 and castle long.}) 14. Ne4 Nc6 15. Nf6+ Nxf6 16. exf6 O-O-O {We happily offer the g-pawn and get our king to safety. White is in trouble here, as the attack against his king cannot be stopped.} 17. fxg7 h5 18. Qg3 h4 {We offer the h-pawn to open up files for our rooks. Black is going to have all the fun attacking White's king. The engine also jumps with joy, giving us an almost -1 advantage!} ({Qg4} 18... Qa5 $1 {First, we drive away the bishop.} 19. Bb2 (19. Bf8 {White holds on to the g7 –pawn but loses c3 .} Qxc3 20. Rad1 {h3! A cool idea to open up the g-file. Qxh3} ({( g3 f5} 20. Qh3 Nxd4 {)}) {Qxh3 gxh3} 20... Rdxf8 {White can't take on rook due to the pin.}) 19... Qf5 $1 {This queen trade favors us since we win the g7 –pawn. Qxf5 exf5 and Black wins g7 next, with a big edge.}) *

