hite is about to get the bishop pair, which is a long-term asset. Thus, we need to get our counterplay going quickly.} 6. Ng3 {This is a more ambitious plan as White doesn't mind doubling their pawns after ... Bxc3 + bxc3 .} Bxc3+ {We take the opportunity to weaken White's pawn structure.} 7. bxc3 d5 {Black doesn't mind eliminating White's doubled pawn as long as the light-squared bishops are traded.} 8. Qf3 {A natural move, using a tactic on the diagonal to stop our idea of taking on c4 . This was played by Nakamura vs. Caruana at Norway Chess 2024.} O-O {It's always nice to be the first one to castle!} 9. cxd5 Bxf1 {Initially, the engine doesn't like this move at all, giving a close to +1 advantage. But trust me, Black is totally fine! This is incredibly deep prep by the former World Champion Challenger!} ({If you're an ambitious player and don't shy away from complications, then I recommend Caruana's approach with . However, I also give a much simpler line with} 9... Qxd5 {.}) 10. dxe6 {This is the most principled, of course! Now, Black is ready to sacrifice the rook on a8 .} Bc4 {Please take my rook!} 11. Qxa8 Nd5 {The key move with the idea of trapping White's queen.} 12. e4 a6 {A brilliant, quiet move, locking in the lady in the corner! Once the engine sees this idea, the eval drops dramatically, close to zero. But the complexity remains! The position is rich in possibilities.} 13. exd5 Bxd5 14. Qa7 fxe6 15. O-O {This natural move loses to a cool trick.} Qc8 {A simple idea to trap the queen, now ... Nc6 cannot be stopped, winning the lady.} *

