1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein Variation. White is not worried about Black taking on c3 and doubling the pawns for now. Instead, White aims for a solid setup either with 5.Bd3 & Nge2 or 5.Bd3 & Nf3 or the immediate 5.Nge2 .} {Luckily, my original recommendation from Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time, and I would recommend it for this course as well, b6! Of course, I did a complete overhaul and have lots of improvements ready for you!} b6 ({We answer White's slow play with a sound idea of developing our light-squared bishop. If White plays for Nge2 & a3 , we develop the bishop to a6 to challenge White on the f1 - a6 diagonal.   If White goes for a classical setup with Bd3 & Nf3 or Bd3 & Nge2 , we fianchetto the bishop on b7 . The good news is that this line still hasn't gained as much popularity as the autopilot move} 4... O-O {, thus it is likely your opponent may be less prepared.   These days Caruana has championed this move on multiple occasions. He famously used it to win a mini-match vs GM Nakamura at Norway Chess 2024 (Hikaru escaped with a draw in classical but lost in Armageddon). Knowing that Caruana plays this line is the highest stamp of approval!}) 5. Nge2 ({In the Master Database, this move is almost 3 times more common than} 5. Bd3 {, so make sure to be ready for it! White's idea to play a3 next and obtain the bishop pair 'for free', meaning that they don't want to ruin their pawn structure with bxc3 .}) 5... Ba6 {We have to act fast as White is about to get the bishop pair, which is a long-term asset. Thus, we need to get our counterplay going quickly.} 6. Ng3 {This is a more ambitious plan as White doesn't mind doubling their pawns after ... Bxc3 + bxc3 .} Bxc3+ {We take the opportunity to weaken White's pawn structure.} 7. bxc3 d5 {Black doesn't mind eliminating White's doubled pawn as long as the light-squared bishops are traded.} 8. Qf3 {A natural move, using a tactic on the diagonal to stop our idea of taking on c4 . This was played by Nakamura vs. Caruana at Norway Chess 2024.} O-O {It's always nice to be the first one to castle!} 9. cxd5 Qxd5 ({This is a much easier option to learn if you want to avoid memorizing Caruana's} 9... Bxf1 $5 {and the crazy complications that follow from} 10. dxe6 {.}) 10. e4 Qa5 ({Black gets a comfortable position, as there light-squared bishops will get traded. Let's look at both Bxa6 and} 10... Be2 {.}) ({Keep in mind that} 10... e5 {is met with the simple Nd5!}) 11. Bxa6 Qxa6 {We stop White from castling and prepare to reinforce our f6 -knight with ... Nbd7 next.} 12. Bg5 ({Again,} 12. e5 {is easily met with} Nd5 $1) 12... Nbd7 {Black is first to finish development while White can't castle.} 13. Qe2 {A sad necessity, White has to abandon any ambition and try to safeguard their king.} Qa3 {The ambitious choice, as we want to keep the queen to put pressure on White's c3 - & a2 -pawns, but there's nothing wrong with trading into an equal endgame.} 14. Rc1 c5 {We start chipping away at White's center.} 15. O-O h6 {Kicking back the bishop or offering a good trade. Plus, it's a nice to get luft for our king.} 16. Be3 {White keeps the bishop as generally they want to avoid trades in these structures.} cxd4 17. cxd4 Rac8 {We've reached a balanced position where White has to be careful, as long term, our a7 - and b6 -pawns could give us a strong passer. Plus, White's a2 -pawn is quite weak.} ({At the moment, White's center is not dangerous at all, since} 17... e5 {is met with Nd5 .}) *

