{Conclusion:  The Rubinstein Variation Ne2 is met with active piece play with . In both a3 and Ng3 , Black takes on c3 and strikes White's center with ... d5 ! We always welcome the trade of the light-squared bishops and often don't mind giving White the pawn center ( e4 , d4 ) in order to undermine it with ... c5 ! If White chooses Nf4 , we also take on c3 , but instead of ... d5 , we continue piece play with Nc6! Bd3 e5! Again, the light-squared bishops will most likely get traded, with an excellent position for Black.  Keep in mind, once the light-squared bishops come off, most endgames are totally fine for us.} 1. Z0 *

