1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein Variation. White is not worried about Black taking on c3 and doubling the pawns for now. Instead, White aims for a solid setup either with 5.Bd3 & Nge2 or 5.Bd3 & Nf3 or the immediate 5.Nge2 .} {Luckily, my original recommendation from Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time, and I would recommend it for this course as well, b6! Of course, I did a complete overhaul and have lots of improvements ready for you!} b6 ({We answer White's slow play with a sound idea of developing our light-squared bishop. If White plays for Nge2 & a3 , we develop the bishop to a6 to challenge White on the f1 - a6 diagonal.   If White goes for a classical setup with Bd3 & Nf3 or Bd3 & Nge2 , we fianchetto the bishop on b7 . The good news is that this line still hasn't gained as much popularity as the autopilot move} 4... O-O {, thus it is likely your opponent may be less prepared.   These days Caruana has championed this move on multiple occasions. He famously used it to win a mini-match vs GM Nakamura at Norway Chess 2024 (Hikaru escaped with a draw in classical but lost in Armageddon). Knowing that Caruana plays this line is the highest stamp of approval!}) 5. Bd3 {White is going for classical development, and is not worried about ... Bxc3 + for now.} Bb7 6. Nge2 {This is a less popular move, as White sacrifices the g2 -pawn. However, it's not without venom, as we saw recently when GM Giri faced this move at the 2024 Olympiad and lost with Black.} Bxg2 {We are brave and take the pawn!} 7. Rg1 Bf3 {The most precise. Now, White has to deal with two pins!} 8. Rxg7 {White is eager to win the pawn back, but this enables Black to quickly seize the initiative.} (8. b3 {is met by} Nc6 $1) 8... Nh5 {Kicking back the rook.} ({This is even stronger than} 8... Ng4 {.}) 9. Rg1 Bxc3+ {Let's ruin White's pawn structure first.} 10. bxc3 Qh4 {Black is fully in control now, as the h2 -pawn will fall. Our plan is to develop with ... Nc6 & ... O-O-O next. White, on the other hand, has difficulty finishing development, as they need to make 3 moves to castle long.} *

