1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein Variation. White is not worried about Black taking on c3 and doubling the pawns for now. Instead, White aims for a solid setup either with 5.Bd3 & Nge2 or 5.Bd3 & Nf3 or the immediate 5.Nge2 .} {Luckily, my original recommendation from Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time, and I would recommend it for this course as well, b6! Of course, I did a complete overhaul and have lots of improvements ready for you!} b6 ({We answer White's slow play with a sound idea of developing our light-squared bishop. If White plays for Nge2 & a3 , we develop the bishop to a6 to challenge White on the f1 - a6 diagonal.   If White goes for a classical setup with Bd3 & Nf3 or Bd3 & Nge2 , we fianchetto the bishop on b7 . The good news is that this line still hasn't gained as much popularity as the autopilot move} 4... O-O {, thus it is likely your opponent may be less prepared.   These days Caruana has championed this move on multiple occasions. He famously used it to win a mini-match vs GM Nakamura at Norway Chess 2024 (Hikaru escaped with a draw in classical but lost in Armageddon). Knowing that Caruana plays this line is the highest stamp of approval!}) 5. Bd3 {White is going for classical development, and is not worried about ... Bxc3 + for now.} Bb7 6. Nge2 {This is a less popular move, as White sacrifices the g2 -pawn. However, it's not without venom, as we saw recently when GM Giri faced this move at the 2024 Olympiad and lost with Black.} Bxg2 {We are brave and take the pawn!} 7. Rg1 Bf3 {The most precise. Now, White has to deal with two pins!} 8. Rg3 {White immediately tries to break the pin. This was seen in Lodici-Giri, Chess Olympiad 2024.} Bxc3+ {I like Giri's idea to ruin White's pawn structure first.} ({This is even better than} 8... Bh5 {, as White gets to play for e4 next.}) 9. bxc3 Be4 {Excellent opening prep from Anish Giri. It's important to trade a pair of bishops to reduce White's attacking potential.} 10. Qc2 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Nh5 {The knight hits the rook with a tempo and guards the g7 -pawn.} ({Black could also play} 11... g6 {followed by ... Nh5 , which would transpose.}) 12. Rh3 g6 13. e4 {White takes over the center and opens up his c1 -bishop. However, I believe White's compensation is good for equality at best, as Black has several promising setups. Let me share my improvement on Giri's play.} e5 ({There's nothing wrong with Giri's} 13... d6 {, which is a solid approach. However, we're trying to strike the center and save a tempo on ... d6 .}) 14. dxe5 {An ugly move, but the engine thinks it's objectively best.} (14. d5 $2 {is positional suicide after} Na6 $1 {, and our knight is heading to c5 .}) 14... Qe7 15. Be3 Nc6 ({Not} 15... Qxe5 $2 {due to .}) 16. f4 Qe6 {Now, White's rook is looking odd on h3 .} 17. Bf2 (17. Bd4 {could be met with} O-O-O {.}) 17... d6 {Black has many other good moves, but I like the simplicity of this approach. We take the game into a favorable endgame.} 18. exd6 Qxd6 19. Qxd6 ({Moving the queen with something like} 19. Qc2 {doesn't make sense for White as after} O-O-O {, our king is safe on c8 while White's king is stuck in the center.}) 19... cxd6 20. O-O-O O-O-O {While the material is even, it's clear that White has more pawn weaknesses than Black. We will target White's pawns with ... Rhe8 and ... Na5 next.} *

