1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein Variation. White is not worried about Black taking on c3 and doubling the pawns for now. Instead, White aims for a solid setup either with 5.Bd3 & Nge2 or 5.Bd3 & Nf3 or the immediate 5.Nge2 .} {Luckily, my original recommendation from Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time, and I would recommend it for this course as well, b6! Of course, I did a complete overhaul and have lots of improvements ready for you!} b6 ({We answer White's slow play with a sound idea of developing our light-squared bishop. If White plays for Nge2 & a3 , we develop the bishop to a6 to challenge White on the f1 - a6 diagonal.   If White goes for a classical setup with Bd3 & Nf3 or Bd3 & Nge2 , we fianchetto the bishop on b7 . The good news is that this line still hasn't gained as much popularity as the autopilot move} 4... O-O {, thus it is likely your opponent may be less prepared.   These days Caruana has championed this move on multiple occasions. He famously used it to win a mini-match vs GM Nakamura at Norway Chess 2024 (Hikaru escaped with a draw in classical but lost in Armageddon). Knowing that Caruana plays this line is the highest stamp of approval!}) 5. Bd3 {White is going for classical development, and is not worried about ... Bxc3 + for now.} Bb7 6. f3 {A somewhat rare move. White tries to blunt our b7 -bishop and play e4 next.} c5 {We strike the center before White gets a chance to play e4 .} 7. a3 {White forces us to take on c3 . Now, the game is similar to the Sämisch Variation 4.a3 .} Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nc6 {We develop naturally while keeping an eye on the center. Please note that the knight is heading to a5 soon.} 9. Ne2 {Here, Black has many different ideas. However, I recommend the simple plan of ... Na5 and ... Ba6 , which we already covered in the Sämisch Variation.} Na5 10. e4 Ba6 {Now, the c4 -pawn is about to drop.} 11. e5 (11. Qa4 $2 {is too slow and Black is better after .}) 11... Ng8 12. O-O Bxc4 (12... Bxc4 {Nxc4 Qd3 Na5} 13. f4 f5 $1 {An important idea to slow down White's attack.} 14. exf6 $2 {This only speeds up our development.} Nxf6 15. f5 Nb3 16. Rb1 Nxc1 17. Rxc1 O-O {and Black is just a pawn up.}) *

