{The Rubinstein with 5.Bd3 & Nge2 is an aggressive but risky setup, and we should take the pawn with Bxg2! The key idea is to meet Rg1 with Bf3! , setting up another pin. We are never worried about White winning back the pawn with Rxg7 , as Black gets huge counterplay with ... Nh5 ! and ... Qh4 . Remember the cool novelty e5! , improving on Lodici-Giri, and taking over the initiative.  In general, once you have studied these lines carefully, you will have the confidence to punish White for this risky setup.} 1. Z0 *

