1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein Variation. White is not worried about Black taking on c3 and doubling the pawns for now. Instead, White aims for a solid setup either with 5.Bd3 & Nge2 or 5.Bd3 & Nf3 or the immediate 5.Nge2 .} {Luckily, my original recommendation from Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time, and I would recommend it for this course as well, b6! Of course, I did a complete overhaul and have lots of improvements ready for you!} b6 {We answer White's slow play with a sound idea of activating our light-squared bishop. If White plays for 5. Nge2 & a3 we develop the bishop to a6 to challenge White on the f1 - a6 diagonal. If White goes for a classical setup with Bd3 / Nf3 or Bd3 / Nge2 we fianchetto the bishop on b7 .   The good news is that this line still hasn't gained as much popularity as the autopilot move 4... O-O , thus it is likely your opponent may be less prepared.   These days Caruana has championed this move on multiple occasions. He famously used it to win a mini-match vs GM Nakamura as Norway Chess 2024 (Hikaru escaped with a draw in classical but lost in Armageddon). Knowing that Caruana plays this line is the highest stamp of approval!} 5. Bd3 {White is going for classical development, and is not worried about ... Bxc3 + for now.} Bb7 6. Nf3 {White's most popular setup. They are going for rapid development, aiming to castle quickly. The drawback is, of course, that we can double their pawns with Bxc3+ .} O-O 7. O-O Bxc3 {This is my preferred choice, as I believe it fits our general strategy of establishing a clear pawn weakness and attacking it next.} 8. bxc3 {Now, White's pawn structure is ruined, but it's not easy to attack it yet. Therefore, we continue with normal development.} c5 {We apply the well-known positional motif of 'fixing' the double pawns, i.e., blocking them with our pawn to make them immobile.  White's main plan is to prepare e4 , which they can do with Nd2 , Qe2 , or Re1 . We will examine all of these options.} 9. Qe2 {White is ready to play e4 next, which means it's time for ... Ne4 !} Ne4 {An instructive idea!} 10. Ne1 {White is ready to kick our knight with f3 , but we use this opportunity to strike in the center.} d5 {Normally, we avoid moves like these, as they help White undouble their pawns. However, here it works because White's pieces are poorly coordinated.} ({An alternative is} 10... f5 11. f3 Nd6 {, which leads to a solid position for Black.}) 11. cxd5 Nxc3 {A nice intermezzo!} 12. Qc2 Nxd5 {We sacrifice the h7 -pawn!} 13. Bxh7+ Kh8 14. Be4 Nd7 {I believe that our activity and better development compensates the h7 -pawn.} 15. Bb2 Rc8 {Black uses an X-ray to put pressure on White's queen.} 16. Qe2 Kg8 {Stopping a basic two-move mate.} 17. Rc1 (17. Qh5 {gets nowhere after .}) 17... c4 {We now have 3 pawns vs 1 on the queenside, with a serious initiative.} ({I like this even more than} 17... cxd4 $5 {, which is not bad either.}) ({Now, Rxc4 drops the exchange after} 17... Ba6 {Rxc8 Bxe2 Rxd8 Rxd8-+}) *

