referred choice, as I believe it fits our general strategy of establishing a clear pawn weakness and attacking it next.} 8. bxc3 {Now, White's pawn structure is ruined, but it's not easy to attack it yet. Therefore, we continue with normal development.} c5 {We apply the well-known positional motif of 'fixing' the double pawns, i.e., blocking them with our pawn to make them immobile.  White's main plan is to prepare e4 , which they can do with Nd2 , Qe2 , or Re1 . We will examine all of these options.} 9. Nd2 {White's main idea is to play for e4 and mobilize their center.} Nc6 {We develop and apply extra pressure on the d-pawn. Now, White can either overprotect the d-pawn with Nb3 or Bb2 , or sacrifice a pawn with e4!? .} 10. e4 {This is White's most ambitious option, but not without its risks, since they give up the central pawn.} cxd4 11. cxd4 Nxd4 {The most principled approach. We ask White to demonstrate their compensation for the central pawn.} 12. e5 {The most direct, opening up their bishop with tempo and hitting our knight.} ({Please note that slow moves like} 12. Bb2 {are met with} e5 $1) 12... Ne8 {The only move, but solid. Now, time is of the essence. Can White create some threats before their initiative fizzles out?} 13. Ba3 {White is attacking our rook, but are they really?} f5 {A nice positional exchange sacrifice in the style of the great Tigran Petrosian, the former World Champion who pioneered positional exchange sacrifices.} 14. Bxf8 Qg5 {An important intermezzo to activate our queen.} 15. f3 {The only move.} Qe3+ 16. Kh1 Qxd3 {We get some material back. For now, Black has a pawn for the exchange.} 17. Be7 Nc2 {This wins the exchange back by force.} 18. Nb3 Qxd1 19. Raxd1 Ne3 20. Rxd7 Bc6 21. Rdd1 Nxf1 22. Rxf1 Kf7 23. Bb4 (23. Bh4 {is met with} Rc8 $1 {, with the idea to put pressure on the c4 -pawn.}) 23... Rd8 {The dust has settled and it's clear that Black has a pleasant endgame. We control the only open file and will try to create a second weakness with ... g5 .} *

