1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. e3 {This is called the Rubinstein Variation. White is not worried about Black taking on c3 and doubling the pawns for now. Instead, White aims for a solid setup either with 5.Bd3 & Nge2 or 5.Bd3 & Nf3 or the immediate 5.Nge2 .} {Luckily, my original recommendation from Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time, and I would recommend it for this course as well, b6! Of course, I did a complete overhaul and have lots of improvements ready for you!} b6 {We answer White's slow play with a sound idea of activating our light-squared bishop. If White plays for 5. Nge2 & a3 we develop the bishop to a6 to challenge White on the f1 - a6 diagonal. If White goes for a classical setup with Bd3 / Nf3 or Bd3 / Nge2 we fianchetto the bishop on b7 .   The good news is that this line still hasn't gained as much popularity as the autopilot move 4... O-O , thus it is likely your opponent may be less prepared.   These days Caruana has championed this move on multiple occasions. He famously used it to win a mini-match vs GM Nakamura as Norway Chess 2024 (Hikaru escaped with a draw in classical but lost in Armageddon). Knowing that Caruana plays this line is the highest stamp of approval!} 5. Bd3 {White is going for classical development, and is not worried about ... Bxc3 + for now.} Bb7 6. Nf3 {White's most popular setup. They are going for rapid development, aiming to castle quickly. The drawback is, of course, that we can double their pawns with Bxc3+ .} O-O 7. O-O Bxc3 {This is my preferred choice, as I believe it fits our general strategy of establishing a clear pawn weakness and attacking it next.} 8. bxc3 {Now, White's pawn structure is ruined, but it's not easy to attack it yet. Therefore, we continue with normal development.} c5 {We apply the well-known positional motif of 'fixing' the double pawns, i.e., blocking them with our pawn to make them immobile.  White's main plan is to prepare e4 , which they can do with Nd2 , Qe2 , or Re1 . We will examine all of these options.} 9. Nd2 {White's main idea is to play for e4 and mobilize their center.} Nc6 {We develop and apply extra pressure on the d-pawn. Now, White can either overprotect the d-pawn with Nb3 or Bb2 , or sacrifice a pawn with e4!? .} 10. e4 {This is White's most ambitious option, but not without its risks, since they give up the central pawn.} cxd4 11. cxd4 Nxd4 {The most principled approach. We ask White to demonstrate their compensation for the central pawn.} 12. e5 {The most direct, opening up their bishop with tempo and hitting our knight.} ({Please note that slow moves like} 12. Bb2 {are met with} e5 $1) 12... Ne8 {The only move, but solid. Now, time is of the essence. Can White create some threats before their initiative fizzles out?} 13. Qh5 {A straightforward move, but we have a simple defense.} f5 {Remember this defensive idea!} (13... g6 $2 {would be too weakening and too slow.}) 14. exf6 Nxf6 {The knight is back, baby! It's now perfectly placed to defend our king.} 15. Qh3 {This move steps out of ... Nf5 , but Black has many other strong ideas.} Qc7 16. Ba3 Rf7 17. Rae1 e5 {White may have some compensation for the pawn due to the bishop pair, but I believe our strong knight, supported by the e5 -pawn, gives us the easier game.} *

