referred choice, as I believe it fits our general strategy of establishing a clear pawn weakness and attacking it next.} 8. bxc3 {Now, White's pawn structure is ruined, but it's not easy to attack it yet. Therefore, we continue with normal development.} c5 {We apply the well-known positional motif of 'fixing' the double pawns, i.e., blocking them with our pawn to make them immobile.  White's main plan is to prepare e4 , which they can do with Nd2 , Qe2 , or Re1 . We will examine all of these options.} 9. Nd2 {White's main idea is to play for e4 and mobilize their center.} Nc6 {We develop and apply extra pressure on the d-pawn. Now, White can either overprotect the d-pawn with Nb3 or Bb2 , or sacrifice a pawn with e4!? .} 10. e4 {This is White's most ambitious option, but not without its risks, since they give up the central pawn.} cxd4 11. cxd4 Nxd4 {The most principled approach. We ask White to demonstrate their compensation for the central pawn.} 12. e5 {The most direct, opening up their bishop with tempo and hitting our knight.} ({Please note that slow moves like} 12. Bb2 {are met with} e5 $1) 12... Ne8 {The only move, but solid. Now, time is of the essence. Can White create some threats before their initiative fizzles out?} 13. Qh5 {A straightforward move, but we have a simple defense.} f5 {Remember this defensive idea!} (13... g6 $2 {would be too weakening and too slow.}) 14. exf6 Nxf6 {The knight is back, baby! It's now perfectly placed to defend our king.} 15. Qh4 Nf5 {Now ... Nf5 comes with tempo.} 16. Qh3 {Taking on f5 would only help us, as White will be down a pawn for nothing.} Qc7 {A clever move that connects our rooks and sets a small trap in case White is eager to win back the pawn.} 17. Bxf5 {This falls right into our trap!} exf5 18. Qxf5 Nd5 {A nice discovered attack. Now, no matter where White retreats with the queen, Black will follow up with ... Nf4 !, setting up a deadly attack.} 19. Qg4 Nf4 {Now, our pieces work together like clockwork. The engine already gives a winning edge of -3 here!} *

