referred choice, as I believe it fits our general strategy of establishing a clear pawn weakness and attacking it next.} 8. bxc3 {Now, White's pawn structure is ruined, but it's not easy to attack it yet. Therefore, we continue with normal development.} c5 {We apply the well-known positional motif of 'fixing' the double pawns, i.e., blocking them with our pawn to make them immobile.  White's main plan is to prepare e4 , which they can do with Nd2 , Qe2 , or Re1 . We will examine all of these options.} 9. Nd2 {White's main idea is to play for e4 and mobilize their center.} Nc6 {We develop and apply extra pressure on the d-pawn. Now, White can either overprotect the d-pawn with Nb3 or Bb2 , or sacrifice a pawn with e4!? .} 10. Nb3 {White overprotects d4 and gets ready to play e4 next.} d6 {We protect our c5 -pawn.} 11. e4 {White achieves the central grab, but now we have a very nice idea.} a5 {Please remember this little pawn move! We have a direct threat of ... a4 next.} 12. a4 {White stops our idea, but weakens the b4 -square.} cxd4 13. cxd4 Nb4 {The key idea! Now both the e4 -pawn and the bishop are under attack.} 14. d5 Ba6 {Black is fine. We will follow up with ... Rc8 to target the c4 -pawn and can take the bishop on d3 at any moment.} *

