1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. a3 {This is the most direct way to deal with the pin, known as the Sämisch Variation, named after the German chess player and theoretician Friedrich Sämisch.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {We have a classic imbalance in chess: White gets a bishop pair and a strong center (with f3 & e4 next), but at the cost of doubled pawns.} b6 {It's very important for Black to attack the c4 -pawn as quickly as possible with ... Nc6 , ... Ba6 & ... Na5 next. Some rules of thumb to remember:   1) Don't castle short early! As a matter of fact, we often leave our king in the center or castle queenside.   2) Don't play an early ... d5 pawn push, as this will only help White to undouble the pawns.} ({Please note that} 5... Nc6 6. f3 b6 {will transpose .}) 6. e4 {This rare pawn move has only been played on a few occasions. White wants to meet Nxe4 with Qg4 , but let me show you a simple line that leads to a pleasant endgame for us.} Nxe4 7. Qg4 f5 {We secure the knight and invite White to take the g7 -pawn.} 8. Qxg7 Qf6 {Simple and strong. White can't avoid the queen trade.} 9. Qxf6 Nxf6 {I believe White's bishop pair is not enough compensation for their ruined pawn structure. We will play the typical plan of ... Nc6 , ... Ba6 , and ... Na5 , targeting the c4 -pawn.} *

