1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. a3 {This is the most direct way to deal with the pin, known as the Sämisch Variation, named after the German chess player and theoretician Friedrich Sämisch.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {We have a classic imbalance in chess: White gets a bishop pair and a strong center (with f3 & e4 next) but at the cost of doubled pawns.} b6 {It's very important for Black to attack the c4 -pawn as quickly as possible with ... Nc6 , ... Ba6 & ... Na5 next. Some rules of thumb to remember:   1) Don't castle short early! As a matter of fact we often leave our king in the center or castle queenside.   2) Don't play an early ... d5 pawn push, as this will only help White to undouble the pawns. Please note that 5... Nc6 6. f3  b6 will transpose.} 6. f3 {White is getting ready to play e4 to build the big center.} ({Please note that if White doesn’t fight for the center with moves like} 6. Nf3 {or e3 , our plan is the same: play …Nc6, …Ba6, and …Na5, targeting the c4 -pawn.}) 6... Nc6 ({We could also start with} 6... Ba6 {first, as it would transpose after} 7. e4 Nc6 {.}) 7. e4 Ba6 {White has achieved the goal of grabbing the center, but notice that all of their pieces are still on the initial row, while we already developed 3 minor pieces and about to play ... Na5 next.} ({Here White has three ways to continue: Bg5 , going for the pin, Bd3 with the idea to meet} 7... Na5 {with} 8. Qe2 {,  or} e5 {, going for even more space.}) 8. Be3 {This logical move allows us to demonstrate our plan.} Na5 {Hitting the c4 -pawn, White's reply is more or less forced.} 9. Qa4 {The queen has to babysit the pawn, not a good sign!} O-O {Now that White's queen is in no man's land, we can safely castle.} 10. Bd3 d5 {We break open the center and White's position totally collapses. The engine already gives Black a winning edge! This is the real danger White can face in this opening.} *

