1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. a3 {This is the most direct way to deal with the pin, known as the Sämisch Variation, named after the German chess player and theoretician Friedrich Sämisch.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {We have a classic imbalance in chess: White gets a bishop pair and a strong center (with f3 & e4 next) but at the cost of doubled pawns.} b6 {It's very important for Black to attack the c4 -pawn as quickly as possible with ... Nc6 , ... Ba6 & ... Na5 next. Some rules of thumb to remember:   1) Don't castle short early! As a matter of fact we often leave our king in the center or castle queenside.   2) Don't play an early ... d5 pawn push, as this will only help White to undouble the pawns. Please note that 5... Nc6 6. f3  b6 will transpose.} 6. f3 {White is getting ready to play e4 to build the big center.} ({Please note that if White doesn’t fight for the center with moves like} 6. Nf3 {or e3 , our plan is the same: play …Nc6, …Ba6, and …Na5, targeting the c4 -pawn.}) 6... Nc6 ({We could also start with} 6... Ba6 {first, as it would transpose after} 7. e4 Nc6 {.}) 7. e4 Ba6 {White has achieved the goal of grabbing the center, but notice that all of their pieces are still on the initial row, while we already developed 3 minor pieces and about to play ... Na5 next.} ({Here White has three ways to continue: Bg5 , going for the pin, Bd3 with the idea to meet} 7... Na5 {with} 8. Qe2 {,  or} e5 {, going for even more space.}) 8. Bg5 {This is the preferred setup by some of the top GMs. Recently, Firouzja tried it against Magnus.} h6 {Asking the bishop its intentions.} ({I like it a bit more than originally recommended} 8... Qc8 {, as it gives our knight an extra option to retreat to h7 after e5 .}) 9. Bh4 ({We, of course, welcome the} 9. Bxf6 $2 Qxf6 {trade, as White gives up his major trump, the bishop pair!}) 9... Qc8 {This original idea from Dzindzi withstood the test of time and is still one of the top moves! The point is to break the pin without compromising our pawn structure with ... g5 , while preparing a cool idea to get our queen involved in attacking the c4 -pawn.} 10. Bxf6 gxf6 {I believe that this trade favors Black, as it's not easy for attack Black's kingside weaknesses since we didn't castle.} 11. Bd3 Na5 12. Qe2 c5 ({This is even stronger than} 12... Qb7 {, as we are threatening to win the pawn with ... cxd4 & ... Bxc4 .}) 13. d5 Qc7 {Getting ready to castle queenside.} 14. Nh3 O-O-O 15. O-O f5 {We get a big attack, since we have the half-open g-file for our rooks. White, on the other hand, can't get to our king at all!} ({Here's an example how White can get into trouble: exf5 exf5! We open the e-file. Rae1} 15... Rde8 $1 {We don't mind trading 2 rooks for the queen. Qxe8 Rxe8 Rxe8+ Kb7 The resulting imbalance is in our favor, since the c4 -pawn drops and White's rooks will be dominated by Black's queen.}) *

