st Magnus.} h6 {Asking the bishop its intentions.} ({I like it a bit more than originally recommended} 8... Qc8 {, as it gives our knight an extra option to retreat to h7 after e5 .}) 9. Bh4 ({We, of course, welcome the} 9. Bxf6 $2 Qxf6 {trade, as White gives up his major trump, the bishop pair!}) 9... Qc8 {This original idea from Dzindzi withstood the test of time and is still one of the top moves! The point is to break the pin without compromising our pawn structure with ... g5 , while preparing a cool idea to get our queen involved in attacking the c4 -pawn.} 10. Bd3 ({White goes for typical development, intending to meet Na5 with} 10. Qe2 {.}) 10... Na5 11. Qe2 Qb7 {This was the idea behind ... Qc8 ; our queen is heading to c6 .} 12. e5 {You may wonder, won't Be4 be really annoying?} Nh5 {The best square for the knight, now ... Nf4 is a serious threat.} 13. Be4 c6 ({Simple chess. We stop White's threat and their position totally collapses as the c4 -pawn can't be protected since Bd3 is met by} 13... Nf4 $1) *

