1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. a3 {This is the most direct way to deal with the pin, known as the Sämisch Variation, named after the German chess player and theoretician Friedrich Sämisch.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {We have a classic imbalance in chess: White gets a bishop pair and a strong center (with f3 & e4 next) but at the cost of doubled pawns.} b6 {It's very important for Black to attack the c4 -pawn as quickly as possible with ... Nc6 , ... Ba6 & ... Na5 next. Some rules of thumb to remember:   1) Don't castle short early! As a matter of fact we often leave our king in the center or castle queenside.   2) Don't play an early ... d5 pawn push, as this will only help White to undouble the pawns. Please note that 5... Nc6 6. f3  b6 will transpose.} 6. f3 {White is getting ready to play e4 to build the big center.} ({Please note that if White doesn’t fight for the center with moves like} 6. Nf3 {or e3 , our plan is the same: play …Nc6, …Ba6, and …Na5, targeting the c4 -pawn.}) 6... Nc6 ({We could also start with} 6... Ba6 {first, as it would transpose after} 7. e4 Nc6 {.}) 7. e4 Ba6 {White has achieved the goal of grabbing the center, but notice that all of their pieces are still on the initial row, while we already developed 3 minor pieces and about to play ... Na5 next.} ({Here White has three ways to continue: Bg5 , going for the pin, Bd3 with the idea to meet} 7... Na5 {with} 8. Qe2 {,  or} e5 {, going for even more space.}) 8. Bg5 {This is the preferred setup by some of the top GMs. Recently, Firouzja tried it against Magnus.} h6 {Asking the bishop its intentions.} ({I like it a bit more than originally recommended} 8... Qc8 {, as it gives our knight an extra option to retreat to h7 after e5 .}) 9. Bh4 ({We, of course, welcome the} 9. Bxf6 $2 Qxf6 {trade, as White gives up his major trump, the bishop pair!}) 9... Qc8 {This original idea from Dzindzi withstood the test of time and is still one of the top moves! The point is to break the pin without compromising our pawn structure with ... g5 , while preparing a cool idea to get our queen involved in attacking the c4 -pawn.} 10. Bd3 ({White goes for typical development, intending to meet Na5 with} 10. Qe2 {.}) 10... Na5 11. Qe2 Qb7 {This was the idea behind ... Qc8 ; our queen is heading to c6 .} 12. Rb1 {This interesting move was tried by GM Salem vs So in a recent TT blitz game in 2023.} Qc6 {Simple and strong.} ({I don't like Wesley's} 12... Nh5 $2 {, as it speeds up White's development after} 13. Nh3 Qc6 14. d5 $1 Qc5 15. Bf2 $1 Qxa3 16. O-O {, with a big initiative.}) 13. d5 Qc5 14. Bf2 {White sacrifices the pawn, but I don't think he has enough.} ({Better is} 14. Rb4 O-O {, but even here, White's natural moves get him in trouble. For example:} 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Nh3 {loses to} exd5 $1 {And now either recapture leads to material loss for White:} 17. exd5 Rfe8 {or cxd5 Qxc3+ .}) 14... Qxa3 {Hitting the c3 -pawn as well.} 15. Bd4 d6 {Now ... e5 is a big threat.} 16. f4 c5 {Forcing matters.} 17. dxc6 e5 18. fxe5 dxe5 19. Bxe5 Nxc6 20. Bxf6 gxf6 {The engine already gives Black a winning edge! We will castle long next while White is still stuck with a weak c3 -pawn and a poor king on e1 .} *

