1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. a3 {This is the most direct way to deal with the pin, known as the Sämisch Variation, named after the German chess player and theoretician Friedrich Sämisch.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {We have a classic imbalance in chess: White gets a bishop pair and a strong center (with f3 & e4 next) but at the cost of doubled pawns.} b6 {It's very important for Black to attack the c4 -pawn as quickly as possible with ... Nc6 , ... Ba6 & ... Na5 next. Some rules of thumb to remember:   1) Don't castle short early! As a matter of fact we often leave our king in the center or castle queenside.   2) Don't play an early ... d5 pawn push, as this will only help White to undouble the pawns. Please note that 5... Nc6 6. f3  b6 will transpose.} 6. f3 {White is getting ready to play e4 to build the big center.} ({Please note that if White doesn’t fight for the center with moves like} 6. Nf3 {or e3 , our plan is the same: play …Nc6, …Ba6, and …Na5, targeting the c4 -pawn.}) 6... Nc6 ({We could also start with} 6... Ba6 {first, as it would transpose after} 7. e4 Nc6 {.}) 7. e4 Ba6 {White has achieved the goal of grabbing the center, but notice that all of their pieces are still on the initial row, while we already developed 3 minor pieces and about to play ... Na5 next.} ({Here White has three ways to continue: Bg5 , going for the pin, Bd3 with the idea to meet} 7... Na5 {with} 8. Qe2 {,  or} e5 {, going for even more space.}) 8. e5 {An ambitious space grab, but I believe that White is getting in danger of being overextended after moving a pawn again for the 7th (!) time in 8 moves} Ng8 9. Nh3 Na5 {Already White is facing difficulties defending the c4 -pawn.} 10. Qa4 Ne7 ({I believe this is even stronger than the usual} 10... Qc8 {.}) 11. Bd3 O-O {We are not afraid to castle, as White's B+N combo is not enough to cause us serious problems.} 12. Ng5 h6 {Simple chess! White's attack is easily repelled. Here are some example lines:} ({Nh7} 12... Re8 {Bxh6 gxh6 Nf6+ Kh8 Nxe8 Qxe8-+ White runs out of attacking potential and Black's minor pieces will dominate the game. For example:} 13. O-O d5 14. Qxe8+ {Rxe8 and the c4 -pawn falls.}) ({Bh7+} 12... Kh8 13. Bb1 f5 $1 {(Taking the knight is risky due to hxg5 h4! )} 14. exf6 Rxf6 15. h4 Bxc4 $1 {Black wins a pawn and just ignores White's knight.} 16. Qc2 Qg8 $1 {No need to panic, everything is under control.}) ({h4 hxg5 hxg5} 12... g6 {Black will play ... Kg7 and ... Rh8 next.}) *

