n the original book recommendation of} 9... Qc8 {, since after} 10. e5 Ng8 {, White can get a big initiative with} 11. Nh3 $1) ({For those who like to explore more forcing lines, I can also recommend} 9... c5 $5 {.}) 10. f4 {White's most popular move, with the idea to play Nf3 next.} d5 {This unusual idea is an important novelty! It seems counterintuitive to play ... d6 first and then ... d5 , giving a tempo, but chess is a concrete game! The point is to take advantage of White's weakened light squares.} 11. exd5 Qe7 {The key move to remember, we are getting ready to trade queens!} 12. dxe6 Qxe6 13. Qxe6+ fxe6 {White has an extra pawn, but it is only temporary, as c4 will be lost.} 14. Nf3 O-O ({We are not rushing to take on c4 yet, but of course, there's nothing wrong with} 14... Bxc4 {right away.}) 15. Ne5 Rad8 {Preparing the knight trade with ... Nd7 .} 16. O-O Nd7 {The pawn on c4 will fall with at least equality for Black.} ({Here's one sample line:} 16... c5 {Bxd3 Nxd3 Nxc5 Nxc5 bxc5} 17. dxc5 Nb3 18. Rb1 Nxc1 19. Rbxc1 {Rf5 , with a drawn rook endgame.}) *

