1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. f3 {This line was very popular in the 1990s and was chosen by many attacking players, such as the young Alexei Shirov. White tries to improve on the Saemisch Variation without losing the tempo with 3.a3 and aims to take over the center with d5 next.} d5 {We stop White's plan as soon as possible. Please note that it is rare for us to move our d-pawn this early in this opening. Thus, the structure arising from these lines is not typical of the Nimzo, and you have to be precise early on!} {Now, since White can't easily play e4 , opening up the game with cxd5 exd5 is not recommended as the knight on g1 gets stranded.} 5. a3 {White's best move! Now that we have committed our d-pawn to d5 , White doesn't mind if we take on c3 , as they will undouble their pawns next.} Be7 {We have to be precise! Taking on c3 only helps White, as they will strengthen their center, undouble their pawns, and maintain the bishop pair.} 6. e4 {White achieves their plan, but we have a little surprise for them!} dxe4 7. fxe4 e5 ({I like this idea recommended in the original book, even though these days} 7... c5 {is much more popular at the top level. This is actually good news since your opponent will not expect it!  Black forces White to weaken dark-squares by playing} 8. d5 {, otherwise White's center will be destroyed.}) 8. d5 {The best move, grabbing more space. However, it also weakens the dark squares, especially the g1 - a7 diagonal.} c6 {A fresh idea to undermine the large white center right away! This is an extremely rare move, with only 8 games out of about 10 million in my DB! Even if your opponent is a Grandmaster, they are guaranteed to be surprised!} (8... Bc5 {was recommended in the book Chess Openings for Black, Explained . Even Magnus Carlsen has played this way for a few years. However, modern engines show that after} 9. Nf3 Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 {, White's bishop pair and space advantage promise them good chances for an advantage.}) 9. Be2 {This is another way White can try to develop. The idea is to control the g4 -square to play Be3 next.} ({Please note that the immediate} 9. Be3 $6 {runs into} Ng4 {.}) 9... O-O {Black is the first to castle, which gives us a nice development edge.} 10. Be3 {White has managed to secure the g1 - a7 diagonal, however, they still need to figure out how to get the g1 -knight out and castle.} Na6 {The knight is heading to c5 , where it would attack the e4 -pawn.} 11. b4 {White gains more space and restricts our knight.} Nc7 {We stop c5 (as the d5 -pawn wouldhang at the end) and get ready to undermine White's structure with ... a5 .} 12. Nf3 Ng4 {Now, we ask the bishop where it wants to go.} 13. Bg1 {This is probably White's best.} (13. Bd2 {is met with} a5 $1 14. Rb1 cxd5 15. cxd5 axb4 16. axb4 f5 $1 {with nice counterplay for Black.}) 13... f5 {We take advantage of White's king being stuck in the center and open up the game. White will need to play accurately in order not to be worse.} *

