1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. f3 {This line was very popular in the 1990s, and was a choice of many attacking players such as the young Alexei Shirov. White tries to improve on the Sämisch Variation without losing the tempo on 3. a3 and take over the center with d5 next.} d5 {We stop White's plan as soon as possible. Please note that it is rare for us to move our d-pawn this early in this opening. Thus, the structure arising from these lines is not typical of the Nimzo, and you have to be precise early on!} {Now, since White can't easily play e4 , opening up the game with cxd5 exd5 is not recommended as the knight on g1 gets stranded.} 5. a3 {White's best move! Now that we have committed our d-pawn to d5 , White doesn't mind if we take on c3 , as they will undouble their pawns next.} Be7 {We have to be precise! Taking on c3 only helps White, as they will strengthen their center, undouble their pawns, and maintain the bishop pair.} 6. e4 {White achieves their plan, but we have a little surprise for them!} dxe4 7. fxe4 e5 {I like this idea, even though these days 7... c5 is way more popular at the top level. This is actually good news since your opponent will not expect it! Black forces White to weaken the dark squares by playing 8. d5 , otherwise White's center will be destroyed.} 8. d5 {The best move, grabbing more space. However, it also weakens the dark squares, especially the g1 - a7 diagonal.} c6 {A fresh idea to undermine the large white center right away! This is an extremely rare move, with only 8 games out of about 10 million in my DB! Even if your opponent is a Grandmaster, they are guaranteed to be surprised!} (8... Bc5 {was recommended in the book Chess Openings for Black, Explained . Even Magnus Carlsen has played this way for a few years. However, modern engines show that after} 9. Nf3 Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 {, White's bishop pair and space advantage promise them good chances for an advantage.}) 9. Nf3 {White's most logical development move, they also attack our e5 -pawn ...but do they?} O-O {We offer a pawn for development!} 10. Nxe5 {Taking the pawn is risky, as White is seriously behind in development.} cxd5 11. cxd5 Bc5 {We seize the g1 - a7 diagonal and open up the e-file for our rook.} 12. Be2 Re8 13. Bf4 Nbd7 14. Nxd7 Bxd7 {Please note that all of Black's pieces are developed, whereas White's king is still stuck in the center.} 15. e5 Qb6 {This is a fun line, we sacrifice the knight!} 16. exf6 Qxb2 17. Bd2 Bd4 {Black is down a piece but it's clear that we are having all the fun. The engine claims that White can hold with the right moves, but good luck!} *

