t of about 10 million in my DB! Even if your opponent is a Grandmaster, they are guaranteed to be surprised!} (8... Bc5 {was recommended in the book Chess Openings for Black, Explained . Even Magnus Carlsen has played this way for a few years. However, modern engines show that after} 9. Nf3 Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 {, White's bishop pair and space advantage promise them good chances for an advantage.}) 9. Nf3 {White's most logical development move, they also attack our e5 -pawn ...but do they?} O-O {We offer a pawn for development!} 10. Nxe5 {Taking the pawn is risky, as White is seriously behind in development.} cxd5 11. exd5 Re8 {Simple chess. We just want to move the bishop and kill White on the e-file.} 12. Be2 Bc5 {We prevent White from castling while hitting the knight on e5 .} 13. Bf4 Nbd7 {We don't mind the trade, as it opens up our rook even more.} 14. Nxd7 {This logical move already gets White into trouble!} Bxd7 15. Qd3 Ng4 {And White is in trouble due to the weak f2 -square.} *

