t of about 10 million in my DB! Even if your opponent is a Grandmaster, they are guaranteed to be surprised!} (8... Bc5 {was recommended in the book Chess Openings for Black, Explained . Even Magnus Carlsen has played this way for a few years. However, modern engines show that after} 9. Nf3 Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 {, White's bishop pair and space advantage promise them good chances for an advantage.}) 9. Nf3 {White's most logical development move, they also attack our e5 -pawn ...but do they?} O-O {We offer a pawn for development!} 10. Bd3 {The most logical, White develops and gets ready to castle.} cxd5 ({We start chipping away at White's center. Let's take a look what happens after two logical recaptures:} 10... cxd5 {and} 11. exd5 {.}) 11. exd5 e4 {A beautiful pawn sac to open up the e-file for our rook.} 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Bh4+ 14. g3 Re8 {The rook enters the fight.} 15. O-O Rxe4 16. Nxh4 {White managed to survive the first wave of attack, and they even have an extra pawn for now, but we continue aggressively!} Bh3 17. Qf3 {White tries to play actively as well.} Qe8 {An important defensive move to protect the rook on e4 and the pawn on f7 .} 18. Nf5 {This line simplifies into a drawish endgame.} Bxf1 19. Nd6 Be2 {A nice intermezzo.} 20. Qxe4 Qxe4 21. Nxe4 Bxc4 22. Bf4 Nd7 {Black finishes development and the game is roughly even due to the opposite-colored bishops.} ({Not} 22... Bxd5 $4 {due to} 23. Rd1 {and Black loses.}) *

