t of about 10 million in my DB! Even if your opponent is a Grandmaster, they are guaranteed to be surprised!} (8... Bc5 {was recommended in the book Chess Openings for Black, Explained . Even Magnus Carlsen has played this way for a few years. However, modern engines show that after} 9. Nf3 Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 {, White's bishop pair and space advantage promise them good chances for an advantage.}) 9. Nf3 {White's most logical development move, they also attack our e5 -pawn ...but do they?} O-O {We offer a pawn for development!} 10. Bd3 {The most logical, White develops and gets ready to castle.} cxd5 ({We start chipping away at White's center. Let's take a look what happens after two logical recaptures:} 10... cxd5 {and} 11. exd5 {.}) 11. cxd5 {White's most solid choice to maintain the central grip with e4 & d5 .} Bc5 {Just in time! We stop White from castling.} 12. Na4 {A logical attempt to get rid of the annoying bishop.} Nbd7 {We don't mind trading the bishop, as the knight will replace it on c5 , applying central pressure on e4 .} 13. Nxc5 {Surprisingly, this natural move is a mistake.} Nxc5 {We are hitting the e4 -pawn twice now.} 14. Qe2 Nxd3+ 15. Qxd3 Bf5 {WARNING: This star move may cause your opponent to drop from their chair!} 16. exf5 e4 {Now it's clear that Black will get their piece back with dividends!} 17. Qb3 exf3 18. O-O fxg2 19. Kxg2 Re8 {We go for the maximum damage! With ideas of ... Re2 + and taking on d5 at any moment, Black has a winning initiative.} ({Alternatively,} 19... Qxd5+ 20. Qxd5 Nxd5 {is, of course, a nice pawn-up endgame.}) *

