[White "8) Nimzo: 4.f3"]
[Black "Nimzo: 4.f3 - 8.d5 / 9.Nf3 #11"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E20"]
[PlyCount "34"]
[GameId "2176748629701546"]

1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. f3 {This line was very popular in the 1990s, and was a choice of many attacking players such as the young Alexei Shirov. White tries to improve on the Sämisch Variation without losing the tempo on 3. a3 and take over the center with d5 next.} d5 {We stop White's plan as soon as possible. Please note that it is rare for us to move our d-pawn this early in this opening. Thus, the structure arising from these lines is not typical of the Nimzo, and you have to be precise early on!} {Now, since White can't easily play e4 , opening up the game with cxd5 exd5 is not recommended as the knight on g1 gets stranded.} 5. a3 {White's best move! Now that we have committed our d-pawn to d5 , White doesn't mind if we take on c3 , as they will undouble their pawns next.} Be7 {We have to be precise! Taking on c3 only helps White, as they will strengthen their center, undouble their pawns, and maintain the bishop pair.} 6. e4 {White achieves their plan, but we have a little surprise for them!} dxe4 7. fxe4 e5 {I like this idea, even though these days 7... c5 is way more popular at the top level. This is actually good news since your opponent will not expect it! Black forces White to weaken the dark squares by playing 8. d5 , otherwise White's center will be destroyed.} 8. d5 {The best move, grabbing more space. However, it also weakens the dark squares, especially the g1 - a7 diagonal.} c6 {A fresh idea to undermine the large white center right away! This is an extremely rare move, with only 8 games out of about 10 million in my DB! Even if your opponent is a Grandmaster, they are guaranteed to be surprised!} (8... Bc5 {was recommended in the book Chess Openings for Black, Explained . Even Magnus Carlsen has played this way for a few years. However, modern engines show that after} 9. Nf3 Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 {, White's bishop pair and space advantage promise them good chances for an advantage.}) 9. Nf3 {White's most logical development move, they also attack our e5 -pawn ...but do they?} O-O {We offer a pawn for development!} 10. Bd3 {The most logical, White develops and gets ready to castle.} cxd5 ({We start chipping away at White's center. Let's take a look what happens after two logical recaptures:} 10... cxd5 {and} 11. exd5 {.}) 11. cxd5 {White's most solid choice to maintain the central grip with e4 & d5 .} Bc5 {Just in time! We stop White from castling.} 12. Na4 {A logical attempt to get rid of the annoying bishop.} Nbd7 {We don't mind trading the bishop, as the knight will replace it on c5 , applying central pressure on e4 .} 13. b4 {White's best try.} Bd6 14. O-O a5 {Black undermines White's pawns on the queenside.} 15. Bd2 b5 {Taking advantage of the overloaded bishop on d3 , which also has to protect the e4 -pawn.} 16. Nb2 ({After} 16. Bxb5 Nxe4 {we are happy to swap a side pawn for a center one. Black will follow up with kingside expansion with ... f5 .}) 16... Ng4 {Creating a non-masked threat of ... Qb6 +.} 17. Kh1 f5 {Black plays on both wings! I believe in Black's dynamic potential in this position as the game will open up on the kingside. We will activate the other knight with ... Ndf6 next with an attack.} *

