{Against f3 remember to strike the center right away with d5! This direct approach is not typical for our repertoire, where we usually keep the pawn on d7 and sometimes move it to d6 . However, active play is important, and after a3 , we have to move the bishop back with Be7! Yes, we allow White to play e4 but with the timely trade dxe4 fxe4 , we strike the center with e5! After White's d5 , you will surprise your opponent with my fresh idea to undermine the pawn center with c6!? The ensuring positions are fun to play and often White's king gets stuck in center, allowing us a big attack.} 1. Z0 *

