1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Bg5 {This is the Leningrad Variation. White answers a pin with a pin, hoping to induce ... h6 and ... g5 to take advantage of Black's weakened kingside. These days, it's a rare guest at tournaments for all levels.} c5 ({This is more accurate than} 4... h6 {as there are lines where the bishop on g5 will be attacked via our queen on a5 .}) 5. e3 {This natural move is a serious mistake as it allows us the main idea of ... Qa5 .} Qa5 {A nice tactical idea, we are attacking c3 -knight while setting an X-ray on the g5 -bishop.} 6. Nge2 Ne4 ({Even stronger than} 6... cxd4 {as White will have the intermezzo} 7. Bxf6 {.}) 7. Qd3 {White's best try. Moving the bishop will lose after ... Nxc3 .} cxd4 ({Don't take the bishop, as} 7... Nxg5 {is met by} 8. h4 $1 {and White is back in the game.}) 8. exd4 Nxf2 {We sacrifice the knight and open up the enemy king.} ({Please note that again} 8... Nxg5 {is met with} 9. h4 {and our knight is trapped.}) 9. Kxf2 Qxg5 {The dust has settled and Black has a free pawn, two bishops and White's open king. A nice outcome for any opening!} *

