1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Bg5 {This is the Leningrad Variation. White answers a pin with a pin, hoping to induce ... h6 and ... g5 to take advantage of Black's weakened kingside. These days, it's a rare guest at tournaments for all levels.} c5 ({This is more accurate than} 4... h6 {as there are lines where the bishop on g5 will be attacked via our queen on a5 .}) 5. d5 {This is White's most common move.} Bxc3+ {We take the opportunity to ruin White's pawn structure.} {If we start with first, this would give White an option to defend the knight with Rc1 .} 6. bxc3 d6 ({Please note that} 6... h6 7. Bh4 d6 {will transpose.}) 7. f3 {White wants to play for e4 .} h6 8. Bh4 Qe7 {I like this rare idea to prepare for White's e4 push.} 9. e4 Nbd7 {We keep developing and are ready to meet Bd3 with Ne5!} 10. Ne2 Ne5 11. Nc1 {An awkward move, but where else can the knight go? Ng3 & Nf4 are met with ... g5 !} Ng6 12. Bf2 O-O ({Black's pieces are perfectly placed, while White is still having major problems with development. We will meet Be2 or Bd3 with} 12... Nh5 $1 {next.}) *

