1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Bg5 {This is the Leningrad Variation. White answers a pin with a pin, hoping to induce ... h6 and ... g5 to take advantage of Black's weakened kingside. These days, it's a rare guest at tournaments for all levels.} c5 ({This is more accurate than} 4... h6 {as there are lines where the bishop on g5 will be attacked via our queen on a5 .}) 5. d5 {This is White's most common move.} Bxc3+ {We take the opportunity to ruin White's pawn structure.} {If we start with first, this would give White an option to defend the knight with Rc1 .} 6. bxc3 d6 ({Please note that} 6... h6 7. Bh4 d6 {will transpose.}) 7. e3 h6 {A useful intermezzo to push the bishop to h4 .} 8. Bh4 e5 {We've achieved a dream setup in the Nimzo known as the Huebner Wall. Please note that White's pawn is on e3 here, which is a better version for Black! That's the reason why top GMs stopped playing this setup as White. Let's take a look at how the game may continue:} 9. Qc2 {This flexible move, stopping ... Bf5 , is White's most common idea.} Qe7 {We are getting ready to meet Bd3 with ... g5 & ... e4 !} 10. Nf3 g5 {We still go for the classic ... g5 & ... e4 plan. This is even stronger than previously recommended 10... Nbd7 .} 11. Bg3 e4 12. Nd2 Bf5 {We have gained quite a lot of space on the kingside. Let me show you a possible plan.} 13. Be2 Nbd7 14. O-O {This natural move is asking for trouble!} ({After} 14. h4 O-O-O {, I still prefer Black as White's king has nowhere to hide.}) 14... h5 {Of course, we attack with no hesitation. White is in big trouble now.} 15. h3 h4 16. Bh2 Rg8 {We will play ... g4 next and pry out White's king. Please note that Black's monarch is totally safe on e8 for now.} *

