1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Bg5 {This is the Leningrad Variation. White answers a pin with a pin, hoping to induce ... h6 and ... g5 to take advantage of Black's weakened kingside. These days, it's a rare guest at tournaments for all levels.} c5 ({This is more accurate than} 4... h6 {as there are lines where the bishop on g5 will be attacked via our queen on a5 .}) 5. d5 {This is White's most common move.} Bxc3+ {We take the opportunity to ruin White's pawn structure. If we start with first, this would give White an option to defend the knight with .} 6. bxc3 d6 ({Please note that} 6... h6 7. Bh4 d6 {will transpose.}) 7. e4 {This is a common move at lower levels. At first, it looks logical to win the center in one go since the knight is pinned. However, White now has to part with the bishop pair.} h6 8. Bxf6 ({Please note that} 8. Bh4 $2 {drops a pawn after} g5 {& ... Nxe4 next.}) 8... Qxf6 {Black has achieved a typical Nimzo structure. White's loss of the bishop pair and doubled c-pawns give us long-term targets for free.} *

