1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. g3 {White goes for the immediate fianchetto of their light-squared bishop. This is called the Romanishin Variation, named after the Ukrainian GM Oleg Romanishin.} (4. Nf3 c5 5. g3 {is another common transposition to our setup.}) 4... c5 {We answer with an attack in the center!} 5. Nf3 Ne4 {White's slow play enables us to put more pressure on the pinned c3 -knight. Now, the most common response is to cover the knight with either Qd3 or Qc2 when our reaction will be the same in both cases: we trade on d4 and play ... Qa5 next.} 6. Qc2 ({Now, similarly to} 6. Qd3 {, we take on d4 and play ... Qa5 .}) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Qa5 8. Nb3 {This allows an important nuance!} Qf5 {Now that White's queen is on c2 , Black uses the X-ray against the unprotected queen to his advantage. We also hit the f2 -pawn. White is losing already.} 9. f3 Nxc3 10. Qxf5 Na4+ {A nice intermezzo! We will take on f5 next, winning a piece!} *

