1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. g3 {White goes for the immediate fianchetto of their light-squared bishop. This is called the Romanishin Variation, named after the Ukrainian GM Oleg Romanishin.} (4. Nf3 c5 5. g3 {is another common transposition to our setup.}) 4... c5 {We answer with an attack in the center!} 5. Nf3 Ne4 {White's slow play enables us to put more pressure on the pinned c3 -knight. Now, the most common response is to cover the knight with either Qd3 or Qc2 when our reaction will be the same in both cases: we trade on d4 and play ... Qa5 next.} 6. Qc2 ({Now, similarly to} 6. Qd3 {, we take on d4 and play ... Qa5 .}) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Qa5 8. Bg2 {This is White's best try.} Nxc3 9. O-O {This piece sac was introduced at the highest level in a blitz game Carlsen-Caruana from 2016. Black should not be greedy and develop normally.} Nc6 {Simple chess by Caruana.} 10. bxc3 Bxc3 {A nice double attack, but White has a way out.} 11. Nb3 {Attacking our queen and now you must know the following move:} Nd4 {The key move and the only one that leads to rough equality.} 12. Nxd4 Bxd4 13. Rb1 {The dust has settled. White has lost a pawn but gained a lead in development. However, with accurate moves Black will neutralize White's initiative.} d6 {This is the key move to establish a strong outpost for our d4 -bishop if attacked by the queen.} ({The natural} 13... O-O $2 {allows White to gain serious edge:} 14. Rb5 Qc7 15. Qd3 Bf6 16. Ba3 Re8 17. Bd6) 14. Rb5 Qc7 15. Qd3 Bc5 16. Bb2 O-O {Black's king is safe and we will play ... Rb8 , ... b6 and ... Bb7 next, holding on to our extra pawn.} *

