1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. g3 {White goes for the immediate fianchetto of their light-squared bishop. This is called the Romanishin Variation, named after the Ukrainian GM Oleg Romanishin.} (4. Nf3 c5 5. g3 {is another common transposition to our setup.}) 4... c5 {We answer with an attack in the center!} 5. Nf3 Ne4 {White's slow play enables us to put more pressure on the pinned c3 -knight. Now, the most common response is to cover the knight with either Qd3 or Qc2 when our reaction will be the same in both cases: we trade on d4 and play ... Qa5 next.} 6. Bd2 {This is a somewhat passive move and allows quick liquidation where Black will enjoy a superior pawn structure for free.} Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Nxc3 8. bxc3 d6 {Black wants to develop the knight to d7 first.} 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O Nd7 {Our next moves are easy: ... Qc7 , ... Rb8 and ... b6 . Once the light-squared bishop is developed on b7 or a6 we will play against White's weak c4 -pawn.} *

