1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. g3 {White goes for the immediate fianchetto of their light-squared bishop. This is called the Romanishin Variation, named after the Ukrainian GM Oleg Romanishin.} (4. Nf3 c5 5. g3 {is another common transposition to our setup.}) 4... c5 {We answer with an attack in the center!} 5. Nf3 Ne4 {White's slow play enables us to put more pressure on the pinned c3 -knight. Now, the most common response is to cover the knight with either Qd3 or Qc2 when our reaction will be the same in both cases: we trade on d4 and play ... Qa5 next.} 6. Qd3 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Qa5 {We add another attack on the c3 -knight.} 8. Bd2 {This line gives Black some easy targets.} Nxd2 9. Qxd2 Bxc3 10. bxc3 {White clearly has some serious pawn weaknesses, but at least their pieces are better developed.} O-O 11. Bg2 Nc6 12. O-O Ne5 {White's better development is enough to keep the balance but the pawn on c4 is quite weak. For example:} 13. Nb3 Qc7 14. c5 Rb8 {We will play ... b6 next and develop our bishop to b7 or a6 with an easy game.} *

