1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. g3 {White goes for the immediate fianchetto of their light-squared bishop. This is called the Romanishin Variation, named after the Ukrainian GM Oleg Romanishin.} (4. Nf3 c5 5. g3 {is another common transposition to our setup.}) 4... c5 {We answer with an attack in the center!} 5. Nf3 Ne4 {White's slow play enables us to put more pressure on the pinned c3 -knight. Now, the most common response is to cover the knight with either Qd3 or Qc2 when our reaction will be the same in both cases: we trade on d4 and play ... Qa5 next.} 6. Qd3 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Qa5 {We add another attack on the c3 -knight.} 8. Nb3 {This is the most principled move, now we enter some fun tactics that you should try to learn and remember well!} Nxc3 {The key move, offering White a free queen...} 9. Nxa5 {Most players will take the queen, but we have something up our sleeve.} Ne4+ {This beautiful discovery is the point! Now, we will win our queen back but it's White who has to be careful.} 10. Kd1 {This autopilot move loses on the spot!} Nxf2+ 11. Kc2 Nxd3 12. exd3 Bxa5 {Black is up a piece in a winning endgame!} *

