1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Bd2 {White immediately stops the pin and gets ready to play a3 later and recapture on c3 with the bishop, thus avoiding the doubled pawns.   This line was always considered harmless for Nimzo players, but recently some top players decided to explore it deeper and found some ideas for White.} c5 ({I believe that challenging White in the center is the simplest approach, as the previously recommended} 4... O-O {gives White too many options.}) 5. e3 {This protects the central pawn. Now we have an easy equalizer.} cxd4 6. exd4 Nc6 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Bd3 d5 {This is the key idea! We are happy to trade into a symmetrical d-pawns middlegame.} ({Or, if White advances with c5 , to undermine the center with} 8... b6 $1) 9. cxd5 exd5 ({The simplest, but if you must avoid symmetry,} 9... Nxd5 {is a standard IQP structure.}) 10. O-O Bg4 {It's clear that Black solved all their opening problems. While the position is symmetrical, it is far from drawish!} 11. a3 Bxc3 12. Bxc3 Re8 13. h3 Bh5 14. Rc1 Ne4 {And it's clear that our bishop and e4 -knight are monsters.} *

