1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Bd2 {White immediately stops the pin and gets ready to play a3 later and recapture on c3 with the bishop, thus avoiding the doubled pawns.   This line was always considered harmless for Nimzo players, but recently some top players decided to explore it deeper and found some ideas for White.} c5 ({I believe that challenging White in the center is the simplest approach, as the previously recommended} 4... O-O {gives White too many options.}) 5. dxc5 {This trade typically makes us happy as we traded a side pawn for a center pawn.} Bxc5 ({We can also start with} 5... O-O {, but it will likely transpose after} 6. Nf3 Bxc5 {.}) 6. Nf3 O-O {We are first to castle, while White still needs to make 3 moves to evacuate his majesty.} 7. e3 {This is too passive, and it's clear that bishop on d2 is now misplaced. Black has a lot of options here as pretty much all development moves are playable.} b6 ({This is more typical for our repertoire, but natural moves like} 7... d5 {or Nc6 are fine as well.}) 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. O-O Nc6 {This keeps the game a bit more complex, but ... d5 equalizes on the spot.} 10. a3 Be7 {We anticipate b4 .} 11. b4 a5 {Let's lure White's pawn to b5 .} 12. b5 Nb8 {Now, we will play hedgehog style with ... d6 and ... Nbd7 with a great outpost on c5 for our knight. I prefer Black in the long term.} *

