1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Bd2 {White immediately stops the pin and gets ready to play a3 later and recapture on c3 with the bishop, thus avoiding the doubled pawns.   This line was always considered harmless for Nimzo players, but recently some top players decided to explore it deeper and found some ideas for White.} c5 ({I believe that challenging White in the center is the simplest approach, as the previously recommended} 4... O-O {gives White too many options.}) 5. dxc5 {This trade typically makes us happy as we traded a side pawn for a center pawn.} Bxc5 ({We can also start with} 5... O-O {, but it will likely transpose after} 6. Nf3 Bxc5 {.}) 6. Nf3 O-O {We are first to castle, while White still needs to make 3 moves to evacuate his majesty.} 7. g3 {It's more natural to fianchetto the bishop.} d5 {I believe that this version of IQP is a dream one for Black since White is behind in development and doesn't have control over d4 -outpost.} 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bg2 Nc6 10. O-O d4 {By advancing one square this pawn is now a strength rather than a weakness!} 11. Na4 Be7 12. Rc1 Be6 {We develop naturally and set up a small trap.} 13. Nc5 {White falls for our trap as they think the a2 -pawn is poisoned.} ({After} 13. a3 Bd5 {, Black is totally fine.}) 13... Bxc5 14. Rxc5 Bxa2 {We take the bait!} 15. b3 {It looks like our bishop is trapped on a2 , but...} Qb6 {This star move attacking the rook and the b3 -pawn gives Black a nice edge as our bishop is now rescued.} *

