1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Bd2 {White immediately stops the pin and gets ready to play a3 later and recapture on c3 with the bishop, thus avoiding the doubled pawns.   This line was always considered harmless for Nimzo players, but recently some top players decided to explore it deeper and found some ideas for White.} c5 ({I believe that challenging White in the center is the simplest approach, as the previously recommended} 4... O-O {gives White too many options.}) 5. a3 {White forces matters.} Bxc3 6. Bxc3 {White achieves their goal of two bishops and no pawn weaknesses, but not for long!} Ne4 {This puts a damper on White's plans. Now the bishop on c3 has nowhere to run from the trade.} 7. Qc2 ({Or} 7. Qd3 {.}) 7... Nxc3 {We happily trade for the bishop.} 8. Qxc3 cxd4 9. Qxd4 O-O {Now, it's clear that White's strategy didn't accomplish much since their queen is about to be attacked with ... Nc6 and their king will take a while to castle short.} 10. Nf3 Nc6 11. Qc3 b6 {This is the simplest, but Black has many other good moves.} 12. e4 {White tries to take more space in the center, but Black has plenty of ideas.} d6 13. Be2 e5 {We put our pawns on the dark squares. This structure is very common in various Sicilians.} 14. O-O (14. h3 {stops} Bg4 {, but we can play for ... Bb7 and ... f5 ! instead.}) 14... Bg4 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Nd4 {Our knight clearly dominates the bishop.} *

