1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Bd2 {White immediately stops the pin and gets ready to play a3 later and recapture on c3 with the bishop, thus avoiding the doubled pawns.   This line was always considered harmless for Nimzo players, but recently some top players decided to explore it deeper and found some ideas for White.} c5 ({I believe that challenging White in the center is the simplest approach, as the previously recommended} 4... O-O {gives White too many options.}) 5. a3 {White forces matters.} Bxc3 6. Bxc3 {White achieves their goal of two bishops and no pawn weaknesses, but not for long!} Ne4 {This puts a damper on White's plans. Now the bishop on c3 has nowhere to run from the trade.} 7. Rc1 {This was played by some GMs, but I believe Black can now pose some serious problems with their next move.} Qh4 {All of a sudden, White is paying the price for neglecting their kingside development.} 8. g3 Nxc3 {An important intermezzo to remember!} 9. bxc3 {Otherwise the d4 -pawn drops.} ({Taking our queen leads to a worse endgame for White after} 9. gxh4 Nxd1 {.}) 9... Qe7 {White tried so hard to avoid the doubled pawns, but clearly something went wrong with their opening strategy!} 10. Bg2 O-O 11. Nf3 d6 12. O-O Nc6 13. Qd2 e5 {Black has achieved a dream Nimzo setup, we have no weaknesses and our e5 - d6 - c5 pawn triangle is strong. White, on the other hand, has a ruined pawn structure on the queenside. We will develop our bishop next or can even play aggressively with ... f5 .} *

