1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Nf3 {This is often called the Kasparov Variation, as young Kasparov famously uncorked it during his 2nd match vs Karpov in 1985.} ({However, since Kasparov typically answered} 4. c5 {with g3 , this would transpose to the Romanishin Variation, analyzed here .  For this chapter, I focus on e3 , which will transpose to a well-known line of the Rubinstein known as the Huebner Variation, named after a famous German Grandmaster, Robert Huebner.}) 4... c5 ({Please note that normally against the Rubinstein e3 , we answer with} 4... b6 {. However, if we play b6 now, we would have to learn a big chapter with} 5. Bg5 {. Not that it's any dangerous for Black, but I don't want to overwhelm you with learning too much theory of a rare line. Instead, I will teach you the Huebner Wall!}) 5. e3 Nc6 {We develop normally and put pressure on White's center.} 6. Bd3 {White's most common move, they go for rapid development as well.} Bxc3+ {Let's double White's pawns and create a longterm pawn weakness.} 7. bxc3 d6 {Black is ready to setup the Huebner wall with ... e5 next.} 8. e4 e5 {This setup is known as the Huebner Variation or the Huebner Wall. Black builds a wall of pawns on the dark squares, limiting the scope of White's bishops.   These positions are bread and butter for Nimzo players, and I'd like to teach you the common plans and ideas.} 9. d5 {White gains space but locks up the center.} Ne7 {Sometimes Black plays ... Na5 to put pressure on c4 -pawn, but in the Huebner Variation this is the best retreating square for the knight. We aim to play on the kingside with ... Ng6 where the knight will cover the vital f4 -square.} 10. O-O Ng6 11. Ne1 h6 {Black achieved a dream setup, covering both g5 & f4 squares. White's typical plan of g3 & f4 is almost impossible to achieve. Let me show you how White can get in trouble.} 12. g3 Bh3 {A nice square for our bishop!} 13. Ng2 {White is ready to play f4 next but as long as we don't castle kingside, White will not have a clear target! In fact, let me know show you how to counterattack White here.} h5 {A cool idea to remember, we will play ... h4 next.} (13... O-O $6 {naturally 'securing' our king only gives White a clear target for attack.} 14. Re1 Nh7 15. Qh5 Qd7 16. Ne3 Ng5 17. Nf5 {with a big attack.}) 14. f4 h4 {We open up the h-file for our rook.} 15. f5 Nf8 16. gxh4 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Rxh4 {Black will play ... Qd7 and castle long while White ran out of attacking options and left with a weak king.} *

