1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Nc3 {The starting position of the Nimzo-Indian Defense. White develops the knight behind the c-pawn to its most natural square, and takes more control of the e4 -square. This can lead to more sharp variations than the Bogo-Indian.} Bb4 4. Qb3 {This is called the Spielmann Variation, named after the famous chess player Rudolf Spielmann, known as the last master of the romantic school of chess.   This is an extremely rare setup for White, being only the 9th most played move in this position. White is attacking our bishop directly and tries to provoke us to take on c3 .} c5 ({I like this direct way of undermining White's center, however, you can also play the same way as against Qc2 with} 4... Nc6 {here.}) 5. Nf3 Nc6 {We keep on attacking the center, and provoking dxc5 .} 6. e3 {Black has a number of good moves, but I like to castle and attack White's center with ... d5 .} O-O 7. Bd3 d5 {Here, we go for very quick central play, as White's queen is quite misplaced from the action on b3 .} 8. a3 {A logical move to force us to take runs into a funny tactic.} Na5 ({This is even stronger than} 8... Bxc3+ {.}) 9. Qc2 Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 dxc4 ({You can also start with} 10... cxd4 {, which would transpose.}) 11. Bxc4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 {Allows us to take over the game.} e5 13. Nf3 Nxc4 14. Qxc4 Bg4 {And White is in big trouble as we have a big threat of ... Bxf3 , ruining White's pawn structure.} ({Please note that Nxe5?} 14... Qd1+ {is checkmate.}) *

