1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. a3 ({This move clearly stops ... Bb4 , but White cannot fight for an opening advantage with such moves. I will give you two weapons against this:  • A fighting Benoni with} 3. c5 {, where a3 is a waste of time, since White often needs to play a4 . • A simple central strategy with} d5 {, aiming to get a QGD/QGA up a tempo, with easy equality.}) 3... c5 {This is the fighting option, inviting White to a Benoni where they are a tempo down.} 4. d5 g6 {We complete our fianchetto first and deal with White's d5 -pawn later.} 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. e4 d6 {We keep the tension and will take on d5 at the right moment.} 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Be2 exd5 {We clarify the situation in the center.} 9. cxd5 b5 {The most forcing way to get counterplay.} ({We could also play} 9... Bg4 {with a more positional game, intending to expand with ... a6 & ... b5 later.}) 10. Bxb5 ({Taking with the knight,} 10. Nxb5 {, allows} Nxe4 {, which is a favorable trade for us.}) 10... Nxe4 {The key tactical idea, we will follow up with ... Qa5 + next.} 11. Nxe4 Qa5+ 12. Nfd2 {White's best.} (12. Nc3 $2 {gets White in trouble after} Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Qxb5 {, and now they can't castle.}) 12... Qxb5 13. Nxd6 Qa6 {We prevent White from castling. White can still achieve equality by finding the correct moves.} 14. N2c4 Nd7 15. O-O Ne5 16. Nxc8 Raxc8 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 {This is a well-known Benoni position where Black has enough play for the pawn. At some point, we will play ... Rfd8 & ... Bd4 and win the d5 -pawn. The engine pretty much gives 0.0.} *

