1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. a3 ({This move clearly stops ... Bb4 , but White cannot fight for an opening advantage with such moves. I will give you two weapons against this:  • A fighting Benoni with} 3. c5 {, where a3 is a waste of time, since White often needs to play a4 . • A simple central strategy with} d5 {, aiming to get a QGD/QGA up a tempo, with easy equality.}) 3... d5 {This is, of course, the most principled reply, as we fight for the center.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 c6 {We achieve a classic QGD structure with an extra tempo. You might wonder whether a3 helps White in the long term as they plan to launch a minority attack with b4 and b5 . The key is that Black can develop the bishop to f5 . Often, when the trade of the light-squared bishop occurs, we can easily deal with the minority attack.} 6. Bg5 Bf5 {We use the free tempo to develop our bishop to f5 . Normally, the pawn would be on e3 , and White would answer this move with Qf3 ! and Bxf6 , ruining our pawn structure. Even there, it's considered a playable line of the QGD.} 7. e3 Nbd7 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Be7 10. Nf3 O-O 11. O-O Re8 {Black has already equalized and can aim for more with the classic ... Ne4 idea.} *

