1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. a3 ({This move clearly stops ... Bb4 , but White cannot fight for an opening advantage with such moves. I will give you two weapons against this:  • A fighting Benoni with} 3. c5 {, where a3 is a waste of time, since White often needs to play a4 . • A simple central strategy with} d5 {, aiming to get a QGD/QGA up a tempo, with easy equality.}) 3... d5 {This is, of course, the most principled reply, as we fight for the center.} 4. Nc3 c5 {We keep striking at the center!} 5. cxd5 cxd4 ({This is even stronger than} 5... exd5 {, as we force White's queen to lose some tempi.}) 6. Qxd4 Nc6 7. Qd3 exd5 {If you don't mind playing with an IQP, this is the best version for Black. Active piece play is required, and often Black's dynamic play will compensate for the IQP. Interestingly, the engine already favors Black!} 8. Nf3 Bg4 {Active play.} 9. g3 d4 {The IQP should always be advanced when possible! We are already fighting for an advantage.} 10. Ne4 Be7 {We protect the f6 -knight and get ready to castle.} 11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. Bg2 O-O 13. O-O Re8 {Black is already better, as it's clear that White didn't get their typical counterplay against the IQP. Now, the e2 -pawn is quite weak. We will follow up with ... Qd7 to connect the rooks. The engine gives us a -0.5 advantage.} *

