1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. a3 ({This move clearly stops ... Bb4 , but White cannot fight for an opening advantage with such moves. I will give you two weapons against this:  • A fighting Benoni with} 3. c5 {, where a3 is a waste of time, since White often needs to play a4 . • A simple central strategy with} d5 {, aiming to get a QGD/QGA up a tempo, with easy equality.}) 3... d5 {This is, of course, the most principled reply, as we fight for the center.} 4. Nc3 c5 {We keep striking at the center!} 5. e3 {This is logical in combination with 3.a3 , but Black now gets good version of the QGA.} dxc4 6. Bxc4 a6 {The last two moves are typical of the QGA. We will develop our bishop to ... b7 after the ... b5 expansion.} 7. Nf3 b5 8. Ba2 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 {Black has very easy development, while White's b2 -bishop is quite stuck.} 10. Qe2 Bd6 {The simplest, we just develop.} 11. Rd1 O-O 12. dxc5 Bxc5 {Please note that White can't take advantage of the pin on our d7 -knight. We will play ... Qb6 next.} 13. b4 Be7 14. Bb2 Qb6 {Both sides have completed development, resulting in a roughly even game. We will activate the rooks next with ... Rfd8 and ... Rac8 .} *

