1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. g4 {This gambit was first introduced on the big stage by the ever-innovative Azeri GM Mamedyarov against Esipenko in 2022. These days, even Caruana has played it, but only in blitz!} d5 {We don't care about the pawn and strike in the center! Remember, flank attacks are best countered by central play.} 4. g5 ({After} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g5 Ne4 {, Black is clearly better, with threats of ... Nxg5 & ... Bb4 +.}) 4... Ne4 {Our knight is very active on e4 now. We attack g5 and get ready to play ... Bb4 +.} 5. Bg2 Bb4+ {A strong move, asking White a serious question. Now, White has to play Kf1 , since both Nd2 / Bd2 are met with ... Qxg5 .} 6. Kf1 O-O {We go for rapid development and prepare a piece sacrifice.} 7. f3 {Is our knight trapped?} f5 {The point of ... O-O is revealed. Now, the game opens up with a strong attack against White's king. The roles are reversed: the gambiteer becomes the defender!} 8. a3 Be7 9. fxe4 fxe4+ 10. Ke1 {White managed to keep the extra piece.} Bxg5 {Black has two pawns for the piece but White's open king and our monster pawns give us a winning edge already. The engine shows -2 here!} 11. Nh3 Bh6 {The simplest. We are opening the way for our queen.} 12. Bxh6 Qh4+ 13. Kd2 Qxh6+ 14. Kc2 Nc6 15. Nc3 e5 {We blow open the game and get our bishop involved in the attack. The position is no fun for White.} *

