1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Bf4 {This is a rare line with the idea of meeting ... Bb4 + with Nd2 , aiming to develop similarly to the London System with Nf3 , e3 , etc.  It's becoming more trendy and has been played by Carlsen, Pragg, Abdusattorov, Firouzja, and many other top players.  The main point is to avoid opening theory and reach a simple, playable position.} Bb4+ {We still go for the Bogo check.} 4. Nd2 (4. Nc3 {leads to a good Nimzo for Black after thematic .}) 4... c5 {We put pressure on the center right away.} 5. e3 Nc6 6. Ngf3 d6 {Black has many good moves, but I think this plan suits our Nimzo/Bogo style, as we plan to play for ... e5 .} 7. Be2 e5 {We offer White a pawn, let's see if they take the bait.} 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Bxe5 {This is the correct way to win a pawn, although Black gets great counterplay.} Bf5 ({Simple chess! White can't easily break the pin on the d2 -knight, as} 9... O-O $2 {loses a piece to Nxe5 and ... Qxd2 .}) 10. Bc3 {White breaks the pin but gets doubled pawns.} Bxc3 11. bxc3 Qe7 {We are waiting for White to castle.} 12. O-O O-O-O {The point! Now, Black gets a big attack after ... h6 & ... g5 . White can't use the b-file to get their attack going, so it's a one-way street!} *

