1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Bf4 {This is a rare line with the idea of meeting ... Bb4 + with Nd2 , aiming to develop similarly to the London System with Nf3 , e3 , etc.  It's becoming more trendy and has been played by Carlsen, Pragg, Abdusattorov, Firouzja, and many other top players.  The main point is to avoid opening theory and reach a simple, playable position.} Bb4+ {We still go for the Bogo check.} 4. Nd2 (4. Nc3 {leads to a good Nimzo for Black after thematic .}) 4... c5 {We put pressure on the center right away.} 5. dxc5 {This is the most common move, but we generally don't mind trading the d-pawn for our c-pawn.} Bxc5 {We have many options, but sooner or later, we have to take this pawn.} 6. e3 b6 {We go for the most natural plan of fianchetto.} 7. Ngf3 Bb7 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Be7 {This marks the start of regrouping to reach the Hedgehog pawn structure ( e6 + d6 & b6 + a6 ). It’s very effective against the bishop on f4 and the knight on d2 .} 10. h3 d6 11. a3 a6 {We've achieved the Hedgehog pawn formation.} 12. Rc1 Nbd7 13. b4 e5 {We push the bishop back.} 14. Bh2 Ra7 {A cool idea to know! We will play ... Qa8 and exert more pressure on the long diagonal. I prefer Black in the resulting middlegame, as White's bishop on h2 is passive.} *

