1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. Bg5 {This is called the Seirawan Attack. Recently, Grischuk has played it exclusively in blitz, and now Erigaisi picked it up. I don't know what the appeal is as it's just a bad line!} h6 {A good idea to push the bishop back to h4 .} 4. Bh4 {Taking on f6 makes no sense, as Black gets the bishop pair for free.} g5 {We keep chasing the bishop.} 5. Bg3 h5 {Now, the threat of ... h4 & ... d6 is real, we are about to win the bishop pair.} 6. f3 {Grischuk has played this move in blitz on several occasions.} c5 {I like this approach with the idea of inducing d5 . The resulting positions will resemble the Benoni structure, derived from the King's Indian Sämisch variation.} ({If you prefer more solid play, then} 6... h4 {followed by ... d5 is fine as well.}) 7. d5 {The most principled, and played by Grischuk twice.} h4 {Yet another tempo on the bishop!} 8. Bf2 exd5 9. cxd5 d6 10. e4 {We've reached an interesting position. If we move the pawns back to h7 and g6 , we get a classic King's Indian Sämisch variation. However, here it feels like a much better version for Black, as we often push these pawns anyway to gain space.  White does get a strong g2 - d5 pawn chain, but still, having so many extra tempi must be good for Black!} Bg7 ({Black can even skip this move and play} 10... Nbd7 11. Qd2 Nh5 $1 {to stop g3 , and the knight is heading to f4 .}) 11. Nc3 Nbd7 12. Be3 Nh7 {We protect the g5 -pawn and open up our bishop. So far, we are following a rapid game of Grischuk.} 13. Qd2 Ne5 {The knight is perfectly placed. It's not easy for White to develop as Nge2 runs into Nc4!} 14. g3 Ng6 ({A logical novelty with the idea of meeting gxh4 with Nxh4 . In a rapid game, Grischuk-Tsydypov, 2023, Black played} 14... a6 {, to which Grischuk responded with} 15. gxh4 {, giving White an edge.}) 15. O-O-O {A logical idea to get the king to safety of the queenside.} O-O {We've reached a very unusual but exciting position! I prefer Black, as our attack will unfold naturally with ... b5 , while White struggles to break through our defensive line on the kingside.} *

