1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. g3 {This is an attempt by White to get into the Catalan but deny Black the option of the solid Queen's Indian Defense (QID) since b6? is now met with . However, since we play ... Bb4 + anyways, it's not a big deal for us. The only lines we have to learn is when White keeps the knight on g1 .} Bb4+ ({We aim to transpose to the Bogo after Bd2} 3... Qe7) ({or the Nimzo after Nc3} 3... c5 {.}) 4. Nd2 {A sneaky line. We can't play the same way as in the Bogo since b6? is met with Bg2! But don't worry, I will show you a simple central strategy based on an early 4... c5 ! idea.} c5 {We strike the center ASAP taking advantage of White's poor development.} 5. a3 {White's most logical move to get the bishop pair.} Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nc6 {We develop quickly and put pressure on White's center.} 7. d5 Nd4 {Very unpleasant for White.} 8. Qd1 exd5 9. e3 Qe7 {White is facing an annoying pin and simply plays a pawn down.} *

