1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. g3 {This is an attempt by White to get into the Catalan but deny Black the option of the solid Queen's Indian Defense (QID) since b6? is now met with . However, since we play ... Bb4 + anyways, it's not a big deal for us. The only lines we have to learn is when White keeps the knight on g1 .} Bb4+ ({We aim to transpose to the Bogo after Bd2} 3... Qe7) ({or the Nimzo after Nc3} 3... c5 {.}) 4. Nd2 {A sneaky line. We can't play the same way as in the Bogo since b6? is met with Bg2! But don't worry, I will show you a simple central strategy based on an early 4... c5 ! idea.} c5 {We strike the center ASAP taking advantage of White's poor development.} 5. a3 {White's most logical move to get the bishop pair.} Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nc6 {We develop quickly and put pressure on White's center.} 7. dxc5 Ne4 {Our knights are very annoying.} 8. Qe3 Qa5+ {A cool tactic to remember! Now White has to block with the bishop.} 9. Bd2 (9. b4 $2 {loses to} Nxb4 $1 {and ... Qxa1 .}) 9... Nxd2 10. Qxd2 Qxc5 {We get our pawn back with a roughly even game.} 11. Rc1 Qd4 12. Nf3 Qxd2+ 13. Nxd2 b6 14. Bg2 Bb7 {We will play ... Ke7 with easy play in the endgame.} *

