1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. g3 {This is an attempt by White to get into the Catalan but deny Black the option of the solid Queen's Indian Defense (QID) since b6? is now met with . However, since we play ... Bb4 + anyways, it's not a big deal for us. The only lines we have to learn is when White keeps the knight on g1 .} Bb4+ ({We aim to transpose to the Bogo after Bd2} 3... Qe7) ({or the Nimzo after Nc3} 3... c5 {.}) 4. Nd2 {A sneaky line. We can't play the same way as in the Bogo since b6? is met with Bg2! But don't worry, I will show you a simple central strategy based on an early 4... c5 ! idea.} c5 {We strike the center ASAP taking advantage of White's poor development.} 5. a3 {White's most logical move to get the bishop pair.} Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nc6 {We develop quickly and put pressure on White's center.} 7. Nf3 Na5 {A cool move to target the b3 -square.} 8. Qc2 b5 {What an incredible idea that has only been seen in a few game. We blow open the queenside for active piece play.} 9. cxb5 c4 {We secure the b3 -outpost.} 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. O-O a6 {We play in Benko style!} 12. bxa6 Be4 {A nice intermezzo to force the queen to a bad square.} 13. Qa4 Nb3 14. Ra2 Qc8 {A strong move to protect the c4 -pawn. Now, White is in big trouble due to ... Rxa6 idea. Plus, if White is not careful, we can trap the rook with ... Bb1 .} *

