1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. g3 {This is an attempt by White to get into the Catalan but deny Black the option of the solid Queen's Indian Defense (QID) since b6? is now met with . However, since we play ... Bb4 + anyways, it's not a big deal for us. The only lines we have to learn is when White keeps the knight on g1 .} Bb4+ ({We aim to transpose to the Bogo after Bd2} 3... Qe7) ({or the Nimzo after Nc3} 3... c5 {.}) 4. Bd2 {This is White's most common move.} Qe7 {We defend the bishop and give White a chance to transpose to the Bogo with 5. Nf3} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. e3 {This is the only independent try we need to examine as 6. Nf3 transposes to the Bogo after 6... Bxd2 +.} e5 {We take advantage of White's knight still being on g1 and execute our key strategic idea.} 7. d5 {White grabs more space and hits our knight with a tempo.} Bxd2+ {We first trade the bishops before White gets a chance to play Nc3 .} 8. Nxd2 Nb8 9. Ne2 d6 10. O-O h5 {A cool idea that we'll see in the Symmetrical English .} 11. h3 a5 {The game is balanced. We will play ... Na6 and ... O-O next.} *

