1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. g3 {This is an attempt by White to get into the Catalan but deny Black the option of the solid Queen's Indian Defense (QID) since b6? is now met with . However, since we play ... Bb4 + anyways, it's not a big deal for us. The only lines we have to learn is when White keeps the knight on g1 .} Bb4+ ({We aim to transpose to the Bogo after Bd2} 3... Qe7) ({or the Nimzo after Nc3} 3... c5 {.}) 4. Bd2 {This is White's most common move.} Qe7 {We defend the bishop and give White a chance to transpose to the Bogo with 5. Nf3} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. e3 {This is the only independent try we need to examine as 6. Nf3 transposes to the Bogo after 6... Bxd2 +.} e5 {We take advantage of White's knight still being on g1 and execute our key strategic idea.} 7. d5 {White grabs more space and hits our knight with a tempo.} Bxd2+ {We first trade the bishops before White gets a chance to play Nc3 .} 8. Qxd2 Nb8 {By now, a familiar retreat square. We will play for ... d6 , ... a5 and ... Na6 - c5 regrouping later.} 9. d6 {White tries to clog up our development with this pawn sacrifice.} Qxd6 10. Qxd6 cxd6 11. Nc3 Na6 {A natural square for our knight as it may head to ... c5 or ... c7 .} 12. Nge2 Nc7 {We prepare to sacrifice the pawn back with ... d5 !} 13. O-O d5 14. cxd5 d6 {Our bishop is now able to develop and the game is balanced. We will play ... Bd7 next with options to castle either side or keep the king in the center with ... Ke7 .} *

