1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. c4 e6 {We are getting ready to develop our bishop to b4 against both Nc3 and Nf3 .} 3. g3 {This is an attempt by White to get into the Catalan but deny Black the option of the solid Queen's Indian Defense (QID) since b6? is now met with . However, since we play ... Bb4 + anyways, it's not a big deal for us. The only lines we have to learn is when White keeps the knight on g1 .} Bb4+ ({We aim to transpose to the Bogo after Bd2} 3... Qe7) ({or the Nimzo after Nc3} 3... c5 {.}) 4. Bd2 {This is White's most common move.} Qe7 {We defend the bishop and give White a chance to transpose to the Bogo with 5. Nf3} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. e3 {This is the only independent try we need to examine as 6. Nf3 transposes to the Bogo after 6... Bxd2 +.} e5 {We take advantage of White's knight still being on g1 and execute our key strategic idea.} 7. d5 {White grabs more space and hits our knight with a tempo.} Bxd2+ {We first trade the bishops before White gets a chance to play Nc3 .} 8. Qxd2 Nb8 {By now, a familiar retreat square. We will play for ... d6 , ... a5 and ... Na6 - c5 regrouping later.} 9. Nc3 d6 10. Nge2 a5 {We secure a c5 -outpost for our knight.} 11. O-O h5 {We've seen this idea vs the Symmetrical English where White went for Nge2 plan. It works here just as well! We would like to play ... h4 next.} 12. h3 {White is ready to meet ... h4 with g4 .} Na6 {We continue with original plan of getting the knight to c5 .} 13. f4 Nc5 14. Rae1 O-O {We will play ... Bd7 and connect our rooks. The game is balanced but I prefer Black since it's hard for White to generate counterplay on either side.} *

