1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {White skips the c4 -move and goes for the Pseudo-Catalan. Since this move order avoids the Bogo (3. c4  Bb4 +) and we don't play the Queen's Indian Defense (QID) with 3... b6 , we need a new weapon.   Luckily, our original recommendation of the aggressive 3... b5 ! is quite strong, and that's what I recommend.} b5 {We take advantage of White skipping the move c4 and advance our pawn to two squares. This gives up excellent central control and an ability to neutralize White's strong LSB.} 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O ({White typically castles first. Please note that} 5. a4 b4 {will transpose.}) 5... c5 {We strike the center, hoping to trade a side pawn for a central pawn.} 6. a4 b4 {We restrict the b1 -knight.} 7. c3 Na6 {Remember, this is the best way to develop our knight. We defend both the c5 & b4 pawns and don't block the bishop.} 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Nbd2 O-O {Black has completed development and has a solid position. White is having difficulty coming up with a plan as Black controls the key central square e4 .} ({Here's an example of how the Ukrainian genius, Ivanchuk, outplayed White from this position in a blitz game: Re1} 9... Rc8 10. e4 bxc3 11. bxc3 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nb4 $1 {the knight is doing great on b4 .} 13. Qb3 a5 $1 {Securing the outpost.} 14. e5 Nfd5 15. Bxe7 Nxe7 16. Ne4 Bd5 17. Qe3 Nc2 {Brunner, N (2430)-Ivanchuk, V (2656) chess.com INT 2023}) *

