1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {White skips the c4 -move and goes for the Pseudo-Catalan. Since this move order avoids the Bogo (3. c4  Bb4 +) and we don't play the Queen's Indian Defense (QID) with 3... b6 , we need a new weapon.   Luckily, our original recommendation of the aggressive 3... b5 ! is quite strong, and that's what I recommend.} b5 {We take advantage of White skipping the move c4 and advance our pawn to two squares. This gives up excellent central control and an ability to neutralize White's strong LSB.} 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O ({White typically castles first. Please note that} 5. a4 b4 {will transpose.}) 5... c5 {We strike the center, hoping to trade a side pawn for a central pawn.} 6. c3 {This is a solid move and was played by Dubov vs Carlsen at World Blitz in 2022.} Be7 {We go for the natural development.} 7. Bg5 (7. dxc5 Bxc5 {is a favorable trade for us. Yes, we wasted a tempo by moving twice with the bishop, but c3 is hardly a developing move.}) 7... Na6 {The best square for the knight! We don't block the bishop and support our c5 -pawn.} 8. Nbd2 (8. a4 b4 {transposes to the 6.a4 line .}) 8... O-O {Magnus completes his development. The game is about equal as both sides are quite solid.} 9. a3 {Dubov is preparing b4 . I also had this position as Black vs GM Ramirez in 2018.} cxd4 {Magnus decides to clarify the situation, but Black can keep the tension with ... h6 . This was my choice vs Ramirez.} ({My game continued:} 9... h6 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. b4 d6 12. e3 Qb6 {with equal chances, Ramirez-Perelshteyn, Reykjavik Open, 2018.}) 10. cxd4 h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. e3 Qb6 {This a natural square for our queen.} 13. Qe2 Rac8 {White's solid structure is hard to break even though Black has the bishop pair. The game was eventually drawn on move 30. Dubov,D (2708)-Carlsen, M (2859) Almaty, 2022.} *

