1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {White skips the c4 -move and goes for the Pseudo-Catalan. Since this move order avoids the Bogo (3. c4  Bb4 +) and we don't play the Queen's Indian Defense (QID) with 3... b6 , we need a new weapon.   Luckily, our original recommendation of the aggressive 3... b5 ! is quite strong, and that's what I recommend.} b5 {We take advantage of White skipping the move c4 and advance our pawn to two squares. This gives up excellent central control and an ability to neutralize White's strong LSB.} 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O ({White typically castles first. Please note that} 5. a4 b4 {will transpose.}) 5... c5 {We strike the center, hoping to trade a side pawn for a central pawn.} 6. Bg5 {This move was recommended in the popular Chessable course Keep It Simple 1. d4 by IM Christof Sielecki, so we have to take it seriously!} cxd4 {We take the opportunity to execute a favorable trade.} 7. Nxd4 Bxg2 {We don't mind the trade of light-squared bishops as it weakens White's king.} 8. Kxg2 Be7 {A rare move, offering the b5 -pawn. I think this move is as good as the more popular choices of ... Qb6 or ... a6 . But now, White is likely out of book and has to navigate the tricky lines after Nxb5 .} 9. Nxb5 {This is the principled approach. Any slow move like 9.c3 allows ... Qb6 , and White can't ruin our pawn structure on the kingside anymore with Bxf6 due to ... Bxf6 .} Qb6 {We put pressure on the knight and X-ray the b2 -pawn.} 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Nd6+ {This only helps us.} Ke7 {And White is losing material.} *

