1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {White skips the c4 -move and goes for the Pseudo-Catalan. Since this move order avoids the Bogo (3. c4  Bb4 +) and we don't play the Queen's Indian Defense (QID) with 3... b6 , we need a new weapon.   Luckily, our original recommendation of the aggressive 3... b5 ! is quite strong, and that's what I recommend.} b5 {We take advantage of White skipping the move c4 and advance our pawn to two squares. This gives up excellent central control and an ability to neutralize White's strong LSB.} 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O ({White typically castles first. Please note that} 5. a4 b4 {will transpose.}) 5... c5 {We strike the center, hoping to trade a side pawn for a central pawn.} 6. Bg5 {This move was recommended in the popular Chessable course Keep It Simple 1. d4 by IM Christof Sielecki, so we have to take it seriously!} cxd4 {We take the opportunity to execute a favorable trade.} 7. Bxf6 {White hopes that by decoying the queen to f6 , they would take over the queenside.} Qxf6 8. Nxd4 Bxg2 9. Kxg2 {This is the position from Keep It Simple 1. d4 course. IM Sielecki only examines the passive 9…a6, which is too slow but playable for Black. Instead, I will give you a more active approach with ... Nc6 !} Nc6 {We develop and offer White a free pawn.} 10. Nxb5 (10. Nxc6 dxc6 {leads to a roughly even game where Black has no problems and can even outplay White with a bishop vs knight imbalance.}) 10... Rb8 ({This is the key move! Make sure you don't take the b2 -pawn as} 10... Qxb2 $2 11. N1c3 $1 {gives White a big edge.}) 11. N1c3 {This is White's best, going for rapid development.} a6 {A second invitation to give us the check on c7 , and White can also win the a6 -pawn!} 12. Nd6+ Bxd6 13. Qxd6 Rxb2 {We take the pawn and the c3 -knight is also under attack.} 14. Qa3 Rb4 ({I like this the most as we will castle next, but} 14... Rxc2 {is good as well.}) 15. Qxa6 O-O ({Not} 15... Qxc3 $2 16. Qc8+ {and we lose the h8 -rook. Black has excellent compensation for the pawn! White's king is exposed, and it's not easy to find a good square for the knight.}) *

