1. d4 Nf6 {We develop our knight first and take control over the vital e4 -square. The underlining theme of my course is to fight for the center with the pieces.} 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 {White skips the c4 -move and goes for the Pseudo-Catalan. Since this move order avoids the Bogo (3. c4  Bb4 +) and we don't play the Queen's Indian Defense (QID) with 3... b6 , we need a new weapon.   Luckily, our original recommendation of the aggressive 3... b5 ! is quite strong, and that's what I recommend.} b5 {We take advantage of White skipping the move c4 and advance our pawn to two squares. This gives up excellent central control and an ability to neutralize White's strong LSB.} 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O ({White typically castles first. Please note that} 5. a4 b4 {will transpose.}) 5... c5 {We strike the center, hoping to trade a side pawn for a central pawn.} 6. Bg5 {This move was recommended in the popular Chessable course Keep It Simple 1. d4 by IM Christof Sielecki, so we have to take it seriously!} cxd4 {We take the opportunity to execute a favorable trade.} 7. Bxf6 {White hopes that by decoying the queen to f6 , they would take over the queenside.} Qxf6 8. Nxd4 Bxg2 9. Kxg2 {This is the position from Keep It Simple 1. d4 course. IM Sielecki only examines the passive 9…a6, which is too slow but playable for Black. Instead, I will give you a more active approach with ... Nc6 !} Nc6 {We develop and offer White a free pawn.} 10. Nxb5 (10. Nxc6 dxc6 {leads to a roughly even game where Black has no problems and can even outplay White with a bishop vs knight imbalance.}) 10... Rb8 ({This is the key move! Make sure you don't take the b2 -pawn as} 10... Qxb2 $2 11. N1c3 $1 {gives White a big edge.}) 11. N1c3 {This is White's best, going for rapid development.} a6 {A second invitation to give us the check on c7 , and White can also win the a6 -pawn!} 12. Nc7+ {Wrong again!} Kd8 13. Nxa6 Rb6 {This time White is just worse (instead of being lost as in the 11.Nc7+? line ).} 14. Ne4 ({This is White's best try.} 14. Qd3 {is still met with} Qd4 $1) 14... Qf5 {At the moment both knights are under attack.} 15. Qd3 Ne5 {The key move! White has to give up the knight now.} 16. Qd4 {The only move.} Rxa6 17. Rfd1 d5 {It's true that White has compensation for the piece with precise moves, but still it's Black who's playing for a win.} ({For example: c4} 17... Nc6 18. Qd3 Nb4 {Qb1 Bd6! cxd5 Ke7! dxe6 fxe6} 19. Nd6 {Qxb1 Raxb1} Rxd6 {Rxd6 Kxd6 Black has consolidated and has good winning chances in this N vs 3 pawn endgame.}) *

