1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 {White goes for the solid London System, a popular setup at all levels. Once an obscure opening with a bad reputation, it got introduced at the top level by GM Gata Kamsky. However, it took decades for this setup to gain popularity and eventually all top level GMs starting playing it.   Here's just a short list of some names: Carlsen, Erigaisi, Gukesh, Firouzja, Grischuk and Giri. At the same time, popular streamers and YouTubers like Eric Rosen, Alex Banzea and many others popularized it for the masses.} ({I expect your opponent to be well-prepared in the main lines, and I will show you a totally fresh approach to deny White the easy setup. Please note that} 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 {will transpose.}) 2... e6 {Our standard reaction is the same as vs 2. c4 .} 3. Nf3 ({White's most popular move order, but} 3. e3 c5) ({or} 3. c3 c5 {will likely transpose.}) 3... c5 {We immediately strike at White's center. Remember, the key strategic idea is we are always happy to trade the side c-pawn for White's center d-pawn.} 4. dxc5 {This is a big concession and most London System players would not do it. But let me show you a simple setup here as well.} Bxc5 5. e3 Qb6 {A nice way to take advantage of White's early bishop sortie to f4 . Now, it’s not easy to defend the b2 -pawn without making some sort of concession.} 6. Qc1 {This is a less weakening defense than b3 , but the queen is misplaced on c1 .} Nc6 7. c4 {This is perhaps White's better try, but still Black has no problems at all.} Nh5 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 d5 {We don't mind the IQP as our pieces are more active.} 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nc3 {White attacks our pawn, but we will open up the game even more with ... d4 next!} d4 13. exd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 15. Bb5+ Kf8 {An instructive moment! Our king will be quite safe on g7 .} 16. O-O Nxg3 17. hxg3 Be6 {It's clear that Black's bishop pair dominates the open board. We will play ... Kg7 next and take over the center with our rooks.} *

