1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 {White goes for the solid London System, a popular setup at all levels. Once an obscure opening with a bad reputation, it got introduced at the top level by GM Gata Kamsky. However, it took decades for this setup to gain popularity and eventually all top level GMs starting playing it.   Here's just a short list of some names: Carlsen, Erigaisi, Gukesh, Firouzja, Grischuk and Giri. At the same time, popular streamers and YouTubers like Eric Rosen, Alex Banzea and many others popularized it for the masses.} ({I expect your opponent to be well-prepared in the main lines, and I will show you a totally fresh approach to deny White the easy setup. Please note that} 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 {will transpose.}) 2... e6 {Our standard reaction is the same as vs 2. c4 .} 3. Nf3 ({White's most popular move order, but} 3. e3 c5) ({or} 3. c3 c5 {will likely transpose.}) 3... c5 {We immediately strike at White's center. Remember, the key strategic idea is we are always happy to trade the side c-pawn for White's center d-pawn.} 4. dxc5 {This is a big concession and most London System players would not do it. But let me show you a simple setup here as well.} Bxc5 5. e3 Qb6 {A nice way to take advantage of White's early bishop sortie to f4 . Now, it’s not easy to defend the b2 -pawn without making some sort of concession.} 6. b3 {This move seriously weakens White's queenside, especially the c3 & b4 squares.} d5 {Simple chess, we just take over the center.} 7. Bd3 Nc6 8. O-O Nh5 {If we can trade this knight for the bishop, it's usually a good idea.} 9. Bg3 Nxg3 10. hxg3 O-O {We are not afraid of White's attack.} 11. Ng5 f5 {We blunt the bishop first.} 12. Qh5 h6 {And now we kick back the knight.} 13. Nh3 Bd7 {Black has a big edge already with lots of different plans to choose from such as ... e5 or ... Ne5 .} *

