1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 {White goes for the solid London System, a popular setup at all levels. Once an obscure opening with a bad reputation, it got introduced at the top level by GM Gata Kamsky. However, it took decades for this setup to gain popularity and eventually all top level GMs starting playing it.   Here's just a short list of some names: Carlsen, Erigaisi, Gukesh, Firouzja, Grischuk and Giri. At the same time, popular streamers and YouTubers like Eric Rosen, Alex Banzea and many others popularized it for the masses.} ({I expect your opponent to be well-prepared in the main lines, and I will show you a totally fresh approach to deny White the easy setup. Please note that} 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 {will transpose.}) 2... e6 {Our standard reaction is the same as vs 2. c4 .} 3. Nf3 ({White's most popular move order, but} 3. e3 c5) ({or} 3. c3 c5 {will likely transpose.}) 3... c5 {We immediately strike at White's center. Remember, the key strategic idea is we are always happy to trade the side c-pawn for White's center d-pawn.} 4. e3 {White's main move. They are hoping for the classic London Setup after 4... d5 when they will play the following moves on autopilot: c3 , Bd3 , h3 , O-O etc. and start the attack with Ne5 .} (4. c3 Be7 5. e3 {transposes to the 4. e3 lines.}) 4... Be7 {This rare move is my recommendation! In the Master DB it is only the 6th most played move, thus your opponent will not expect it!   The key part of our plan is NOT to play ... d5 at all. We need to keep the d-pawn on d7 for now and see how White reacts.} 5. Nc3 {Not a typical London move, but here White is thinking of playing Nb5 at some point.} a6 {Simple chess, we stop any Nd5 jumps.} 6. d5 {This is a somewhat ambitious idea to grab more space. Now the game is looking like Benoni pawn structure.} d6 7. e4 b5 {This is the typical Benoni pawn expansion. White didn't get a chance to stop it with a4 .} 8. dxe6 Bxe6 9. a3 Nc6 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O h6 {We've reached a comfortable position for Black. Our plan is to regroup with ... Re8 and ... Bf8 and break open the center with a timely ... d5 push.} *

