1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 {White goes for the solid London System, a popular setup at all levels. Once an obscure opening with a bad reputation, it got introduced at the top level by GM Gata Kamsky. However, it took decades for this setup to gain popularity and eventually all top level GMs starting playing it.   Here's just a short list of some names: Carlsen, Erigaisi, Gukesh, Firouzja, Grischuk and Giri. At the same time, popular streamers and YouTubers like Eric Rosen, Alex Banzea and many others popularized it for the masses.} ({I expect your opponent to be well-prepared in the main lines, and I will show you a totally fresh approach to deny White the easy setup. Please note that} 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 {will transpose.}) 2... e6 {Our standard reaction is the same as vs 2. c4 .} 3. Nf3 ({White's most popular move order, but} 3. e3 c5) ({or} 3. c3 c5 {will likely transpose.}) 3... c5 {We immediately strike at White's center. Remember, the key strategic idea is we are always happy to trade the side c-pawn for White's center d-pawn.} 4. e3 {White's main move. They are hoping for the classic London Setup after 4... d5 when they will play the following moves on autopilot: c3 , Bd3 , h3 , O-O etc. and start the attack with Ne5 .} (4. c3 Be7 5. e3 {transposes to the 4. e3 lines.}) 4... Be7 {This rare move is my recommendation! In the Master DB it is only the 6th most played move, thus your opponent will not expect it!   The key part of our plan is NOT to play ... d5 at all. We need to keep the d-pawn on d7 for now and see how White reacts.} 5. dxc5 {This is a logical move to try to win a tempo, however I believe most London players won't play it as it ruins their setup.} Qa5+ {It's better to take the pawn with our queen.} 6. Nbd2 {This is the most logical way to block the check.} Qxc5 {We've achieved our strategic objective. Black has two central pawns: e6 & d7 vs White's one: the e3 -pawn.} 7. c4 ({If White plays} 7. c3 {then after} d5 {we get an even bigger chunk of the center.}) 7... d6 {We build a small center with ... e6 & ... d6 and get ready to launch ... e5 in the future.} (7... d5 $2 {allows White to get an edge after} 8. a3 a5 9. cxd5 Qxd5 ({(} 9... Nxd5 $2 10. Rc1 $1 {wins the bishop )}) 10. Nc4 {and b6 is too weak.}) 8. Be2 e5 {We use our central pawn to push back the bishop.} 9. Bg5 Nbd7 10. O-O {This natural move loses a piece by force!} e4 11. Bxf6 exf3 12. Bxe7 fxe2 {The key intermezzo!} 13. Qxe2 Kxe7 {And Black is winning here with an extra piece.} *

