1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 {White goes for the solid London System, a popular setup at all levels. Once an obscure opening with a bad reputation, it got introduced at the top level by GM Gata Kamsky. However, it took decades for this setup to gain popularity and eventually all top level GMs starting playing it.   Here's just a short list of some names: Carlsen, Erigaisi, Gukesh, Firouzja, Grischuk and Giri. At the same time, popular streamers and YouTubers like Eric Rosen, Alex Banzea and many others popularized it for the masses.} ({I expect your opponent to be well-prepared in the main lines, and I will show you a totally fresh approach to deny White the easy setup. Please note that} 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 {will transpose.}) 2... e6 {Our standard reaction is the same as vs 2. c4 .} 3. Nf3 ({White's most popular move order, but} 3. e3 c5) ({or} 3. c3 c5 {will likely transpose.}) 3... c5 {We immediately strike at White's center. Remember, the key strategic idea is we are always happy to trade the side c-pawn for White's center d-pawn.} 4. e3 {White's main move. They are hoping for the classic London Setup after 4... d5 when they will play the following moves on autopilot: c3 , Bd3 , h3 , O-O etc. and start the attack with Ne5 .} (4. c3 Be7 5. e3 {transposes to the 4. e3 lines.}) 4... Be7 {This rare move is my recommendation! In the Master DB it is only the 6th most played move, thus your opponent will not expect it!   The key part of our plan is NOT to play ... d5 at all. We need to keep the d-pawn on d7 for now and see how White reacts.} 5. c3 {This is the most common move seen in 51% of blitz games. White completes their central triangle setup. However, I believe it's quite a serious inaccuracy, as it allows us to go after the DSB with ... Nh5 !} Nh5 {Remember this idea! Since White never played h3 , we will trade our knight for this bishop. Please note that we also cover the g5 -square and now you can see why ... Be7 was such a sneaky move!   As a rule of thumb, if White allows this trade, they can already forget about any opening advantage!} 6. Bg3 {A standard retreat in order to recapture back with hxg3 .} Nc6 {We can take on g3 at any point, so we develop keeping our options open.} 7. Nbd2 {White is thinking about a Nc4 jump next.} (7. Bd3 g6 8. Nbd2 d5 {transposes.}) 7... d5 {Please note that normally we don't play this move as it weakens the e5 -square, but since White is about to lose their DSB, this is totally justified.} 8. Ne5 {White takes over the outpost, but it's only temporary.} Nxg3 9. hxg3 Nxe5 10. dxe5 {As long as we don't play ... O-O , White has no attack. As a matter of fact Black is already better as long as we castle long!} Bd7 {Getting ready for long castling with ... Qc7 & ... O-O-O .} 11. Bd3 Qc7 12. Nf3 O-O-O {Black's king is much safer, plus we have the bishop pair advantage. The engine already gives us a nice -1.3 advantage. Please note that the pawn on h7 is taboo as we always have ... g6 to trap the bishop on h7 .} *

