this trade, they can already forget about any opening advantage!} 6. Bg3 {A standard retreat in order to recapture back with hxg3 .} Nc6 {We can take on g3 at any point, so we develop keeping our options open.} 7. Nbd2 {White is thinking about a Nc4 jump next.} (7. Bd3 g6 8. Nbd2 d5 {transposes.}) 7... d5 {Please note that normally we don't play this move as it weakens the e5 -square, but since White is about to lose their DSB, this is totally justified.} 8. Bd3 {A standard square for the LSB in the London.} g6 {A simple waiting move. Of course we can castle, but I'd rather not show White our hand yet.} 9. Qe2 {A flexible move. White keeps their options open where to castle.} Bd7 {Black has many good moves, but I like this simple approach to develop our bishop and wait to see where White would castle.} 10. O-O-O {This is White's most ambitious option and also turns out to be a losing mistake!} c4 {We launch our pawn storm ASAP!} 11. Bb1 b5 {Believe it or not but White is already lost here! They can't stop ... b4 with a winning attack. The engine gives us a -2.8 advantage!} ({Here's a fun line to illustrate this point: e4 b4 exd5 exd5} 11... Bh4 {bxc3 bxc3 Qa5 Qe3 Qa3+} 12. Kc2 {Bf5+-+}) *

