1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 {White goes for the solid London System, a popular setup at all levels. Once an obscure opening with a bad reputation, it got introduced at the top level by GM Gata Kamsky. However, it took decades for this setup to gain popularity and eventually all top level GMs starting playing it.   Here's just a short list of some names: Carlsen, Erigaisi, Gukesh, Firouzja, Grischuk and Giri. At the same time, popular streamers and YouTubers like Eric Rosen, Alex Banzea and many others popularized it for the masses.} ({I expect your opponent to be well-prepared in the main lines, and I will show you a totally fresh approach to deny White the easy setup. Please note that} 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 {will transpose.}) 2... e6 {Our standard reaction is the same as vs 2. c4 .} 3. Nf3 ({White's most popular move order, but} 3. e3 c5) ({or} 3. c3 c5 {will likely transpose.}) 3... c5 {We immediately strike at White's center. Remember, the key strategic idea is we are always happy to trade the side c-pawn for White's center d-pawn.} 4. e3 {White's main move. They are hoping for the classic London Setup after 4... d5 when they will play the following moves on autopilot: c3 , Bd3 , h3 , O-O etc. and start the attack with Ne5 .} (4. c3 Be7 5. e3 {transposes to the 4. e3 lines.}) 4... Be7 {This rare move is my recommendation! In the Master DB it is only the 6th most played move, thus your opponent will not expect it!   The key part of our plan is NOT to play ... d5 at all. We need to keep the d-pawn on d7 for now and see how White reacts.} 5. h3 {If our opponent is alert, they will play this standard move, anticipating ... Nh5 !} O-O ({This is more accurate than ... b6 , since} 5... b6 {allows} 6. Nc3 $1 {with the idea of Nb5 .}) 6. c3 {White has achieved their setup and expects an easy game with Bd3 , Nbd2 , O-O etc.   However, we have a special surprise for them!} b6 {The point! We don't play ... d5 but rather get ready to trade light-squared bishops with ... Ba6 !} 7. Bd3 {This autopilot move is now met with ... Ba6 !} Ba6 {The key idea for you to remember! We generally welcome the trade of light-squared bishops in the London System.} 8. Bxa6 Nxa6 9. O-O {We achieved our goal of trading the light-squared bishop, but now our knight is a bit misplaced on a6 .} Qc8 {Black has several good moves such as 9... d5 , but I'd like to be flexible and first transfer our queen to b7 .} 10. Nbd2 Qb7 11. Qe2 {Both sides have completed development and the position is about even. Black has many good plans, but I'd like to recommend to trade on d4 and get a familiar structure first.} cxd4 12. exd4 {This is the autopilot way for White to recapture and we get the same type of position covered in the main line after 7. Nbd2 but up a tempo for Black since White played Bd3 then Bxa6 .} Nc7 {Let's improve our knight first.} 13. a4 {White stops ... b5 .} d6 14. Rfe1 Ncd5 15. Bh2 a6 {We have a good Hedgehog setup with pawns on e6 , d6 , b6 , & a6 , denying White any outposts in the center. Black will play for ... b5 next with a clear plan to put pressure on the queenside while it's unclear what White should do.} *

