1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 {White goes for the solid London System, a popular setup at all levels. Once an obscure opening with a bad reputation, it got introduced at the top level by GM Gata Kamsky. However, it took decades for this setup to gain popularity and eventually all top level GMs starting playing it.   Here's just a short list of some names: Carlsen, Erigaisi, Gukesh, Firouzja, Grischuk and Giri. At the same time, popular streamers and YouTubers like Eric Rosen, Alex Banzea and many others popularized it for the masses.} ({I expect your opponent to be well-prepared in the main lines, and I will show you a totally fresh approach to deny White the easy setup. Please note that} 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 {will transpose.}) 2... e6 {Our standard reaction is the same as vs 2. c4 .} 3. Nf3 ({White's most popular move order, but} 3. e3 c5) ({or} 3. c3 c5 {will likely transpose.}) 3... c5 {We immediately strike at White's center. Remember, the key strategic idea is we are always happy to trade the side c-pawn for White's center d-pawn.} 4. e3 {White's main move. They are hoping for the classic London Setup after 4... d5 when they will play the following moves on autopilot: c3 , Bd3 , h3 , O-O etc. and start the attack with Ne5 .} (4. c3 Be7 5. e3 {transposes to the 4. e3 lines.}) 4... Be7 {This rare move is my recommendation! In the Master DB it is only the 6th most played move, thus your opponent will not expect it!   The key part of our plan is NOT to play ... d5 at all. We need to keep the d-pawn on d7 for now and see how White reacts.} 5. h3 {If our opponent is alert, they will play this standard move, anticipating ... Nh5 !} O-O ({This is more accurate than ... b6 , since} 5... b6 {allows} 6. Nc3 $1 {with the idea of Nb5 .}) 6. c3 {White has achieved their setup and expects an easy game with Bd3 , Nbd2 , O-O etc.   However, we have a special surprise for them!} b6 {The point! We don't play ... d5 but rather get ready to trade light-squared bishops with ... Ba6 !} 7. Bd3 {This autopilot move is now met with ... Ba6 !} Ba6 {The key idea for you to remember! We generally welcome the trade of light-squared bishops in the London System.} 8. O-O Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nc6 10. Nbd2 d5 {Black has achieved the Dream version of the Classical London System but WITHOUT the light-squared bishops. This means that White has no attack and no advantage! The position is even, but let me show you a possible line.} 11. Ne5 {White still pins their hopes on this standard idea.} Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Nd7 13. Bg3 Qc8 {The queen is heading to a nice square on b7 .} 14. f4 {White tries to attack, but it will only backfire.} f5 {We have a famous double Stonewall setup but clearly White didn't get the memo and put his pawns on the color of his bishop, thus violating the Capablanca rule: Don't Put Pawns On the Color of Your Bishop or they may be targets.} 15. Nf3 c4 16. Qc2 b5 {We will play for the ... b4 pawn push while it's unclear what White should be doing as they don't have any attack.} *

