e wants to save a tempo and meet} 7. Ba6 {with} Bxa6 {in one go.}) 7... cxd4 {This trade is quite typical but it's best to do it now to force White's e3 -pawn to d4 .} (7... Ba6 8. Bxa6 Nxa6 {allows White to play e4 or Qe2 followed by e4 . Even here, the position remains even.}) 8. cxd4 d6 {Of course we can swap the bishops right away with ... Ba6 , but why not try to gain a tempo?} 9. Qa4 {White stops our ... Ba6 idea} Bb7 {The bishop is well-placed on the h1 - a8 diagonal.} 10. Bd3 Nbd7 {We develop naturally to not obstruct our bishop.} 11. O-O {This natural move is a big blunder!} e5 {And now White loses a piece by force due to the loose bishop on d3 .} 12. dxe5 (12. Bg3 {loses a piece after a} e4 {fork.}) 12... dxe5 13. Nxe5 {If White doesn't take the pawn and retreats the bishop then we win with a ... Nc5 fork!} Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Qxd3 {Black is up a piece and totally winning.} *

