1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 {White goes for the solid London System, a popular setup at all levels. Once an obscure opening with a bad reputation, it got introduced at the top level by GM Gata Kamsky. However, it took decades for this setup to gain popularity and eventually all top level GMs starting playing it.   Here's just a short list of some names: Carlsen, Erigaisi, Gukesh, Firouzja, Grischuk and Giri. At the same time, popular streamers and YouTubers like Eric Rosen, Alex Banzea and many others popularized it for the masses.} ({I expect your opponent to be well-prepared in the main lines, and I will show you a totally fresh approach to deny White the easy setup. Please note that} 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 {will transpose.}) 2... e6 {Our standard reaction is the same as vs 2. c4 .} 3. Nf3 ({White's most popular move order, but} 3. e3 c5) ({or} 3. c3 c5 {will likely transpose.}) 3... c5 {We immediately strike at White's center. Remember, the key strategic idea is we are always happy to trade the side c-pawn for White's center d-pawn.} 4. e3 {White's main move. They are hoping for the classic London Setup after 4... d5 when they will play the following moves on autopilot: c3 , Bd3 , h3 , O-O etc. and start the attack with Ne5 .} (4. c3 Be7 5. e3 {transposes to the 4. e3 lines.}) 4... Be7 {This rare move is my recommendation! In the Master DB it is only the 6th most played move, thus your opponent will not expect it!   The key part of our plan is NOT to play ... d5 at all. We need to keep the d-pawn on d7 for now and see how White reacts.} 5. h3 {If our opponent is alert, they will play this standard move, anticipating ... Nh5 !} O-O ({This is more accurate than ... b6 , since} 5... b6 {allows} 6. Nc3 $1 {with the idea of Nb5 .}) 6. c3 {White has achieved their setup and expects an easy game with Bd3 , Nbd2 , O-O etc.   However, we have a special surprise for them!} b6 {The point! We don't play ... d5 but rather get ready to trade light-squared bishops with ... Ba6 !} 7. Nbd2 ({White wants to save a tempo and meet} 7. Ba6 {with} Bxa6 {in one go.}) 7... cxd4 {This trade is quite typical but it's best to do it now to force White's e3 -pawn to d4 .} (7... Ba6 8. Bxa6 Nxa6 {allows White to play e4 or Qe2 followed by e4 . Even here, the position remains even.}) 8. exd4 {This is the autopilot recapture in the London, White typically likes their b2 - c3 - d4 pawn chain.} Ba6 {This is the key strategic idea of our setup! By trading light-squared bishops we take the string out of the London System. In my original book, we recommended the Hedgehog setup for Black after 8... Bb7 , d6 , a6 , Nbd7 and going for the e5 break after ... Re8 , Bf8 , e5 , but I think this is a much easier plan.} 9. c4 {This move, trying to stop the bishop trade, is ill-advised due to the fact that we can undermine the c4 -pawn with ... d5 .} d5 {Now, White gets a bad pawn structure.} 10. b3 Nc6 11. Be2 dxc4 12. Nxc4 {Now, Black has a big positional edge, White's weak d4 -pawn also known as the IQP.} Ne4 {This the most ambitious but other moves like ... Nd5 are great too.} 13. Rc1 Bb4+ {White can't easily block the check as they will lose the d4 -pawn.} 14. Kf1 Nc3 {Black is almost winning here! The engine gives -3 already.} *

