1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 {White goes for the solid London System, a popular setup at all levels. Once an obscure opening with a bad reputation, it got introduced at the top level by GM Gata Kamsky. However, it took decades for this setup to gain popularity and eventually all top level GMs starting playing it.   Here's just a short list of some names: Carlsen, Erigaisi, Gukesh, Firouzja, Grischuk and Giri. At the same time, popular streamers and YouTubers like Eric Rosen, Alex Banzea and many others popularized it for the masses.} ({I expect your opponent to be well-prepared in the main lines, and I will show you a totally fresh approach to deny White the easy setup. Please note that} 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 {will transpose.}) 2... e6 {Our standard reaction is the same as vs 2. c4 .} 3. Nf3 ({White's most popular move order, but} 3. e3 c5) ({or} 3. c3 c5 {will likely transpose.}) 3... c5 {We immediately strike at White's center. Remember, the key strategic idea is we are always happy to trade the side c-pawn for White's center d-pawn.} 4. e3 {White's main move. They are hoping for the classic London Setup after 4... d5 when they will play the following moves on autopilot: c3 , Bd3 , h3 , O-O etc. and start the attack with Ne5 .} (4. c3 Be7 5. e3 {transposes to the 4. e3 lines.}) 4... Be7 {This rare move is my recommendation! In the Master DB it is only the 6th most played move, thus your opponent will not expect it!   The key part of our plan is NOT to play ... d5 at all. We need to keep the d-pawn on d7 for now and see how White reacts.} 5. h3 {If our opponent is alert, they will play this standard move, anticipating ... Nh5 !} O-O ({This is more accurate than ... b6 , since} 5... b6 {allows} 6. Nc3 $1 {with the idea of Nb5 .}) 6. c3 {White has achieved their setup and expects an easy game with Bd3 , Nbd2 , O-O etc.   However, we have a special surprise for them!} b6 {The point! We don't play ... d5 but rather get ready to trade light-squared bishops with ... Ba6 !} 7. Nbd2 ({White wants to save a tempo and meet} 7. Ba6 {with} Bxa6 {in one go.}) 7... cxd4 {This trade is quite typical but it's best to do it now to force White's e3 -pawn to d4 .} (7... Ba6 8. Bxa6 Nxa6 {allows White to play e4 or Qe2 followed by e4 . Even here, the position remains even.}) 8. exd4 {This is the autopilot recapture in the London, White typically likes their b2 - c3 - d4 pawn chain.} Ba6 {This is the key strategic idea of our setup! By trading light-squared bishops we take the string out of the London System. In my original book, we recommended the Hedgehog setup for Black after 8... Bb7 , d6 , a6 , Nbd7 and going for the e5 break after ... Re8 , Bf8 , e5 , but I think this is a much easier plan.} 9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. O-O {Both sides have finished development, and it's clear that White is missing their star piece: the light-squared bishop on d3 . Without this bishop, White can't generate any attack.   Now, the game enters the maneuvering stage, where we slowly improve our pieces and bring the a6 -knight back in the game.} Nc7 {The knight will eventually head to d5 -outpost.} 11. Qe2 {White connects their rooks.} Qc8 {We also improve our queen as she's heading to b7 .} 12. Rfe1 Qb7 13. a4 {White tries to slow us down as ... b5 is a common idea.} Ncd5 {Kicking back the bishop.} 14. Bh2 a6 {Black will play ... b5 next with a nice bind on the queenside. White's position remains solid, but without a plan. This position happened in a blitz game Wojtaszek-Leko in 2016 which I give below.} ({Nc4} 14... h6 15. Qd3 b5 $1 16. axb5 {axb5 Nd6} Bd6 17. Bxd6 Rfc8 {Nd2} 18. Ra6 {Be5 d6 Bh2 Rca8 Black is about to win the a-file. Rxa6} Qxa6 {Black is clearly better, but white defended well to hold the draw.} 19. b3 {Rc8 c4 bxc4 bxc4} Nb6 {Bxd6} 20. Nc4 {Bc5} Qa5 {Nf3} 21. Nxb6 {Bxb6} Qxb6 22. Rb1 Qxd6 23. g3 Rd8 {Qb5 Qd5 Qxd5 Nxd5 Rb7 f6} 24. h4 h5 25. Kf1 Kf8 26. Ke2 {Ra8 Nd2 Ra2 Kd3 Ra3+ Rb3}) *

