1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {This move is a clear indication that White wants to play 3. e4 next.   However, the biggest drawback is that after logical 2... d5 the knight on c3 is always misplaced since White can't easily play in the Queen's Gambit style with c4 .} d5 {Of course, we stop White's e4 plan right away. In this chapter we will cover the trendy Jobava Attack after 3. Bf4 .   Please see Veresov 3.Bg5 and the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit .} 3. Bf4 {This is the Jobava London, a trendy and popular line at both GM and club level. It was popularized by famous streamers and YouTubers IM Eric Rosen and IM Levy Rozman.   White combines the idea with the London System and aims to play Nb5 next to target the c7 -pawn.} a6 {I like this simple prophylactic move. We stop Nb5 forever and plan to develop naturally with ... Bf5 & ... e6 next.} 4. e3 Bf5 {I recommend to get the bishop outside the pawn chain first, and only then follow up with ... e6 .   Here, White has two approaches: an immediate kingside expansion with f3 & g4 or develop with natural moves such as Nf3 and Bd3 .} 5. Nf3 {White typically aims to establish the knight on e5 as quickly as possible in this line.} e6 6. Ne5 {This is White's best try. Ukrainian GM Bortnyk has played this countless times online with good success. It is also the main recommendation by GM Hans Niemann and FM James Canty in their Chessable courses.} Bb4 {Surprisingly, this natural development move, pinning the knight hasn't been played at the top level much.} 7. g4 {This is really the only move you need to worry about as Black. Since it's recommended by GM Niemann, we need to be ready for it!} Nxg4 {First, we sacrifice a knight!} 8. Nxg4 h5 ({And this is the key follow-up! We are actually planning to trap their bishop after Ne5} 8... g5 $1) 9. Ne5 g5 ({Now, our idea becomes clear. The bishop retreat Bg3 will be met with} 9... h4 $1 {and we get our piece back.}) 10. Nxf7 {This is recommended by Hans, but I believe Black is totally fine after} Kxf7 11. Be5 Rh7 {Yes, it's true that Black lost the right to castle. However, we will follow up with ... Nd7 next to trade for the strong e5 -bishop. Then it will be quite clear that White's shattered structure will be no match for our bishop pair.} 12. Be2 {A tempo on the h5 -pawn, but we just ignore it!} Nd7 13. Bxh5+ Ke7 {Our king is very safe in the center while White's monarch is having trouble being evacuated from the center.} 14. Bg3 Nf6 {A nice tempo move.} 15. Bf3 ({The only move, please note that} 15. Be2 {loses to} Ne4 $1) 15... g4 16. Bg2 ({Again} 16. Be2 {is met with} Ne4 $1) 16... Ne4 17. Bxe4 Bxe4 {It's clear that Black has excellent compensation for the pawn as we will play ... Bf3 next and take full control over the light squares. While objectively White's position is holdable, in practice it's no fun at all!} *

