1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {This move is a clear indication that White wants to play 3. e4 next.   However, the biggest drawback is that after logical 2... d5 the knight on c3 is always misplaced since White can't easily play in the Queen's Gambit style with c4 .} d5 {Of course, we stop White's e4 plan right away. In this chapter we will cover the trendy Jobava Attack after 3. Bf4 .   Please see Veresov 3.Bg5 and the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit .} 3. Bf4 {This is the Jobava London, a trendy and popular line at both GM and club level. It was popularized by famous streamers and YouTubers IM Eric Rosen and IM Levy Rozman.   White combines the idea with the London System and aims to play Nb5 next to target the c7 -pawn.} a6 {I like this simple prophylactic move. We stop Nb5 forever and plan to develop naturally with ... Bf5 & ... e6 next.} 4. e3 Bf5 {I recommend to get the bishop outside the pawn chain first, and only then follow up with ... e6 .   Here, White has two approaches: an immediate kingside expansion with f3 & g4 or develop with natural moves such as Nf3 and Bd3 .} 5. Bd3 {This is totally harmless move and best way to deal with it is to drop the bishop on g6 .} Bg6 {Just like in the Slav Defense, this standard idea works here as well. We are always ready to recapture on g6 with the h-pawn.} 6. Nf3 e6 7. Ne5 {White's ideal square for the knight. However, our bishop on g6 is rock solid and we just continue with the standard plan of ... c5 next.} c5 {We undermine White's center and don't mind any trade on g6 .} 8. O-O {This move was played in a blitz game by Jobava himself! However, Black has no problems after the natural ... Nbd7 .} Nbd7 ({The simplest, we don't want to give White any targets as in this line} 8... Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {.}) 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. h3 Be7 11. a4 O-O {Black's king is totally safe and we have easy play on the queenside with ... Rc8 and ... Qb6 next. White doesn't really have a plan.} *

