1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {This move is a clear indication that White wants to play 3. e4 next.   However, the biggest drawback is that after logical 2... d5 the knight on c3 is always misplaced since White can't easily play in the Queen's Gambit style with c4 .} d5 {Of course, we stop White's e4 plan right away. In this chapter we will cover the trendy Jobava Attack after 3. Bf4 .   Please see Veresov 3.Bg5 and the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit .} 3. Bf4 {This is the Jobava London, a trendy and popular line at both GM and club level. It was popularized by famous streamers and YouTubers IM Eric Rosen and IM Levy Rozman.   White combines the idea with the London System and aims to play Nb5 next to target the c7 -pawn.} a6 {I like this simple prophylactic move. We stop Nb5 forever and plan to develop naturally with ... Bf5 & ... e6 next.} 4. e3 Bf5 {I recommend to get the bishop outside the pawn chain first, and only then follow up with ... e6 .   Here, White has two approaches: an immediate kingside expansion with f3 & g4 or develop with natural moves such as Nf3 and Bd3 .} 5. f3 {This the most aggressive setup. White will follow up with g4 & h4 kingside expansion next. But we will be ready for it!} e6 6. g4 Bg6 7. h4 {It looks as though our bishop is getting trapped but in reality, Black is totally fine!} h6 {Simple chess! We create a safety square for our bishop on h7 .} ({Please note that} 7... h5 {is playable as well, but I prefer this move. Now, White can play 8. Bd3 right away or insert 8. h5 first.}) 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 c5 {Just like in the 8.Bd3 line , we will play ... Nc6 and ... c4 ! with initiative on the queenside.} 11. Nge2 Nc6 12. O-O-O c4 {Black executes the standard attack with a tempo!} 13. Qd2 b5 {We will follow up with ... b4 with a deadly attack. Please note that our king is quite safe.} *

