1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {This move is a clear indication that White wants to play 3. e4 next.   However, the biggest drawback is that after logical 2... d5 the knight on c3 is always misplaced since White can't easily play in the Queen's Gambit style with c4 .} d5 {Of course, we stop White's e4 plan right away. In this chapter we will cover the trendy Jobava Attack after 3. Bf4 .   Please see Veresov 3.Bg5 and the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit .} 3. Bf4 {This is the Jobava London, a trendy and popular line at both GM and club level. It was popularized by famous streamers and YouTubers IM Eric Rosen and IM Levy Rozman.   White combines the idea with the London System and aims to play Nb5 next to target the c7 -pawn.} a6 {I like this simple prophylactic move. We stop Nb5 forever and plan to develop naturally with ... Bf5 & ... e6 next.} 4. e3 Bf5 {I recommend to get the bishop outside the pawn chain first, and only then follow up with ... e6 .   Here, White has two approaches: an immediate kingside expansion with f3 & g4 or develop with natural moves such as Nf3 and Bd3 .} 5. f3 {This the most aggressive setup. White will follow up with g4 & h4 kingside expansion next. But we will be ready for it!} e6 6. g4 Bg6 7. h4 {It looks as though our bishop is getting trapped but in reality, Black is totally fine!} h6 {Simple chess! We create a safety square for our bishop on h7 .} ({Please note that} 7... h5 {is playable as well, but I prefer this move. Now, White can play 8. Bd3 right away or insert 8. h5 first.}) 8. Bd3 {This is a more common move, keeping the h4 + g4 pawns flexible.} Bxd3 9. cxd3 {This recapture is rare, but our reaction is the same.} c5 {This is the simplest, but Black had a interesting alternative with the 9... Nc6 and ... Bd6 plan.} 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. d4 Bd6 {We don't mind the trade of the bishops as White will loosen up the grip over the e5 -square.} 12. Nge2 Nc6 13. Kf2 {We have a dream version of the Exchange Slav for Black as the trade of the light-squared bishops favors us. Now, I'd like to show you a cool idea.} h5 {Fixing the pawns and forcing further weakening with g5 .} 14. g5 Ng8 {The knight is heading to e7 where it will control key squares on the kingside.} 15. Rc1 Nge7 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. Nf4 g6 {We've achieved an impenetrable fortress and can safely castle kingside. I prefer Black as White's position is a bit shaky with an exposed king and a weak h4 -pawn. Our knight has a perfect outpost on f5 .} *

