1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {This move is a clear indication that White wants to play 3. e4 next.   However, the biggest drawback is that after logical 2... d5 the knight on c3 is always misplaced since White can't easily play in the Queen's Gambit style with c4 .} d5 {Of course, we stop White's e4 plan right away. In this chapter we will cover the trendy Jobava Attack after 3. Bf4 .   Please see Veresov 3.Bg5 and the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit .} 3. Bf4 {This is the Jobava London, a trendy and popular line at both GM and club level. It was popularized by famous streamers and YouTubers IM Eric Rosen and IM Levy Rozman.   White combines the idea with the London System and aims to play Nb5 next to target the c7 -pawn.} a6 {I like this simple prophylactic move. We stop Nb5 forever and plan to develop naturally with ... Bf5 & ... e6 next.} 4. e3 Bf5 {I recommend to get the bishop outside the pawn chain first, and only then follow up with ... e6 .   Here, White has two approaches: an immediate kingside expansion with f3 & g4 or develop with natural moves such as Nf3 and Bd3 .} 5. f3 {This the most aggressive setup. White will follow up with g4 & h4 kingside expansion next. But we will be ready for it!} e6 6. g4 Bg6 7. h4 {It looks as though our bishop is getting trapped but in reality, Black is totally fine!} h6 {Simple chess! We create a safety square for our bishop on h7 .} ({Please note that} 7... h5 {is playable as well, but I prefer this move. Now, White can play 8. Bd3 right away or insert 8. h5 first.}) 8. Bd3 {This is a more common move, keeping the h4 + g4 pawns flexible.} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 {This is the automatic recapture. White is hoping we will castle short and launch a deadly attack. However, remember to keep the king in the center for now, where it is safest!} c5 {A standard idea to undermine White's center.} 10. Nge2 Nc6 11. O-O-O {White typically goes for the queenside castle and hopes to use the kingside expansion to attack us. However, as long as you keep the king on e8 , it is totally safe!} c4 {Black launches the attack on the enemy king!} 12. Qd2 b5 {I already prefer Black as our attack plays itself, just push the pawns and open up White's king. Here's one possible line:} 13. g5 Nh5 {Our knight helps cement the kingside.} 14. e4 {White strikes in the center, but our attack comes first!} b4 {This is most direct and best.} 15. Na4 c3 {An instructive moment, we don't care about pawns as we pry open the enemy king.} 16. Qe3 {This is White's best.} Nxf4 {The simplest.} 17. Qxf4 Bd6 {A nice tempo, trying to induce e5 .} 18. e5 cxb2+ {Another intermezzo.} 19. Nxb2 Be7 ({The dust has settled a bit but White is on the precipice as they only have one move to keep the game alive with} 19... g6 $1) 20. Kb1 ({This natural move loses to an instructive regrouping. After} 20. gxh6 Rxh6 {Black's king is still quite safe.}) 20... Na7 {The knight is coming to b5 with a deadly attack. The engine already gives -2.5 for Black!} *

