1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {The Trompowsky Attack is aimed at ruining our structure with Bxf6 , but as a result White gives up the bishop pair. Most of our ideas from the original book Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time! I recommend the sharp and aggressive setup based on 2... c5 !} c5 {White usually chooses among 3. d5 , gaining space or 3. Bxf6 , doubling our pawns. We will also cover 3. Nc3 inviting us into a Sicilian-like battle with 3... cxd4 , but instead the solid 3... d5 ! would be my recommendation.} 3. Nc3 {White invites us to a Sicilian structure after cxd4 Qxd4 , where they want to play Qh4 , e4 and O-O-O .} d5 {The best move! While we don't usually play early ... d5 in our repertoire, trust me that this is the simplest and best.} 4. e4 {White wants to open up the game.} Nxe4 {The simplest, by trading the knights we reduce White's attacking potential.} 5. Nxe4 dxe4 6. dxc5 {This simplifies into an equal endgame.} Qxd1+ 7. Rxd1 Bd7 {The most precise. We aim to play for ... e6 or ... e5 next and stop the obvious Rd8 #.} 8. Bc4 e6 {Now White's c4 -bishop is restricted.} 9. Be3 Nc6 10. Ne2 Na5 11. Bb3 Rc8 {We will win the c5 -pawn and also get to trade for the b3 -bishop. White is clearly worse.} *

