1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {The Trompowsky Attack is aimed at ruining our structure with Bxf6 , but as a result White gives up the bishop pair. Most of our ideas from the original book Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time! I recommend the sharp and aggressive setup based on 2... c5 !} c5 {White usually chooses among 3. d5 , gaining space or 3. Bxf6 , doubling our pawns. We will also cover 3. Nc3 inviting us into a Sicilian-like battle with 3... cxd4 , but instead the solid 3... d5 ! would be my recommendation.} 3. Nc3 {White invites us to a Sicilian structure after cxd4 Qxd4 , where they want to play Qh4 , e4 and O-O-O .} d5 {The best move! While we don't usually play early ... d5 in our repertoire, trust me that this is the simplest and best.} 4. e4 {White wants to open up the game.} Nxe4 {The simplest, by trading the knights we reduce White's attacking potential.} 5. Nxe4 dxe4 6. d5 {I don't believe in this pawn sacrifice for White.} Qb6 {We put pressure on the b2 -pawn. You can also start with 6... g6 .} 7. Ne2 {White invites us to take the 2nd pawn, but we have other plans.} g6 {Let's not be greedy and finish development first. We take over the long diagonal and having the extra e4 -pawn helps!} *

