1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {The Trompowsky Attack is aimed at ruining our structure with Bxf6 , but as a result White gives up the bishop pair. Most of our ideas from the original book Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time! I recommend the sharp and aggressive setup based on 2... c5 !} c5 {White usually chooses among 3. d5 , gaining space or 3. Bxf6 , doubling our pawns. We will also cover 3. Nc3 inviting us into a Sicilian-like battle with 3... cxd4 , but instead the solid 3... d5 ! would be my recommendation.} 3. Nc3 {White invites us to a Sicilian structure after cxd4 Qxd4 , where they want to play Qh4 , e4 and O-O-O .} d5 {The best move! While we don't usually play early ... d5 in our repertoire, trust me that this is the simplest and best.} 4. Bxf6 exf6 {We aim for the same structure as against 3. Bxf6 .} 5. e3 Nc6 6. dxc5 Be6 {The pawn on c5 is not going anywhere.} 7. Nf3 Bxc5 8. Be2 d4 {We get rid of our weakness and open up the game for the bishops.} *

