1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {The Trompowsky Attack is aimed at ruining our structure with Bxf6 , but as a result White gives up the bishop pair. Most of our ideas from the original book Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time! I recommend the sharp and aggressive setup based on 2... c5 !} c5 {White usually chooses among 3. d5 , gaining space or 3. Bxf6 , doubling our pawns. We will also cover 3. Nc3 inviting us into a Sicilian-like battle with 3... cxd4 , but instead the solid 3... d5 ! would be my recommendation.} 3. Bxf6 exf6 {This rare move was our original recommendation in 2005, and it withstood the test of time! Modern engines understand that Black gets huge counterplay with the bishops in the ensuring an IQP structure once the d- & c- pawns are traded.} 4. d5 {It's funny how dogmatic most White players are! This is the best move ONLY if Black takes back on f6 with the g-pawn, but a huge positional mistake here. The reason is that we get a dream Benoni structure, where White is missing their best piece, the dark-squared bishop. I have won several games like this as Black against strong masters!} f5 {First we take away the e4 -square from White.} 5. Nc3 {White can also play 5. c4 , but we will execute the similar Benoni plan: fianchetto our DSB, play ... d6 and prepare ... b5 pawn break in the future.} d6 6. e3 g6 {We fianchetto our bishop, where it will rule the long diagonal, unopposed!} 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O a6 {We prepare the classic Benoni ... b5 expansion. Black can also play ... Na6 - c7 first, but it's a matter of taste.} 10. a4 {White stops our plan.} b6 {Easy does it. We have ALL THE TIME in the world to prepare ... b5 with ... Nd7 - f6 , ... Rb8 , ... Bd7 . White has no plan whatsoever! Our bishop on g7 is an absolute monster.} *

