{White is totally lost as c3 drops the bishop to .} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {The Trompowsky Attack is aimed at ruining our structure with Bxf6 , but as a result White gives up the bishop pair. Most of our ideas from the original book Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time! I recommend the sharp and aggressive setup based on 2... c5 !} c5 {White usually chooses among 3. d5 , gaining space or 3. Bxf6 , doubling our pawns. We will also cover 3. Nc3 inviting us into a Sicilian-like battle with 3... cxd4 , but instead the solid 3... d5 ! would be my recommendation.} 3. Bxf6 exf6 {This rare move was our original recommendation in 2005, and it withstood the test of time! Modern engines understand that Black gets huge counterplay with the bishops in the ensuring an IQP structure once the d- & c- pawns are traded.} 4. dxc5 {White immediately clarifies the pawn structure.} Bxc5 5. e3 Qb6 {We immediately show White their weakness, the b2 -pawn!} 6. b3 {This is too weakening. For example:} d5 {We are happy to sacrifice the pawn for rapid development.} 7. Qxd5 O-O 8. Nf3 Rd8 9. Qe4 Nc6 {We just keep developing.} 10. Bd3 f5 {A nice tempo move.} 11. Qh4 Be7 {All of a sudden White's queen is running short of squares.} 12. Qh5 g6 13. Qh6 Bf8 (13... Bf6 {is good too.}) 14. Qh4 Bg7 {It's funny how we took advantage of White's 6. b3 weakness many moves later.} *

