1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {The Trompowsky Attack is aimed at ruining our structure with Bxf6 , but as a result White gives up the bishop pair. Most of our ideas from the original book Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time! I recommend the sharp and aggressive setup based on 2... c5 !} c5 {White usually chooses among 3. d5 , gaining space or 3. Bxf6 , doubling our pawns. We will also cover 3. Nc3 inviting us into a Sicilian-like battle with 3... cxd4 , but instead the solid 3... d5 ! would be my recommendation.} 3. Bxf6 exf6 {This rare move was our original recommendation in 2005, and it withstood the test of time! Modern engines understand that Black gets huge counterplay with the bishops in the ensuring an IQP structure once the d- & c- pawns are traded.} 4. dxc5 {White immediately clarifies the pawn structure.} Bxc5 5. e3 Qb6 {We immediately show White their weakness, the b2 -pawn!} 6. Qc1 d5 7. c3 {White's solid pawn formation may look good at first as Black has a clear weakness, the isolated queen pawn (IQP). However, in reality our bishop pair and space advantage give Black a nice edge. Let me show you a possible plan.} O-O 8. Nf3 f5 {With idea ... f4 , opening up the g1 - a7 diagonal.} 9. g3 Re8 {We renew the threat.} 10. Be2 f4 {Anyways, we blow open the position for our bishops.} 11. gxf4 Nc6 {It's funny that we are down a pawn, don't have immediate threats but the eval is -1.7 already!} 12. Nbd2 Bf5 13. Rg1 {It looks as though White is solid, but...} Bxe3 {We pry open White's king with this natural bishop sacrifice.} 14. fxe3 Qxe3 {The attack is deadly as White's king is stuck in the center. The engine already gives us almost -3, a winning advantage.} ({Here's a possible line: Rg2} 14... d4 $1 {We blow up the center!} 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. cxd4 Rac8 $1 {The other rook joins the party. White is totally paralyzed and will get mated or lose tons of material.}) *

