1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {The Trompowsky Attack is aimed at ruining our structure with Bxf6 , but as a result White gives up the bishop pair. Most of our ideas from the original book Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time! I recommend the sharp and aggressive setup based on 2... c5 !} c5 {White usually chooses among 3. d5 , gaining space or 3. Bxf6 , doubling our pawns. We will also cover 3. Nc3 inviting us into a Sicilian-like battle with 3... cxd4 , but instead the solid 3... d5 ! would be my recommendation.} 3. Bxf6 exf6 {This rare move was our original recommendation in 2005, and it withstood the test of time! Modern engines understand that Black gets huge counterplay with the bishops in the ensuring an IQP structure once the d- & c- pawns are traded.} 4. dxc5 {White immediately clarifies the pawn structure.} Bxc5 5. e3 Qb6 {We immediately show White their weakness, the b2 -pawn!} 6. Qd5 {This unusual move is White's best try. Trust me, most of your opponents won't figure it out unless they bought Kamil Plichta's Chessable course on the Trompowsky.} Nc6 ({Of course, we don't fall for White's trap. After} 6... Qxb2 $2 7. Qxc5 Qxa1 8. Qxc8+ {wins.}) 7. Qb3 {This is White's best. They want to trade queens and claim a superior pawn structure in the endgame. But let me show you how to neutralize White with two bishops and activity.} d5 {We grab more central space and don't mind the queen trade.} 8. Qxb6 axb6 {Another unusual decision to double our pawns, but the a-file is worth it!} 9. c3 {At first, it looks like White is better due to their superior pawn structure. However, Black is about to unleash the pawn storm!} f5 {The f-pawn is ready to blow up the game with ... f4 next.} 10. Nf3 f4 {The point! We open up the game regardless of material loss.} 11. exf4 O-O {White can't castle as ... Re1 + is next, we will play for ... d4 and attack White even without the queens! The engines already prefer Black.} *

