1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {The Trompowsky Attack is aimed at ruining our structure with Bxf6 , but as a result White gives up the bishop pair. Most of our ideas from the original book Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time! I recommend the sharp and aggressive setup based on 2... c5 !} c5 {White usually chooses among 3. d5 , gaining space or 3. Bxf6 , doubling our pawns. We will also cover 3. Nc3 inviting us into a Sicilian-like battle with 3... cxd4 , but instead the solid 3... d5 ! would be my recommendation.} 3. Bxf6 exf6 {This rare move was our original recommendation in 2005, and it withstood the test of time! Modern engines understand that Black gets huge counterplay with the bishops in the ensuring an IQP structure once the d- & c- pawns are traded.} 4. dxc5 {White immediately clarifies the pawn structure.} Bxc5 5. e3 Qb6 {We immediately show White their weakness, the b2 -pawn!} 6. Qd5 {This unusual move is White's best try. Trust me, most of your opponents won't figure it out unless they bought Kamil Plichta's Chessable course on the Trompowsky.} Nc6 ({Of course, we don't fall for White's trap. After} 6... Qxb2 $2 7. Qxc5 Qxa1 8. Qxc8+ {wins.}) 7. Qb3 {This is White's best. They want to trade queens and claim a superior pawn structure in the endgame. But let me show you how to neutralize White with two bishops and activity.} d5 {We grab more central space and don't mind the queen trade.} 8. Qxb6 axb6 {Another unusual decision to double our pawns, but the a-file is worth it!} 9. c3 {At first, it looks like White is better due to their superior pawn structure. However, Black is about to unleash the pawn storm!} f5 {The f-pawn is ready to blow up the game with ... f4 next.} 10. Ne2 {This or 10.Nh3 is White's best. They need to stop ... f4 .} ({Please note that} 10. g3 {is met with} g5 $1 {with similar ideas.}) 10... g5 ({I like this aggressive move, but nothing wrong with} 10... O-O {first.}) 11. h4 {White's most logical move, trying to undermine our structure since we don't have ... h6 .} f4 {We still go for it as the complications favor Black.} 12. exf4 (12. hxg5 fxe3 {is good for us as the game opens up for our bishops.}) 12... g4 {Remember this idea! We opened up the game and use the g-pawn to smother White's kingside.} 13. Nd2 O-O {It's clear that White is having problems with their king.} 14. Ng3 (14. g3 $2 {loses to} Re8 {and the pin on the e-file is deadly for White.}) 14... Re8+ 15. Be2 Bd6 ({Black's active pieces give us excellent compensation for the pawn. Now, White has to be careful not to play the logical O-O? as it loses to . After the best Nh5!} 15... Be7 $1 {(stopping Nf6 + & preventing White from castling as the h4 -pawn is hit) the game remains balanced, but I prefer the activity of Black's pieces.}) *

