1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {The Trompowsky Attack is aimed at ruining our structure with Bxf6 , but as a result White gives up the bishop pair. Most of our ideas from the original book Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time! I recommend the sharp and aggressive setup based on 2... c5 !} c5 {White usually chooses among 3. d5 , gaining space or 3. Bxf6 , doubling our pawns. We will also cover 3. Nc3 inviting us into a Sicilian-like battle with 3... cxd4 , but instead the solid 3... d5 ! would be my recommendation.} 3. d5 {White's most popular move. They grab the center and hope to follow up with Nc3 & e4 . However, we take advantage of the misplaced bishop right way.} Ne4 {Remember this key move! Black attacks the bishop with a tempo and in some lines the weakness of the b2 -pawn will be felt after a timely ... Qb6 .} 4. Bc1 {This passive retreat allows us easy plan in the center.} e6 5. c4 ({White's most logical move to keep the center alive. Please note that} 5. f3 {loses to a little tactic} Qh4+ 6. g3 Nxg3 {where's} 7. dxe6 fxe6 {gives us a massive pawn center.}) 5... Be7 {A sneaky developing move that invites f3 .} 6. f3 ({And White falls into our trap. A better move is} 6. e3 {but after} Qa5+ {we get excellent counterplay.}) 6... Qa5+ ({You can also start with} 6... Bh4+ {, which would likely transpose.}) 7. Nd2 Bh4+ 8. g3 Nxg3 9. hxg3 Bxg3# {A fun line!} *

