1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {The Trompowsky Attack is aimed at ruining our structure with Bxf6 , but as a result White gives up the bishop pair. Most of our ideas from the original book Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time! I recommend the sharp and aggressive setup based on 2... c5 !} c5 {White usually chooses among 3. d5 , gaining space or 3. Bxf6 , doubling our pawns. We will also cover 3. Nc3 inviting us into a Sicilian-like battle with 3... cxd4 , but instead the solid 3... d5 ! would be my recommendation.} 3. d5 {White's most popular move. They grab the center and hope to follow up with Nc3 & e4 . However, we take advantage of the misplaced bishop right way.} Ne4 {Remember this key move! Black attacks the bishop with a tempo and in some lines the weakness of the b2 -pawn will be felt after a timely ... Qb6 .} 4. h4 {This move hopes to invite us into an interesting imbalance after 4... Nxg5 5.hxg5, but I recommend to hold off taking the bishop for now.} d6 ({A rare waiting move. Most people play} 4... Qb6 {, which I don't like as White gets good counterplay after} 5. Nd2 $1) 5. Nd2 {A logical move to get rid of our strong knight.} Nxg5 {Now that White's knight is misplaced on d2 (it should be on c3 ), we take the bishop.} 6. hxg5 e6 {Simple chess. We are ready to open up the game for our bishops. At the moment, White has to deal with two pawns being attacked.} 7. dxe6 Bxe6 8. Ngf3 {Only a handful of games reached this position, but I believe Black is already better. Our two bishops and the central control is more than enough.} Be7 9. e3 Nc6 {We don't care about the g5 -pawn for now and just continue natural development.} 10. c3 d5 {Black enjoys a nice space advantage as well as the bishop pair. White's g5 -pawn is a liability.} *

