{And White is in trouble since g3 is met with thematic .} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {The Trompowsky Attack is aimed at ruining our structure with Bxf6 , but as a result White gives up the bishop pair. Most of our ideas from the original book Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time! I recommend the sharp and aggressive setup based on 2... c5 !} c5 {White usually chooses among 3. d5 , gaining space or 3. Bxf6 , doubling our pawns. We will also cover 3. Nc3 inviting us into a Sicilian-like battle with 3... cxd4 , but instead the solid 3... d5 ! would be my recommendation.} 3. d5 {White's most popular move. They grab the center and hope to follow up with Nc3 & e4 . However, we take advantage of the misplaced bishop right way.} Ne4 {Remember this key move! Black attacks the bishop with a tempo and in some lines the weakness of the b2 -pawn will be felt after a timely ... Qb6 .} 4. Bf4 {White's most popular move, keeping the bishop active.} e6 {I believe this is a simpler move than the original recommendation of 4... Qb6 .} ({Yes, there's one bonus of the original recommendation is that after} 4... Qb6 5. Nd2 $2 {White falls for a trap with} Qxb2 $1 6. Nxe4 Qb4+ $1 {and we win back the piece due to tactics. But the problem is that White can play 5. Bc1 and Black has to show some accuracy.}) 5. f3 {White hopes to kick out the knight in order to play e4 next. But we have a surprise for them!} Bd6 {This is the key move you have to remember! Once the dark-squared bishops are traded, White will have serious dark-squared weaknesses in their camp.} 6. Bxd6 Nxd6 7. e4 b5 {Another precise move! We gain more space on the queenside, similar to the Benoni opening.} 8. e5 {This only makes things worse for White.} Nf5 9. Bxb5 Qh4+ *

