1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {The Trompowsky Attack is aimed at ruining our structure with Bxf6 , but as a result White gives up the bishop pair. Most of our ideas from the original book Chess Openings for Black, Explained withstood the test of time! I recommend the sharp and aggressive setup based on 2... c5 !} c5 {White usually chooses among 3. d5 , gaining space or 3. Bxf6 , doubling our pawns. We will also cover 3. Nc3 inviting us into a Sicilian-like battle with 3... cxd4 , but instead the solid 3... d5 ! would be my recommendation.} 3. d5 {White's most popular move. They grab the center and hope to follow up with Nc3 & e4 . However, we take advantage of the misplaced bishop right way.} Ne4 {Remember this key move! Black attacks the bishop with a tempo and in some lines the weakness of the b2 -pawn will be felt after a timely ... Qb6 .} 4. Bf4 {White's most popular move, keeping the bishop active.} e6 {I believe this is a simpler move than the original recommendation of 4... Qb6 .} ({Yes, there's one bonus of the original recommendation is that after} 4... Qb6 5. Nd2 $2 {White falls for a trap with} Qxb2 $1 6. Nxe4 Qb4+ $1 {and we win back the piece due to tactics. But the problem is that White can play 5. Bc1 and Black has to show some accuracy.}) 5. f3 {White hopes to kick out the knight in order to play e4 next. But we have a surprise for them!} Bd6 {This is the key move you have to remember! Once the dark-squared bishops are traded, White will have serious dark-squared weaknesses in their camp.} 6. Bxd6 Nxd6 7. Nc3 {This move allows us an interesting queen maneuver.} Qh4+ 8. g3 Qb4 {A cool idea! We weakened White's kingside and now target the b2 -pawn as well as preparing ... Nb5 jump.} 9. Rb1 Nb5 {And White is having trouble with this pin.} 10. Qd2 Nxc3 11. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 12. bxc3 exd5 {Black enjoys the extra pawn for now. We will finish development with natural moves: ... d6 & ... Ke7 . White's ruined pawns on the queenside are a serious long-term weakness.} *

