1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack is a cousin of the London System. White hopes to play an e3 , Bd3 , c3 setup next.} h6 {We attack White's bishop right away. Now, White has a choice between 4. Bxf6 and 4. Bh4 .} 4. Bh4 {This is a more positional idea, White keeps the bishop pair.} c5 {We strike the center right away.} 5. e3 cxd4 {We clarify the pawn structure in the center.} 6. exd4 Be7 7. Bd3 {White can also start with 8. Nbd2 or 8. c3 , likely transposing.} O-O {Here White can try 8. c3 or 8. c4 .} ({Please note that} 7... O-O {b6 will likely transpose.}) 8. c4 d5 {This is the best way to handle the center as White will now play with an IQP.} 9. Nc3 Nc6 ({Or, we can start with} 9... dxc4 {.}) 10. O-O dxc4 11. Bxc4 {White is now playing with a serious positional weakness, the Isolated Queen Pawn (IQP). Let me show you an instructive way to play here for Black.} b6 {Getting ready to play ... Bb7 next.} 12. a3 Bb7 13. Ba2 Nh5 {This is the main point. White normally wants to avoid trades in the IQP structure, but here they can't avoid it.} 14. Bxe7 Nxe7 {Black has a dream setup against the IQP. All of our pieces are perfectly placed. The d5 blockading outpost is fully under our control, and the knight is about to jump to f4 with counterplay. The engine agrees, giving us a small edge.} *

