1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack is a cousin of the London System. White hopes to play an e3 , Bd3 , c3 setup next.} h6 {We attack White's bishop right away. Now, White has a choice between 4. Bxf6 and 4. Bh4 .} 4. Bh4 {This is a more positional idea, White keeps the bishop pair.} c5 {We strike the center right away.} 5. e3 cxd4 {We clarify the pawn structure in the center.} 6. exd4 Be7 7. Bd3 {White can also start with 8. Nbd2 or 8. c3 , likely transposing.} O-O {Here White can try 8. c3 or 8. c4 .} ({Please note that} 7... O-O {b6 will likely transpose.}) 8. c3 {This is more in the spirit of the London system, white builds a  b2 - c3 - d4 pawn chain and hopes to attack our king in the future.} b6 9. O-O Ba6 {We execute the same positional idea as we've seen in the London System. Once the light-squared bishops are traded, White will not have any attack.} 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. Qd3 Nc7 12. Nbd2 d6 {This is a better move than ... d5 as we control the d6 -outpost.} 13. Rfe1 {This logical move enables a cool tactical trick.} g5 14. Bg3 ({Probably} 14. Nxg5 {is best in lieu of what is about to happen...}) 14... g4 {Forcing the knight to the rim.} 15. Nh4 Nfe8 {Oops, and the knight is trapped on h4 . White is just losing a piece.} *

