1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack is a cousin of the London System. White hopes to play an e3 , Bd3 , c3 setup next.} h6 {We attack White's bishop right away. Now, White has a choice between 4. Bxf6 and 4. Bh4 .} 4. Bh4 {This is a more positional idea, White keeps the bishop pair.} c5 {We strike the center right away.} 5. e3 cxd4 {We clarify the pawn structure in the center.} 6. exd4 Be7 7. Bd3 {White can also start with 8. Nbd2 or 8. c3 , likely transposing.} O-O {Here White can try 8. c3 or 8. c4 .} ({Please note that} 7... O-O {b6 will likely transpose.}) 8. c3 {This is more in the spirit of the London system, white builds a  b2 - c3 - d4 pawn chain and hopes to attack our king in the future.} b6 9. Qe2 {White stops our ... Ba6 idea, but we don't mind developing the bishop on b7 , where it controls the long diagonal.} Bb7 10. Nbd2 d6 11. O-O Nh5 {A good idea to remember! We force the trade of the bishops.} 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Now, White has to deal with the ... Nf4 fork.} 13. Qe3 Nd7 {We've reached an even middlegame. White's position is quite solid, but they don't have a clear plan. Black's extra pawn in the center gives us a long-term idea to prepare ... e5 .} *

