{Black managed to fend off White's attack and is simply a pawn up. We are about to castle next and take over the game. Nxe5 Nxe5 f4 Be6! fxe5 Bxe5 Qe2 O-O-O Qxe5 Bxd5∓ and White is just down a pawn for nothing.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack is a cousin of the London System. White hopes to play an e3 , Bd3 , c3 setup next.} h6 {We attack White's bishop right away. Now, White has a choice between 4. Bxf6 and 4. Bh4 .} 4. Bxf6 {White gives up the bishop pair, hoping to build a strong center with e4 & d4 .} Qxf6 5. e4 {White achieves their goal, but I believe the bishop pair and the flexible pawn structure gives us better chances long term.} d6 {We first secure the e5 -square.} 6. Nc3 g6 {Our original recommendation is still approved by modern engines 20 years later! The bishop is more powerful on the long diagonal.} 7. Qd2 {White prepares to castle long.} Bg7 8. O-O-O a6 {We get ready to counterattack with ... b5 next.} ({Please note that} 8... Qe7 {first , followed by ... b5 is fine as well. Here, White can try: 9. Bd3 , 9. Qe3 , and 9. e5 .}) 9. e5 {This is probably White's best try.} Qe7 {We dip back and don't mind the trade on d6 .} 10. d5 ({White goes 'all-in', but it doesn't work. Probably more sane is} 10. Bd3 Nd7 {, and Black will follow up with ... O-O and ... b5 next.}) 10... dxe5 {We take the pawn!} 11. Re1 Nd7 12. Bc4 exd5 13. Nxd5 Qd6 *

