{Here's a sample line: Kb1 b4 Nd1 Bd5 b3 Qf6-+ White is probably asking himself, why did I trade my DSB?} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack is a cousin of the London System. White hopes to play an e3 , Bd3 , c3 setup next.} h6 {We attack White's bishop right away. Now, White has a choice between 4. Bxf6 and 4. Bh4 .} 4. Bxf6 {White gives up the bishop pair, hoping to build a strong center with e4 & d4 .} Qxf6 5. e4 {White achieves their goal, but I believe the bishop pair and the flexible pawn structure gives us better chances long term.} d6 {We first secure the e5 -square.} 6. Nc3 g6 {Our original recommendation is still approved by modern engines 20 years later! The bishop is more powerful on the long diagonal.} 7. Qd2 {White prepares to castle long.} Bg7 8. O-O-O a6 {We get ready to counterattack with ... b5 next.} ({Please note that} 8... Qe7 {first , followed by ... b5 is fine as well. Here, White can try: 9. Bd3 , 9. Qe3 , and 9. e5 .}) 9. Qe3 {White is preparing to go e5 next.} Nd7 10. h4 (10. e5 Qe7 {with similar play.}) 10... b5 11. Re1 Bb7 12. e5 Qe7 {We just drop back with our queen and will take over the game as White is getting overextended.} 13. h5 g5 {A typical idea to lock up the kingside.} 14. exd6 cxd6 15. d5 {This was seen in Mikhalevski-Sandipan, 2002. Black is better with many moves here as both bishops will tear up the board.} O-O 16. dxe6 Nc5 {We don't care about pawns and activate all our pieces.} 17. exf7+ Qxf7 {Black has a winning attack already. The engine gives us -2.} *

