1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 {This is a solid move that White plays if they are going for a setup with Bd3 , O-O , c3 , & Nbd2 known as the Colle System. Often, White keeps the pawn on c2 and play for b3 & Bb2 known as the Colle-Zukertort.   These openings rely more on general plans and strategic understanding rather than sharp, tactical lines. I will teach you effective setups for Black against both of these systems.} c5 {We immediately strike in the center with ... c5 . This idea is quite familiar by now as we play it against the London System as well.} 4. Bd3 ({This is White's most common move by far. Keep in mind that} 4. b3 {or c3 will likely transpose.}) 4... Nc6 {We go for central development and put pressure on d4 .} 5. O-O {White first completes kingside development before embarking on queenside play.} d5 {We fight for the center. Please note that we don't play this way vs the London System as with the bishop on f4 , it's a totally different story. Here, White can't easily use the e5 -outpost as we shall see.   Now, White has a choice: 6. b3 going for the Colle-Zukertort or 6. c3 aiming for the Colle System.} 6. Ne5 {This is premature.} cxd4 7. Nxc6 ({Otherwise White loses a pawn} 7. exd4 Nxd4 {.}) 7... bxc6 8. exd4 Qb6 9. c3 Bd6 {Black is doing great. We will play ... O-O followed by ... c5 or ... Ba6 .} *

