1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 {This is a solid move that White plays if they are going for a setup with Bd3 , O-O , c3 , & Nbd2 known as the Colle System. Often, White keeps the pawn on c2 and play for b3 & Bb2 known as the Colle-Zukertort.   These openings rely more on general plans and strategic understanding rather than sharp, tactical lines. I will teach you effective setups for Black against both of these systems.} c5 {We immediately strike in the center with ... c5 . This idea is quite familiar by now as we play it against the London System as well.} 4. Bd3 ({This is White's most common move by far. Keep in mind that} 4. b3 {or c3 will likely transpose.}) 4... Nc6 {We go for central development and put pressure on d4 .} 5. O-O {White first completes kingside development before embarking on queenside play.} d5 {We fight for the center. Please note that we don't play this way vs the London System as with the bishop on f4 , it's a totally different story. Here, White can't easily use the e5 -outpost as we shall see.   Now, White has a choice: 6. b3 going for the Colle-Zukertort or 6. c3 aiming for the Colle System.} 6. c3 {This is the Colle System.} Bd6 {We develop naturally and don't mind allowing dxc5 & b4 .} 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. dxc5 {White tries to use a tempo to expand with b4 or e4 next.} ({If they play slowly with} 8. b3 {we can answer with} b6 {& ... Bb7 .}) 8... Bxc5 9. e4 Qc7 {We keep an eye on the key e5 -square and prevent White from playing e5 .} 10. Qe2 {White renews the threat of e5 .} h6 {A useful move. We get ready for the e5 pawn push.} 11. h3 Nh5 {A strong idea, the knight is heading to g3 or f4 .} 12. Nb3 Ng3 {A nice intermezzo.} 13. Qc2 dxe4 ({Don't take the rook as} 13... Nxf1 $2 14. Nxc5 {and the knight on f1 is trapped.}) 14. Bxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Bd6 {Black is better here due to the bishop pair. The plan is to expand with ... f5 next.} *

