1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 {This is a solid move that White plays if they are going for a setup with Bd3 , O-O , c3 , & Nbd2 known as the Colle System. Often, White keeps the pawn on c2 and play for b3 & Bb2 known as the Colle-Zukertort.   These openings rely more on general plans and strategic understanding rather than sharp, tactical lines. I will teach you effective setups for Black against both of these systems.} c5 {We immediately strike in the center with ... c5 . This idea is quite familiar by now as we play it against the London System as well.} 4. Bd3 ({This is White's most common move by far. Keep in mind that} 4. b3 {or c3 will likely transpose.}) 4... Nc6 {We go for central development and put pressure on d4 .} 5. O-O {White first completes kingside development before embarking on queenside play.} d5 {We fight for the center. Please note that we don't play this way vs the London System as with the bishop on f4 , it's a totally different story. Here, White can't easily use the e5 -outpost as we shall see.   Now, White has a choice: 6. b3 going for the Colle-Zukertort or 6. c3 aiming for the Colle System.} 6. c3 {This is the Colle System.} Bd6 {We develop naturally and don't mind allowing dxc5 & b4 .} 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. dxc5 {White tries to use a tempo to expand with b4 or e4 next.} ({If they play slowly with} 8. b3 {we can answer with} b6 {& ... Bb7 .}) 8... Bxc5 9. b4 {A standard idea, White expands on the queenside in order to play Bb2 , a3 , c4 next.} Be7 {I like this rare move. The bishop is better placed here after the eventual ... e5 break.} 10. Bb2 e5 {We take over the center.} 11. e4 ({White's best. Please note that} 11. b5 e4 $1 {favors us.}) 11... Be6 {We don't mind allowing the b5 -push.} 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. b5 Nxc3 {These complications favor Black!} 14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Qc2+ Kg8 16. Qxc3 Nd4 {We force the endgame now.} 17. Nxd4 exd4 18. Qxd4 Qxd4 19. Bxd4 {The dust has settled and we are down a pawn. However, two monster bishops give us full compensation! The engine agrees and gives Black a tiny edge. For example:} Rfd8 20. Nf3 Ba3 {We fix the a2 -pawn and try to win it in the future. Our next move is ... a6 .} *

