1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 {This is a solid move that White plays if they are going for a setup with Bd3 , O-O , c3 , & Nbd2 known as the Colle System. Often, White keeps the pawn on c2 and play for b3 & Bb2 known as the Colle-Zukertort.   These openings rely more on general plans and strategic understanding rather than sharp, tactical lines. I will teach you effective setups for Black against both of these systems.} c5 {We immediately strike in the center with ... c5 . This idea is quite familiar by now as we play it against the London System as well.} 4. Bd3 ({This is White's most common move by far. Keep in mind that} 4. b3 {or c3 will likely transpose.}) 4... Nc6 {We go for central development and put pressure on d4 .} 5. O-O {White first completes kingside development before embarking on queenside play.} d5 {We fight for the center. Please note that we don't play this way vs the London System as with the bishop on f4 , it's a totally different story. Here, White can't easily use the e5 -outpost as we shall see.   Now, White has a choice: 6. b3 going for the Colle-Zukertort or 6. c3 aiming for the Colle System.} 6. b3 {This is the most popular move. White goes for the Colle-Zukertort System.} b6 {We also go for the fianchetto plan.} 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. Nbd2 {White can also start with 8. a3 , but it will likely transpose.} cxd4 ({I prefer to define the pawn structure in the center. We can also start with} 8... Bd6 {, but in this case we have deal with} 9. dxc5 {ideas.}) 9. exd4 {Now the bishop on b2 is paralyzed by the d4 -pawn.} Bd6 {This is the most active square for our bishop. It's also important to keep the e7 -square available for our knight.} 10. Ne5 {White's main idea in this opening. They can start with 10. a3 first, but eventually they go for this plan.} O-O 11. a3 {Stopping ... Nb4 . the immediate f4 is met with ... Nb4 !} ({For example:} 11. f4 Nb4 $1 12. Be2 Ne4 $1 {with great counterplay. We've reached the main tabiya of the Colle-Zukertort. White has a strong knight on e5 , and if Black is not careful, we can get under a strong attack with ... f4 , ... Qf3 , ... Qh3 etc. However, I will show you a cool regrouping that deals with this plan. The key is to win the e4 -outpost.}) 11... Rc8 {First we activate our rook and X-ray the c2 -pawn.} 12. f4 Ne7 {This is the key idea! The knight is heading to f5 , and the fight is revolving around the e4 -square now.} 13. Qf3 Nf5 {We provoke g4 .} 14. g4 ({Slow moves like} 14. Rae1 {are met with} h5 $1) 14... Nh4 15. Qe2 (15. Qh3 Ne4 $1 {with similar ideas.}) 15... Ne4 {We play ... Ne4 ! anyways and sacrifice a pawn.} 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Bxe4 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 f5 {We take over the kingside now.} 19. gxf5 Bxe5 {A nice intermezzo.} 20. fxe5 Rxf5 {Black is much better, just take a look at White's king!} 21. Rxf5 exf5 22. Qe2 Rc6 {And the attack is unstoppable.} *

