rong knight on e5 , and if Black is not careful, we can get under a strong attack with ... f4 , ... Qf3 , ... Qh3 etc. However, I will show you a cool regrouping that deals with this plan. The key is to win the e4 -outpost.}) 11... Rc8 {First we activate our rook and X-ray the c2 -pawn.} 12. f4 Ne7 {This is the key idea! The knight is heading to f5 , and the fight is revolving around the e4 -square now.} 13. Qe2 Nf5 {We activate our knight on a great outpost and provoke g4 .} 14. g4 Nh4 {We are not afraid of g5 .} 15. g5 Ne4 {The key idea! We happily sacrifice a pawn to weaken White's light square.} 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Bxe4 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 Bxe5 {A good trade for us.} 19. dxe5 Nf5 {Even though we are down a pawn, Black is much better. The key is our knight is very strong and White's bishop is just too passive. White's king is extremely exposed as well.} *

