1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bg5 {This is known as the Richter-Veresov Attack. However, I propose the name 'Attack' should be changed to 'Defense' after I show you a simple way of handling this line.} h6 ({It's funny how the Jobava London is easily parried with the a-pawn ( Bf4} 3... a6 $1 {) and the Veresov is stopped with the h-pawn! Now, White has a choice to take on f6 or play Bg4 . Most players prefer to take.}) 4. Bh4 c5 5. e4 {This is an inferior line that is common from the Trompowsky, but with the insertion of ... h6 & Bh4 this is quite bad for White.} Nxe4 {Of course we grab the pawn.} 6. Nxe4 dxe4 7. dxc5 Qa5+ {A nice intermezzo.} 8. Qd2 Qxd2+ {The easiest.} 9. Kxd2 e6 10. b4 a5 {A standard idea.} 11. c3 {Now, many moves give Black an edge, but let me show you a nice forcing sequence.} axb4 12. cxb4 g5 {A nice tempo to get our bishop to g7 .} 13. Bg3 Bg7 14. Rb1 Rxa2+ {We get the pawn back and will follow up with ... Nc6 with a big attack.} *

