1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bg5 {This is known as the Richter-Veresov Attack. However, I propose the name 'Attack' should be changed to 'Defense' after I show you a simple way of handling this line.} h6 ({It's funny how the Jobava London is easily parried with the a-pawn ( Bf4} 3... a6 $1 {) and the Veresov is stopped with the h-pawn! Now, White has a choice to take on f6 or play Bg4 . Most players prefer to take.}) 4. Bh4 c5 5. e4 {This is an inferior line that is common from the Trompowsky, but with the insertion of ... h6 & Bh4 this is quite bad for White.} Nxe4 {Of course we grab the pawn.} 6. Nxe4 dxe4 7. dxc5 Qa5+ {A nice intermezzo.} 8. c3 g5 {We don't waste time winning c5 -pawn and go for rapid development instead.} 9. Bg3 Bg7 {It's quite hard for White to develop as Bc4 is met with Bxc3+!} 10. Ne2 Nc6 11. h4 (11. b4 {is met with} Nxb4 $1) 11... Be6 12. hxg5 hxg5 13. Rxh8+ Bxh8 {Again, White is having hard time with development.} 14. Qc2 f5 {With ideas of ... f4 or simple .... O-O-O & ... Qxc5 Black will have all the fun. The engine already gives us -3!} *

