1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bg5 {This is known as the Richter-Veresov Attack. However, I propose the name 'Attack' should be changed to 'Defense' after I show you a simple way of handling this line.} h6 ({It's funny how the Jobava London is easily parried with the a-pawn ( Bf4} 3... a6 $1 {) and the Veresov is stopped with the h-pawn! Now, White has a choice to take on f6 or play Bg4 . Most players prefer to take.}) 4. Bh4 c5 5. e3 {White goes for a passive approach. But it's well-known that the knight on c3 is always misplaced in these structures.} Nc6 {Simple and strong, we are never worried about dxc5 due to .} 6. Nf3 cxd4 {We'd like to establish a fixed pawn structure.} 7. exd4 Bf5 {If possible, it's a good idea to get the bishop outside the pawn chain prior to playing ... e6 .} 8. Bb5 e6 9. Ne5 Rc8 {The knight on c6 is easily protected.} 10. O-O Be7 {Black enjoys a small edge as we will play ... O-O and expand on the queenside.} *

