1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bg5 {This is known as the Richter-Veresov Attack. However, I propose the name 'Attack' should be changed to 'Defense' after I show you a simple way of handling this line.} h6 ({It's funny how the Jobava London is easily parried with the a-pawn ( Bf4} 3... a6 $1 {) and the Veresov is stopped with the h-pawn! Now, White has a choice to take on f6 or play Bg4 . Most players prefer to take.}) 4. Bxf6 exf6 {Remember, to take back with the e-pawn! Normally, it's an autopilot response to take toward the center, but here, we are going for active piece play and we need the f8 - a3 diagonal for our bishop later.} ({You also see this idea in the Trompowsky ( d4 Nf6 Bg5} 4... c5 {Bxf6 exf6! )}) 5. e4 {This only helps Black as we have the bishop pair!} Bb4 {Simple! We develop and pin the knight.} 6. exd5 Qxd5 7. Nf3 O-O {We are first to castle and enjoy a nice initiative.} 8. Be2 Qa5 {Let's apply more pressure on the knight!} 9. Qd2 Nd7 {Black has many good plans, but transferring the knight on b6 is the simplest.} 10. O-O Nb6 11. a3 {White finally breaks the pin as ... Nd5 / a4 was a serous threat.} Bxc3 12. Qxc3 Qxc3 13. bxc3 Na4 {This is a classic case of White's doubled pawns being worse than our f-pawns. We will enjoy a slight advantage in the resulting endgame.} *

