1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bg5 {This is known as the Richter-Veresov Attack. However, I propose the name 'Attack' should be changed to 'Defense' after I show you a simple way of handling this line.} h6 ({It's funny how the Jobava London is easily parried with the a-pawn ( Bf4} 3... a6 $1 {) and the Veresov is stopped with the h-pawn! Now, White has a choice to take on f6 or play Bg4 . Most players prefer to take.}) 4. Bxf6 exf6 {Remember, to take back with the e-pawn! Normally, it's an autopilot response to take toward the center, but here, we are going for active piece play and we need the f8 - a3 diagonal for our bishop later.} ({You also see this idea in the Trompowsky ( d4 Nf6 Bg5} 4... c5 {Bxf6 exf6! )}) 5. e3 c6 {We strengthen the d5 -pawn, so that our bishop may go to d6 later.} 6. Bd3 g6 {Let's tease White a bit as though we plan to fianchetto...} 7. Nge2 Nd7 8. O-O Bd6 {And of course, we never planned to play ... Bg7 in the first place. We need the pawn on g6 to support an ... f5 & ... h5 push for the attack. Let me show you how easily White gets into trouble if they carelessly play on the queenside.} 9. a3 f5 {Grabbing more space and taking over the e4 -square. So far it looks like we lost some time by making pawn moves, but the powerful f5 - & d5 - pawns give us a nice central control and a platform to attack White’s king as you will see shortly.} 10. b4 Nf6 11. Rb1 {A bit too passive.} h5 {We don't even need to castle and can attack directly.} 12. b5 {And this loses outright...} Bxh2+ {Of course, the good old Greek Gift sacrifice!} 13. Kxh2 Ng4+ 14. Kg3 (14. Kg1 Qh4 {etc. with an easy win.}) 14... h4+ 15. Kf3 Nh2+ 16. Kf4 g5+ {Not the only mate, but prettiest!} 17. Ke5 f6# {A beautiful mate with a pawn in the middle of the board. FYI, Black had 2 other mates in one as well!} *

