1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. e4 {This is the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit. White gives up the central pawn, hoping to get quick counterplay after 4. f3 .   I have already published the refutation of this gambit in my Chessable course, Every Gambit Refuted, and am happy to share it with you here!} dxe4 {Of course, we take the pawn in order to refute the gambit.} 4. f3 {This improved version of the gambit by a German master, Emil Josef Diemer, was suggested in his book published in the 1950s. White offers the trade of the e4 -pawn to quickly develop the g1 -knight.} Bf5 {I suggest this move, which is quite rare but just as good as the main line of taking on f3 .   According to the Lichess DB, we see: 4... exf3 played in over 2 million games (White scores 53%) and 4... Bf5 played only in 200,000 games (White scores 48%)   Based on the above statistics, your opponent is mostly likely out of book and won't know what to do, while Black has natural development and retains the extra pawn for now. In this position, White's most common moves are 5. fxe4 and 5. g4 .} (4... exf3 {is the most common move.} 5. Nxf3 {White gets some compensation for the pawn, but objectively not enough.}) 5. g4 {This aggressive move will win back the pawn but makes White's structure irreversibly weak.} Bg6 6. g5 Nd5 {Centralization is important!} 7. Nxe4 {White wins the pawn back, but at what cost? Their kingside structure is ruined.} e5 {Black strikes in the center and plays counter-gambit! Quiet moves like ... e6 or ... Nc6 are good here as well.} 8. dxe5 Nc6 {Black's plan is simple: play ... Qd7 next and castle queenside to attack White's weakened king.} 9. Bb5 Qd7 10. c4 Ndb4 11. Qxd7+ Kxd7 {The resulting endgame is unpleasant for White.} 12. Kf2 {Sidestepping the ... Nc2 fork.} a6 {Black is happy to get the bishop pair. Nothing wrong with the immediate ... Re8 or ... Rd8 to manually castle.} 13. Ba4 {White keeps the pin alive.} Rd8 {A bit more accurate than ... Re8 .} (13... Re8 14. Ne2 Kc8 15. Rd1 {keeps the balance for White as Black can't take the pawn due to the pin.}) 14. Ne2 Kc8 {Black completes the manual castle, now the e5 -pawn is under attack.} 15. Bxc6 Nxc6 16. Bf4 Re8 {Black will take on e5 next and get a pleasant edge due to the bishop pair and a superior pawn structure. Please note that White's g-pawn march to g5 doesn't make for a good endgame for White.} *

