1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. e4 {This is the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit. White gives up the central pawn, hoping to get quick counterplay after 4. f3 .   I have already published the refutation of this gambit in my Chessable course, Every Gambit Refuted, and am happy to share it with you here!} dxe4 {Of course, we take the pawn in order to refute the gambit.} 4. f3 {This improved version of the gambit by a German master, Emil Josef Diemer, was suggested in his book published in the 1950s. White offers the trade of the e4 -pawn to quickly develop the g1 -knight.} Bf5 {I suggest this move, which is quite rare but just as good as the main line of taking on f3 .   According to the Lichess DB, we see: 4... exf3 played in over 2 million games (White scores 53%) and 4... Bf5 played only in 200,000 games (White scores 48%)   Based on the above statistics, your opponent is mostly likely out of book and won't know what to do, while Black has natural development and retains the extra pawn for now. In this position, White's most common moves are 5. fxe4 and 5. g4 .} (4... exf3 {is the most common move.} 5. Nxf3 {White gets some compensation for the pawn, but objectively not enough.}) 5. g4 {This aggressive move will win back the pawn but makes White's structure irreversibly weak.} Bg6 6. g5 Nd5 {Centralization is important!} 7. Nxe4 {White wins the pawn back, but at what cost? Their kingside structure is ruined.} e5 {Black strikes in the center and plays counter-gambit! Quiet moves like ... e6 or ... Nc6 are good here as well.} 8. dxe5 Nc6 {Black's plan is simple: play ... Qd7 next and castle queenside to attack White's weakened king.} 9. Bb5 Qd7 10. Ne2 {A natural developing move in order to castle. But funny enough, White's king won't be safer on g2 as you will see shortly.} O-O-O {Black is first to castle and will have real threats on the d-file soon.} 11. O-O {White castles too, but look how weak their king is on g1 . As the saying goes White's king went out of the frying pan and into the fire!} Qh3 {A natural move. We get our queen closer to White's monarch and open up our d8 -rook. Believe it or not, but White is already lost here! The engines show a -2 advantage for Black, who's a pawn down!} 12. Bxc6 Bxe4 {A nice intermezzo, setting up a cool tactic!} 13. fxe4 Ne3 {The key discovery that wins on the spot. White either loses the queen or gets mated.} *

