1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. e4 {This is the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit. White gives up the central pawn, hoping to get quick counterplay after 4. f3 .   I have already published the refutation of this gambit in my Chessable course, Every Gambit Refuted, and am happy to share it with you here!} dxe4 {Of course, we take the pawn in order to refute the gambit.} 4. f3 {This improved version of the gambit by a German master, Emil Josef Diemer, was suggested in his book published in the 1950s. White offers the trade of the e4 -pawn to quickly develop the g1 -knight.} Bf5 {I suggest this move, which is quite rare but just as good as the main line of taking on f3 .   According to the Lichess DB, we see: 4... exf3 played in over 2 million games (White scores 53%) and 4... Bf5 played only in 200,000 games (White scores 48%)   Based on the above statistics, your opponent is mostly likely out of book and won't know what to do, while Black has natural development and retains the extra pawn for now. In this position, White's most common moves are 5. fxe4 and 5. g4 .} (4... exf3 {is the most common move.} 5. Nxf3 {White gets some compensation for the pawn, but objectively not enough.}) 5. fxe4 {This is the most common move you will see here.} Nxe4 {It's natural to take with the knight to retain the strong light-squared bishop.} 6. Nxe4 Bxe4 {A free pawn for Black.} 7. Nf3 e6 8. Bd3 Bxd3 {We are happy with the trades since we have the extra pawn.} 9. Qxd3 Nc6 {A bit more active than ... Nd7 as it puts pressure on White's center but Black has many good plans here.} 10. O-O Be7 {Black seizes control over g5 and gets ready to castle.} 11. c3 O-O {Black has easily finished development and stands clearly better due to the extra pawn. White's half-open f-file is not enough to generate serious threats.   Black's plan is easy: activate the queen to connect the rooks and seek trades & endgames.} *

