1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. e4 {This is the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit. White gives up the central pawn, hoping to get quick counterplay after 4. f3 .   I have already published the refutation of this gambit in my Chessable course, Every Gambit Refuted, and am happy to share it with you here!} dxe4 {Of course, we take the pawn in order to refute the gambit.} 4. f3 {This improved version of the gambit by a German master, Emil Josef Diemer, was suggested in his book published in the 1950s. White offers the trade of the e4 -pawn to quickly develop the g1 -knight.} Bf5 {I suggest this move, which is quite rare but just as good as the main line of taking on f3 .   According to the Lichess DB, we see: 4... exf3 played in over 2 million games (White scores 53%) and 4... Bf5 played only in 200,000 games (White scores 48%)   Based on the above statistics, your opponent is mostly likely out of book and won't know what to do, while Black has natural development and retains the extra pawn for now. In this position, White's most common moves are 5. fxe4 and 5. g4 .} (4... exf3 {is the most common move.} 5. Nxf3 {White gets some compensation for the pawn, but objectively not enough.}) 5. fxe4 {This is the most common move you will see here.} Nxe4 {It's natural to take with the knight to retain the strong light-squared bishop.} 6. Qf3 {White's best option, trying to put pressure on our minor pieces, while x-raying the b7 -pawn.} Nxc3 {Black's best move, giving White several options for which piece to capture.} 7. Qxb7 {The worst capture since Black is able to save the piece.} Be4 {A nice rejoinder, Black saves the rook with a tempo.} 8. Qb3 Nd5 {A winning position.} *

