1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. e4 {This is the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit. White gives up the central pawn, hoping to get quick counterplay after 4. f3 .   I have already published the refutation of this gambit in my Chessable course, Every Gambit Refuted, and am happy to share it with you here!} dxe4 {Of course, we take the pawn in order to refute the gambit.} 4. f3 {This improved version of the gambit by a German master, Emil Josef Diemer, was suggested in his book published in the 1950s. White offers the trade of the e4 -pawn to quickly develop the g1 -knight.} Bf5 {I suggest this move, which is quite rare but just as good as the main line of taking on f3 .   According to the Lichess DB, we see: 4... exf3 played in over 2 million games (White scores 53%) and 4... Bf5 played only in 200,000 games (White scores 48%)   Based on the above statistics, your opponent is mostly likely out of book and won't know what to do, while Black has natural development and retains the extra pawn for now. In this position, White's most common moves are 5. fxe4 and 5. g4 .} (4... exf3 {is the most common move.} 5. Nxf3 {White gets some compensation for the pawn, but objectively not enough.}) 5. fxe4 {This is the most common move you will see here.} Nxe4 {It's natural to take with the knight to retain the strong light-squared bishop.} 6. Qf3 {White's best option, trying to put pressure on our minor pieces, while x-raying the b7 -pawn.} Nxc3 {Black's best move, giving White several options for which piece to capture.} 7. Qxf5 {is the most tempting since now Black's knight looks a bit stranded. However...} e6 {A nice tempo move on the queen also activates the f8 -bishop.} 8. Qd3 {White hits the knight and tries to use the b5 -square for the queen.} Nd5 9. Qb5+ {A tempting check to win the b7 -pawn. This is exactly what we want our opponent to do as we have a little surprise ready!} Nc6 {Please take the free pawn...} 10. Qxb7 {White takes the bait, unaware of the dangers.} Bb4+ 11. c3 Nxd4 {What an awesome shot! Definitely a good one to remember and show to your friends! Black wins in all lines now.} 12. cxb4 Nc2+ ({The simplest, but} 12... Qh4+ $1 {is crushing as well.}) 13. Kf2 O-O {We finish development and just want to take on a1 .} ({Again} 13... Qh4+ {works as well. Nxa1 also wins.}) 14. Rb1 Qh4+ 15. g3 Qd4+ {White is getting crushed here as he has zero development.} ({For example: Kg2} 15... Ne1 {Kh3 h5 threatening mate in one, Qg4 #} 16. Be2 Qe4 {Black will win one of the rooks with a deadly attack.}) *

