1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. e4 {This is the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit. White gives up the central pawn, hoping to get quick counterplay after 4. f3 .   I have already published the refutation of this gambit in my Chessable course, Every Gambit Refuted, and am happy to share it with you here!} dxe4 {Of course, we take the pawn in order to refute the gambit.} 4. f3 {This improved version of the gambit by a German master, Emil Josef Diemer, was suggested in his book published in the 1950s. White offers the trade of the e4 -pawn to quickly develop the g1 -knight.} Bf5 {I suggest this move, which is quite rare but just as good as the main line of taking on f3 .   According to the Lichess DB, we see: 4... exf3 played in over 2 million games (White scores 53%) and 4... Bf5 played only in 200,000 games (White scores 48%)   Based on the above statistics, your opponent is mostly likely out of book and won't know what to do, while Black has natural development and retains the extra pawn for now. In this position, White's most common moves are 5. fxe4 and 5. g4 .} (4... exf3 {is the most common move.} 5. Nxf3 {White gets some compensation for the pawn, but objectively not enough.}) 5. fxe4 {This is the most common move you will see here.} Nxe4 {It's natural to take with the knight to retain the strong light-squared bishop.} 6. Qf3 {White's best option, trying to put pressure on our minor pieces, while x-raying the b7 -pawn.} Nxc3 {Black's best move, giving White several options for which piece to capture.} 7. bxc3 {White's best, but not an easy decision since it doubles their pawns.} e6 {Black plays a developing move, sacrificing the b7 -pawn for initiative!} 8. Qxb7 {White takes the pawn and accepts the challenge. Now, Black is the one playing gambit style and goes for rapid development and piece play.} Nd7 9. Nf3 Rb8 {We might as well sac the a7 -pawn!} 10. Qxa7 Bxc2 {Grabbing some snacks along the way.} 11. Bg5 ({A tempo on the queen.} 11. Bf4 Bd6 $1 {with similar play as the main line.}) 11... f6 (11... Qc8 $1 {is strong too.}) 12. Bf4 {White hits the c7 -pawn.} Bd6 {An important move! We don't mind the trade of these bishops. It's important to avoid losing the c7 -pawn.} 13. Bxd6 cxd6 14. Bc4 {A natural development move, White hits the e6 -pawn and about to castle.} Ke7 ({A cool idea, setting up a trap...} 14... d5 {is the safe option} 15. Be2 O-O {.}) 15. O-O {A logical move.} Qc8 {Black hits the bishop and gets ready to trap the queen with ... Ra8 . White has to be careful now.} 16. Qa6 {The only move! White goes into a worse endgame.} (16. Be2 $2 Ra8 {traps the queen and wins. Bb3? Ra8 traps the queen and wins.}) 16... Nb6 17. Bd3 Qxa6 {We don't mind trading queens here as we have a better pawn structure.} 18. Bxa6 Ra8 {Driving the bishop back.} 19. Be2 Ra3 {Black is much better here! Why? Just notice how weak White's pawns are. Also, Black's rooks are way more active.} ({A game could continue: c4} 19... Na4 $1 {the knight is heading to c3} 20. Rfc1 Bf5 {c5 dxc5 dxc5 Nc3} 21. Bf1 {Rc8-+ Now the c5 -pawn falls and the a2 -pawn will follow, Black should be able to convert this position.}) *

