[Black "Symmetrical English Intro"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A37"]
[PlyCount "14"]
[GameId "2176748630025298"]

1. c4 ({White can also start with} 1. Nf3 {, followed by c4 . This way they avoid Nimzo/Bogo by keeping the pawn on d2 . Therefore, we need a new weapon for Black, and I recommend a simple and effective Symmetrical English that works well with my Hyper-Accelerated Dragon recommendation ( e4} c5 {Nf3 g6 ) and the dark-square strategy overall.}) 1... c5 {Black fights for the center and prevents d4 from White. The game generally takes a slow and positional approach, where both sides develop and delay major confrontation in the opening. However, you have to be aware of various move order tries and how to meet them. For this especially, I recommend you watch the videos and pay attention to the ideas.} 2. Nf3 ({White typically plays this move, but both} 2. g3 {and Nc3 are playable and may transpose. The good news is our 2nd move ... g6 is quite universal against these moves. g3 g6 Bg2 Bg7 Nc3 Nc6 and White has several options to delay Nf3 all covered here .}) 2... g6 {Black is ready to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop and the ideas are somewhat similar to my Hyper-Accelerated Dragon (HAD) Repertoire (1. e4  c5 2. Nf3  g6 ). As a matter of fact, there's one line where White tries to build the Maroczy Bind, which is a direct transposition to my HAD course.} 3. g3 {This is the most common way for White to develop in the English. They first fianchetto the bishop and castle and only then fight for the center.} (3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 $1 {An important move to stop White from playing e4} 5. Nc3 ({( Or,} 5. g3 h5 $1 {)}) 5... d5 $1 {The key move to prevent White from getting the Maroczy Bind with e4 ! It's covered here}) (3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {This is an inferior version for White if they try to get to the Maroczy Bind since they would have to make a concession: either retreat the knight and lose a tempo or play a dubious move 5. e3 . This is covered here ( here )}) (3. e4 {White wants to play d4 next, building a Maroczy Bind, a famous structure where White puts a serious grip in the center with their e- & c- pawns.} Bg7 4. d4 Qa5+ $1 {This is a fresh and original way to avoid the dreadful Maroczy Bind. Since it is a very important line for our repertoire, I have dedicated a significant amount to it, in this chapter. If you already have my HAD course, you might have studied it already. However, if you're still searching for a weapon against 1. e4 , then I would wholeheartedly recommend my course! https://www.chessable.com/lifetime-repertoires-hyper-accelerated-dragon/course/131928/}) 3... Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 {It's important to take control over d4 -outpost in these structures as early as possible for us.} 5. O-O d6 {Black sets the Dragon formation and opens up the c8 -bishop. Please note that for this course I decided to give you a more flexible setup with ... d6 and ... Bf5 , keeping the pawn on e7 in the true Dragon style.   The reversed Botvinnik Setup with ... e5 and ... Nge7 was recommended in the original book, Chess Openings for Black, Explained. However, I believe that keeping the pawn on e7 is more flexible and doesn't give White an easy target, the d5 -outpost.} 6. Nc3 Bf5 7. d3 Qd7 {We immediately set up the battery in order to go for White's biggest trump, the g2 -bishop. Often, we even follow up with Harry the h-pawn push ... h5 & ... h4 , involving our rook in the attack! This is covered here.} *

