1. c4 c5 2. g3 {With this move order White often tries to delay Nf3 , or play without Nf3 .} g6 {Our response is simple to continue with symmetry, but keep in the mind we like symmetry as long as White doesn't play Nf3 . Make sure that you don't accidentally meet Nf3 with ... Nf6 ? as this would ruin our entire setup!} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {For now, we still continue with symmetrical development. It's very important to keep full control over the d4 -outpost, thus we need to keep the knight on g8 . Now, White has to make a big decision here:} {Go for the main line with Nf3 or play a tricky waiting move a3!? or try to develop e3 and Nge2 . We will cover both 5. a3 !? and 5. e3 in this chapter.} 5. e3 {White wants to develop the knight with 6. Nge2 and castle next.} h5 {Remember this important idea! Whenever White is going for Nge2 plan we would love to get our pawn to h4 or provoke h4 from White.} 6. Nge2 h4 {Harry the h-pawn is putting serious pressure on White. The engines already give Black a slight preference!} 7. gxh4 {This is positional capitulation as White's pawn structure is now ruined.} Rxh4 8. O-O d6 9. d3 Bh3 {Black already has a winning advantage. The attack with ... Qd7 and ... O-O-O is unstoppable.} *

