1. c4 c5 2. g3 {With this move order White often tries to delay Nf3 , or play without Nf3 .} g6 {Our response is simple to continue with symmetry, but keep in the mind we like symmetry as long as White doesn't play Nf3 . Make sure that you don't accidentally meet Nf3 with ... Nf6 ? as this would ruin our entire setup!} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {For now, we still continue with symmetrical development. It's very important to keep full control over the d4 -outpost, thus we need to keep the knight on g8 . Now, White has to make a big decision here:} {Go for the main line with Nf3 or play a tricky waiting move a3!? or try to develop e3 and Nge2 . We will cover both 5. a3 !? and 5. e3 in this chapter.} 5. e3 {White wants to develop the knight with 6. Nge2 and castle next.} h5 {Remember this important idea! Whenever White is going for Nge2 plan we would love to get our pawn to h4 or provoke h4 from White.} 6. Nge2 h4 {Harry the h-pawn is putting serious pressure on White. The engines already give Black a slight preference!} 7. d4 {A logical move, White follows the known principle to meet the flank attack with play in the center.} Nf6 {We develop our knight and offer White to grab even more central space with d5 .} 8. d5 ({A logical follow-up. After} 8. dxc5 Qa5 {we win back our pawn, which is always a favorable trade for Black.}) 8... h3 {A nice intermezzo to draw the bishop to f3 .} 9. Bf3 Ne5 {And now you can see the triumph of Black's strategy: the bishop on f3 will be traded and White just falls apart on the light squares.} 10. Nf4 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 d6 12. O-O Bg4 13. Qh1 {A sad position for White's queen...} b5 {We blow open the queenside in the style of the Benko Gambit! Of course, Black has many other good moves here as well.} 14. cxb5 a6 15. bxa6 Qb6 {Black has a dream version of the Benko Gambit. We will have all the fun with active piece play on the queenside, while White's queen is taking a vacation in the corner of the board!} *

