1. c4 c5 2. g3 {With this move order White often tries to delay Nf3 , or play without Nf3 .} g6 {Our response is simple to continue with symmetry, but keep in the mind we like symmetry as long as White doesn't play Nf3 . Make sure that you don't accidentally meet Nf3 with ... Nf6 ? as this would ruin our entire setup!} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {For now, we still continue with symmetrical development. It's very important to keep full control over the d4 -outpost, thus we need to keep the knight on g8 . Now, White has to make a big decision here:} {Go for the main line with Nf3 or play a tricky waiting move a3!? or try to develop e3 and Nge2 . We will cover both 5. a3 !? and 5. e3 in this chapter.} 5. e3 {White wants to develop the knight with 6. Nge2 and castle next.} h5 {Remember this important idea! Whenever White is going for Nge2 plan we would love to get our pawn to h4 or provoke h4 from White.} 6. h3 {This quiet move is probably White's best. Now they would meet ... h4 with g4 ! So, we need to delay this push by one more move.} d6 7. Nge2 h4 {This is the sharpest continuation, but Black can also play the calm ... e5 and ... Nge7 plan.} 8. g4 f5 {The point. We still insist of breaking open White's kingside.} 9. g5 {This is White's best try. They would prefer to keep the kingside locked up and calmly prepare the central d4 break.} e5 {We need to stop d4 . Yes, d5 -outpost is now in White's hands but we will play ... Nge7 next to fight for it. In the meantime, g5 -pawn is under attack.} 10. f4 Nge7 {Make sure not to play the tempting 10... e4 ? as after 11.d3! we won't be able to keep the pawn chain intact.} 11. d3 b6 {Black's best square for the bishop is b7 as on e6 it's too passive after Nd5 .} 12. O-O Bb7 13. b3 {White goes for the natural fianchetto as well.} Qd7 {We prepare the trade of light-squared bishops with ... Nb4 !} 14. Bb2 Nb4 {White has to trade or play e4 .} 15. Bxb7 ({After} 15. e4 O-O {we get plenty of counterplay.}) 15... Qxb7 16. a3 Nbc6 17. Nd5 {White's control of d5 is temporary.} Nxd5 18. cxd5 Nd8 {The knight is heading to f7 , anticipating action in the center to support the e5 pawn.} 19. e4 Nf7 {We've reached a complex middlegame with plenty of fight ahead. We have several plans to choose from as natural ... O-O or a more aggressive ... O-O-O are all playable! Keep in mind that White's king is quite weak without the LSB.} *

