1. c4 c5 2. g3 {With this move order White often tries to delay Nf3 , or play without Nf3 .} g6 {Our response is simple to continue with symmetry, but keep in the mind we like symmetry as long as White doesn't play Nf3 . Make sure that you don't accidentally meet Nf3 with ... Nf6 ? as this would ruin our entire setup!} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {For now, we still continue with symmetrical development. It's very important to keep full control over the d4 -outpost, thus we need to keep the knight on g8 . Now, White has to make a big decision here:} {Go for the main line with Nf3 or play a tricky waiting move a3!? or try to develop e3 and Nge2 . We will cover both 5. a3 !? and 5. e3 in this chapter.} 5. a3 {A tricky waiting move! White wants to see how Black develops and then choose their setup. Plus a3 is a useful move as they can play for the typical English plan with Rb1 & b4 next. Remember, White is basically playing the Dragon with reversed colors and wants to swing with the tail!} b6 {I love this rare move! It's based on a very simple concept: do you want to play for a3 & b4 ? Then, be my guest! Black will have time to set up the fianchetto on b7 and neutralize White's best piece, the g2 bishop. Plus, there's another bonus idea to Black's setup as you will see shorty.} 6. b4 {White even gets to play b4 in one go!} Bb7 {We neutralize White's g2 -bishop.} 7. b5 Na5 8. Bxb7 Nxb7 {Remember, this trade is almost always favorable for Black as White's kingside is quite weak now.} 9. Bb2 e6 {The idea is to play for ... Nge7 and ... d5 !} 10. Nf3 Ne7 11. O-O d5 12. d3 d4 {Black takes over the center and enjoys a nice space advantage.} *

