1. c4 c5 2. g3 {With this move order White often tries to delay Nf3 , or play without Nf3 .} g6 {Our response is simple to continue with symmetry, but keep in the mind we like symmetry as long as White doesn't play Nf3 . Make sure that you don't accidentally meet Nf3 with ... Nf6 ? as this would ruin our entire setup!} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {For now, we still continue with symmetrical development. It's very important to keep full control over the d4 -outpost, thus we need to keep the knight on g8 . Now, White has to make a big decision here:} {Go for the main line with Nf3 or play a tricky waiting move a3!? or try to develop e3 and Nge2 . We will cover both 5. a3 !? and 5. e3 in this chapter.} 5. a3 {A tricky waiting move! White wants to see how Black develops and then choose their setup. Plus a3 is a useful move as they can play for the typical English plan with Rb1 & b4 next. Remember, White is basically playing the Dragon with reversed colors and wants to swing with the tail!} b6 {I love this rare move! It's based on a very simple concept: do you want to play for a3 & b4 ? Then, be my guest! Black will have time to set up the fianchetto on b7 and neutralize White's best piece, the g2 bishop. Plus, there's another bonus idea to Black's setup as you will see shorty.} 6. b4 {White even gets to play b4 in one go!} Bb7 {We neutralize White's g2 -bishop.} 7. Bb2 Nh6 {I like this slightly unusual square for the knight in order not to block our g7 -bishop.} 8. Nh3 {White does the same!} Qc8 {We protect our bishop while making ... cxb4 a threat.} 9. bxc5 Na5 {A really cool idea to remember!} 10. Bxb7 Qxb7 {We attack the rook on h1 and c4 -pawn at the same time.} 11. O-O Nxc4 {Now, we take back with another tempo!} 12. Rb1 bxc5 {The most precise for an edge, but other moves are good as well.} 13. Ba1 Qc6 {The dust has settled and Black is clearly better. We managed to trade White's best piece, the g2 -bishop. We will castle next and try to target White's king.} *

