1. c4 c5 2. g3 {With this move order White often tries to delay Nf3 , or play without Nf3 .} g6 {Our response is simple to continue with symmetry, but keep in the mind we like symmetry as long as White doesn't play Nf3 . Make sure that you don't accidentally meet Nf3 with ... Nf6 ? as this would ruin our entire setup!} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {For now, we still continue with symmetrical development. It's very important to keep full control over the d4 -outpost, thus we need to keep the knight on g8 . Now, White has to make a big decision here:} {Go for the main line with Nf3 or play a tricky waiting move a3!? or try to develop e3 and Nge2 . We will cover both 5. a3 !? and 5. e3 in this chapter.} 5. a3 {A tricky waiting move! White wants to see how Black develops and then choose their setup. Plus a3 is a useful move as they can play for the typical English plan with Rb1 & b4 next. Remember, White is basically playing the Dragon with reversed colors and wants to swing with the tail!} b6 {I love this rare move! It's based on a very simple concept: do you want to play for a3 & b4 ? Then, be my guest! Black will have time to set up the fianchetto on b7 and neutralize White's best piece, the g2 bishop. Plus, there's another bonus idea to Black's setup as you will see shorty.} 6. b4 {White even gets to play b4 in one go!} Bb7 {We neutralize White's g2 -bishop.} 7. Rb1 {A standard idea. White's rook gets out of the long diagonal, creating a threat of bxc5 .} Bxc3 {This is the bonus surprise that I mentioned earlier! Normally, one would not trade this beautiful bishop for the c3 knight, but this is an exception! The key idea is like in the Nimzo-Indian, White's doubled c-pawns are too much of a liability.} 8. dxc3 d6 {We secure the c5 -pawn and White is now playing with a ruined pawn structure on the queenside. There have only been a handful of games in the DB with this position, so it's quite fresh!} 9. b5 {This always favors Black, as we are happy to trade the bishops.} Na5 10. Bxb7 Nxb7 11. Nf3 Qd7 {I like this clever idea, we may even castle long!} 12. O-O Nf6 13. Bh6 {White thinks that we want to castle short...} Ng4 14. Bf4 O-O-O {But it's long castle that we aim for! Now the attack against White's king is one-sided, while our king is totally safe!} *

