is met by} Ng4 $1) 10... O-O 11. Bh6 Re8 {At first, it may seem really dangerous for us with White's bishop on h6 . However, my analysis shows that White can't really create tangible threats while we have a clear plan in mind: trade light-squared bishops and target the c4 -pawn.} 12. Nd2 Qc7 {With the idea to play ... Ne5 next, trading the bishops.} 13. Qb3 Ne5 14. Bxb7 Qxb7 {Black has a serious advantage as the c4 -pawn is quite weak. Plus, White's king is exposed as well: imagine our queen coming to h3 and playing ... Ng4 .} *

