1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. g3 {White plans to develop via Bg2 , O-O , Nc3 and then focus on the center. It's an easy few moves for us as well. We will play ... Bg7 , ... Nc6 , and ... d6 .} (3. e4 {For this, please the Anti-Maroczy.}) (3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d5 {For this variation, please see here.}) (3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 ({(} 4. e3 Nf6 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {For this variation, please see here. )}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {For this variation, please see the here.}) 3... Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. O-O d6 6. Nc3 Bf5 {We've reached the main tabiya of our setup. Black plans to play ... Qd7 and set up a classic battery to prepare ... Bh3 .   Please note that it's vital for us to stop White from playing d4 too easily, thus we keep the knight on g8 for now. Sometimes, we also launch Harry the h-pawn for a caveman attack! White's most common options are:} {1) Continue with normal development and play d3 2) Stop our battery with h3 and Kh2 3) Go for the double fianchetto with b3} 7. h3 {White is planning to meet Qd7 with .} Qc8 {This move was the idea of the creative genius Daniil Dubov, who crushed Svidler in 30 moves in Russian Championship, 2017. The point is to vacate the d7 square for the bishop in case of the future e4 .} 8. Kh2 Nf6 {Black now goes for normal development.} 9. d3 O-O 10. e4 Bd7 {Now, it's clear why Black played ... Qc8 instead of ... Qd7 earlier.} 11. Be3 a6 {Remember, the Dragon swings with the tail!} 12. Rc1 Rb8 13. Nd5 Qd8 {Getting out of any danger on the c-file.} 14. b3 {After this move, Black starts to take over.} e6 15. Nc3 e5 {It turns out our pieces are better suited for symmetry as ... b5 and ... Nd4 are coming.} 16. Ng1 Nd4 17. Nge2 b5 {Black is clearly better and won on move 31. Let me give you the rest of the game as it's instructive how Dubov won so easily.} ({f4 exf4 gxf4 b4 Bxd4 cxd4 Nb1} 17... Nh5 {Nd2 f5 c5 dxc5 e5 g5 Rxc5 Qe7} 18. Qc2 Rc8 {Qc4+ Be6 Qxe6+ Qxe6 Bd5 Rxc5 Bxe6+ Kh8 Bc4} 19. Nf4 {(0-1 (31) Svidler, P - Dubov, D St Petersburg, 2017.}) *

