1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. g3 {White plans to develop via Bg2 , O-O , Nc3 and then focus on the center. It's an easy few moves for us as well. We will play ... Bg7 , ... Nc6 , and ... d6 .} (3. e4 {For this, please the Anti-Maroczy.}) (3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d5 {For this variation, please see here.}) (3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 ({(} 4. e3 Nf6 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {For this variation, please see here. )}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {For this variation, please see the here.}) 3... Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. O-O d6 6. Nc3 Bf5 {We've reached the main tabiya of our setup. Black plans to play ... Qd7 and set up a classic battery to prepare ... Bh3 .   Please note that it's vital for us to stop White from playing d4 too easily, thus we keep the knight on g8 for now. Sometimes, we also launch Harry the h-pawn for a caveman attack! White's most common options are:} {1) Continue with normal development and play d3 2) Stop our battery with h3 and Kh2 3) Go for the double fianchetto with b3} 7. h3 {White is planning to meet Qd7 with .} e5 {This is a solid approach. Black abandons the attacking ideas and goes for the good old Botvinnik setup with ... Nge7 next. Now, the h3 -pawn could be weak.} 8. d3 Nge7 9. a3 {White is planning to go Rb1 & b4 next.} O-O 10. Rb1 a5 {We've reached a typical English position with mutual chances. Black will play ... Qd7 next to connect rooks. It's hard for White to execute the classic b4 and they would need to find another plan.} *

