1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. g3 {White plans to develop via Bg2 , O-O , Nc3 and then focus on the center. It's an easy few moves for us as well. We will play ... Bg7 , ... Nc6 , and ... d6 .} (3. e4 {For this, please the Anti-Maroczy.}) (3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d5 {For this variation, please see here.}) (3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 ({(} 4. e3 Nf6 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {For this variation, please see here. )}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {For this variation, please see the here.}) 3... Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. O-O d6 6. Nc3 Bf5 {We've reached the main tabiya of our setup. Black plans to play ... Qd7 and set up a classic battery to prepare ... Bh3 .   Please note that it's vital for us to stop White from playing d4 too easily, thus we keep the knight on g8 for now. Sometimes, we also launch Harry the h-pawn for a caveman attack! White's most common options are:} {1) Continue with normal development and play d3 2) Stop our battery with h3 and Kh2 3) Go for the double fianchetto with b3} 7. b3 {White goes for the double fianchetto with Bb2 next.} Qd7 {We continue with our plan, setting up the battery.} 8. Bb2 h5 {There's nothing wrong with 8... Bh3 , but I'd like to induce h4 .} 9. h4 {A logical way to stop our expansion.} Nh6 {A clever way to develop, avoiding blocking our bishop on g7 . Let me share with you this analysis that shows how easily White can get under a powerful attack.} 10. Ng5 O-O-O {A cool idea to remember! We will need to blow open the kingside, thus we bring our king to the queenside for safety. We also activate the other rook.} 11. d3 Bxc3 {An unusual trade, but since we plan to push with ... f6 next it makes sense.} 12. Bxc3 f6 13. Ne4 Rdg8 {Black's attack is quite strong as ... g5 is coming. For example:} 14. a3 Bxe4 15. Bxe4 g5 16. hxg5 Rxg5 {And our pieces are perfectly set up for the final assault on the enemy king.} *

