1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. g3 {White plans to develop via Bg2 , O-O , Nc3 and then focus on the center. It's an easy few moves for us as well. We will play ... Bg7 , ... Nc6 , and ... d6 .} (3. e4 {For this, please the Anti-Maroczy.}) (3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d5 {For this variation, please see here.}) (3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 ({(} 4. e3 Nf6 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {For this variation, please see here. )}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {For this variation, please see the here.}) 3... Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. O-O d6 6. Nc3 Bf5 {We've reached the main tabiya of our setup. Black plans to play ... Qd7 and set up a classic battery to prepare ... Bh3 .   Please note that it's vital for us to stop White from playing d4 too easily, thus we keep the knight on g8 for now. Sometimes, we also launch Harry the h-pawn for a caveman attack! White's most common options are:} {1) Continue with normal development and play d3 2) Stop our battery with h3 and Kh2 3) Go for the double fianchetto with b3} 7. d3 Qd7 {This is the natural follow-up move for our plan. Now, White has to make a choice, allow the bishop trade or not.} 8. Nd5 ({This is a clever way to stop our ...Bh3 idea, since} 8. Bh3 $2 Bxh3 {Qxh3 allows Nc7+ with a fork.}) 8... Nf6 {At this point we need to abandon the attack plan for now, and go for development. Keep in mind we are happy to trade the knights.} 9. Bd2 {This was played by Grischuk vs Anand in blitz back in 2018. White wants to play Bc3 next.} O-O {We continue with natural development. 9... Nxd5 is fine as well.} 10. Bc3 Bh3 ({I believe this is an easier approach. Vishy took on d5 with} 10... Nxd5 {, which is playable, but I like it less.}) 11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. Bxf6 exf6 {White managed to ruin our pawn structure, but let me show you that it's not a big deal.} 13. d4 {A logical idea to grab more central space.} Rad8 {Inviting d5 .} 14. d5 Ne5 ({I prefer Black in this middlegame as I don't see any active plan for White. They would have to tolerate our strong knight since taking} 14... Ne5 {would undouble our pawns after . Black has lots of promising plans such as ... h5 and possible attack with ... Kg7 , Rh8 , h4 or Benoni-style ... b5 ideas.}) *

