1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. g3 {White plans to develop via Bg2 , O-O , Nc3 and then focus on the center. It's an easy few moves for us as well. We will play ... Bg7 , ... Nc6 , and ... d6 .} (3. e4 {For this, please the Anti-Maroczy.}) (3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d5 {For this variation, please see here.}) (3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 ({(} 4. e3 Nf6 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {For this variation, please see here. )}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {For this variation, please see the here.}) 3... Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. O-O d6 6. Nc3 Bf5 {We've reached the main tabiya of our setup. Black plans to play ... Qd7 and set up a classic battery to prepare ... Bh3 .   Please note that it's vital for us to stop White from playing d4 too easily, thus we keep the knight on g8 for now. Sometimes, we also launch Harry the h-pawn for a caveman attack! White's most common options are:} {1) Continue with normal development and play d3 2) Stop our battery with h3 and Kh2 3) Go for the double fianchetto with b3} 7. d3 Qd7 {This is the natural follow-up move for our plan. Now, White has to make a choice, allow the bishop trade or not.} 8. Re1 {This is the autopilot reaction to the threat of ... Bh3 . White is getting the rook out of the way to meet ... Bh3 with Bh1 .} Bh3 {It's a good idea to force the bishop in the corner.} 9. Bh1 {Of course, taking on h3 makes no sense if you play Re1 .} h5 {Harry the h-pawn joins the party! White has to be careful as the timely ... h4 push may open up his king for a deadly attack.} 10. Bg5 {With this move, White hopes to stop ... h4 .} h4 {We offer the h-pawn to open up the rook for a big attack. Now, White has to walk a tight rope to avoid losing.} 11. Bxh4 f6 {And the poor bishop will get trapped after ... g5 next.} *

