1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. e4 {This is the most testing option. White plans to go for the Maroczy setup with 4. d4 next. Luckily, I have an interesting fresh idea to share with you that I covered in my Hyper-Accelerated Dragon (HAD) Lifetime Repertoire on Chessable already. We go for 3... Bg7 and an early 4... Qa5 +!?. The way I reach this via a 1. e4 move order is:} (3. e4 {c5 Nf3 g6 c4}) 3... Bg7 4. d4 Qa5+ {As I mentioned, this is covered in detail in my 1. e4  c5 HAD course and I'm happy to share the full analysis here.} 5. Bd2 Qb6 {The pressure on d4 & b2 forces White to put their bishop on c3 , where it's clearly misplaced.} 6. Bc3 cxd4 7. Nxd4 {Leads to a harmless bind.} Nf6 8. Nd2 d6 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Nfd7 {Putting pressure on the d4 -knight.} 11. N2f3 Nc5 12. Qc2 e5 {An unusual idea for the bind, but it works great here!} 13. Nb3 Nc6 14. Rad1 Qc7 15. h3 a5 {Black has a nice flexible structure while White's pieces are lacking any harmony.} *

