1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. e4 {This is the most testing option. White plans to go for the Maroczy setup with 4. d4 next. Luckily, I have an interesting fresh idea to share with you that I covered in my Hyper-Accelerated Dragon (HAD) Lifetime Repertoire on Chessable already. We go for 3... Bg7 and an early 4... Qa5 +!?. The way I reach this via a 1. e4 move order is:} (3. e4 {c5 Nf3 g6 c4}) 3... Bg7 4. d4 Qa5+ {As I mentioned, this is covered in detail in my 1. e4  c5 HAD course and I'm happy to share the full analysis here.} 5. Nc3 {White's most popular reply} d6 {With this move Black keeps White guessing how he would release the tension in the center. Our main idea is to apply more pressure with a future ... Nc6 or ... Bg4 .} 6. d5 {This is the most ambitious try. White takes the game into the closed structure that resembles the Dzindzi-Indian. But keep in mind, typically 1. e4 players hate playing closed positions!} Bxc3+ {The main idea of the Dzindzi-Indian. Black ruins White's structure.} 7. bxc3 Bg4 ({I like this rare move, putting more pressure on White. Keep in mind that in closed positions, knights are better than bishops.} 7... Qxc3+ $6 {is playable but too risky} 8. Bd2 {with good compensation for the pawn and easy play for White.}) 8. Rb1 Nd7 9. Be2 (9. Rxb7 {is too risky due to .}) 9... Bxf3 10. gxf3 ({Forced.} 10. Bxf3 $2 {allows Black to collect some pawns} Qxc3+ 11. Bd2 Qxc4) 10... Ngf6 11. O-O O-O-O {A natural novelty, given that it's part of our plan! Black wants to attack on the kingside while White's half-open b-file is not too dangerous for us.} ({Here's a possible line: Be3} 11... g5 $1 12. Qb3 Qc7 13. Kh1 Rg8 {Black is already better as they have a clear plan of attack: blow open the kingside!}) *

