1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 {This is White's attempt to get a Maroczy Setup, but it is an inferior version compared to 3. e4 as the knight on d4 is unstable.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {The point! Now, the knight either has to move to c2 / b3 or White has to play a very passive move 6. e3} 6. e3 {Clearly, this is not what White wanted as the pawn is quite passive on e3 , blocking the c1 -bishop.} Nf6 7. Be2 d5 ({With this move Black easily equalizes as White is not able to get a grip in the center. Please note that} 7... O-O {allows} 8. Nc2 {, which is still fine for Black.}) 8. O-O ({After} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Na4 {we will transpose.}) 8... O-O 9. cxd5 Nxd5 ({Here, White has tried either} 9... Nxd5 {or} 10. Nxc6 {, in both cases Black gets an easy game.}) 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Na4 {White tries to avoid the trade and hopes to put pressure on c6 -pawn.} ({Please note that} 11. Bd2 Nxc3 {is easy equality for Black.}) 11... Bf5 {Black has many moves that all lead to equality, but this is the easiest. We develop our last piece and prevent e4 . We will play ... Rb8 next and it's unclear how White will develop the c1 -bishop.} *

