1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 {This is White's attempt to get a Maroczy Setup, but it is an inferior version compared to 3. e4 as the knight on d4 is unstable.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {The point! Now, the knight either has to move to c2 / b3 or White has to play a very passive move 6. e3} 6. e3 {Clearly, this is not what White wanted as the pawn is quite passive on e3 , blocking the c1 -bishop.} Nf6 7. Be2 d5 ({With this move Black easily equalizes as White is not able to get a grip in the center. Please note that} 7... O-O {allows} 8. Nc2 {, which is still fine for Black.}) 8. O-O ({After} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Na4 {we will transpose.}) 8... O-O 9. cxd5 Nxd5 ({Here, White has tried either} 9... Nxd5 {or} 10. Nxc6 {, in both cases Black gets an easy game.}) 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. Bf3 Qc5 {The simplest square as we guard the knight, but pretty much most queen retreats are equal.} 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Qa4 {It seems as though White is targeting our weak pawn, but...} Be6 {We just develop and don't care! It's more important to activate our pieces and play against the bad bishop on c1 .} 14. Qxc6 Qa5 {We make our intentions clear, Black is playing for a win now! Of course, trading queen and ... Rab8 is fine as well.} 15. Qxa8 {White thinks they are winning more material as typically two rooks are better than the queen... If they don't take on a8 , Black will play ... Rab8 with nice pressure.} Rxa8 16. Bxa8 Be5 {Black is now ready to launch the kingside pawns with ... h5 and ... g5 next. Even though we are technically "down" material, it's clear that White's rooks and the c1 -bishop are totally stuck. The engine gives us a nice -1 edge already!} *

