1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 {This is White's attempt to get a Maroczy Setup, but it is an inferior version compared to 3. e4 as the knight on d4 is unstable.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {The point! Now, the knight either has to move to c2 / b3 or White has to play a very passive move 6. e3} 6. Nb3 Bxc3+ {We play the same ideas as vs 6. Nc2 .} 7. bxc3 d6 8. e4 Nf6 {We are now playing a typical Maroczy bind but with the trade of our bishop for the c3 -knight. I believe this favors Black as White can't really create an attack, while the doubled pawns are super weak.} 9. f3 Be6 10. Bh6 Nd7 {Getting out of Bg7 ideas.} 11. Be2 f6 {An instructive idea! We build an strong defensive structure on the kingside and will focus on attacking the weak pawns.} 12. O-O Qc7 13. Nd4 Nd8 {We don't mind trading the e6 -bishop for a strong d4 -knight.} 14. Nxe6 Nxe6 {I believe the two knights are superior to White's bishops as we control the c5 -outpost.} 15. Be3 {Otherwise ... g5 will trap the bishop.} Ndc5 16. a4 g5 17. a5 O-O-O {Our king is totally safe as the c5 -knight guards b7 . We will play with ... h5 next, launching a big attack.} *

