1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 {This is White's attempt to get a Maroczy Setup, but it is an inferior version compared to 3. e4 as the knight on d4 is unstable.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {The point! Now, the knight either has to move to c2 / b3 or White has to play a very passive move 6. e3} 6. Nc2 {This is White's most common move. They still hope to get some kind of bind with g3 , Bg2 , or e4 .} ({Please note that} 6. Nxc6 $6 {Improves our structure as White will no longer achieve the bind. I prefer the endgame after . Yes, we lose the castling rights but our king is quite safe in this endgame.  For example: Qxd8+ Kxd8 Bd2 Kc7 O-O-O} h5 7. e4 e5 {Black’s plan is to trade the dark-squared bishops with ... Bh6 and try to land a knight on the d4 -outpost.}) 6... Bxc3+ {Remember this very important idea! Yes, we part with our best piece, but we create chronic weaknesses in White's camp. As a Nimzo player, we are used to these ideas!} 7. bxc3 Qa5 {I like the idea of targeting c3 -pawn as White often reacts poorly with an autopilot Bd2 .} 8. e4 {White should not care about pawns and go for rapid development. Plus, it's too dangerous for us to grab the c3 -pawn as it opens up the h8 - a1 diagonal for White's bishop.} d6 ({Don't take the pawn as} 8... Qxc3+ $2 9. Bd2 {gives White ample compensation and an easy game.}) 9. Be2 Nf6 {We develop and hit the e4 -pawn with a tempo.} 10. f3 Be6 11. O-O O-O 12. Bh6 Rfc8 {I believe that Black is a bit better as one of the pawns c4 / c3 will fall. In the meantime, White's compensation is probably just enough to hold the balance.} *

