1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 {This is White's attempt to get a Maroczy Setup, but it is an inferior version compared to 3. e4 as the knight on d4 is unstable.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {The point! Now, the knight either has to move to c2 / b3 or White has to play a very passive move 6. e3} 6. Nc2 {This is White's most common move. They still hope to get some kind of bind with g3 , Bg2 , or e4 .} ({Please note that} 6. Nxc6 $6 {Improves our structure as White will no longer achieve the bind. I prefer the endgame after . Yes, we lose the castling rights but our king is quite safe in this endgame.  For example: Qxd8+ Kxd8 Bd2 Kc7 O-O-O} h5 7. e4 e5 {Black’s plan is to trade the dark-squared bishops with ... Bh6 and try to land a knight on the d4 -outpost.}) 6... Bxc3+ {Remember this very important idea! Yes, we part with our best piece, but we create chronic weaknesses in White's camp. As a Nimzo player, we are used to these ideas!} 7. bxc3 Qa5 {I like the idea of targeting c3 -pawn as White often reacts poorly with an autopilot Bd2 .} 8. Bd2 {This is the most common reply, but I believe the bishop is misplaced on d2 .} f5 {I like this aggressive move to stop e4 .} 9. g3 b6 {We are getting ready to counter White's g2 bishop with ... Bb7 .} 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. O-O Nd8 ({A simple concept: by trading light-squared bishops we eliminate their bishop pair and weakening White's king.} 11... Nf6 {is also fine.}) 12. Bxb7 Nxb7 {I believe Black is already a bit better as we plan to finish development and target White's weak c4 -pawn.} 13. a4 Nf6 14. Bh6 Rg8 {We stop Bg7 . Keep in mind that our king is totally safe for now.} 15. Qd3 Nc5 16. Qf3 Nce4 {Black will play ... Rc8 next and will likely win the c4 - or c3 -pawn next. The king is actually quite comfy on f7 .} *

