1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e3 {White aims to play for d4 push, so we need to prepare with a classic ... d5 counter. Thus we play ... Nf6 !} Nf6 {We are ready to meet d4 with cxd4 and ... d5 !} 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {Now, we have transposed to a well-known line from the Caro-Kann Panov-Botvinnik. It is considered totally harmless for Black as often White gets a typical Isolated Pawn weakness (IQP).} 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Nc6 9. h3 {Black has a very pleasant position and I recommend the instructive plan of ... dxc4 , ... Na5 and ... Be6 !} dxc4 10. Bxc4 Na5 {Driving the bishop away from controlling d5 .} 11. Be2 Be6 {Black has won the key strategic d5 -outpost and enjoys a longterm advantage against the IQP. We will play ... Rc8 next and put our knight or bishop on d5 .} *

