1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e3 {White aims to play for d4 push, so we need to prepare with a classic ... d5 counter. Thus we play ... Nf6 !} Nf6 {We are ready to meet d4 with cxd4 and ... d5 !} 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {Now, we have transposed to a well-known line from the Caro-Kann Panov-Botvinnik. It is considered totally harmless for Black as often White gets a typical Isolated Pawn weakness (IQP).} 7. Bg5 {White hopes to force us to take on c4 , but...} O-O {Development above all! We are happy to sacrifice the d5 -pawn.} 8. Bxf6 exf6 {I prefer this over 8... Bxf6 , but both are good.} ({The point is to avoid a tempo loss after} 8... Bxf6 9. Nxd5 {and save the bishop pair.}) 9. cxd5 Nd7 {The knight is heading to b6 .} 10. Be2 Nb6 11. Qb3 {White hopes to hold the pawn.} a5 {with idea to dislodge the queen with ... a4 .} 12. a4 Qd6 {Preparing ... Rd8 next.} 13. O-O Rd8 {The d5 -pawn is doomed and our bishops will eventually take over.} *

