1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e3 {White aims to play for d4 push, so we need to prepare with a classic ... d5 counter. Thus we play ... Nf6 !} Nf6 {We are ready to meet d4 with cxd4 and ... d5 !} 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {Now, we have transposed to a well-known line from the Caro-Kann Panov-Botvinnik. It is considered totally harmless for Black as often White gets a typical Isolated Pawn weakness (IQP).} 7. c5 {White avoids the IQP structure but loses a vital tempo in the opening.} O-O 8. Be2 Nc6 9. O-O Ne4 {The key idea to remember! We get lots of activity with our pieces.} 10. Be3 b6 {Simple chess, we undermine White's small pawn chain and force them to trade the c5 -pawn.} 11. cxb6 Nxc3 {A nice intermezzo to ruin their structure.} 12. bxc3 axb6 {I prefer Black. We have a simple plan of ... Ba6 , trade the bishops and start playing against White weak pawns. Plus, if we can get our knight to c4 , it would dominate the queenside.} *

