1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e3 {White aims to play for d4 push, so we need to prepare with a classic ... d5 counter. Thus we play ... Nf6 !} Nf6 {We are ready to meet d4 with cxd4 and ... d5 !} 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {Now, we have transposed to a well-known line from the Caro-Kann Panov-Botvinnik. It is considered totally harmless for Black as often White gets a typical Isolated Pawn weakness (IQP).} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bc4 {White should try to resolve the situation with the d5 -knight ASAP. Otherwise, they risk of getting into a passive IQP structure with a monster knight on d5 .} ({After} 8. Qb3 {we also play} Nxc3 {with similar ideas.}) 8... Nxc3 {We happily trade, shifting our advantage to another well-known structure, the hanging pawns.} 9. bxc3 Qc7 {A nice tempo on the bishop.} 10. Qb3 O-O 11. O-O Nc6 {Now, White has to deal with a powerful ... Na5 fork.} 12. Be2 Be6 {A nice tempo on the queen.} 13. Qa3 Rac8 {Black's pieces are perfectly place to target White's weak pawns, and especially the squares in front of the pawns. We will play ... Rfd8 next and dominate on the light-squared with ... b6 & Na5 .} *

