1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. d4 {White tries to establish the central control with the knight on d4 right away.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 {White is about to play e4 and get the classic Maroczy Bind. Remember, we have to stop it!} Nf6 {Stopping e4 . Here White can renew the threat of e4 with logical 5. Nc3 or go back to slow English approach with 5. g3} 5. g3 {White goes for the slow English approach of developing the bishop first. Here, I have a nice surprise for our opponent.} h5 {This is a very rare move with only a handful of games in the DB, but it scores really well. White is now a bit uncomfortable facing ... h4 and need to decide whether to allow it with Bg2 or stop it with h4 or h3 moves.} 6. h4 {This is an autopilot response to ... h5 , but you will see that having the g4 -outpost for our knight or bishop gives Black easy play.} Nc6 {We can also play ... Bg7 first, but it would transpose.} 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. O-O Ng4 {The knight is perfectly placed on g4 and now White has to make some concession with his central stallion.} 9. Nc2 d6 10. Nc3 Bxc3 {I like this trade to ruin White's structure.} 11. bxc3 Bd7 {We will play ... Rc8 , ... b6 and go after the c4 -pawn.} *

