1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. d4 {White tries to establish the central control with the knight on d4 right away.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 {White is about to play e4 and get the classic Maroczy Bind. Remember, we have to stop it!} Nf6 {Stopping e4 . Here White can renew the threat of e4 with logical 5. Nc3 or go back to slow English approach with 5. g3} 5. g3 {White goes for the slow English approach of developing the bishop first. Here, I have a nice surprise for our opponent.} h5 {This is a very rare move with only a handful of games in the DB, but it scores really well. White is now a bit uncomfortable facing ... h4 and need to decide whether to allow it with Bg2 or stop it with h4 or h3 moves.} 6. h3 {Another typical reaction, White plans to meet ... h4 with g4 !} d5 {Now that White stopped our ... h4 idea, it's best to play in the center.} 7. Bg2 e5 {We take over the center with a tempo. Notice the energetic play with our pawns!} 8. Nb3 a5 {We take advantage of the awkward placement of White's knight to push it further back with ... a4 .} 9. cxd5 a4 10. N3d2 Nxd5 {It's clear that Black achieved great success with their rook pawns and central play.} 11. O-O Nc6 12. Ne4 Be7 {Perhaps not an obvious decision after having played ... g6 previously, but the bishop is much better placed on e7 where it controls more squares.} 13. Nbc3 Nxc3 14. Qxd8+ Bxd8 15. bxc3 Be7 {We will play ... O-O next with an about even game.} *

