1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. d4 {White tries to establish the central control with the knight on d4 right away.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 {White is about to play e4 and get the classic Maroczy Bind. Remember, we have to stop it!} Nf6 {Stopping e4 . Here White can renew the threat of e4 with logical 5. Nc3 or go back to slow English approach with 5. g3} 5. g3 {White goes for the slow English approach of developing the bishop first. Here, I have a nice surprise for our opponent.} h5 {This is a very rare move with only a handful of games in the DB, but it scores really well. White is now a bit uncomfortable facing ... h4 and need to decide whether to allow it with Bg2 or stop it with h4 or h3 moves.} 6. Bg2 {White ignores our threats and goes for rapid development.} h4 {We execute our Harry the h-pawn march. It is seen in many instances of our repertoire. Remember, I proposed this idea vs the e3 , Nge2 setup. It's also a common idea against the main line where we play with a ... Bf5 & ... Qd7 battery.} 7. Nc3 Bg7 (7... Nc6 {would likely transpose after} 8. O-O Bg7 {.}) 8. O-O {White bravely castles into the danger area.} Nc6 {For now, we need to develop as we don't have enough firepower yet to create an attack.} 9. c5 {White tries to take advantage that we didn't play ... d6 yet.} ({After} 9. Bg5 {we play} h3 $1 {with similar ideas as the 8.Bg5 line.}) 9... Rh5 {Very creative plan and why not!? Our rook is active and we attack the pawn.} 10. Nb3 hxg3 {We clarify the pawn structure on the kingside. We could delay it as well but likely will transpose.} 11. hxg3 d5 {We fight for the center and activate our c8 -bishop.} 12. cxd6 Bh3 {A cool attacking idea, we don't care about pawns!} 13. dxe7 Qxe7 {We've reached a completely fresh position. White is up a pawn, but clearly Black is getting counterplay against White's king. I prefer to take Black here as I believe in our attack.} 14. Bxh3 Rd8 {A nice intermezzo!} 15. Bd2 Rxh3 16. Qc2 ({A logical move to sidestep the pin, but this already gets White in trouble. Apparently,} 16. Kg2 {is the only move but after} Qe6 {, Black is having all the fun.}) 16... Ng4 {And already White is seriously worse and has to seek the queen trade.} 17. Qe4 f5 18. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {White managed to trade queens, but the attack doesn't stop. We will play ... Rdh8 next. The engine already gives us -2 advantage!} *

