1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. d4 {White tries to establish the central control with the knight on d4 right away.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 {White is about to play e4 and get the classic Maroczy Bind. Remember, we have to stop it!} Nf6 {Stopping e4 . Here White can renew the threat of e4 with logical 5. Nc3 or go back to slow English approach with 5. g3} 5. Nc3 {White renews the threat of e4 and we have to play ... d5 !} d5 {An absolute must move, otherwise the Maroczy Bind cannot be stopped. Often this leads to massive trades and some drawish structures. However, I will show you that it's still possible to play for a win!} ({Both} 5... Nc6 {and Bg7 allow} 6. e4 {with a classic bind.}) 6. Nf3 {White puts pressure on d5 , but we have a simple way to defend it.} Be6 7. Ng5 {White's kingside knight has a made a total of 4 moves (!) already, and now it would be traded for our bishop that has made only one move.} d4 {We don't mind the trade on e6 and try to go for active play right away.} 8. Nxe6 fxe6 9. Nb1 {We've reached a very unusual position. White has a better pawn structure and the bishop pair, but no development. This should give us enough time to generate counterplay.} Qb6 {I like this active queen move. Our queen still guards d4 , attacks b2 and is ready to meet g3 with ... Qc6 .} ({A normal move like} 9... Nc6 {would allow White to develop with} 10. g3 {, Bg2 and to consolidate.}) 10. g3 Qc6 {The point of our last move! Now, it's now easy for White to continue development.} 11. f3 e5 {We can also take on c4 , but I think this is easier. We just develop.} 12. Bg2 Bg7 13. O-O Qc7 {White was threatening f4 , so we move out of the way.} 14. f4 Nc6 15. fxe5 Ng4 {I think Black has excellent dynamic chances to fight for initiative as e5 -pawn will drop.} 16. Na3 O-O-O {Remember, active play!} 17. Bh3 h5 18. Nb5 {A logical move, but actually it only helps us.} Qb6 {And due to many threats, Blacks takes over the game.} *

