1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {White has many different move orders, but they more or less reach the key position we see on move 6.} ({White can start with} 2. Nf3 {c5 and then play c4 or .}) ({White can start with c4 c5} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 {and now play Nf3 , etc.}) 2... g6 3. d4 {White tries to establish the central control with the knight on d4 right away.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 {White is about to play e4 and get the classic Maroczy Bind. Remember, we have to stop it!} Nf6 {Stopping e4 . Here White can renew the threat of e4 with logical 5. Nc3 or go back to slow English approach with 5. g3} 5. Nc3 {White renews the threat of e4 and we have to play ... d5 !} d5 {An absolute must move, otherwise the Maroczy Bind cannot be stopped. Often this leads to massive trades and some drawish structures. However, I will show you that it's still possible to play for a win!} ({Both} 5... Nc6 {and Bg7 allow} 6. e4 {with a classic bind.}) 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Ndb5 {With this move, White is seeking to force an endgame with Nxc3 Qxd8+ intermezzo.} Nxc3 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nxc3 {At first, it looks like a slightly better endgame for White as we lost the right to castle. But in reality, Black is totally fine since our king is quite safe in the center. Let me show you a simple setup.} Bg7 10. Bd2 {White's most solid option to deny us the opportunity to ruin their structure with ... Bxc3 .} Be6 11. O-O-O {White castles while creating a discovery threat on our king with Bh6 +.} Ke8 {As I mentioned earlier, our king is totally fine on e8 . We will play ... Nc6 and ... Rc8 next.} 12. g3 {A logical way to develop and put pressure on the long diagonal.} Nc6 13. Bg2 Rc8 14. Kb1 {A logical move to sidestep the X-ray from the rook.} h5 {A powerful novelty that gives Black easy equality and more! The point is to expand on the kingside with ... h4 , taking advantage of well-placed rook on h8 .   Remember, in the endgame the king is fine in the center! Both Giri & Svidler had this position vs GM Le Quang Liem, but they played an inferior ... f5 idea.} ({After} 14... f5 $6 15. Nd5 $1 Bd7 16. h4 $1 {White is better, and if} Kf7 $2 {then} 17. Nf4 $1) 15. h4 {White stops our advance, but now the g4 -square is weakened. 15.Nd5 h4 ! is the point. Black is a bit better now.} Be5 {We prepare ... f6 & ... Kf7 to connect our rooks.} 16. Nd5 f6 {Giving our king the f7 -square in order to connect the rooks.} 17. f4 Bb8 18. Bc3 Kf7 19. e4 Bg4 {Now, you can see how the g4 -square is useful for us, Black is a bit better as we will play ... Rhd8 next.} *

