1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. e4 {This is the setup known as the Botvinnik English. White wants to play Nge2 , O-O , & d3 next and try to attack us with a future f4 - f5 pawn push.   However, I believe it's a bit slow and will recommend you a simple yet aggressive plan based on the early ... a6 & b5 pawn sacrifice.} ({I have also recommended this setup in my HAD course (} 5. e4 {c5 c4 move order will reach this position).}) 5... a6 {A rare move that many White players underestimate and answer with the autopilot Nge2 .} 6. a4 {A solid choice, stopping ... b5 . However, now White is saddled with two glaring weaknesses: the d4 & b4 holes.} d6 ({I'm sticking with this standard Dragon structure throughout my course. But also strong is the} 6... e6 {and ... Nge7 setup.}) 7. Nge2 Bg4 {I prefer to ask White a question with this move. Shall you venture to play the weakening f3 / h3 or allow the annoying pin, my good sir?} 8. h3 Bxe2 {Black's strategic aim is to win the d4 -outpost, thus trading the bishop for the knight is a good idea!} 9. Nxe2 Nf6 (9... e6 {is also quite strong:} 10. O-O Nge7 11. d3 Rb8 12. Rb1 b5 $1) 10. O-O Nd7 11. d3 Nf8 {An interesting idea to fight for the d4 -outpost via e6 .} 12. f4 Ne6 13. f5 Ned4 {Black controls all the key dark squares and stands better. White has no clear plan. We have moved our knight 5 times in a row!. Normally, this would be against all opening principles, but here the position is closed. Thus, winning the key outpost justifies our plan.} *

