1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. e4 {This is the setup known as the Botvinnik English. White wants to play Nge2 , O-O , & d3 next and try to attack us with a future f4 - f5 pawn push.   However, I believe it's a bit slow and will recommend you a simple yet aggressive plan based on the early ... a6 & b5 pawn sacrifice.} ({I have also recommended this setup in my HAD course (} 5. e4 {c5 c4 move order will reach this position).}) 5... a6 {A rare move that many White players underestimate and answer with the autopilot Nge2 .} 6. Nge2 b5 {The point! Black happily sacrifices the pawn and gets huge Benko-style counterplay.} 7. d3 {Perhaps this is best.} Rb8 8. O-O b4 {Black's natural plan in the Dragon structure!} 9. Nd5 d6 {A natural novelty to open up the c8 -bishop.} 10. f4 Bg4 {An instructive moment: Black happily trades the bishop for e2 -knight winning the d4 -outpost.} 11. h3 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 e6 13. Ne3 Nge7 {Black has a nice flexible structure with long-term control of the d4 outpost.} *

