1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. e4 {This is the setup known as the Botvinnik English. White wants to play Nge2 , O-O , & d3 next and try to attack us with a future f4 - f5 pawn push.   However, I believe it's a bit slow and will recommend you a simple yet aggressive plan based on the early ... a6 & b5 pawn sacrifice.} ({I have also recommended this setup in my HAD course (} 5. e4 {c5 c4 move order will reach this position).}) 5... a6 {A rare move that many White players underestimate and answer with the autopilot Nge2 .} 6. Nge2 b5 {The point! Black happily sacrifices the pawn and gets huge Benko-style counterplay.} 7. cxb5 axb5 8. Nxb5 Ba6 9. Nbc3 {The most common move, but Black is actually better!} Nb4 {Now you can see the point of the pawn sac. Black takes control over d3 -square with some serious threats.} (9... h5 $5 {is strong as well} 10. O-O h4 {with a big attack.}) 10. O-O Bd3 {Creating total paralysis of the queenside. White's only move to free himself is...} 11. a3 Bc2 12. Qe1 Nd3 {Winning the queen.} *

