1. Nf3 {In this chapter we will cover the Reti opening where White goes for the immediate kingside fianchetto with 2. g3 , 3. Bg2 , and 4. O-O .} c5 2. g3 ({After} 2. c4 g6 {we transpose to the English lines.}) 2... g6 {We also fianchetto our bishop.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O Nc6 5. d3 {White still has a choice to go for 6. e4 or 6. c4 plans.} d6 {We also achieved our Dragon setup and wait for White to show us their plan.} 6. c4 {White goes for the symmetry. However, we don't have to mirror White's setup, and I will show you a simple plan based on a double fianchetto.} e6 {First, we develop the knight to e7 .} 7. Nc3 Nge7 8. Bd2 {White is about to execute the standard queenside expansion with a3 , Rb1 and b4 .} b6 {Remember this key idea! We are about to play ... Bb7 with a rock-solid structure.} 9. a3 Bb7 10. Rb1 O-O 11. b4 Qd7 {We've reached an even game with lots of fight still ahead. Notice that White can't really make progress on the queenside.} ({If they play bxc5 we take back with the d-pawn, . If they push the pawn with} 11... b5 {, we play} 12. Nd4 $1 {Black has a plan of kingside expansion with ... h6 & ... f5 .}) *

