1. Nf3 {In this chapter we will cover the Reti opening where White goes for the immediate kingside fianchetto with 2. g3 , 3. Bg2 , and 4. O-O .} c5 2. g3 ({After} 2. c4 g6 {we transpose to the English lines.}) 2... g6 {We also fianchetto our bishop.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O Nc6 5. d3 {White still has a choice to go for 6. e4 or 6. c4 plans.} d6 {We also achieved our Dragon setup and wait for White to show us their plan.} 6. e4 {This approach takes the game into the King's Indian Attack (KIA) or the Closed Sicilian territory. If you already studied my HAD course, you know what to do: we finish development with ... Nf6 & ... O-O and start playing on the queenside with ... Rb8 and ... b5 . Remember the basic rule of thumb when coming up with a plan: The Dragon swings with his tail!} Nf6 {We continue to develop the kingside. White typically fights for the center with c3 , Re1 & d4 or goes 7. Nbd2 .} 7. c3 {White aims to play 8.Re1 & d4 next.} O-O 8. Re1 {White is ready to play for d4 .} e5 {An important idea to remember! We need to be aware of White's plan and prepare for it.} ({Please note that} 8... Rb8 {is still playable, but allows .}) 9. Nbd2 Rb8 {We still continue with the Dragon tail swing plan.} 10. Nc4 b5 11. Ne3 a5 {Grabbing more space.} 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 Ne7 {Black is already better as we can play on both wings now. White's central d4 -pawn push still doesn't work.} 14. d4 exd4 15. cxd4 c4 {Black has a big initiative on the queenside while White is stuck with a weak d5 -pawn.} *

