1. Nf3 c5 2. b3 {This combo of Nf3 & b3 is a aimed to stop our plan of ... g6 . However, I will show you a cool idea where we still get to fianchetto our bishop.} Nc6 3. Bb2 Nf6 {We don't mind the trade on f6 as it would give us two powerful bishops.} 4. g3 {White goes for the double fianchetto, but gives us central control.} d5 {We grab the center of course! Please note that we still don't mind the trade on f6 , as we will capture ... exf6 .} 5. Bg2 Qc7 {I like this quiet queen move, preparing a center push ... e5 .} 6. O-O e5 ({We have won the battle for the center, and White has a bad version of the reversed King's Indian Defense as the bishop on b2 is quite passive and at risk of being locked up after} 6... c4 7. d4 $1) 7. d3 Be7 {We continue with natural development.} 8. Nbd2 (8. c4 {is always met with} d4 $1 {locking up the b2 -bishop.}) 8... Be6 {We provoke Ng5 . Please note that we can also castle or play ... h6 .} 9. Ng5 Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 {The point. Now it's hard for White to get their e-pawn moving. Let's see what happens when they drive our bishop away.} 11. g4 Bg6 12. e3 h5 {And now White is probably lost! We will castle long and open up the kingside for a deadly attack. The engine already gives a -3 advantage to Black!} *

