1. Nf3 c5 2. b3 {This combo of Nf3 & b3 is a aimed to stop our plan of ... g6 . However, I will show you a cool idea where we still get to fianchetto our bishop.} Nc6 3. Bb2 Nf6 {We don't mind the trade on f6 as it would give us two powerful bishops.} 4. Bxf6 exf6 {We've seen this idea from Trompowsky. We take away from the center to open up our f8 -bishop.} 5. c4 {If White doesn't play 5. c4 , we answer with ... d5 anyway!} d5 {Opening up the game for our bishops.} 6. cxd5 Qxd5 7. Nc3 Qd6 {The queen is perfectly safe on d6 .} 8. e3 Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Rd8 {We keep an eye on White's backward d-pawn.} 11. Rc1 f5 {We grab more central space and aim to use our two bishops once the game opens up. White also has a clear weakness, the backward d-pawn.} 12. d4 cxd4 13. Nb5 {White uses a tactic to win back the pawn.} Qh6 14. Nbxd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 f4 {We break open the game and our bishops come to life. Black is slightly better in the resulting middlegame.} *

