1. Nf3 c5 2. b3 {This combo of Nf3 & b3 is a aimed to stop our plan of ... g6 . However, I will show you a cool idea where we still get to fianchetto our bishop.} Nc6 3. Bb2 Nf6 {We don't mind the trade on f6 as it would give us two powerful bishops.} 4. e3 {This is the most common move. White prepares d4 and plans to play Be2 & O-O .} g6 {We still fianchetto our bishop! Again, we are not afraid of Bxf6 exf6 structures. GM Nakamura has played this line with White many times in blitz. He typically goes for Bxf6 or d4 plans. Let's take a look.} 5. Bxf6 exf6 {We get a powerful bishop pair and seek to open up the game.} 6. c3 ({Hikaru's choice in blitz. After} 6. c4 d5 $1 {we open up the game.}) 6... d5 7. d4 cxd4 {We don't mind create an IQP as our active bishops will get plenty of play. Plus, White will have a weak c3 -pawn after 8. Nxd4 .} 8. Nxd4 Bd6 ({This is a nice improvement over Nakamura-Giri, 2024 Titled Tuesday blitz game, where Black played} 8... Bg7 {. I believe the bishop is much better placed on d6 .}) 9. Bb5 Bd7 10. O-O O-O {Black is first to finish development. As I mentioned, the bishop pair is so strong than they compensate for our weakened pawn structure. Plus, we set up a small trap after White's natural move 11. Nd2 .} 11. Nd2 Nxd4 12. Bxd7 Nxb3 {The key intermezzo! Now we win a pawn.} 13. Nxb3 Qxd7 {Black is simply a pawn up since White can't take on d5 due to a ... Bxh2 + discovery tactic.} *

