1. Nf3 c5 2. b3 {This combo of Nf3 & b3 is a aimed to stop our plan of ... g6 . However, I will show you a cool idea where we still get to fianchetto our bishop.} Nc6 3. Bb2 Nf6 {We don't mind the trade on f6 as it would give us two powerful bishops.} 4. e3 {This is the most common move. White prepares d4 and plans to play Be2 & O-O .} g6 {We still fianchetto our bishop! Again, we are not afraid of Bxf6 exf6 structures. GM Nakamura has played this line with White many times in blitz. He typically goes for Bxf6 or d4 plans. Let's take a look.} 5. d4 {This is probably White's best, they fight for the center.} cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {This is ideal structure for Black. Our d-pawn is both fighting for the center and keeps the b2 -bishop locked up. The game may continue:} 7. Bb5 Bg7 8. Ne5 {White's attack on our c6 -knight is easy to deal with.} Qc7 {The simplest, but 8... O-O !? sacrificing a pawn is quite interesting as well.} 9. O-O O-O {Here, we set up a small trap against the natural 10.Nd2.} 10. Nd2 ({White falls for our trap! Better is} 10. Re1 Bf5 {with a complex game, where I believe Black will dominate on the queenside.}) 10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 Ng4 ({And White is losing the e5-pawn after Nf3 Nxe5 . Please note that f4? is even worse after} 11... Qc5 {& ... Qxb5 .}) *

