1. Nc3 {I believe this is called the Dunst or the Van Geet opening.} d5 {The most natural and strongest move. Please note that we can transpose to the Jobava London after 2.d4 Nf6 3.Bf4 a6 ! covered here.} 2. e4 {This is White's most common move. They provoke ... d4 .} d4 {Why not grab more space with a tempo? White's knight is getting ready for some serious hopping.} 3. Nce2 e5 4. Ng3 {White opens up the f1 -bishop, which plans to go to c4 . However, the knight has already moved 3 times in the opening!} Be6 {Simple chess. We develop our bishop and deny White's LSB the c4 -square.} 5. Nf3 f6 {We build a powerful pawn chain that will restrict White's counterplay.} 6. d3 {This admits that White's opening didn't go as planned. Black can continue with natural development.} g6 7. Be2 c5 8. h4 h5 {It's important to stop White from playing h5 .} 9. c3 Nc6 10. O-O Nh6 {I like the simple idea of the knight getting g4 or f7 . For now, our goal is to restrict White and stop any counterplay and eventually slowly squeeze them as their pieces are running out of moves.} 11. a3 a5 {We stop b4 .} 12. cxd4 cxd4 13. Bd2 a4 {Now, Black enjoys total domination on both wings as White has no pawn breaks.} *

