1. Nc3 {I believe this is called the Dunst or the Van Geet opening.} d5 {The most natural and strongest move. Please note that we can transpose to the Jobava London after 2.d4 Nf6 3.Bf4 a6 ! covered here.} 2. e4 {This is White's most common move. They provoke ... d4 .} d4 {Why not grab more space with a tempo? White's knight is getting ready for some serious hopping.} 3. Nce2 e5 4. Ng3 {White opens up the f1 -bishop, which plans to go to c4 . However, the knight has already moved 3 times in the opening!} Be6 {Simple chess. We develop our bishop and deny White's LSB the c4 -square.} 5. Nf3 f6 {We build a powerful pawn chain that will restrict White's counterplay.} 6. Bb5+ c6 7. Ba4 {White hopes to challenge our bishop with Bb3 next in order to fight for the light squares.} Nd7 8. Bb3 Nc5 {Our knight is getting ready to recapture on e6 .} 9. Bxe6 Nxe6 10. d3 {White has achieved a favorable trade of LSB, but their position still lacks space. Let me show you an aggressive setup to attack White on the kingside.} Qd7 {We plan to castle long in this game!} 11. O-O O-O-O 12. a4 h5 {It's clear that Black's attack is faster. Here's one possible line:} 13. a5 h4 14. Ne2 g5 (14... h3 {is more positional and works too.}) 15. a6 b6 {We just lock up the queenside.} 16. h3 Nh6 {We will prepare ... g4 eventually and blow open White's kingside.} *

