1. a3 {This is called the Anderssen's Opening, named after the famous Adolf Anderssen who played it 3 times vs Paul Morphy in 1858 match.} {These days it's an attempt to sidestep the opening theory and to get Black into some sort of reversed Sicilian after e5 . (However, we need to stick to our game plan and play on the dark squares. That's why I recommend 1... c5 .) If White allows, we will play 2... g6 , ... Bg7 etc. similar to our setup vs the English.} c5 {Of course, Black has many good moves such as 1... e5 and 2... d5 , but we also fight for the center and aim to invite White back into the Symmetrical English after:} ({c4} 1... g6 2. g3 Bg7 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. Nc3 b6 {covered in this chapter .}) 2. b4 {This is the logical follow-up of a3 .} ({Please note that} 2. e4 g6 {transposes to my HAD course.}) 2... Nc6 {I like this rare move! We attack b4 and happily sacrifice our c5 -pawn.} 3. bxc5 e5 {Now the e5 -pawn will fall.} 4. e3 Bxc5 {We develop with a tempo.} 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. d4 {White's center grab is only an illusion of control. In reality, they have serious structural weaknesses.} exd4 7. exd4 Bb6 8. Be2 (8. d5 {is met with} Ne4 $1) 8... d5 {We stabilize the center.} 9. O-O O-O 10. Bb2 Bg4 {Our rooks will enter the game with ... Re8 and ... Rc8 with a nice edge. White's structure is quite weak.} *

