1. a3 {This is called the Anderssen's Opening, named after the famous Adolf Anderssen who played it 3 times vs Paul Morphy in 1858 match.} {These days it's an attempt to sidestep the opening theory and to get Black into some sort of reversed Sicilian after e5 . (However, we need to stick to our game plan and play on the dark squares. That's why I recommend 1... c5 .) If White allows, we will play 2... g6 , ... Bg7 etc. similar to our setup vs the English.} c5 {Of course, Black has many good moves such as 1... e5 and 2... d5 , but we also fight for the center and aim to invite White back into the Symmetrical English after:} ({c4} 1... g6 2. g3 Bg7 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. Nc3 b6 {covered in this chapter .}) 2. b4 {This is the logical follow-up of a3 .} ({Please note that} 2. e4 g6 {transposes to my HAD course.}) 2... Nc6 {I like this rare move! We attack b4 and happily sacrifice our c5 -pawn.} 3. b5 {White tries to use the tempo to gain more space.} Na5 {Our knight is temporarily out of the game, but don't worry it will come back via c4 or b6 . In the meantime, White's queenside is quite weak.} 4. Nf3 d5 {We grab more space in the center.} 5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2 g6 {Our bishop is aiming for g7 to fight for the long diagonal.} 7. O-O Bg7 8. d3 (8. Bb2 {again runs into} Nc4 $1) 8... O-O 9. Bb2 b6 {We go for the double fianchetto. It's an easy plan to remember as it's similar to one of our plans vs the Symmetrical English with an early a3 move.} 10. Nbd2 Bb7 {Black's space advantage and fluid development should give us a small edge. While our knight on a5 doesn't have any moves, it actually plays an important role on stabilizing the queenside.} *

