1. h3 {This is called the Clemenz Opening. I guess White is trying to play the improved Grob with 2. g4 next. The most important part now is... to allow it, of course!} Nf6 {We give White a chance to play a sensible move like d4 next, which would lead to normal openings up a tempo for us. It's rare that h3 is a useful move in closed openings.} 2. g4 {White plays the improved Grob!} d5 ({We can also play} 2... e5 {, but this is simple and strong: we put our pawn in the center.}) 3. Bg2 e5 {When given a chance, it's always a good idea to grab the center with d5 & e5 .} 4. c4 {White plays in the English style.} d4 ({We grab more space and get a good version of the reversed Benoni. Please note that} 4... dxc4 {is fine as well.}) 5. d3 Nc6 {We are never worried about Bxc6 as after ... dxc6 , White's kingside is too weak.} 6. a3 a5 {This is a thematic move to stop the Benoni b4 expansion.} 7. Nd2 Be7 {We are not worried about g5 and go for rapid development.} 8. g5 Nh5 {The knight is well-placed here as it controls f4 .} 9. Ne4 O-O {We will prepare ... f5 next and will take over the kingside. White doesn't really have any counterplay and just has to sit back and wait for us to execute our plan. Black is clearly better.} *

