1. h3 {This is called the Clemenz Opening. I guess White is trying to play the improved Grob with 2. g4 next. The most important part now is... to allow it, of course!} Nf6 {We give White a chance to play a sensible move like d4 next, which would lead to normal openings up a tempo for us. It's rare that h3 is a useful move in closed openings.} 2. g4 {White plays the improved Grob!} d5 ({We can also play} 2... e5 {, but this is simple and strong: we put our pawn in the center.}) 3. Bg2 e5 {When given a chance, it's always a good idea to grab the center with d5 & e5 .} 4. d4 {This was played several times by a Ukrainian GM Vovk.} exd4 {This is even stronger than ... e4} 5. Qxd4 Nc6 {We develop with a tempo.} 6. Qa4 Bd7 {We continue development while making White's queen uncomfortable.} 7. g5 Ne4 8. Bxe4 {It seems as though White wins a win, but...} b5 {The killer intermezzo. Now, White's position is collapsing.} 9. Qxb5 Nb4 {The key follow-up.} 10. Qa5 dxe4 {Now c2 -pawn hangs.} 11. Na3 Bd6 {Black's rapid development gives us a big edge. The engine gives us -2 already. Just take a look at how pathetic White's kingside is. We will complete development with ... O-O next and overwhelm White in the middlegame.} *

