1. e3 {This rare first move doesn't really have any deep ideas and usually transposes to 1. Nf3 & 2. b3  chapter or to 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 chapter. Let's try to cover other White tries here.} c5 ({We invite White to play d4 and transpose to the Colle with} 1... Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 {etc.}) 2. b3 {We have examined these ideas after 1. Nf3 , but let's focus on lines where White doesn't develop the knight early.} Nc6 3. Bb2 Nf6 {We don't mind the trade on f6 as after ... exf6 Black's bishop pair will dominate.} 4. f4 ({Please note that} 4. Nf3 g6 {is good for us.}) 4... d6 {We plan to go for the Dragon setup with ... g6 next.} 5. Nf3 (5. Bb5 {is met with .}) 5... g6 {We prepare the fianchetto} 6. Bxf6 {White's last attempt to ruin our pawn structure before we play ... Bg7 .} exf6 7. c4 d5 ({We open up the game.} 7... Bg7 {is quite good too.}) 8. cxd5 Qxd5 9. Nc3 Qd8 10. Bb5 Bd7 11. O-O Be7 {The bishop is better placed on e7 where it has more room.} 12. Rc1 O-O {Both sides have finished development and I believe the bishop pair should give us a small edge.} *

