1. e3 {This rare first move doesn't really have any deep ideas and usually transposes to 1. Nf3 & 2. b3  chapter or to 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 chapter. Let's try to cover other White tries here.} c5 ({We invite White to play d4 and transpose to the Colle with} 1... Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 {etc.}) 2. b3 {We have examined these ideas after 1. Nf3 , but let's focus on lines where White doesn't develop the knight early.} Nc6 3. Bb2 Nf6 {We don't mind the trade on f6 as after ... exf6 Black's bishop pair will dominate.} 4. f4 ({Please note that} 4. Nf3 g6 {is good for us.}) 4... d6 {We plan to go for the Dragon setup with ... g6 next.} 5. Nf3 (5. Bb5 {is met with .}) 5... g6 {We prepare the fianchetto} 6. Bb5 Bd7 {We don't allow White to double our pawns with Bxc6 .} 7. O-O Bg7 8. d3 O-O {Black is first to finish development and we setup a nasty trap if White plays a natural Nbd2?} 9. Nbd2 {White falls into our trap!} Nd5 {The key move!} 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 {And now it's clear that White has to make some concessions due to ... Nxe3 and ... Nc3 fork threats.} 11. Bxc6 Nxe3 {A nice intermezzo!} 12. Qe2 Nxf1 13. Bxd7 Nxd2 14. Qxd2 Qxd7 {The dust has settled and Black is up an exchange and a pawn with an easy win.} *

