1. c3 {This is not a serious opening as it will likely transpose to the London or to the Colle Openings.} Nf6 2. d4 e6 3. Bg5 {This is the most common move, White is playing like the Torre Attack but without the inclusion of Nf3 .} (3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Be7 {this transposes to the London System .}) 3... c5 {Our standard reaction against the London/Torre.} 4. e3 h6 {Always a useful move, asking the bishop a question.} 5. Bxf6 Qxf6 6. Nd2 d5 {Remember, we are never afraid to play the London System when White trades his DSB. Black's bishop pair will eventually take over.} 7. Ngf3 Nc6 8. Bd3 Bd6 9. O-O O-O 10. Qe2 g5 {An ambitious space grab on the kingside! This is totally justified as we have more space and the bishop pair.} 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. e4 Bd7 13. h3 Qg7 14. Rae1 Bb6 {White ran out of useful moves and will either take on d5 or push e5 .} 15. e5 f6 {We open up the f-file.} 16. exf6 Rxf6 {Black will apply pressure on the f-file and f2 -square is extremely weak. White doesn't have any counterplay and clearly stands worse.} *

