1. c3 {This is not a serious opening as it will likely transpose to the London or to the Colle Openings.} Nf6 2. d4 e6 3. Bg5 {This is the most common move, White is playing like the Torre Attack but without the inclusion of Nf3 .} (3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Be7 {this transposes to the London System .}) 3... c5 {Our standard reaction against the London/Torre.} 4. e3 h6 {Always a useful move, asking the bishop a question.} 5. Bh4 Qb6 {Let's take advantage of White's early bishop sortie and attack b2 .} ({Black can of course play normally with} 5... Be7 {with similar play as in our Torre Attack chapter.}) 6. Qb3 {We generally don't want to trade on b3 as it improves White's structure.} Nc6 7. Nd2 d5 {We grab more central space. Please note that we are not worried about doubled pawns after Bxf6 ... gxf6 since our bishops will rule the board.} 8. Ngf3 Bd7 9. Be2 Be7 10. O-O g5 {Black has many moves that maintain solid equilibrium, but I like this approach going after the bishop pair.} 11. Bg3 Nh5 12. dxc5 {Probably White should simplify.} Bxc5 13. Be5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Nf6 15. Nxd7 Nxd7 {The presence of opposite-color bishops make this position drawish, but I believe there's still plenty of fight left.} *

