1. g3 {This could transpose to our Symmetrical English chapter, but here I will cover the double fianchetto setup by White known as the reversed Hippo.} c5 ({We invite White into the Symmetrical English after c4} 1... g6 {, or the Closed Sicilian after} 2. e4 {g6 covered in my HAD course.}) 2. Bg2 Nc6 3. b3 {White gives up the center and goes for the double fianchetto.} d5 4. Bb2 e5 {Of course, given the opportunity we grab the center.} 5. e3 {White wants to play Ne2 , d3 , Nd2 going for the 'Hippo' setup.} h5 {I like this most aggressive approach! We plan to meet Ne2 with ... h4 !} 6. Ne2 h4 {Our Harry the h-pawn is making it hard for White to castle kingside now.} 7. d3 Nge7 ({We keep our options open with this move, but immediate} 7... h3 {is also strong, after} 8. Bf3 Be6 {, we will follow up with Qd7 with a positional clamp.}) 8. Nd2 Be6 9. e4 {This allows us a thematic reversed KID clamp.} h3 10. Bf3 d4 {Black has a big space advantage while White's bishop pair is totally blocked now.} 11. O-O Qd7 12. Bh1 g5 {A nice prophylactic move against f4 .} 13. f4 {This is suicidal for White.} gxf4 14. gxf4 Rg8+ 15. Ng3 exf4 16. Rxf4 Bh6 {It's over as White is losing material due to ... Be3 +.} *

