1. g3 {This could transpose to our Symmetrical English chapter, but here I will cover the double fianchetto setup by White known as the reversed Hippo.} c5 ({We invite White into the Symmetrical English after c4} 1... g6 {, or the Closed Sicilian after} 2. e4 {g6 covered in my HAD course.}) 2. Bg2 Nc6 3. b3 {White gives up the center and goes for the double fianchetto.} d5 4. Bb2 e5 {Of course, given the opportunity we grab the center.} 5. e3 {White wants to play Ne2 , d3 , Nd2 going for the 'Hippo' setup.} h5 {I like this most aggressive approach! We plan to meet Ne2 with ... h4 !} 6. Ne2 h4 {Our Harry the h-pawn is making it hard for White to castle kingside now.} 7. d3 Nge7 ({We keep our options open with this move, but immediate} 7... h3 {is also strong, after} 8. Bf3 Be6 {, we will follow up with Qd7 with a positional clamp.}) 8. Nd2 Be6 9. a3 {White's typical waiting more in such setups.} Qd7 ({White is running out of moves. If they play O-O they are getting mated with} 9... hxg3 {& ... Bh3 in a classic attack.}) 10. c4 d4 {The simplest. Now, we have a good reversed Benoni setup with a bad bishop on b2 .} 11. exd4 exd4 (11... cxd4 {would allow} 12. b4 {, but even there Black is better.}) 12. Nf4 Bg4 13. f3 Bf5 14. Ne4 O-O-O {Black happily sacrifices the c5 -pawn for initiative.} ({Nxc5} 14... Qc7 {Ne4 g5!} 15. Ng5 {Bh6 Ne4} hxg3 16. hxg3 {Bxf4 gxf4} Rxh1+ 17. Bxh1 {Rh8 Bg2} Ng6 {With a big attack.}) *

