1. g3 {This could transpose to our Symmetrical English chapter, but here I will cover the double fianchetto setup by White known as the reversed Hippo.} c5 ({We invite White into the Symmetrical English after c4} 1... g6 {, or the Closed Sicilian after} 2. e4 {g6 covered in my HAD course.}) 2. Bg2 Nc6 3. b3 {White gives up the center and goes for the double fianchetto.} d5 4. Bb2 e5 {Of course, given the opportunity we grab the center.} 5. e3 {White wants to play Ne2 , d3 , Nd2 going for the 'Hippo' setup.} h5 {I like this most aggressive approach! We plan to meet Ne2 with ... h4 !} 6. h3 {A standard reaction to meet ... h4 with g4 .} h4 7. g4 f5 {We blow open the game, knowing that resulting complications favor Black as we have more space.} 8. gxf5 Bxf5 9. d3 Nf6 10. Nd2 Qe7 ({This is even stronger than} 10... Qd7 {as we protect the e5 -pawn in case of N1f3 .}) 11. Ne2 O-O-O {Black is first to castle and enjoys a nice space advantage. We will attack White's king next with a timely ... e4 or ... d4 push, or expand with ... g5 .} *

