1. g4 {The Grob Attack! It was invented by the Swiss International Master Henri Grob (1904–1974). Later, it was picked up by the English International Master Michael Basman with some success.   These days it's known to be quite unsound. White is daring Black: either refute the opening or lose trying and make one for the lolz! Now that you bought my course, hopefully moves such as 1. g4 will bring a smile to your face as I present you the simple refutation.} d5 {Simple chess! Black takes control over the center and attacks the g4 -pawn.} 2. Bg2 {White gambits the g4 -pawn, hoping for rapid development and quick use of the long a8 - h1 diagonal.} (2. f3 $2 {this was seen at GM level and White lost the game in 5 moves, after} e5 3. d3 Qh4+ 4. Kd2 h5 5. h3 hxg4 {and Black resigned in Hou Yifan -Lalith, B Caleta, 2017.  You may wonder, did the former Women's World Champion have a bad day? The answer is actually quite simple: this is her protest game against the organizers after she was paired in 7 out of 9 games vs women in a big open tournament with lots of men! An interesting way to get your message across...}) (2. h3 {just gives away all central control} e5 {and Black will have all the fun with two central pawns.}) 2... Bxg4 {Of course, we take the free pawn!} 3. c4 {The point. Now that the bishop is lured away from c8 , you can see that both b7 & d5 are quite weak.} c6 {Simple chess. Black just supports the key d5 -pawn.} 4. Qb3 {Played by GMs Hikaru Nakamura vs Mamedyarov.} Nf6 {Black happily sacrifices the b7 -pawn for initiative.} (4... e6 $1 5. Qxb7 Nd7 {is also quite strong.}) 5. Qxb7 {White's most popular move, taking the challenge!} Nbd7 {Black develops, offering another pawn.} 6. Qxc6 {This is one pawn too many for White as yet another tempo is given to Black for free.} Rc8 {The rook enters the fight with a lot of juicy targets on the c-file.} 7. Qa4 (7. Qb5 Rxc4 8. Nc3 e6 {with a big initiative for Black}) 7... Rxc4 {A simple double attack.} 8. Qd1 {A sad but necessary retreat as the bishop on c1 was also hit.} Ne5 {Setting up a cool trick, but pretty much any developing move gives Black a big edge.} 9. d3 (9. h3 Nd3+ $1 {same idea!}) 9... Nxd3+ {The shocker! White is totally lost now.} 10. Qxd3 Rxc1+ {Believe it or not but all of this happened in a correspondence game in 1986! (Rabold, H - Forster, D).} 11. Kd2 Qc8 {White is dead lost as Black dominates the back rank.} *

