1. f4 {This is the Bird's Opening. White plays in the spirit of the reversed Dutch.} d5 ({We can start with} 1... g6 {as recommended in the original book, since} 2. e4 c5 {transposes to our favorite Sicilian. But most people will react to g6 with} 3. Nf3 {and} d5 {will just transpose.}) 2. Nf3 g6 {The fianchetto plan is the most effective weapon vs various reversed Dutch formations.} {Now, White can choose between g3 aiming for reversed Leningrad Dutch or e3 with a Stonewall setup after d4 and c3 .} 3. g3 {White plans to fianchetto the bishop, playing the Leningrad Dutch with reversed colors. Typically, the extra tempo in closed structures is insignificant for gaining an opening advantage.} Bg7 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. O-O O-O 6. d3 Re8 {This is a very rare move with idea to prepare an eventual ... e5 break after ... Nbd7 . It's also a bit of a waiting move, to see how White proceeds next.} ({The immediate} 6... Nbd7 {is playable, but after} 7. Nc3 {we no longer have the option of ... d4 !}) ({Whereas now Nc3?! is met with} 6... d4 $1) 7. c3 Nbd7 8. Ne5 {White stops our ... e5 idea.} c6 {A clever waiting move. We set up a trap in case White plays the natural Nbd2 next.} 9. Nd2 {This allows our main idea!} Nxe5 10. fxe5 Ng4 {And due to many threats, the e5 -pawn will now fall.} *

