1. f4 {This is the Bird's Opening. White plays in the spirit of the reversed Dutch.} d5 ({We can start with} 1... g6 {as recommended in the original book, since} 2. e4 c5 {transposes to our favorite Sicilian. But most people will react to g6 with} 3. Nf3 {and} d5 {will just transpose.}) 2. Nf3 g6 {The fianchetto plan is the most effective weapon vs various reversed Dutch formations.} {Now, White can choose between g3 aiming for reversed Leningrad Dutch or e3 with a Stonewall setup after d4 and c3 .} 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 {This is a bit of a passive approach. White goes for rapid development but gives up the center.} c5 {We take up more central space.} 5. O-O Nc6 6. d3 Nf6 {We continue with natural development.} 7. Qe1 {White's most popular move, preparing Qh4 . But I have good news for you: we can just ignore this pseudo-attack!} O-O 8. Qh4 {White transferred the queen over but has zero threats.} b5 {Let's get ambitious and take more space on the queenside.} 9. Nbd2 Qb6 {Creating a nice X-ray on White's king.} 10. Kh1 c4 ({Black is enjoying a nice space advantage. The game many continue: e4} 10... a5 {e5 Ng4! The knight is ready to jump to e3} 11. Ng5 {Nh6! Black can play ... h5 as well, but this is quite strong too. We will kick the knight with ... f6 next and get our knight to f5 with a nice edge.}) *

