1. b3 {This is the Larsen's Opening where White tries to delay the fight for the center and fianchetto the dark-squared bishop. I recommend an idea based on the central strategy 1... e5 but with a twist: we plan to sacrifice our central pawn for the bishop pair later.} e5 {We fight for the center from move one!} 2. Bb2 Nc6 {We develop our knight and defend the pawn, aiming to take over the center with ... d5 next. Here, White has two approaches:} ({e3 with the idea to meet} 2... d5 {with a Bb5 pin. This is the main line.}) {Or, c4 trying to get the game into English territory.} 3. c4 {White stops ... d5 and takes in the game into the English territory.} Nge7 ({I believe this is a better square for our knight than f6 as we prepare a tricky central pawn sacrifice after Nf3} 3... d5 $1 {This is similar to the main lines.}) 4. Nf3 d5 {We offer White the central e5 -pawn.} 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nxe5 Nxe5 7. Bxe5 {White has won the central pawn, but now we use the e-file to create tactical threats.} Qe7 8. Bb2 Nb4 {Creating a not-so-subtle threat of ... Nd3 mate.} 9. d3 Bf5 {We renew our threat.} 10. e4 O-O-O ({Black has a great attack, for example: Nd2} 10... Bg6 {Qb1 f5!∓ .}) *

