1. b3 {This is the Larsen's Opening where White tries to delay the fight for the center and fianchetto the dark-squared bishop. I recommend an idea based on the central strategy 1... e5 but with a twist: we plan to sacrifice our central pawn for the bishop pair later.} e5 {We fight for the center from move one!} 2. Bb2 Nc6 {We develop our knight and defend the pawn, aiming to take over the center with ... d5 next. Here, White has two approaches:} ({e3 with the idea to meet} 2... d5 {with a Bb5 pin. This is the main line.}) {Or, c4 trying to get the game into English territory.} 3. c4 {White stops ... d5 and takes in the game into the English territory.} Nge7 ({I believe this is a better square for our knight than f6 as we prepare a tricky central pawn sacrifice after Nf3} 3... d5 $1 {This is similar to the main lines.}) 4. Nf3 d5 {We offer White the central e5 -pawn.} 5. Nxe5 {White takes the bait!} Nxe5 6. Bxe5 d4 {The point! Since our knight is on e7 , White doesn't have the option of playing Bxf6 , and we are about to play ... Nc6 next. The ideas are very similar to our main lines with 4... Nge7 !.} 7. e3 Nc6 8. Bg3 h5 {We continue the chase!} 9. h4 Qf6 {We create a deadly threat of ... dxe3 as White's rook is unprotected.} 10. Qf3 Qg6 {We avoid the queen trade and get ready to develop our bishop.} 11. Be2 Bg4 {We will keep chasing the queen with a big attack! The engine already gives us -2 advantage!} *

