1. b3 {This is the Larsen's Opening where White tries to delay the fight for the center and fianchetto the dark-squared bishop. I recommend an idea based on the central strategy 1... e5 but with a twist: we plan to sacrifice our central pawn for the bishop pair later.} e5 {We fight for the center from move one!} 2. Bb2 Nc6 {We develop our knight and defend the pawn, aiming to take over the center with ... d5 next. Here, White has two approaches:} ({e3 with the idea to meet} 2... d5 {with a Bb5 pin. This is the main line.}) {Or, c4 trying to get the game into English territory.} 3. c4 {White stops ... d5 and takes in the game into the English territory.} Nge7 ({I believe this is a better square for our knight than f6 as we prepare a tricky central pawn sacrifice after Nf3} 3... d5 $1 {This is similar to the main lines.}) 4. e3 {This takes the game into a reversed Sicilian type of position.} d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. a3 {White stops ... Ndb4 & ... Nd3 jumps.} Be6 7. Qc2 Qd7 {We go for the most aggressive setup against the Sicilian known as the English Attack (with reversed colors of course).} 8. Nf3 f6 {Black solidifies the center and gets ready to castle long.} 9. b4 {A natural way to expand against our plan.} O-O-O {We still castle long.} 10. b5 Na5 {The knight is safe for now as Qa4 is met with .} 11. d4 e4 ({Remember this idea! White cannot take the pawn as it allows a huge attack with Qxe4} 11... Bf5 $1 {Qh4 g5! And the queen is likely to get trapped or White will lose a piece.}) 12. Nfd2 f5 {Black has achieved a stronghold in the center.} 13. Nc3 Nb6 {We avoid the trade and plan to continue development with ... Bd6 next. If you love to attack, you will enjoy this position!} *

