{We've reached a sharp position with opposite-side castling. I believe we have great counterplay due to the bishop pair and will meet f3 with f5 to preserve a strong pawn chain. White has to be careful as Ne2 will be met with the a-pawn storm.} 1. b3 {This is the Larsen's Opening where White tries to delay the fight for the center and fianchetto the dark-squared bishop. I recommend an idea based on the central strategy 1... e5 but with a twist: we plan to sacrifice our central pawn for the bishop pair later.} e5 {We fight for the center from move one!} 2. Bb2 Nc6 {We develop our knight and defend the pawn, aiming to take over the center with ... d5 next. Here, White has two approaches:} ({e3 with the idea to meet} 2... d5 {with a Bb5 pin. This is the main line.}) {Or, c4 trying to get the game into English territory.} 3. e3 {This is the main line. White wants to meet d5 with .} d5 {We grab the full control of the center.} 4. Bb5 {White creates a direct threat of Bxe5 , using the pin tactic.} Nge7 ({We 'fall' for White's trap! This idea was a shocking revelation to me a few years ago, when I started working with neural network engine, Leela. Now, it's a known concept and just as popular as the main line} 4... Bd6 {.}) 5. Nf3 {White doesn't take our pawn and prefers development.} e4 {We take advantage of this tempo move, grabbing more space in the center.} 6. Ne5 a6 {We break the pin and force White to trade on c6 .} 7. Nxc6 (7. Qh5 {will transpose after .}) 7... Nxc6 {There's no need to ruin our structure yet.} 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 {White doubled our pawns but also gave up the bishop pair.} 9. Qh5 Be6 10. Nc3 Bd6 {We take the opportunity to develop.} 11. O-O-O O-O *

