1. b4 {This is a rare move known as the Sokolsky or the Polish Opening.} e5 {Just like against the Larsen 1. b3 we take over the center.} 2. Bb2 Bxb4 {This is the major difference vs 1. b3 ,} ({we take the pawn as} 2... Nc6 {runs into .}) 3. Bxe5 {White hopes that the trade of the wing pawn for a central pawn will give the long-term chances. However, the problem is that White is losing too much time as Black's piece get developed very quickly.   In addition, White will need to waste a tempo with their e5 -bishop after the eventual ... Nc6 .} Nf6 4. Nf3 O-O 5. e3 d5 {We continue playing natural moves, taking over the center.} 6. Be2 c5 {We grab even more central space.} 7. O-O Nc6 {Now, we force White to spend any tempo as ... Nxe5 would give us the bishop pair advantage.} 8. Bb2 Re8 {We activate the rook.} 9. d3 Ba5 {Black has a pleasant edge. We will reroute the bishop to c7 to take aim at White's king and plan to gain even more space with ... d4 .} *

