1. b4 {This is a rare move known as the Sokolsky or the Polish Opening.} e5 {Just like against the Larsen 1. b3 we take over the center.} 2. Bb2 Bxb4 {This is the major difference vs 1. b3 ,} ({we take the pawn as} 2... Nc6 {runs into .}) 3. Bxe5 {White hopes that the trade of the wing pawn for a central pawn will give the long-term chances. However, the problem is that White is losing too much time as Black's piece get developed very quickly.   In addition, White will need to waste a tempo with their e5 -bishop after the eventual ... Nc6 .} Nf6 4. c3 {This is the modern way of playing for White. It has been tried by both Carlsen and Nakamura in blitz.} Be7 5. g3 {This was played a few times by Carlsen and some strong GMs. White plans to fianchetto his LSB and trade the bishop for the f6 -knight.} c5 {I prefer this rare move. We gain central control and plan to play ... d5 next.} 6. Bg2 d5 {We grab even more central space!} 7. e3 {White hopes to play Ne2 , Bxf6 , and d4 next.} Nbd7 {This is slightly better than ... Nc6 as we can recapture on f6 with the knight if needed.} 8. d4 O-O 9. Ne2 Ng4 {We go after the e5 -bishop and hope to open up the position for our bishops.} 10. Nf4 Ndxe5 ({Or} 10... Ngxe5 {.}) 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Qxd5 {This is White's only way to recapture in order to avoid being seriously worse.} Ng6 {We trade the knights, anticipating a good endgame.} 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Nd5 Rb8 ({The simplest. We get ready to play} 14... Be6 {next with a comfortable position for Black. If White takes on e7 , we will have superior pawn structure in the endgame.}) *

