{The best way to meet Nc3 is with direct d5! We don't mind the structure after e4 d4! Nce2 e5! Ng3 Be6 Nf3 f6! The pawn chain is very powerful and often we can castle queenside in order to launch the pawn storm on the kingside! a3 is best met with c5! and b4 with Nc6! If White grabs the pawn with play with ... e6 and ... Bxc5 , where White is left with a a terrible pawn structure. If White pushes with b5 we play Na5! The plan is quite simple: we grab the center and go for the double fianchetto. Don't worry about the knight on a5 , it controls some vital squares such as c4 & b3 and will help us stabilize. If White's aim with h3 is to prepare g4 , be our guest! We play natural moves like Nf6 and ... d5 and try to take over the center with ... e5 . The pseudo-attack with h3 & g4 can easily be ignored as it just loses time. In all cases Black get easy development and targets on the kingside. e3 c5 is most likely to transpose to 1.Nf3 & b3 or the Colle chapters. However, we examined what happens when White plays b3 and delays the knight development. In this case we go for the Dragon setup. We are never worried about Bxf6 after ... g6 , since we get the bishop pair with ... exf6 . If White goes for the normal development then remember a cool tactical trap after Nbd2? Nd5! White will lose. c3 is most likely to transpose to the London System or the Colle . We took a look Nf6 d4 e6 Bg5 , playing like the Torre Attack. I showed you a nice way to pose some problems for White with an early ... Qb6 !? idea, hitting b2 .   White has many ways to go wrong and give us a nice bishop pair after ... g5 & ... Nh5 ideas. If White plays the 'reversed Hippo' with g3 , Bg2 followed by b3 & Bb2 , we will grab all the center and play a thematic h-pawn push with h5! Remember, we would like to get our pawn to h4 and paralyze White on the kingside. We continue with natural development and prepare to castle long. Black enjoys a long-term initiative and prepares a deadly attack against White's king. The Bird Opening f4 is best met with d5 Nf3 g6 . Remember that the fianchetto plan is the best setup against various reversed Dutch formations.  If White goes for the reversed Leningrad Dutch with g3 then we develop naturally with Bg7 Bg2 Nf6 O-O O-O . Make sure to remember after d3 the rare and tricky move Re8! We will play ... Nbd7 & ... e5 next with excellent central play. If White goes for the reversed Stonewall with e3 Bg7 d4 then we play an unusual but strong Nh6! The point is that the knight is well-placed to support the bishop trade with ... Bf5 . Remember the strategic goal is to trade White's light-squared bishop. Against the Nimzo-Larsen Attack b3 I give you the most aggressive and cutting-edge theory, based on a long-term pawn sacrifice on e5 . We get two bishops and a big edge in development, which is quite fun to play. If White takes the game to English/Reversed Sicilian territory after e5 Bb2 Nc6 c4 , then we go for the most aggressive setup known as the English Attack with Be6 , Qd7 , f6 and castle long. If you love to attack, you will enjoy these lines! The Sokolsky or the Polish Opening b4 is met with a central e5! strike. We trade our e-pawn for the b-pawn and go for quick development. Often, we take more central space with ... c5 & ... d5 moves and get active piece play.} 1. Z0 *

