{This game perfectly illustrates black's strategy in the 6. Bg2 variation of Bogo-Indian. After taking control over the key square on the queenside, Black successfully unfolds a powerful attack on the kingside.   Notice the instructive value of the outpost on c5 as well as the powerful f7 - f5 pawn thrust.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 d6 8. O-O O-O 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Nb8 11. b4 a5 12. a3 Na6 13. Ne1 Bg4 {We force white to play f3 .} {Qb3? loses an exchange due to .} 14. f3 Bd7 15. Nd3 c6 16. bxa5 Qd8 17. Nb3 cxd5 18. cxd5 Bb5 {Up to here, we had been following the theory from our Bogo chapter . We pin the knight and plan to play ... Nfd7 and take over the c5 -outpost.} 19. Rf2 Nd7 20. Nb2 {White decides to preserve his knight, allowing Black to seize the initiative.} (20. Rb1 {Allows us to win the c5 -outpost.} Bxd3 21. Qxd3 Nac5 22. Nxc5 Nxc5 {Black's knight is a monster on c5 and we will win the a5 -pawn next.}) 20... Nac5 21. a4 Ba6 22. Bh3 g6 {Black now shifts his play on the kingside, preparing ... f5 thrust.} 23. Ra3 f5 24. exf5 gxf5 {White's pieces are lacking coordination, while Black's every piece is well-placed.} 25. Qd2 {White should start worrying about his king and not the a5 pawn. White had to play} (25. f4 {to slow down black's play on the kingside.}) 25... Rc8 {Also, 25... f4 ! is quite strong.} 26. Bf1 Kh8 {Preparing for the final assault.} 27. Bb5 Nf6 {All of Black's forces are mobilized.} 28. Nc1 f4 {Now White's position falls apart.} 29. Ne2 (29. gxf4 Nce4 $1 30. fxe4 Nxe4 31. Qd1 Nxf2 32. Kxf2 Rxf4+ {with a crushing attack} 33. Rf3 Qh4+) 29... Nce4 {The killer jump, we pry open White's king.} 30. fxe4 Nxe4 31. Qe1 Nxf2 32. Qxf2 fxg3 33. Qe1 (33. Qg2 Qxa5 {wins.}) 33... gxh2+ 34. Kxh2 (34. Kh1 {loses to} Rc2 35. Nd1 Qg5) 34... Rc2 35. Nd1 Qg5 {Now, it's all over as the attack is deadly.} 36. Re3 Bxb5 37. axb5 Rg8 38. Rg3 Rxe2+ *

