1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 d6 8. O-O e5 9. d5 Nb8 10. e4 a5 11. Ne1 O-O 12. Nd3 Na6 13. a3 Bg4 14. f3 Bd7 15. b4 c6 16. Qb3 cxd5 17. cxd5 axb4 18. axb4 Nc7 {Up to here, we have covered the theory in the Bogo 4.Bd2 & the 6.Bg2 chapters. The knight is now heading to b5 & d4 .} 19. Qb2 {White's idea is to meet ... Nb5 with Nb3 .} (19. Nc4 Nb5 {Black's knight is heading towards the d4 -square.}) 19... Bb5 {The bishop is also quite happy on b5 .} 20. Ra3 Rxa3 21. Qxa3 Ba6 {Now White can't stop ... Nb5 and ... Nd4 .} 22. Rc1 Nb5 23. Qa5 Nd4 24. Bf1 Nh5 {Beliavsky begins to play on the kingside. His idea is ... Qg5 and ... f5 .} 25. Nf2 Be2 {The bishop is joining the attack on White's king.} 26. Rc3 Qg5 27. Qa2 f5 {A positional triumph for the Black army! All of his pieces are participating in the attack while White's army is tied up in hopeless defense of his king.} 28. exf5 Qxf5 29. Bg2 Nf6 30. Rc7 {White decides to make an active move, but this only speeds up the end.} Bxf3 31. Rxb7 Ng4 32. Nxg4 Bxg4 33. Nf1 Ne2+ 34. Kh1 Bf3 {The mate is unstoppable now.} 35. Nd2 Nxg3+ ({White resigned as hxg3} 35... Qh3 {Kg1 Qxg2#}) *

