1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. g3 Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 Qb4 10. Rc1 Qxc3+ 11. Rxc3 d6 12. Bg2 a5 13. O-O Bd7 14. e4 e5 15. d5 Nb8 16. c5 Na6 17. cxd6 cxd6 18. Rfc1 Ke7 19. Nd2 b5 {We have covered the theory up to here in Bogo 4.Bgd2 and 6.Nc3 chapter.   Let's take a look how a strong GM got outplayed here as White in a seemingly equal endgame.} 20. a3 {White's idea is to meet Nc5 with .} b4 {Black is happy to trade pawns as after axb4 axb4 R1c2 we establish a knight on the c5 -outpost with .} 21. R3c2 Nc5 (21... Rhb8 $5 {This is a good alternative, keeping White guessing when the knight would land on c5 .}) 22. Bf1 {White naturally wants to activate his light-squared bishop, but it's too slow.} (22. f4 f6 23. fxe5 fxe5 24. Rxc5 $1 {Drastic measures are needed, and this exchange sacrifice gives White enough counterplay to maintain equality.} dxc5 25. Nc4 $1 {The e5 -pawn will fall and White has enough counterplay.}) 22... Rhc8 (22... Rhb8 $1 {An even stronger move}) 23. axb4 axb4 24. b3 {This creates more weaknesses in White's camp.} (24. f4 f6 25. Kf2 {Keeps White in the game, but Black can still press with ... g5 or ... b3 ideas.}) 24... Ra3 25. Bc4 Rca8 {Black firmly secures the a-file.} (25... f5 $1 {Opening up the 2nd front is quite strong as well. But Black plays it on the next move.}) 26. f3 f5 {Black opens up the 2nd front, now White has to deal with kingside pressure as well.} 27. Kf2 fxe4 28. fxe4 Ra2 29. Rxa2 Rxa2 30. Ke3 Be8 (30... g5 $1 {This expansion is quite strong as well. We will play ... h5 next and White is totally paralyzed.}) 31. Be2 {White blunders likely due to time pressure.} Rxd2 32. Kxd2 Nxb3+ 33. Kc2 Nxc1 34. Kxc1 Kd8 {Now the king walks to c5 and it's all over.} 35. Kb2 Ba4 36. Bc4 Kc7 37. Bb3 Bb5 {White resigned as the king march to c5 decides the game.} *

