1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 Nc6 5. e3 e5 6. d5 Ne7 7. Nge2 a5 8. a3 Bc5 9. Ng3 d6 10. Be2 O-O 11. Na4 Ba7 12. O-O Ng4 13. h3 Nh6 14. b4 f5 {We have covered this in theory in the Nimzo Qc2 chapter .} 15. Nc3 Ng6 {Leela brings another knight to the kingside, but the immediate ... f4 ! is quite strong as well.} 16. c5 Qh4 {The clouds around White's king are getting darker!} 17. Nb5 f4 {Black finally launches the attack. We don't care about the queenside.} 18. exf4 exf4 19. Ne4 Bxh3 {A promising piece sacrifice that White should not accept.} 20. Nxc7 {This loses by force.} (20. Qc3 $1 {This keeps the game alive.} Bf5 21. Bb2 Rf7 {and apparently White should sacrifice a piece on d6 with crazy complications.} 22. Nbxd6 cxd6 23. Nxd6) 20... f3 {The killer blow. Now we open up the king for the final attack.} 21. gxf3 Nf7 ({This gets the job done, but} 21... Ne5 $1 {is even stronger.}) 22. Nxa8 Nfe5 23. Qd1 Bf5 24. Bg5 Qh3 25. Nc7 Bxe4 26. fxe4 Nf4 {Notice how Black is down a rook but totally winning!} 27. Bxf4 Rxf4 {Now the threat of ... Rh4 with mate prompts White to give up his queen.} 28. Qb3 Qxb3 29. Rfc1 Qb2 30. Ne6 Qxe2 31. Nxf4 Qg4+ {A nice miniature by Leela!} *

