{This is one of my most memorable wins against a strong Polish GM. It was played a year after I became a GM thanks to the Black Book the Nimzo + Bogo repertoire!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 Nc6 5. Nf3 d6 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 a5 8. b3 O-O 9. Bb2 Re8 10. Rd1 Qe7 {Aiming for an e5 push that cannot be stopped.} 11. e3 e5 12. Be2 Bg4 13. d5 Nb8 14. Qc2 Nbd7 {We have covered the theory up to here in the Nimzo 4.Qc2 chapter.} 15. h3 Bh5 16. Nh4 Bxe2 17. Nf5 Qf8 18. Qxe2 g6 {Black starts the kingside expansion.} 19. Ng3 h5 20. Qc2 h4 21. Ne2 Nh5 {I'm getting ready to play ... f5 next.} 22. O-O f5 {This is the critical position of the game. A natural way of buffering Black's attack with f4 and opening his bishop turns out to be a mistake as it gives away the key e4 - and g3 -squares.} {Better is b4 with queenside play.} 23. f4 {White chooses the wrong plan, as mentioned, b4 is the right approach.} Nc5 {The knight is heading to e4 .} 24. b4 axb4 25. axb4 Ne4 26. Nc1 {Too slow.} ({Better was} 26. fxe5 dxe5 27. c5 {as it gives White counter-chances with a strong d5 -passer.}) 26... Neg3 {Now, Black takes over the initiative.} 27. Rf2 exf4 28. exf4 Re4 29. Nd3 Rae8 {As it turns out Black's strong knights and control of the e-file is much more important than an open a1 - h8 diagonal for White's bishop, which only 'shoots blanks.'} 30. Kh2 Re2 31. Rxe2 Rxe2 32. Qc3 Kf7 {The best square for the king! White's queen has no entry points.} 33. Ra1 {White's counterplay is lagging behind.} Qe8 34. Ne1 {This loses on the spot, but White's position is already quite bad.} (34. Ne5+ dxe5 35. fxe5 {Gives White some practical chances, but after} g5 36. e6+ Kg6 {Black should convert the extra piece.}) 34... Nf1+ 35. Kg1 Qe3+ (35... Nd2 $1 {This leads to an even faster finish, which I missed in time pressure} 36. Nf3 ({(} 36. Nd3 Qe3+ 37. Kh1 Ng3+ 38. Kh2 Nf3# {)}) 36... Rxg2+ 37. Kxg2 Qe2+) 36. Qxe3 Nxe3 37. Bd4 Nxf4 {Black wins a lot of pawns and should convert the endgame.} 38. Bxe3 Rxe3 39. Nf3 Rc3 40. c5 dxc5 41. bxc5 Rxc5 42. Rb1 b5 43. Ne5+ Kg7 {White resigned as Black is about to pick up a 3rd pawn on d5 .} *

