{This is one of the most important victories in my career as winning this game secured my 3rd and final GM norm!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 {This Catalan move order will eventually transpose to the main line of the Bogo.} Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 O-O 8. O-O d6 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Nb8 11. Ne1 a5 12. Nd3 Na6 13. Qc2 ({A rare but interesting continuation. Normally, White employs either} 13. f4 {or a3 followed by b4 .}) 13... Bd7 ({Played after a long thought. I declined} 13... c6 {due to} 14. dxc6 bxc6 15. c5 $1 {And now Black can take on c5 and ruin his pawn structure, while} d5 {is met by} 16. Rfe1 $1 {forcing the d-pawn to move, thus weakening the c4 -square.}) 14. Qc3 {Victor finds a nice square for his Queen, where it could support the action on both flanks.} b6 15. f4 Ng4 16. Rae1 f6 {Conceding space on the kingside. Although Black's position is cramped, it's rock solid due to the fact that dark-square bishops are exchanged.} 17. b3 {Preparing the expansion on the queenside with a3 & b4 .} (17. a3 $6 a4 $1) 17... Nc5 18. Nb2 Nh6 19. a3 Nf7 20. f5 {White stops a possible threat of taking over the e5 -square via ... exf4 and ... g5 .} g6 21. Qc2 Nh6 ({Forcing White to take on g6 as a threat of} 21... a4 $1 22. b4 Nb3 $1 {is becoming unpleasant.}) 22. fxg6 hxg6 {Here we can say that Black has achieved a small victory on the kingside. Now the balance shifts to the queenside.} 23. b4 Nb7 24. Nd3 c5 (24... axb4 25. axb4 c5 {is met by} 26. dxc6 Bxc6 27. b5 Bd7 28. Nb4 $1) 25. dxc6 Bxc6 26. Nb1 {The knight is heading to d5 .} Nd8 {Black's knight is going to d4 .} 27. Nc3 Ne6 28. Nd5 Qd8 29. Qb2 Kg7 30. Rd1 Nd4 {The struggle has reached its intensity as both sides have finished their maneuvering. I thought my knight on d4 is stronger than its counterpart on d5 , since I can always play ... Bxd5 .} 31. N3f4 {With a threat of Rxd4 and Ne6 , Victor uncorks a powerful move.} Bxd5 32. Rxd4 {A typical blunder, which is caused by time pressure and fatigue. The following lines were possible:} (32. exd5 exf4 ({(} 32... Nhf5 $2 33. Nxg6 $1 Kxg6 34. Be4 {)}) 33. Qxd4 fxg3 34. hxg3 Nf7 {and the knight is heading to e5 .}) (32. Nxd5 Ng8 33. Rxd4 $1 exd4 34. Qxd4 {This should give White sufficient compensation for the exchange.}) 32... Bg8 {Now Black simply wins a piece.} 33. Rd2 exf4 34. e5 Rc8 (34... fxe5 35. Bxa8 Qxa8 {was another possibility, but I wanted to keep my extra material!}) 35. Rxd6 Qe7 {It seems that Black should convert a piece fairly easily, yet the position is still very tricky.} 36. c5 {A start to a beautiful, Houdini-like escape.} bxc5 37. exf6+ {An endgame up a piece? I still didn't see Victor's idea.} Rxf6 38. Rxf6 Qxf6 39. Qxf6+ Kxf6 40. bxa5 {That's the whole point behind 36. c5 ! Now, I frantically had to find a way to stop White's pawn.} Rc7 ({The only move. If} 40... Be6 41. a6 Rc7 42. Bb7 Bc8 43. Rb1 $1 {the a-pawn sneaks through.}) 41. Rb1 {Another great move with multiple threats.} fxg3 (41... Ra7 42. Rb6+ Kg7 43. a6 $1 {and Black still has to work hard for a win after} Bf7 44. gxf4) 42. Bb7 gxh2+ 43. Kxh2 Bc4 {I have nothing better than to give up my bishop for the pawn.} ({A silicon beast offers this line} 43... Ng4+ 44. Kg3 Ne3 45. a6 Bd5 46. a7 Rxb7 47. a8=Q Rxb1 {Yet, somehow I doubt any human would take them up on this offer.}) 44. a4 Nf5 45. a6 Bxa6 46. Bxa6 {After fantastic escape, White is only down one pawn! And I have to start all over to push for the win.} c4 47. Kg2 Ke5 48. Kf2 c3 {A strong passer, plus centralized king and knight should still be winning for Black, yet he has to be careful not to allow White to give up his bishop for two pawns.} 49. Rg1 Kd4 {The king is heading toward the a-pawn.} 50. Rd1+ Kc5 51. Bd3 Kb4 52. Bc2 Rh7 53. Ke2 {This allows a nice finish.} ({But even after a stronger} 53. Rb1+ Kc4 54. Bb3+ Kc5 $1 {Black wins:} 55. a5 Rh2+ 56. Kf3 Rb2 57. Rxb2 cxb2 58. Bc2 Kb5 59. Kf4 Kxa5 60. Kg5 Ne7 61. Kf6 Kb4) 53... Rh2+ 54. Kd3 Rxc2 55. a5 (55. Kxc2 Ne3+ 56. Kc1 Nxd1 57. Kxd1 Kxa4) 55... Rd2+ 56. Rxd2 cxd2 57. Kxd2 Kxa5 *

