1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. e3 b6 6. Be2 Bb7 7. Qa4 Bxd2+ 8. Nbxd2 O-O 9. O-O d6 10. Qa3 c5 {We covered the moves up to here in this chapter .} 11. Qc3 Nbd7 12. Ne1 e5 {Black takes advantage of White's last move as strikes in the center.} 13. d5 e4 {Grabbing more space.} 14. f4 exf3 15. gxf3 b5 {It's a thematic idea to undermine the c4 -pawn.} 16. b3 b4 {Grabbing more space on the queenside.} 17. Qd3 Ne5 18. Qf5 Bc8 19. Qc2 Bh3 {Activating the bishop with a tempo.} (19... Ng6 $1 {is even stronger, after} 20. Ng2 ({(} 20. Qd3 Bf5 21. Qxf5 Qxe3+ {)}) 20... Bh3 21. Qd3 Rfe8) 20. Rf2 Ng6 21. Bf1 {White uses tactics to stay alive.} Qd7 22. Bxh3 Qxh3 23. Nf1 Rae8 {White managed to survive the first wave of Black's attack, but still facing serious problems as both the f3 - & e3 - pawns are weak.} 24. Nd3 Nh4 25. Qe2 Nh5 26. Nd2 Qd7 27. Re1 f5 {The march of the f-pawn helps to shake up White's position even more.} 28. Qf1 f4 29. Nxf4 Nxf4 30. exf4 Rxf4 31. Rfe2 Ref8 32. Re6 Qf7 {Now the f3 -pawn falls.} 33. Qh3 Nxf3+ 34. Nxf3 Rxf3 35. Qg2 Rf2 36. Qg3 Rf1+ 37. Kg2 Qf2+ {This leads to a winning R+P endgame.} 38. Qxf2 R8xf2+ 39. Kg3 Rxe1 40. Rxe1 Rxa2 41. Re6 Rb2 42. Rxd6 Rxb3+ 43. Kf4 Rb1 44. Kf5 b3 45. Rd8+ Kf7 46. Rd7+ Ke8 *

