1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. Qc2 {A bit of a passive move that allows me to demonstrate Black's plan.} Bxd2+ 6. Nbxd2 d6 {I am ready to play the thematic ... e5 push next.} 7. e3 e5 8. c5 {White tries to seek counterplay, but it only slows down his development.} O-O 9. cxd6 cxd6 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Bc4 Nc6 {Black has a nice central pawn.} 12. O-O e4 {Going for more space!} 13. Ng5 {White enters tactics that favor Black.} (13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. exd4 Rd8 {with only a slight edge for Black.}) 13... Bf5 14. f3 {This is what White hoped for, but it turns out to be bad for him.} exf3 15. Qxf5 Qxe3+ 16. Rf2 Nd4 {The key move. Perhaps this is the move that White overlooked. Now, he's in big trouble.} 17. Qd3 Ne2+ 18. Kf1 fxg2+ 19. Rxg2 Qxd3 20. Bxd3 Nf4 21. Bc4 Nxg2 22. Kxg2 {The dust has settled and Black has a rook and two pawns for bishop and knight. This should be winning. The rest is just technique.} h6 23. Ngf3 Rfe8 24. a4 Rad8 25. Ra3 g5 26. h3 Nh5 27. Rb3 Re7 28. Rb5 Kg7 29. Nf1 Rd1 30. b3 Rc1 31. Nd4 Nf4+ 32. Kh2 Kg6 33. h4 Rd7 34. Nf3 Rc2+ 35. Kh1 f6 36. Rc5 Rf2 37. N3h2 h5 38. Bb5 Re7 39. hxg5 fxg5 40. Rc8 g4 41. Rc1 a6 42. Bc4 Kg5 43. Rc3 Re1 44. Kg1 Rb2 45. Rg3 Kh4 46. Re3 Nh3+ 47. Kh1 Rxe3 48. Nxe3 Kg5 49. Nhf1 Nf4 50. Ng3 Nh3 51. a5 Nf2+ 52. Kg1 h4 53. Ne2 Nh3+ 54. Kh1 Rb1+ 55. Kg2 Nf4+ 56. Nxf4 Kxf4 57. Nd5+ Ke5 58. Ne3 Rb2+ 59. Kg1 g3 60. Bf1 Rxb3 61. Nc4+ Kf4 62. Bh3 Rb4 63. Nb6 Rb1+ 64. Kg2 Rb2+ 65. Kg1 Kf3 66. Nc4 Rb1+ 67. Bf1 Kf4 *

