1. Nf3 g6 2. g3 Bg7 3. Bg2 c5 4. O-O Nc6 5. c4 d6 6. Nc3 Bf5 7. Nd5 {White stops our standard ... Qd7 & ... Bh3 plan due to a Bxh3 and Nc7 + fork. However, we can just continue development with ... Nf6 !} Nf6 {Simple chess! We don't mind the trade of the knights as White spent 2 tempi to do it.} 8. d3 O-O 9. Rb1 Qd7 10. Nxf6+ Bxf6 11. Bg5 Bg7 12. a3 a5 {It's important to stop White's only counterplay, b4 .} 13. Qc1 Bh3 14. Bh6 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 e5 {An instructive moment! I anticipate the trade of the dark-squared bishops and don't mind putting the pawn on e5 .} 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. h4 h6 {The idea is to meet h5 with ... g5 !} 18. Qc3 f5 19. e3 Kh7 20. d4 cxd4 21. exd4 e4 {Black creates a strong pawn chain.} 22. Nd2 d5 (22... Rac8 $1 {This is perhaps even stronger than the game.}) 23. cxd5 Qxd5 24. Qb3 {I missed this move, now White hopes to trade queens and hold the endgame.} Qxb3 25. Nxb3 Rfd8 26. Rfd1 Rd5 27. Rbc1 Re8 {I didn't like ... Rad8 due to Nc5 and hope to play ... e3 .} 28. Rc5 Red8 {A good idea to secure the d5 -rook.} 29. a4 Rxc5 30. Nxc5 b6 31. Nb3 {Too passive.} (31. Ne6 Rd6 32. d5 $1 {this keeps White in drawing range.}) 31... Kg7 32. Kf1 Kf6 33. Rc1 Rd6 34. Ke2 Ke6 35. Ke3 Kd7 (35... Kd5 $1 {is even stronger as I will play ... g5 and ... f4 next. The d-pawn is likely to fall.}) 36. Rc4 Nb4 37. Nc1 g5 38. hxg5 hxg5 39. Ne2 Nd5+ 40. Kd2 Re6 41. Rc1 (41. Nc3 $2 e3+ 42. fxe3 Nxe3 {the rook is trapped.}) 41... Rh6 42. Nc3 Nf6 43. Nb5 Rh2 44. Rc7+ Kd8 45. Ke1 Ng4 46. Rf7 Rxf2 47. Nd6 e3 48. Nb7+ Kc8 49. Nd6+ Kb8 50. Rxf5 Rxb2 51. Nc4 Rb4 52. Rxg5 Rxc4 53. Rxg4 Rxa4 54. Ke2 Rb4 55. Kxe3 a4 56. Rh4 a3 57. Rh1 Rb3+ 58. Kd2 Rxg3 59. Kc2 Kc7 60. Kb1 b5 61. Rh6 b4 62. Ra6 Kb7 63. Ra4 Rb3+ 64. Ka1 Kb6 65. Ra8 Kb5 66. Rb8+ Kc4 67. Rc8+ Kd3 68. Ka2 Rb2+ 69. Ka1 Rb3 70. Ka2 Rb2+ 71. Ka1 Rc2 {White flagged but the position is lost.} *

